primitive reticulocyte also known as megalocyte A primitive erythrocyte that has undergone enucleation. This cell type is 3-6 fold bigger than the fetal derived erythrocytes that they co-circulate with during fetal development. Expresses epsilon-gamma hemoglobin chains.

fetal derived definitive erythrocyte also known as macrocyte A fetal liver derived enucleated erythrocyte. This erythrocyte resembles adult erythrocytes in that they are small (3- to 6- times smaller than primitive erythrocytes) and produce adult hemaglobins.
pyrenocyte Derived from the Greek word pyren (the pit of a stone fruit), this is a transient nucleated cell type that results from exclusion of the nucleus from the primitive erythrocyte.
placental hematopoietic stem cell A hematopoietic stem cell of the placenta. This cell type is first observed E10.5 This cell type may give rise to fetal liver hematopoietic stem cells.
AGM hematopoietic stem cell A hematopoietic stem cell from the aorta-gonad-mesonephros region of the developing embryo. First seen at E10.5 in mouse embryos. May give rise to fetal liver HSC.

primitive erythroid progenitor also known as EryP-CFC; inner blood island hemangioblast A progenitor cell that is capable of forming colonies of primitive erythrocytes in the blood island of the yolk sac. First arrive at E7.5 in mouse and expresses CD41.

cerebellar granule cell precursor A cell located in the outermost proliferative zone of the external germinal layer that can differentiate into astroglial cells and granule cells. This cell type is glial fibrillary acidic protein-positive and HNK1-positive.

keratocyte also known as corneal fibroblast; corneal keratocyte A keratocyte is a specialized fibroblast residing in the cornea stroma that has a flattened, dendritic morphology; located between the lamellae with a large flattened nucleus, and lengthy processes which communicate with neighboring cells. This corneal layer, representing about 85-90% of corneal thickness, is built up from highly regular collagenous lamellae and extracellular matrix components. Keratocytes play the major role in keeping it transparent, healing its wounds, and synthesizing its components. This cell type secretes collagen I, V, VI, and keratan sulfate.

cortical thymic epithelial cell also known as cTEC An epithelial cell of the cortical portion of the thymus. Epithelial cells in this region are required for positive selection of CD8-positive T cells.

medullary thymic epithelial cell also known as mTEC An epithelial cell of the medullary thymus. This cell type expresses a diverse range of tissue-specific antigens. This promiscuous gene expression is a cell-autonomous property of medullary epithelial cells and is maintained during the entire period of thymic T cell output.
myometrial cell also known as myometrium smooth muscle cell A smooth muscle cell of the myometrium that enlarges and stretches during pregnancy, and contracts in response to oxytocin.

trabecular meshwork cell also known as trabeculocyte A cell that lines the trabecular meshwork, which is an area of tissue in the eye located around the base of the cornea, near the ciliary body, and is responsible for draining the aqueous humor from the eye via the anterior chamber (the chamber on the front of the eye covered by the cornea). This cell may play a role in regulating intraocular pressure.
respiratory epithelial cell also known as airway epithelial cell An endo-epithelial cell of the respiratory tract.

fungal spore A differentiated form of a fungus produced during or as a result of an asexual or sexual reproductive process; usually a cell with a thick cell wall that stores and protects one or more nuclei. Spores may be produced in response to, and are characteristically resistant to, adverse environmental conditions.

respiratory goblet cell also known as respiratory mucosa goblet cells A simple columnar epithelial cell that secretes mucin. Rough endoplasmic reticulum, mitochondria, the nucleus, and other organelles are concentrated in the basal portion. The apical plasma membrane projects microvilli to increase surface area for secretion.
myotube also known as myofiber; myofibril A transversely striated, multinucleated syncytial muscle cell, formed by the fusion of myoblasts during muscle development.
growth hormone releasing hormone secreting cell also known as GHRH secreting cell; somatocrinin secreting cell A peptide hormone secreting cell that secretes growth hormone releasing hormone.
ear hair cell also known as ear receptor cell A hair cell of the ear that contains the organs of balance and hearing.

Schwann cell precursor also known as Schwann cell precursor cell A multipotent progenitor cell that develops from a migratory neural crest cell. The schwann cell precursor is embedded among axons, with minimal extracellular space separating them from nerve cell membranes. This cell lacks a basal lamina, which distinguishes it from more mature Schwann cells. In rodents, cadherin-19 (Cdh19) serves as a specific marker for this developmental stage.

non-myelinating Schwann cell A glial cell that ensheaths multiple small diameter axons in the peripheral nervous system. The non-myelinating Schwann cell is embedded among neurons (axons) with minimal extracellular spaces separating them from nerve cell membranes and has a basal lamina. Cells can survive without an axon present. These cells can de-differentiate into immature Schwann cells.

immature Schwann cell A glial cell that develops from a Schwann cell precursor. The immature Schwann cell is embedded among neurons (axons) with minimal extracellular spaces separating them from nerve cell membranes and has a basal lamina. Cells can survive without an axon present. Immature Schwann cell can be found communally ensheathing large groups of axons.

immature Vgamma2-positive fetal thymocyte A double negative thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain containing a Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-positive and is found in the fetal thymus.
meningothelial cell also known as arachnoid cap cell A neurecto-epithelial cell found in the arachnoid villi of dura mater. This cell type facilitates flow of cerebrospinal fluid into the blood.
oospore An asexual spore formed by Oomycetes; formed upon fertilization of an oosphere.
uninucleate conidium A conidium that has only one nucleus.
multinucleate conidium A conidium that has more than one nucleus.
conidium of conidiophore head A uninucleate spore formed on specialized cells or projections, sterigma, of a conidiophore head.
uninucleate macroconidium A macroconidium that has only one nucleus.
blastoconidium An oblong or round asexual spore formed from conidial chains.
multinucleate macroconidium A macroconidium that has more than one nucleus.
arthroconidium Cylindrical spore formed by development and compartmentation of hyphae; the hyphae are often supporting blastoconidiophores.
multinucleate arthroconidium An arthroconidium that has more than one nucleus.
uninucleate arthroconidium An arthroconidium that has only one nucleus.
uninucleate blastconidium A blastoconidium that has only one nucleus.
multinucleate blastoconidium A blastoconidium that has more than one nucleus.
intermediate monocyte A monocyte that has characteristics of both patrolling and inflammatory monocytes.

CD141-positive myeloid dendritic cell A myeloid dendritic cell found in the blood, lymph nodes, tonsil, bone marrow, and spleen that is CD141-positive (BDCA-3), XCR1-positive, and Clec9A-positive. This cell-type can cross-present antigen to CD8-positive T cells and can produce inteferon-beta.
Gr1-high classical monocyte A resident monocyte that is Gr-1 high, CD43-negative, CX3CR1-negative, CD115-positive, and B220-negative.
CD14-low, CD16-positive monocyte also known as non-classical monocyte, human A patrolling monocyte that is CD14-low and CD16-positive.
CD14-positive, CD16-positive monocyte also known as CD16+ monocyte A CD14-positive monocyte that is also CD16-positive and CCR2-negative.
Gr1-positive, CD43-positive monocyte An intermediate monocyte that is Gr1-positive, CD43-positive.
CD1c-positive myeloid dendritic cell A myeloid dendritic cell that is CD1c-positive.
fraction B/C precursor B cell A precursor B cell that is AA4-positive, IgM-negative, CD19-positive, CD43-positive and HSA-positive.

mature dendritic epithelial T cell precursor also known as mature DEC precursor; mature DETC precursor A thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain that has as part a Vgamma3 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-negative. This cell-type is found in the fetal thymus with highest numbers occurring at E17-E18.

Peyer's patch B cell also known as Peyers patch B cell A resting mature B cell within the Peyer's patch that is CD19-positive, B220-positive, IgM-positive, AA4-negative, CD23-positive, CD43-negative, and CD5-negative.

mature Vgamma2-positive fetal thymocyte also known as fetal Vgamma2-positive A thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain containing Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-negative. This cell-type is found in the fetal thymus.
fetal thymocyte A thymocyte found in the fetal thymus.

gamma-delta thymocyte also known as gammadelta thymocyte; gd thymocyte A post-natal thymocyte expressing components of the gamma-delta T cell receptor. This cell type is always double-negative (i.e. CD4-negative, CD8-negative).

immature Vgamma2-positive thymocyte A double negative post-natal thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain containing a Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-positive.

mature Vgamma2-positive thymocyte also known as Vgamma2-positive A thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain containing Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-negative.

immature Vgamma2-negative thymocyte A double negative post-natal thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain that does not contain a Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-positive.

mature Vgamma2-negative thymocyte also known as Vgamma2-negative A thymocyte that has a T cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain that does not contain the Vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. This cell type is CD4-negative, CD8-negative and CD24-negative.

pancreatic stellate cell also known as pancreas stellate cell; PaSC A cell that is found in the periacinar space of the exocrine pancreas and in perivascular and periductal regions of the pancreas, and has long cytoplasmic processes that encircle the base of the acinus. Expresses several intermediate filament proteins including vimentin and nestin. Shares many of the characteristics of hepatatic stellate cells, but not stellate cells of the central nervous system. Upon activation, this cell type undergoes morphological and gene expression changes that make the cell suggestive of being a type of myofibroblast.

Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-negative thymocyte also known as Vg1.1-positive, Vd6.3-negative T cell A gamma-delta receptor that expresses Vgamma1.1 but does not express Vdelta6.3 chains in the T-cell receptor.
Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-positive thymocyte also known as Vg1.1+Vd6.3+ T cell A gamma-delta receptor that expresses Vgamma1.1-Vdelta6.3 chains in the T-cell receptor.
mature Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-negative thymocyte A Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-negative thymocyte that is CD24-negative.
immature Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-negative thymocyte A Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-negative thymocyte that is CD24-positive.
immature Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-positive thymocyte also known as immature Vg1.1+Vd6.3+ T cell A Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-positive thymocyte that is CD24-positive.
mature Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-positive thymocyte also known as mature Vg1.1+Vd6.3+ T cell A Vgamma1.1-positive, Vdelta6.3-positive thymocyte that is CD24-negative.
primitive erythroid lineage cell An immature or mature cell of the first erythroid lineage to arise during embryonic development.
hemangioblast A pluripotent cell in the yolk sac that can give rise to mesenchymal cells including erythrocytes and endothelial cells.
mature T cell also known as CD3e-positive T cell; mature T-cell A T cell that expresses a T cell receptor complex and has completed T cell selection.
immature T cell also known as immature T-cell A T cell that has not completed T cell selection.
nucleated reticulocyte A reticulocyte that retains the nucleus and other organelles. Found in birds, fish, amphibians and reptiles.
enucleated reticulocyte A reticulocyte lacking a nucleus and showing a basophilic reticulum under vital staining due to the presence of ribosomes.
DN2a thymocyte A DN2 thymocyte that is Kit-hi.
DN2b thymocyte A DN2 thymocyte that is Kit-low.
early T lineage precursor also known as ETP; preT.ETP.Th A pro-T cell that is lin-negative, CD25-negative, CD127-negative, CD44-positive and kit-positive.
CD11b-positive, CD27-positive natural killer cell, mouse A mature natural killer cell that is CD11b-positive and CD27-positive.
resting double-positive thymocyte also known as T.DP.sm.Th A double-positive, alpha-beta thymocyte that is small and not proliferating.

double-positive blast also known as activated double-positive thymocyte; T.DPb.Th A double-positive thymocyte that is large (i.e. has a high forward scatter signal in flow cytometry) and is actively proliferating.
CD69-positive double-positive thymocyte also known as T.DP69+.Th A double-positive thymocyte that is CD69-positive and has begun positive selection.

CD4-intermediate, CD8-positive double-positive thymocyte also known as T_4int8+_Th; T.4int8+.Th A double-positive thymocyte that is undergoing positive selection, has high expression of the alpha-beta T cell receptor, is CD69-positive, and is in the process of down regulating the CD4 co-receptor.

CD4-positive, CD8-intermediate double-positive thymocyte also known as T_4+8int_Th; T.4+8int.Th A double-positive thymocyte that is undergoing positive selection, has high expression of the alpha-beta T cell receptor, is CD69-positive, and is in the process of down regulating the CD8 co-receptor.

CD24-positive, CD4 single-positive thymocyte also known as CD24-positive_1, CD4 single-positive semimature thymocyte; T.4SP24int.Th A CD4-positive, CD8-negative thymocyte that is CD24-positive and expresses high levels of the alpha-beta T cell receptor.

CD69-positive, CD4-positive single-positive thymocyte also known as intermediate CD4-single-positive; T.4SP69+.Th A CD4-positive, CD8-negative thymocyte that expresses high levels of the alpha-beta T cell receptor and is CD69-positive.

CD24-positive, CD8 single-positive thymocyte also known as CD24-positive_1, CD8 single-positive semimature thymocyte; T.8SP24int.Th A CD8-positive, CD4-negative thymocyte that is CD24-positive and expresses high levels of the alpha-beta T cell receptor.

CD69-positive, CD8-positive single-positive thymocyte also known as intermediate CD8-single-positive; T.8SP69+.Th A CD8-positive, CD4-negative thymocyte that expresses high levels of the alpha-beta T cell receptor and is CD69-positive.
mature CD4 single-positive thymocyte A mature CD4-positive, CD8-negative alpha-beta T cell found in the thymus that is CD24-low and has high expression of the T cell receptor.

mature CD8 single-positive thymocyte also known as T.8SP24-.Th A mature CD8-positive, CD4-negative alpha-beta T cell found in the thymus that is CD24-low and has high expression of the T cell receptor.
NK1.1-positive natural killer cell, mouse also known as NK.sp; NK1.1-positive NK cell A mature NK cell that is NK1.1-positive.
NKGA2-positive natural killer cell, mouse also known as NK.G2A+.SP A NK1.1-positive T cell that is NKGA2-positive.
Ly49D-positive natural killer cell, mouse also known as NK.49D+.Sp A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49D-positive.
CD94-positive natural killer cell, mouse also known as NK.94+.Sp A NK1.1-positive T cell that is CD94-positive.
CD94-negative, Ly49CI-negative natural killer cell, mouse also known as CD94- Ly49I-negative NK cell; NK.49Cl-94-.Sp A NK1.1-positive T cell that is CD94-negative and Ly49Cl-negative.
Ly49CI-positive natural killer cell, mouse also known as Ly49I-positive NK cell; NK.49Cl+.Sp A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49Cl-positive.
Ly49H-positive natural killer cell, mouse also known as LyH49H-positive A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49H-positive.
Ly49D-negative natural killer cell, mouse also known as NK.49D-.Sp A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49D-negative.
Ly49CI-negative natural killer cell, mouse also known as Ly49I-negative NK cell; NK.49Cl-.Sp A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49Cl-negative.
CD94-negative natural killer cell, mouse also known as NK.94-.Sp A NK1.1-positive T cell that is CD94-negative.
Ly49H-negative natural killer cell, mouse also known as LyH49H-negative A NK1.1-positive T cell that is Ly49H-negative.
CD94-positive Ly49CI-positive natural killer cell, mouse also known as NK.49Cl+94+.Sp A NK1.1-positive T cell that is CD94-positive and Ly49Cl-positive.
tether cell A specialized hair cell that has an elongated kinocilium upon which an otolith accretes. The tether cell then anchors the otolith in place.

mammary stem cell A multi-fate stem cell that is the source of cells for growth of the mammary gland during puberty and gestation. This cell type gives rise to both the luminal and myoepithelial cell types of the gland, and have been shown to have the ability to regenerate the entire organ in mice. This cell type also plays an important role in carcinogenesis of the breast. This cell type is Lin-, CD24-positive, CD29-hi.

oligodendrocyte precursor cell A progenitor cell of the central nervous system that can differentiate into oligodendrocytes or type-2 astrocytes. This cell originates from multiple structures within the developing brain including the medial ganglion eminence and the lateral ganglionic eminence. These cells migrate throughout the central nervous system and persist into adulthood where they play an important role in remyelination of injured neurons.

Cd4-negative, CD8_alpha-negative, CD11b-positive dendritic cell also known as DC.8-4-11b+; spleen double-negative dendritic cell Cd4-negative_1, CD8_alpha-negative_1, CD11b-positive dendritic cell is a conventional dendritic cell that is CD11b-positive, CD4-negative, CD8_alpha-negative and is CD205-positive.
CD8_alpha-negative plasmacytoid dendritic cell also known as DC.pDC.8- A CD11c-low plasmacytoid dendritic cell that is CD8alpha-negative and CD4-positive.
CD8_alpha-positive plasmacytoid dendritic cell also known as DC.pDC.8+ A CD11c-low plasmacytoid dendritic cell that is CD8alpha-positive and CD4-positive.
epidermal Langerhans cell A Langerhans cell that is in the epidermis and is CD45-positive, MHCII-positive, and CD11b-positive.
langerin-positive dermal dendritic cell A dermal dendritic cell that is langerin-positive and CD103-positive.
langerin-negative dermal dendritic cell A dermal dendritic cell that is langerin-negative, CD103-negative, and CD11b-positive.
CD8alpha-negative thymic conventional dendritic cell also known as DC.8-.Th A conventional thymic dendritic cell that is CD8alpha-negative.
CD103-positive dendritic cell A conventional dendritic cell that is CD103-positive. This cell type is usually found in non-lymphoid tissue.
adipose dendritic cell A F4/80-negative dendritic cell located in adipose tissue.
SIRPa-positive adipose dendritic cell also known as DC.SIRPa+.Ad An adipose dendritic cell that is SIRPa-positive.
SIRPa-negative adipose dendritic cell also known as DC.SIRPa-.Ad An adipose dendritic cell that is SIRPa-negative.
CD11b-positive dendritic cell A conventional dendritic cell that expresses CD11b (ITGAM).

small intestine serosal dendritic cell also known as DC.11cloSer.SI A CD11b-positive dendritic cell located in the serosal portion of the small intestine epithelium. This cell type is CD45-positive, MHC-II-positive, CD11c-low, CD103-negative.
Gr1-high myeloid suppressor cell also known as MDS.Gr1hi A myeloid suppressor cell that is Gr1-high and CD11c-negative.
Gr1-low myeloid suppressor cell also known as MDS.Gr1lo A myeloid suppressor cell that is Gr1-low and CD11c-positive.
MHC-II-negative classical monocyte also known as Mo.6C+II- Gr1-high monocyte that lacks MHC-II receptor complex.
MHC-II-positive classical monocyte also known as Mo.6c+II Gr1-high monocyte that has a MHC-II receptor complex.
MHC-II-negative non-classical monocyte also known as Mo.6C-II- Gr1-low non-classical monocyte that lacks expression of a MHC-II complex.
MHC-II-low non-classical monocyte also known as Mo.6C-IIint Gr1-low non-classical monocyte that has low to intermediate expression of the MHC-II complex.
MHC-II-high non-classical monocyte also known as Mo.6C-II+ Gr1-low non-classical monocyte that has high surface expression of a MHC-II complex.
lymphoid MHC-II-negative classical monocyte A MHC-II-negative classical monocyte located in lymphoid tissue that is F4/80-positive, CD11c-negative, and CD11b-high.
lymphoid MHC-II-negative non-classical monocyte A MHC-II-negative classical monocyte located in lymphoid tissue that is F4/80-positive, CD11c-intermediate, and CD11b-high.
bone marrow macrophage A tissue-resident macrophage located in the bone marrow. This cell type is B220-negative, CD3e-negative, Ly-6C-negative, CD115-positive, F4/80-positive.
adipose macrophage A macrophage located in adipose tissue that is CD45-positive, CD11c-positive, and SIRPa-positive.

F4/80-negative adipose macrophage also known as MF.Autofl.Ad An adipose macrophage that does not express F4/80but is MHC-II-positive. This cell type exhibits autofluorescence under typical flow cyometry conditions.
F4/80-positive adipose macrophage also known as MF.F480+.Ad An adipose macrophage that does not express MHC-II but is F4/80-positive.
nasal mucosa goblet cell A goblet cell located in the nasal epithelium.
peritubular myoid cell The flattened smooth myoepithelial cells of mesodermal origin that lie just outside the basal lamina of the seminiferous tubule.
dermal melanocyte A melanocyte that produces pigment in the dermis.
hair follicle melanocyte A melanocyte that produces pigment within the hair follicle.
epithelial melanocyte A melanocyte that produces pigment in the epithelium.
retinal melanocyte A melanocyte of the retina. This cell type is distinct from pigmented retinal epithelium.

strial intermediate cell A melanocyte located between the epithelial marginal cell layer and the mesodermal basal cell layer within the intrastrial space; the predominant cellular component of the electrogenic machinery that generates an endocochlear potential (80-100 mV) .
cutaneous/subcutaneous mechanoreceptor cell A neuronal receptor that respond to mechanical pressure or distortion in the skin.

trophoblast giant cell also known as giant trophoblast cell A trophoblast cell that has a large volume of cytoplasm, is polyploid and is usually mononuclear but is also occasionally multi-nucleate. This cell type is important in establishing maternal physiology and remodeling of the vasculature of the placenta.
double negative thymocyte also known as CD4-CD8- T cell; double negative T cell A thymocyte that lacks expression of CD4 and CD8.
organ of Corti supporting cell A supporting cell of the organ of Corti.
auditory epithelial cell A specialized cell involved in auditory sensory perception.

strial marginal cell A polarized columnar cell that covesr the lateral surface of the cochlear duct, secretes potassium ions and forms a continuous sheet in contact with the endolymph; marginal cells form extensive interdigitations with the basal and intermediate cells in the normal adult stria.
strial basal cell A polarized cell that is juxtaposed to fibrocytes in the underlying spiral ligament. This cell type secretes potassium ions derived from fibrocytes through gap junctions.
cardiocyte also known as heart cell A cell located in the heart, including both muscle and non muscle cells.

fetal cardiomyocyte also known as embryonic cardiomyocyte; neonatal cardiomyocyte A fetal and neonatal heart cell that undergoes proliferation and is not yet terminally differentiated into a binucleate or a multinucleate cardiac myocyte.
intraepithelial lymphocyte also known as IEL; intraepithelial T cell; intraepithelial T-cell A T cell that is located in the intestinal epithelium and is capable of a mucosal immune response.
primary trophoblast giant cell A trophoblast giant cell derived from the mural trophectoderm.
secondary trophoblast giant cell A trophoblast giant cell that is derived from ectoplacental cone and, later in gestation, the spongiotrophoblast.
spongiotrophoblast cell also known as spongiotrophoblast A trophoblast cell that arises in the junctional zone (basal plate) of the placenta.
P enteroendocrine cell A P/D1 enteroendocrine cell that is Grimelius positive and stores bombesin-like polypeptide.
type D1 enteroendocrine cell A P/D1 enteroendocrine cell that is argyrophilic and stores vasoactive intestinal polypeptide.
type M enteroendocrine cell An enteroendocrine cell of the small intestine that secretes motilin.
adventitial cell A cell of the adventitial layer of ductal structures such as the uterer, defent duct, biliary duct, etc
enteric smooth muscle cell also known as intestinal smooth muscle cell A smooth muscle cell of the intestine.
liver CD103-negative dendritic cell also known as DC.103-11b+.Lv A CD11b-positive dendritic cell that is CD11b-high, CD45-positive, MHC-II-positive and CD103-negative.
liver CD103-positive dendritic cell also known as DC.103+11b-.Lv A CD11b-positive dendritic cell that is CD11b-low, CD45-positive, MHC-II-high and CD103-positive that is located in the liver.
langerin-positive lymph node dendritic cell A dermal dendritic cell isolated from skin draining lymph nodes that is langerin-positive, MHC-II-positive, and CD4-negative and CD8a-negative.

langerin-negative, CD103-negative lymph node dendritic cell A dermal dendritic cell isolated from skin draining lymph nodes that is langerin-negative, MHC-II-positive, and CD4-negative and CD8a-negative.
CD103-positive, langerin-positive lymph node dendritic cell A langerin-positive lymph node dendritic cell that is CD103-positive and CD11b-low.
CD103-negative, langerin-positive lymph node dendritic cell A langerin-positive lymph node dendritic cell that is CD103-negative and CD11b-high.
CD11b-low, CD103-negative, langerin-negative lymph node dendritic cell A langerin-negative lymph node dendritic cell that is CD103-negative and CD11b-low.
CD11b-high, CD103-negative, langerin-negative lymph node dendritic cell A langerin-negative lymph node dendritic cell that is CD103-negative and CD11b-high.

Vgamma5-positive CD8alpha alpha positive gamma-delta intraepithelial T cell also known as tgd.vg5+.IEL A CD8alpha alpha positive gamma-delta intraepithelial T cell that expresses a TCR encoded in part by the Vgamma5 gene segment.

Vgamma5-negative CD8alpha alpha positive gamma-delta intraepithelial T cell also known as tgd.vg5-.IEL A CD8alpha alpha positive gamma-delta intraepithelial T cell that does not express a TCR partially encoded by the Vgamma5 gene segment.

interrenal norepinephrine type cell also known as interrenal noradrenaline type cell; type n interrenal cell An interrenal chromaffin cell found in teleosts that contain heterogeneous vesicles with electron-dense granules located asymmetrically within the vesicular membrane.
interrenal chromaffin cell A chromaffin cell interspersed among the interrenal epithelial layer of the anterior kidney of teloest fish.

interrenal epinephrin secreting cell also known as type a interrenal cell An interrenal chromaffin cell found in teleosts that contain small, homogeneous electron-lucent granules that are separated from the vesicular membrane by a visible halo.
kidney epithelial cell An epithelial cell of the kidney.

interrenal epithelial cell An interrenal epithelial kidney cell is an epithelial cell found in the anterior kidney of teleosts fish. This cell type is arranged in layers around the posterior cardinal vein and contains many mitochondria with tubulovesicular cristae. Interrenal chromaffin cells are interspersed among the tissue layer created by this cell type.
nephrocyte An insect excretory cell that regulates hemolymph composition by filtration and filtrate endocytosis.
subcutaneous adipocyte also known as subcutaneous fat cell An adipocyte that is part of subcutaneous adipose tissue.
renal filtration cell A renal filtration cell is a specialized cell of the renal system that filter fluids by charge, size or both.

mesonephric podocyte also known as mesonephric glomerular visceral epithelial cell A specialized epithelial cell that contains "feet" that interdigitate with the "feet" of other glomerular epithelial cells in the mesonephros.
disseminated nephrocyte A disseminated nephrocyte is a nephrocyte that filters hemolymph and is found at scattered locations in the fat body or other tissues.

metanephric podocyte also known as metanephric glomerular visceral epithelial cell A specialized epithelial cell that contains "feet" that interdigitate with the "feet" of other glomerular epithelial cells in the metanephros.
CD14-positive dermal dendritic cell also known as CD14+ dermal DC A dermal dendritic cell that is CD1a-negative and CD14-positive.
immature CD14-positive dermal dendritic cell An immature CD14-positive dermal dendritic cell is CD80-low, CD86-low, and MHCII-low.
mature CD14-positive dermal dendritic cell A mature CD14-positive dermal dendritic cell is CD80-high, CD86-high, MHCII-high and is CD83-positive.
CD1a-positive dermal dendritic cell also known as CD1a+ dermal DC A dermal dendritic cell that is CD1a-positive and CD14-negative.
immature CD1a-positive dermal dendritic cell An immature CD1a-positive dermal dendritic cell is CD80-low, CD86-low, and MHCII-low.
mature CD1a-positive dermal dendritic cell A mature CD1a-positive dermal dendritic cell is CD80-high, CD83-positive, CD86-high, and MHCII-high.
CD16-positive myeloid dendritic cell also known as CD16-mDC; CD16+ mDC A myeloid dendritic cell found in the blood that is CD16-positive.
immature CD16-positive myeloid dendritic cell An immature CD16-positive myeloid dendritic cell is CD80-low, CD86-low, and MHCII-low.
mature CD16-positive myeloid dendritic cell A mature CD16-positive myeloid dendritic cell is CD80-high, CD83-positive, CD86-high, and MHCII-high.

epithelial cell of cervix also known as cervical canal epithelial cell; cervical canal of uterus epithelial cell; cervix epithelial cell; cervix of uterus epithelial cell; epithelial cell of cervical canal; epithelial cell of cervical canal of uterus; epithelial cell of cervix of uterus; epithelial cell of neck of uterus; epithelial cell of uterine cervix; neck of uterus epithelial cell; uterine cervix epithelial cell An epithelial cell of the cervix.
epithelial cell of amnion also known as amniotic epithelial cell An epithelial cell that is part of the amnion.
amnion mesenchymal stem cell also known as amniotic membrane stem cell A mesenchymal stem cell of the amnion membrane.

intrahepatic cholangiocyte also known as small bile duct cholangiocyte An epithelial cell of the intrahepatic portion of the bile duct. These cells are flattened or cuboidal in shape, and have a small nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio relative to large/extrahepatic cholangiocytes.
aortic smooth muscle cell A smooth muscle cell of the aorta.
mesenchymal stem cell of the bone marrow A mesenchymal stem cell that is part of the bone marrow.
chorionic membrane mesenchymal stem cell A mesenchymal stem cell of the chorionic membrane.
vein endothelial cell also known as endothelial cell of vein; venous endothelial cell An endothelial cell that is part of the vein.
aortic endothelial cell An arterial endothelial cell that is part of the aorta endothelium.
thoracic aorta endothelial cell An endothelial cell that is part of the thoracic endothelium.
embryonic blood vessel endothelial progenitor cell An endothelial progenitor cell that participates in angiogenesis during development.
fibroblast of the aortic adventitia A fibroblast of the aortic adventitia.
fibroblast of cardiac tissue also known as cardiac fibroblast A fibroblast that is part of the heart.
fibroblast of choroid plexus A fibroblast that is part of the choroid plexus.
fibroblast of the conjunctiva A fibroblast that is part of the conjuctiva of the eye.
fibroblast of dermis Any skin fibroblast that is part of some dermis.
fibroblast of gingiva Any fibroblast that is part of some gingiva.
fibroblast of lung A fibroblast that is part of lung.
fibroblast of lymphatic vessel A fibroblast of the lymphatic system.
fibroblast of mammary gland A fibroblast that is part of the mammary gland.
fibroblast of periodontium A fibroblast of the periodontium.
fibroblast of pulmonary artery A fibroblast of pulmonary artery.
fibroblast of villous mesenchyme A fibroblast that is part of villous mesenchyme.
hair follicle cell An animal cell that is part of a hair follicle.
inner root sheath cell An epithelial cell that resides in the inner root sheath of the hair follicle.
outer root sheath cell An epithelial cell that is part of the outer root sheath.
hair germinal matrix cell also known as trichocyte An epidermal cell that is part of the germinal matrix.
intestinal epithelial cell An epithelial cell of the intestine.
nucleus pulposus cell of intervertebral disc A connective tissue cell of the nucleus pulposus cell of intervertebral disc.
iris pigment epithelial cell A pigment cell located in the epithelium of the iris.
dark melanocyte also known as melanotic melanocyte; melanotic melanophore A melanocyte that appears darker due to content or amount of melanin granules.
light melanocyte also known as amelanotic melanocyte; amelanotic melanophore A melanocyte that appears lighter in color.
mesenchymal stem cell of Wharton's jelly A mesenchymal stem cell that is part of Wharton's jelly.
mesenchymal stem cell of umbilical cord A mesenchymal stem cell of the umbilical cord.
mesenchymal stem cell of adipose tissue also known as mesenchymal stem cell of adipose A mesenchymal stem cell of adipose tissue.
hepatic mesenchymal stem cell A mesenchymal stem cell of liver.
vertebral mesenchymal stem cell A mesenchymal stem cell of the vertebrae.
Schwann cell also known as neurolemmocyte A glial cell that myelinates or ensheathes axons in the peripheral nervous system.
stromal cell of pancreas A stromal cell of the pancreas.
central nervous system pericyte A pericyte of the central nervous system.

perineurial cell also known as perineurial glial cell A glial cell that is part of the perineurium. This cell type has thin long bipolar cytoplasmic processes, pinocytotic vesicles, fragments of external lamina and/or external lamina-like material, attachment plaques, and desmosome-like junctions. Perineurial cells historically have been referred to as fibroblasts because of shape; however, unlike fibroblasts, a perineurial cell: does not have a compact nucleus and large endoplasmic reticulum; does have a double basement membrane opposed to a single basal lamina; is carefully joined to other perineurial cells by tight junctions into a single sheet as opposed to arranged in a large mass; and finally, can surround a small axon bundle at a nerve terminal whereas a fibroblast cannot.
placental epithelial cell An epithelial cell of the placenta.
mesenteric preadipocyte A preadipocyte found in mesenteric tissue.
omentum preadipocyte A preadipocyte that is part of an omentum.
preadipocyte of the breast A preadipocyte that is part of the breast.
perirenal preadipocyte A preadipocyte that is part of a perirenal fat tissue.
visceral preadipocyte A preadipocyte that is part of visceral tissue.
subcutaneous preadipocyte A preadipocyte that is part of subcutaneous tissue.
renal cortical epithelial cell An epithelial cell of the kidney cortex.
retinal blood vessel endothelial cell A blood vessel endothelial cell that is part of the retina.
retinal pigment epithelial cell An epithelial cell of the retinal pigmented epithelium.
smooth muscle cell of the umbilical vein A smooth muscle cell of the umbilical vein.
smooth muscle cell of the brachiocephalic vasculature A smooth muscle cell of the bachiocephalic vasculature.
smooth muscle cell of the brain vasculature A vascular associated smooth muscle cell of the brain vasculature.
smooth muscle cell of the pulmonary artery A smooth muscle of the pulmonary artery.
smooth muscle cell of the coronary artery A smooth muscle cell of the coronary artery.
smooth muscle cell of the internal thoracic artery A smooth muscle of the internal thoracic artery.
smooth muscle cell of the umbilical artery A smooth muscle cell of the umbilical artery.
smooth muscle cell of the subclavian artery A smooth muscle cell of the subclavian artery.
smooth muscle cell of the carotid artery Smooth muscle cell of the carotid artery.
smooth muscle cell of bladder A smooth muscle cell of the bladder.
bronchial smooth muscle cell Any smooth muscle cell that is part of some bronchus.
smooth muscle cell of the esophagus A smooth muscle cell of the esophagus.
smooth muscle cell of trachea A smooth muscle cell of the trachea.
uterine smooth muscle cell A smooth muscle cell of the uterus.
annulus pulposus cell also known as anulus pulposus cell Any connective tissue cell that is part of some annulus fibrosus disci intervertebralis.
astrocyte of the cerebellum An astrocyte of the cerebellum.
hippocampal astrocyte also known as astrocyte of the hippocampal formation; astrocyte of the hippocampus An astrocyte that is part of the hippocampus.
astrocyte of the cerebral cortex A transcriptomically distinct astrocyte that is found in the cerebral cortex.
astrocyte of the spinal cord An astrocyte of the spinal cord.
migratory enteric neural crest cell A neural crest cell that gives rise to cells of the enteric nervous system.
hippocampal neuron A neuron with a soma found in the hippocampus.
raphe nuclei neuron A neuron of the raphe nuclei.
neuron of the dorsal spinal cord A CNS neuron of the dorsal spinal cord.
neuron of the ventral spinal cord A neuron of the ventral spinal cord.
striatum neuron A neuron of the striatum.
neuron of the substantia nigra A neuron of the substantia nigra.
adipocyte of omentum tissue also known as omental adipocyte; omental fat cell An adipocyte that is part of omentum tissue.
perirenal adipocyte also known as perirenal adipocyte cell; perirenal fat cell An adipocyte of perirenal fat tissue.
adipocyte of breast also known as breast adipocyte; fat cell of breast An adipocyte that is part of the breast.
endothelial cell of umbilical vein An endothelial cell of the umbilical vein.

adult endothelial progenitor cell also known as EPC An adult angioblastic cell released from the bone marrow, or from the kidney in some teleost species, capable of blood circulation and participation in angiogenesis by differentiating into blood vessel endothelial cells.
skin fibroblast A fibroblast of skin.
gingival epithelial cell Any epithelial cell that is part of some gingival epithelium.
prostate stromal cell A stromal cell of the prostate.
acinar cell of salivary gland An acinar cell of salivary gland.
paneth cell of the appendix A paneth cell of the appendix.
seminiferous tubule epithelial cell A cell of the seminiferous tubule epithelium.
immature astrocyte also known as immature astrocytic glia An immature astrocyte.
mature astrocyte also known as activated astrocyte; mature astrocytic glia A mature astrocyte that is capable of producing cytokines.
immature microglial cell also known as immature microglia; quiescent microglia; resting microglia An immature microglial cell with a ramified morphology.

mature microglial cell also known as activated microglia; mature microglia; reactive microglia A mature microglial cell that has changed shape to an amoeboid morphology and is capable of cytokine production and antigen presentation.
actinomycete-type spore A spore formed from bacteria in the order Actinomycetales.
epithelial cell of upper respiratory tract Any epithelial cell that is part of some upper respiratory tract epithelium.
epithelial cell of lower respiratory tract Any epithelial cell that is part of some lower respiratory tract epithelium.
respiratory basal cell also known as airway basal cell; airway basal stem cell A basal cell in the respiratory tract.
epithelial cell of anal column An epithelial cell of the anal column.
nonkeratinized epithelial cell of anal column A nonkeratinized epithelial cell of the anal canal.
nonkeratinized epithelial cell of inferior part of anal canal A nonkeratinized cell epithleial cell of the inferior part of the anal canal.
keratinized epithelial cell of the anal canal An epithelial cell of the anal canal that is keratinized. This cell type is found towards the lower, rectal end of the anal canal.

bronchioalveolar stem cell also known as basal epithelial cell of bronchioalveolar duct junction; BASC A respiratory stem cell found at the junction of the terminal (conductive) bronchiole and the respiratory bronchiole. This cell types gives rise to alveolar cell types and club cells in response to lung injury. This cell type expresses markers Scgb1a1 and Sftpc.

amniotic stem cell An amniotic stem cell is a mesenchymalstem cell extracted from amniotic fluid. Amniotic stem cells are able to differentiate into various tissue type such as skin, cartilage, cardiac tissue, nerves, muscle, and bone
amniotic epithelial stem cell An epithelial fate stem cell derived form the amnion membrane.
epithelial cell of esophageal gland proper An epithelial cell of the esophageal gland proper.
epithelial cell of esophageal cardiac gland An epithelial cell of the esophageal cardiac gland that occurs both in the proximal and distal esophagus, within the lamina propia.
nonkeratinized cell of stratum corneum of esophageal epithelium An epithelial cell of stratum corneum of esophageal epithelium that lacks keratin.
endo-epithelial cell of tympanic part of viscerocranial mucosa An endothelial cell of viscerocranial mucosa that is part of the tympanic region of the viscerocranial mucosa.
endo-epithelial cell of pharyngotympanic part of viscerocranial mucosa An endocranial viscerocranial mucosa cell that is part of viscerocranial mucosa.

endothelial cell of venous sinus of spleen also known as stave cell An endothelial cell that is part of the venous sinus of spleen. This endothelial cell has an elongated, spindle-shaped, flattened morphology that is parallel to long axis of sinus. This cell type rests on a basement membrane interrupted by numerous narrow slits.

endothelial cell of high endothelial venule also known as HEV cell A venule endothelial cell that is cubodial, expresses leukocyte-specific receptors, and allows for passage of lymphocytes into bloodstream.
squamous endothelial cell A squamous shaped endothelial cell.
epithelial cell of stratum corneum of esophageal epithelium An epithelial cell of stratum corneum of esophageal epithelium.
epithelial cell of stratum spinosum of esophageal epithelium An epithelial cell of stratum spinosum of esophageal epithelium.
glandular cell of endometrium A glandular epithelial cell of the endometrium.
glandular cell of esophagus A glandular epithelial cell of the esophagus.
glandular cell of the large intestine A glandular epithelial cell of the large intestine.
glandular epithelial cell of stomach also known as glandular cell of stomach A glandular epithelial cell that is part of the stomach.
luminal cell of acinus of lactiferous gland A luminal epithelial cell of mammary gland located in acinus of structure.
luminal cell of lactiferous terminal ductal lobular unit A luminal cell of terminal ducts, i.e.e the terminal branch of a lactiferous duct which alveolar cells drain into.
luminal cell of lactiferous duct A luminal epithelial cell of the lactiferous duct. This cuboidal epithelial cell expresses keratin-18 and is estrogen-receptor alpha positive.
myocardial endocrine cell of atrium A myocardial endocrine cell that is part of the atrium.
cardioblast also known as cardiovascular progenitor cell A stem cell that can give rise to multiple cell types (i.e. smooth muscle, endothelial) in the developing heart.
otic fibrocyte A fibrocyte of the cochlea that has specialized structural and molecular adaptions.

type 2 otic fibrocyte also known as type II otic fibrocyte; type II spiral ligament fibrocyte An otic fibrocyte that underlies the spiral prominence and is part of a mesenchymal gap junction network that regulates ionic homeostasis of the endolymph.

type 5 otic fibrocyte also known as type V otic fibrocyte; type V spiral ligament fibrocyte An otic fibrocyte that resides above the stria vasularis and is part of a mesenchymal gap junction network that regulates ionic homeostasis of the endolymph.
type 4 otic fibrocyte also known as type IV otic fibrocyte; type IV spiral ligament fibrocyte An otic fibrocyte that is lateral to the basilar membrane and anchoris it to the lateral wall.
type 3 otic fibrocyte also known as type III otic fibrocyte; type III spiral ligament fibrocyte An otic fibrocyte that lines the otic capsule.

type 1 otic fibrocyte also known as type I otic fibrocyte; type I spiral ligament fibrocyte An otic fibrocyte that underlies the stria vascularis and is part of a mesenchymal gap junction network that regulates ionic homeostasis of the endolymph.
endothelial stalk cell An endothelial stalk cell is a specialized endothelial cell that follows behind the tip cell of an angiogenic sprout.
retinal progenitor cell A multi-fate stem cell that can give rise to different retinal cell types including rod and cone cells.
tongue muscle cell A skeletal muscle cell that is part of the tongue.
H minus also known as H- cell A S. pombe mating type determined by the mat1-Mc and mat1-Mi on the mat1 locus.
H plus A S. pombe cell type determined by mat1-Pc and mat1-Pi on the mat1 locus.
neural crest derived neuroblast A neuroblast derived from a neural crest cell.
naive regulatory T cell also known as naive regulatory T lymphocyte; naive regulatory T-cell; naive regulatory T-lymphocyte A regulatory T cell that has not encountered antigen.
memory regulatory T cell A CD4-positive, CD25-positive alpha-beta regulatory T cell that has encountered antigen.

natural helper lymphocyte A lymphocyte found in adipose tissue that lacks lineage markers of other lymphocytes but is capable of mediating TH2 cytokine responses. This cell type is found in fat associated lymphoid clusters, proliferates in response to IL2 and produce large amounts of TH2 cytokines such as IL5, IL6 and IL13
PP cell of intestine A PP cell found in intestine.
kidney cortical cell A cell that is part of a cortex of kidney.
bistratified retinal ganglion cell also known as retinal ganglion D cell A retinal ganglion cell that has dendrites stratified in two layers of the inner-plexiform layer.
G1 retinal ganglion cell A retinal ganglion cell that has a small dendritic field and a medium dendritic arbor with post sympatic terminals in sublaminar layer S3.
G2 retinal ganglion cell A mono-stratified retinal ganglion cell that has a small dendritic field and a sparse dendritic arbor with post sympatic terminals in sublaminar layer S3.

G3 retinal ganglion cell A bistratified retinal ganglion cell that has a small dendritic field with sparse density that terminates at the intersection of the S4-S5 sublaminar level, and a second dendrite field that is medium in size and degree of arborization that terminates in sublaminar layer S2.
G4 retinal ganglion cell A mono-stratified retinal ganglion cell that has a small dendritic field and dense dendritic arbor.
G4-ON retinal ganglion cell A G4 retinal ganglion cell that has post sympatic terminals in sublaminar layers S3 and S4 and is depolarized by illumination of its receptive field center.
G4-OFF retinal ganglion cell A G4 retinal ganglion cell that has post sympatic terminals in sublaminar layers S2 and S3 and is depolarized by decreased illumination of their receptive field center
G5 retinal ganglion cell A mono-stratified retinal ganglion cell that has a medium dendritic field and a medium dendritic arbor with post sympatic terminals in sublaminar layer S2.
G6 retinal ganglion cell A mono-stratified retinal ganglion cell that has a medium dendritic field and a sparse dendritic arbor with post sympatic terminals in sublaminar layer S4 and S5.

G7 retinal ganglion cell also known as ON-OFF DS A bistratified retinal ganglion cell that has a dendrite field that terminates in sublaminar layer S2 and a second dendrite field that terminates in sublaminar layer S4.
G8 retinal ganglion cell A mono-stratified retinal ganglion cell that has a large dendritic field and a sparse dendritic arbor with post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer S4.
G9 retinal ganglion cell A mono-stratified retinal ganglion cell that has a large dendritic field and a medium dendritic arbor with post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer S1 and S2.

G10 retinal ganglion cell A mono-stratified retinal ganglion cell that has a large dendritic field, a medium dendritic arbor, and a long secondary dendrite shaft with post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer S4.
G11 retinal ganglion cell A mono-stratified retinal ganglion cell that has a large dendritic field, a medium dendritic arbor, and a medium length secondary dendrite shaft.
G11-ON retinal ganglion cell A G11 retinal ganglion cell that has post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer S4 and is depolarized by illumination of its receptive field center.
G11-OFF retinal ganglion cell A G11 retinal ganglion cell that has post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer S2 and is depolarized by decreased illumination of their receptive field center
retinal ganglion cell B3 outer A retinal ganglion B cell that has post synaptic terminals in S2.
retinal ganglion cell B3 inner A retinal ganglion B3 cell with dentrites terminating in S4.
retinal ganglion cell C outer A retinal ganglion cell C that has post-synaptic terminals in S2.
retinal ganglion cell C4 A retinal ganglion cell C outer that has a medium dendritic field and a dense dendritic arbor.
retinal ganglion cell C5 A retinal ganglion cell C outer that has medium dendritic density and field size.
retinal ganglion cell C6 A retinal ganglion cell C outer that has dense dendritic diversity.
retinal ganglion cell C inner A retinal ganglion cell C with medium cell bodies and large dendritic field.
retinal ganglion cell C3 A retinal ganglion cell C inner that has sparse dendritic density, and large dendritic field.
retinal ganglion cell D1 A bistratified retinal ganglion cell that has a small dendrite fields with a sparse dendrite arbor terminating in S2 and S3.
retinal ganglion cell D2 A bistratified retinal ganglion cell D cell that has medium dendritic arbor and a large dendritic field that terminates in S2 and S4.
M1 retinal ganglion cell A monostratified retinal ganglion cell that has a small dendrite field with a dense dendrite arbor with post synaptic terminals in sublaminer layer S4.
M2 retinal ganglion cell A monostratified retinal ganglion cell that has a small soma, a small dendrite field with a dense dendrite arbor, and post synaptic terminals in sublaminer layer S2 and S3.
M3 retinal ganglion cell A monostratified retinal ganglion cell that has a medium soma and a small dendrite field.
M3-ON retinal ganglion cell A monostratified retinal ganglion cell that has post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer S4 and is depolarized by illumination of its receptive field center.

M3-OFF retinal ganglion cell A monostratified retinal ganglion cell that has post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer S2 and is depolarized by decreased illumination of their receptive field center
M4 retinal ganglion cell A monostratified retinal ganglion cell that has a large soma, a medium dendritic field with post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer S3.
M5 retinal ganglion cell A monostratified retinal ganglion cell that has a small soma, an assymetric dendritic field with post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer S3.
M6 retinal ganglion cell A monostratified retinal ganglion cell that contains opsin.
M7 retinal ganglion cell A monostratified retinal ganglion cell with large soma and large dendritic field, with medium dendritic arbor, and has dendrites in layers 2 and 5.
M7-ON retinal ganglion cell An M7 retinal ganglion cells with synaptic terminals in S4 and is depolarized by illumination of its receptive field center.
M7-OFF retinal ganglion cell An M7 retinal ganglion cells with synaptic terminals in S2 and is depolarized by decreased illumination of their receptive field center
M8 retinal ganglion cell A monostratified retinal ganglion cell with large soma and medium dendritic field, with dense dendritic arbor.
M9 retinal ganglion cell A monostratified retinal ganglion cell with large soma and large dendritic field, with medium dendritic arbor, and has dendrites in layers 1 and 5.
M9-ON retinal ganglion cell An M9 retinal ganglion cells with synaptic terminals in S2 and is depolarized by illumination of its receptive field center.
M9-OFF retinal ganglion cell An M9 retinal ganglion cell with synaptic terminals in S4 that is depolarized by decreased illumination of their receptive field center
M10 retinal ganglion cell A monostratified retinal ganglion cell with large soma and large dendritic field, with dense dendritic arbor.
M11 retinal ganglion cell A bistratified ganglion cell with small, dense dendritic fields that terminate in S1 and S3.
M12 retinal ganglion cell A bistratified ganglion cell with larger, asymetric dendritic fields that terminate in S2 and S4.
M13 retinal ganglion cell A bistratifed retinal ganglion cell that has small, symmetric dendritic fields that terminate in S2 and S4.
M14 retinal ganglion cell A bistratifed retinal ganglion cell that has small, symmetric dendritic fields that terminate in S1 and S4-S5.

L cone cell also known as L cone; L-cone; long wavelength sensitive cone; long- (L) wavelength-sensitive cone; long-wavelength cone A cone cell that detects long wavelength light. Exact peak of spectra detected differs between species. In humans, spectra peaks at 564-580 nm.

M cone cell also known as M cone; M-cone; middle wavelength sensitive cone; middle- (M) wavelength-sensitive cone; middle-wavelength-sensitive (M) cone A cone cell that detects medium wavelength light. Exact peak of spectra detected differs between species. In humans, spectra peaks at 534-545 nm.

S cone cell also known as S cone; S-(short-wavelength sensitive) cone; S-cone; S-cone photoreceptor; short wavelength sensitive cone; short- (S) wavelength-sensitive cone; short-wavelength sensitive cone; short-wavelength-sensitive (S) cone A cone cell that detects short wavelength light. Exact peak of spectra detected differs between species. In humans, spectra peaks at 420-440 nm.
UV cone cell A cone cell that detects ultraviolet (UV) wavelength light.
local interneuron An interneuron whose axon stays entirely within the gray matter region where the cell body resides.
retinal ganglion cell B A monostratified retinal ganglion cell with small to medium soma and small to medium dendritic field.
retinal ganglion cell C A retinal ganglion with cell medium cell bodies and medium to large dendritic fields.
retinal ganglion cell A also known as alpha cell A monostratified retinal ganglion cell with large soma and large dendritic field.

retinal ganglion cell B1 also known as retinal ganglion cell B4 A retinal ganglion cell B that has medium body size, medium dendritic field and dense dendritic arbor, and has post synaptic terminals in S2.

retinal ganglion cell A1 also known as inner alpha retinal ganglion cell A retinal ganglion A cell found in the retina with large somata, often polygonal in shape. The dendritic fields consist of three to seven stout dendrites that are sparce near soma. Dendrites terminate in S4.
retinal ganglion cell B2 A retinal ganglion cell B that has a very small but very dense dendritic field, and has post synaptic terminals in S2.
retinal ganglion cell C1 A retinal ganglion cell C inner that has medium dendritic diversity.
retinal ganglion cell C2 inner A retinal ganglion cell C inner that has dense dendritic diversity.
retinal ganglion cell C2 outer A retinal ganglion cell C outer that has symmetrical and dense dendritic dendritic tree with a large dendritic field.
retinal ganglion cell A2 inner A retinal ganglion A2 cell with dendrites terminating in S4.
retinal ganglion cell A2 also known as outer alpha retinal ganglion cell A retinal ganglion A cell with dense arbor near soma.
retinal ganglion cell A2 outer A retinal ganglion A2 cell with dendrites terminating in S2.
510 nm-cone A cone whose sensitivity measurements have an average spectral peak of 510 nm. These cones are described in rat.
360 nm-cone A cone whose sensitivity measurements have an average spectral peak of 358.2 nm. These cones are described in rat.
retinal ganglion cell B3 A monostratified retinal ganglion cell with medium soma, sparse dendritic tree, and medium dendritic field.
type 3a cone bipolar cell A type of type 3 cone bipolar cell with distinctive curly dendrites.
type 3b cone bipolar cell A type of type 3 cone bipolar cell with distinctive crescent-shaped dendrites.
type 5a cone bipolar cell A type 5 cone bipolar cell with narrowly stratified post synaptic terminals.
type 5b cone bipolar cell A type 5 cone bipolar cell with diffuse axonal branches.
H1 horizontal cell also known as A Horizontal Cell A horizontal cell with a large cell body, thick dendrites, and a large dendritic arbor.
H2 horizontal cell also known as B Horizontal Cell A horizontal cell with a small cell body, thin dendrites, and small dendritic arbor.

A2 amacrine cell A bistratifed retinal amacrine cell with a small dendritic field, dendrite stratification in S1-S2, and a second dendrite stratification in S5. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter glycine.
flag amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a small, asymteric dendritic field.
flag A amacrine cell A flag amacrine cell with post-synaptic terminals in S2 and S3. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter glycine.
flag B amacrine cell A flag amacrine cell with post-synaptic terminals in S3, S4, and S5. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter glycine.

AB diffuse-1 amacrine cell A amacrine cell with a small dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S1, S2, S3, and S4. AB diffuse-1 amacrine cells have a tent-shaped dendritic arbor and undulate dendrites.
AB diffuse-2 amacrine cell A broadly stratifying amacrine cell that has a small dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S2 and S3. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter glycine.
spider amacrine cell A broadly stratifying amacrine cell with a small dendritic field, straight dendrites and post-synaptic terminals in S1, S2, and S3.
monostratified amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a small dendritic field with post-synaptic terminals in S3 and S4.

flat bistratified amacrine cell A bistratified amacrine cell with a small dendritic field. Flat bistratified amacrine cells have post-synaptic terminals both on the border of S1 and S2, and on the border of S3 and S4. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter glycine.
broad diffuse amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a small dendritic field that has post-synaptic terminals in S1, S2, S3, and S4.
A2-like amacrine cell A bistratified amacrine cell with a small dendritic field that has dendrite stratification in S2, and in S3 and S4.

diffuse bistratified amacrine cell A bistratified amacrine cell with a small dendritic field that has post-synaptic terminals in S1 and the border of S1-S2, and termination of a second arbor within the border of S2-S3 and S3.

recurving diffuse amacrine cell A broadly stratifying amacrine cell with a small dendritic field and a complex dendritic arbor. Recurving diffuse amacrine cells have post-synaptic terminals in S2, S3, and S4.

starburst amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a flat dendritic arbor and a medium dendritic field. Starburst amacrine cells have post-synaptic terminals in S2. This cell type releases the neurotransmitters gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) and acetylcholine.

DAPI-3 amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals that stratify at S2, with a second stratification that occurs in S3 and S4. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter glycine.
diffuse multistratified amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S2, and in S3-S4.
AB broad diffuse-1 amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S2 and S3. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA).

AB broad diffuse-2 amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S2, S3, and S4. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA).

fountain amacrine cell A retinal amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S1, S2, S3, and S4. This cell type releases the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA).

asymmetric bistratified amacrine cell A bistratified amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field, a flat and sparse dendritic arbor, and post-synaptic terminals at the intersections of S1 and S2, and S3 and S4.
wavy bistratified amacrine cell A bistratified amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S1-S2, and S4.
WF1 amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a wide dendritic field, dendrites in S1, and post-synaptic terminals in S1.
WF2 amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a wide dendritic field, dendrites in S2, and post-synaptic terminals in S1.
WF3-1 amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a wide dendritic field, dendrites in S3, and post-synaptic terminals in S3. Dendrites of this cell type are straight and minimally branched.

WF3-2 amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a wild dendritic field, dendrites in S3, and post-synaptic terminals in S3. Dendrites have spikes, cross over each other, and cover a larger volume than dendrties of W3-1 retinal amacrine cells.
WF4 amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a wide dendritic field, dendrites in S4, and post-synaptic terminals in S4.

indoleamine-accumulating amacrine cell An amacrine cell with a wide dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in S5. This cell type releases the neurotransmitters gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) and serotonin.
monostratified cell A central nervous system neuron that stratifies at one and only one location.
bistratified cell A neuron that stratifies dendrites at two and only two locations.
bistratified retinal amacrine cell An amicrine that stratifies dendrites at two and only two locations.
narrow field retinal amacrine cell An amicrine that has a narrow dendritic field.
medium field retinal amacrine cell An amicrine that has a medium dendritic field.
wide field retinal amacrine cell An amicrine that has a wide dendritic field.
spinal cord interneuron A CNS interneuron located in the spinal cord.
iridoblast A non-terminally differentiated cell that originates from the neural crest and differentiates into an iridophore.
xanthoblast A non-terminally differentiated cell that differentiates into a xanthophore.
leucoblast A non-terminally differentiated cell that originates from the neural crest and differentiates into a leucophore.
pigment erythroblast A non-terminally differentiated cell that originates from the neural crest and differentiates into an erythrophore.
cyanoblast A non-terminally differentiated cell that originates from the neural crest and differentiates into a cyanophore.

ionocyte Specialized epithelial cells involved in the maintenance of osmotic homeostasis. They are characterized by abundant mitochondria and ion transporters. In amniotes, they are present in the renal system. In freshwater fish, ionocytes in the skin and gills help maintain osmotic homeostasis by absorbing salt from the external environment.

Kolmer-Agduhr neuron also known as KA cell; KA interneuron; KA neuron; Kolmer-Agduhr cell Kolmer-Agduhr neurons are ciliated GABAergic neurons that contact the central canal of the spinal cord and have ipsilateral ascending axons.
macular hair cell An auditory hair cell located in the macula that is sensitive to auditory stimuli.

renal principal cell A cuboidal epithelial cell of the kidney which regulates sodium and potassium balance. The activity of sodium and potassium channels on the apical membrane of the cell is regulated by aldosterone and vasopressin. In mammals this cell type is located in the renal collecting duct system.
renal intercalated cell also known as intercalated cell A cuboidal epithelial cell of the kidney that regulates acid/base balance.
renal alpha-intercalated cell also known as type A intercalated cell; type A-IC A cuboidal epithelial cell of the kidney which secretes acid and reabsorbs base to regulate acid/base balance.

multi-ciliated epithelial cell also known as multiciliated epithelial cell A columnar/cuboidal epithelial cell with multiple motile cilia on its apical surface. These cells facilitate the movement of liquids such as mucus or cerebrospinal fluid across the epithelial surface.
single ciliated epithelial cell A ciliated epithelial cell with a single cilium.

auditory epithelial supporting cell also known as auditory epithelial support cell A non-sensory cell that extends from the basement membrane to the apical surface of the auditory epithelium and provides support for auditory hair cells.
inner phalangeal cell An auditory epithelial support cell that surrounds the nerve fibers and synapses of the auditory inner hair cells.
ghrelin secreting cell A cell that secretes ghrelin, the peptide hormone that stimulates hunger.
pancreatic epsilon cell also known as pancreatic E cell Ghrelin secreting cells found in the endocrine pancreas.
lymphangioblast Lymphatic progenitor cells.
mesenchymal lymphangioblast Mesenchymal derived lymphatic progenitor cells that give rise to the superficial lymphatics.
vascular lymphangioblast Lymphatic progenitor cells, derived from the veins, that give rise to lymphatic endothelial cells.
branchiomotor neuron also known as branchi motor neuron; special visceral motor neuron Cranial motor neuron which innervates muscles derived from the branchial (pharyngeal) arches.
somatomotor neuron also known as somatic motor neuron A motor neuron that innervates a skeletal muscle. These motor neurons are all excitatory and cholinergic.

visceromotor neuron also known as general visceral motor neuron A motor neuron that synapses to parasympathetic neurons that innervate tear glands, sweat glands, and the smooth muscles and glands of the pulmonary, cardiovascular, and gastrointestinal systems.

hepatoblast Multi fate stem cell that gives rise to both hepatocytes and cholangiocytes as descendants. The term often refers to fetal precursors of hepatocytes (differently from 'hepatic stem cell', usually applied to the self-renewing pool of hepatocyte precursors in the adult liver). Hepatoblasts may also be endogenous, as some stem cells found in the liver come from the bone marrow via blood circulation.

preameloblast Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to develop into an ameloblast. Located in the inner enamel epithelium, these cells elongate, their nuclei shift distally (away from the dental papilla), and their cytoplasm becomes filled with organelles needed for synthesis and secretion of enamel proteins.

skeletogenic cell also known as scleroblast Cell that has the potential to form a skeletal cell type (e.g. cells in periosteum, cells in marrow) and produce extracellular matrix (often mineralized) and skeletal tissue (often mineralized).
precementoblast Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to develop into a cementoblast.
preodontoblast Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to form an odontoblast, deposits predentine, and arises from a cranial neural crest cell.

premigratory neural crest cell Cell that is part of the neural crest region of the neuroepithelium, prior to migration. Note that not all premigratory neural crest cells may become migratory neural crest cells.
notochordal cell Cell that is part of the notochord.
chordamesodermal cell also known as axial mesodermal cell Mesodermal cell that is axially located and gives rise to the cells of the notochord.
notochordal sheath cell Notochordal cell that is part of the outer epithelium of the notochord and surrounds the vacuolated notochord cells.
notochordal vacuole cell also known as chordablast; chordoblast Notochordal cell that is inner portion of the notochord and becomes vacuolated as development proceeds.
prechondroblast Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to develop into a chondroblast; and arises from neural crest, meseosdermal and notochordal and connective tissue cells.
preosteoblast also known as osteoprogenitor cell Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to transform into an osteoblast, and develops from neural crest or mesodermal cells.
enteric neuron Neuron that is part of the enteric nervous system.
non-terminally differentiated odontoblast Odontoblast that non-terminally differentiated, located in the odontogenic papilla and dentine tissue, and transforms from a odontoblast cell.
terminally differentiated odontoblast Odontoblast that is terminally differentiated and derived from an odontogenic papilla and associated with dentine.
adaxial cell Muscle precursor cell that is adjacent to the notochord and part of the presomitic mesoderm.
Stiftchenzellen An epidermal cell with apical microvilli or a single apical projection have synaptic associations with nerve fibres in the epidermis.
epidermal ciliary cell Ciliated cell of the embryonic epidermis and functions in embryonic movements.
epidermal mucus secreting cell epidermal mucus secreting cell_1
bottle cell Characteristic early embryonic cell with a bottle or flask shape that is first to migrate inwards at the blastopore during gastrulation in amphibians.

alarm substance cell also known as alarm substance secreting cell; club cell (zebrafish) Secretory cell that produces a chemical mixture that triggers antipredator behavior. The substance is released only upon disruption of the epidermis. [Behavior of teleost fishes, second edition, edited by Pitcher, 1992]

micropylar cell also known as plug cell A specialized pore forming cell of the follicle, located adjacent to the animal pole of the oocyte. The micropylar cell makes the single micropyle (pore) through the chorion through which the sperm fertilizes the egg.
flask cell Epidermal cell rich in mitochondria. In amphibians, appears during metamorphosis.
non-striated muscle cell Any muscle cell in which the fibers are not organised into sarcomeres.
hematopoietic precursor cell Any hematopoietic cell that is a precursor of some other hematopoietic cell type.
skeletal muscle fiber A transversely striated, synctial cell of skeletal muscle. It is formed when proliferating myoblasts exit the cell cycle, differentiate and fuse.
somatic muscle myotube A myotube that is part of some somatic muscle. Examples include arthropod somatic muscle cells.
somatic muscle cell A muscle cell that is part of some somatic muscle.
obliquely striated somatic muscle cell A somatic muscle cell that is obliquely striated and mononucleated. Examples include the somatic muscles of nematodes.

muscle founder cell A myoblast that detemines the properties (size, shape and attachment to the epidermis) of a `somatic muscle myotube` (CL:0008003) . It develops into a somatic muscle myotube via fusion with `fusion component myoblasts` (CL:0000621).
visceral muscle cell A muscle cell that is part of some visceral muscle.
striated visceral muscle cell A visceral muscle cell that is striated. Examples include the visceral muscle cells of arhtropods.
transversely striated visceral muscle cell A visceral muscle that is transversely striated. Examples include the visceral muscle cells of arthropods.
cranial somatomotor neuron A cranial motor neuron whose soma is located in the midbrain andor hindbrain and which innervates the skeletal muscles of the eye or tongue.

skeletal muscle satellite stem cell A skeletal muscle satellite cell that divides by stem cell division. A proportion of this population undergoes symmetric stem cell division, producing two skeletal muscle satellite stem cells. The rest undergo asymmetric stem cell division - retaining their identity while budding off a daughter cell that differentiates into an adult skeletal muscle myoblast.

quiescent skeletal muscle satellite cell A skeletal muscle satellite cell that is mitotically quiescent. These cells are wedge shaped and have a large nuclear to cytoplasmic ratio with few organelles, a small nucleus and condensed interphase chromatin. Satellite cells typically remain in this state until activated following muscle damage.

cranial visceromotor neuron A visceromotor motor neuron whose soma is located in the hindbrain, and which synapses to parasympathetic neurons that innervate tear glands, sweat glands, and the smooth muscles of the head.
inhibitory motor neuron A motor neuron that is capable of directly inhibiting muscle contraction.
activated skeletal muscle satellite cell A skeletal muscle satellite cell that has become mitotically active - typically following muscle damage.

adult skeletal muscle myoblast A skeletal muscle myoblast that is part of a skeletal mucle. These cells are formed following acivation and division of skeletal muscle satellite cells. They form a transient population that is lost when they fuse to form skeletal muscle fibers.
somatic muscle myoblast A myoblast that is commited to developing into a somatic muscle.

mesenchymal cell also known as mesenchyme cell A non-polarised cell precursor cell that is part of some mesenchyme, is associated with the cell matrix but is not connected to other cells and is capable of migration.
skeletal muscle satellite myogenic cell A skeletal muscle satellite cell that undergoes symmetric division to produce two adult skeleltal muscle myoblasts.
anterior lateral line ganglion neuron Any neuron that has its soma located in some anterior lateral line ganglion.

endocardial cushion cell A mesenchymal cell of the endocardial cushion. These cells develop via an epithelial to mesenchymal transition when endocardial cells break cell-to-cell contacts and migrate into the cardiac jelly. Cells from this population form the heart septa and valves.
pancreatic endocrine cell An endocrine cell that is part of the pancreas.
noradrenergic neuron A neuron that release noradrenaline (noriphinephrine) as a neurotransmitter.
open tracheal system tracheocyte An epithelial cell that is part of the epithelium of a tracheal tube in an open tracheal system, such as that found in insects.

rod bipolar cell (sensu Mus) A bipolar neuron found in the retina that is synapsed by rod photoreceptor cells. These neurons have axons that arborize and synapse to targets in inner plexiform layers 4 and 5 and depolarize in response to light.
visual system neuron Any neuron that is capable of part of some visual perception.
cortical interneuron also known as cerebral cortex interneuron An interneuron that has its soma located in the cerebral cortex.
rosehip neuron A GABAergic interneuron in human cortical layer 1 that has large rosehip-shaped axonal boutons and compact arborization.
decidual pericyte also known as decidual perivascular cell A pericyte of the decidual vasculature.
mural cell Mural cells are pericytes and the vascular smooth muscle cells (vSMCs) of the microcirculation.
microcirculation associated smooth muscle cell Any vascular associated smooth muscle cell that is part of some microcirculatory vessel.
extravillous trophoblast also known as EVT; extravillous cytotrophloblast A trophoblast cell that is not part of a placental villous.

gamma motor neuron also known as fusimotor neuron A lower motor neuron that innervates only intrafusal muscle fibers. Unlike the alpha motor neurons, gamma motor neurons do not directly adjust the lengthening or shortening of muscles but function in adjusting the sensitivity of muscle spindles and in keeping muscle spindles taut, thereby allowing the continued firing of alpha neurons.

alpha motor neuron also known as alpha motoneuron A large, multipolar lower motor neuron of the brainstem and spinal cord that innervates the extrafusal muscle fibers of skeletal muscle and are directly responsible for initiating their contraction. While their cell bodies are in the CNS (in the anterior gray horn of the spinal cord), they are part of the somatic nervous system - a branch of the PNS.
lower motor neuron The motor neurons of vertebrates that directly innervate skeletal muscles. They receive input from upper motor neurons.
squamous endothelial cell of venule An endothelial cell of the venule that is squamous shaped. This is in contrast to the cubodial shape of high endothelial venule cells.

extrafusal muscle fiber also known as myofibra extrafusalis A skeletal muscle fiber that is innervated by alpha motor neuron and generates tension by contracting, thereby allowing for skeletal movement. These fibers make up the large mass of skeletal muscle tissue and are attached to bones by tendons.

intrafusal muscle fiber also known as myofibra intrafusalis A skeletal muscle fiber that is part of a muscle spindle. These are specialized muscle fibers that serve as proprioceptors, detecting the amount and rate of change in length of a muscle. They are innervated by both sensory neurons and motor neurons (gamma and beta motorneurons, collectively referred to as fusimotor neurons).

upper motor neuron A glutamatergic motor neuron with a soma in the brainstem or cerebral cortex. They do not synapse directly to muscles but rather to lower motor neurons, which do. They are the main controllers of voluntary movement.

Betz cell also known as pyramidal cell of Betz A giant pyramidal neuron with a soma in layer Vb of the primary motor cortex that sends its axons down the spinal cord via the corticospinal tract, either synapsing directly with alpha motor neurons, or targeting interneurons in the spinal cord. In humans, Betz cells are the largest known in the central nervous system.

sensory neuron of spinal nerve also known as spinal sensory neuron A sensory neuron of the spinal nerve that senses body position and sends information about how much the muscle is stretched to the spinal cord.
compound eye retinal cell Any cell in the compound eye, a light sensing organ composed of ommatidia.
inflammatory cell Any cell participating in the inflammatory response to a foreign substance, e.g. neutrophil, macrophage.
larval midgut cell Any cell in the midgut (middle subdivision of a digestive tract) of an insect larva.
retinal cell Any cell in the retina, the innermost layer or coating at the back of the eyeball, which is sensitive to light and in which the optic nerve terminates.
salivary gland cell Any cell in a salivary gland.
