enteroendocrine cell of small intestine also known as small intestine enteroendocrine cell An enteroendocrine cell that is located in the small intestine.

gastrointestinal tract (lamina propria) macrophage of small intestine also known as small intestine lamina propria resident macrophage A macrophage which is resident in the lamina propria of the small intestine.

gastrointestinal tract (lamina propria) macrophage of large intestine also known as large intestine lamina propria resident macrophage A macrophage which is resident in the lamina propria of the large intestine.
paneth cell of colon also known as paneth cell of epithelium of colon; paneth-like cell A paneth cell that is located in the epithelium of the colon.

transit amplifying cell also known as transient amplifying cell; transit amplifying progenitor cell; transit-amplifying cell Transit-amplifying cells (TACs) are an undifferentiated population in transition between stem cells and differentiated cells.

transit amplifying cell of colon also known as colon transit amplifying cell; transient amplifying cell of colon; transient amplifying cell of crypt of Lieberkuhn of colon; transit amplifying cell of crypt of Lieberkuhn of colon; transit-amplifying cell of colon A rapidly proliferating population of cells that differentiate from stem cells of the intestinal crypt of the colon. Stem cells located in the crypts of Lieberkhn give rise to proliferating progenitor or transit amplifying cells that differentiate into the four major epithelial cell types. These include columnar absorptive cells or enterocytes, mucous secreting goblet cells, enteroendocrine cells and paneth cells.

transit amplifying cell of small intestine also known as small intestine transit amplifying cell; transient amplifying cell of crypt of Lieberkuhn of small intestine; transient amplifying cell of small intestine; transit amplifying cell of crypt of Lieberkuhn of small intestine; transit-amplifying cell of small intestine A rapidly proliferating population of cells that differentiate from stem cells of the intestinal crypt of the small intestine. Stem cells located in the crypts of Lieberkhn give rise to proliferating progenitor or transit amplifying cells that differentiate into the four major epithelial cell types. These include columnar absorptive cells or enterocytes, mucous secreting goblet cells, enteroendocrine cells and paneth cells.

fetal hepatobiliary progenitor cell also known as fetal hepatobiliary hybrid progenitor cell; HHyP cell A progenitor cell with hepatic and biliary lineage potential, identified in mouse and human, and anatomically restricted to the ductal plate of fetal liver.

Peyer's patch lymphocyte also known as Peyer's patch resident lymphocyte A lymphocyte that is part of a Peyer's patch. These cells have a major role in driving the immune response to antigens sampled from the intestinal lumen, and in regulating the formation of follicle-associated epithelium and M cells in Peyer's patches by converting intestitial enterocytes into M cells.
Peyer's patch follicular dendritic cell A follicular dendritic cell located in the Peyer's patch. These cells from a meshwork in which Peyer's patch B cells reside.

intestinal crypt stem cell of large intestine also known as stem cell of large intestine crypt of Lieberkuhn An intestinal stem cell that is located in the large intestine crypt of Liberkuhn. These stem cells reside at the bottom of crypts in the large intestine and are highly proliferative. They either differentiate into transit amplifying cells or self-renew to form new stem cells.

intestinal crypt stem cell of small intestine also known as stem cell of small intestine crypt of Lieberkuhn An intestinal stem cell that is located in the small intestine crypt of Liberkuhn. These stem cells reside at the bottom of crypts in the small intestine and are highly proliferative. They either differentiate into transit amplifying cells or self-renew to form new stem cells.
lymphocyte of large intestine lamina propria also known as lamina propria lymphocyte of large intestine A lymphocyte that resides in the lamina propria of the large intestine.
nephrogenic zone cell also known as cortical nephrogenic niche cell; cortical nephrogenic zone cell A kidney cortical cell that is part of the nephrogenic zone.
tuft cell of appendix also known as appendix tuft cell; tuft cell of appendix vermiformis; tuft cell of vermiform appendix An intestinal tuft cell that is a part of a vermiform appendix.
stromal cell of lamina propria of large intestine A stromal cell found in the lamina propria of the large intestine.
stromal cell of lamina propria of small intestine A stromal cell found in the lamina propria of the small intestine.

small intestine Peyer's patch T cell also known as T cell of Peyer's patch of small intestine; T cell of small intestine Peyer's patch A T cell which resides in the Peyer's patch of the small intestine.
mesothelial cell of small intestine A mesothelial cell that is part of the small intestine.
mesothelial cell of colon A mesothelial cell that is part of the colon.
enterocyte of appendix also known as appendix enterocyte; enterocyte of appendix vermiformis; enterocyte of vermiform appendix An enterocyte that is a part of a vermiform appendix.

transit amplifying cell of appendix also known as appendix transit amplifying cell; transit amplifying cell of appendix vermiformis; transit amplifying cell of vermiform appendix A transit amplifying cell that is part of a crypt of Lieberkuhn of large intestine.

intestinal crypt stem cell of appendix also known as appendix intestinal crypt stem cell; intestinal crypt stem cell of appendix vermiformis; intestinal crypt stem cell of vermiform appendix; stem cell of intestinal crypt of Lieberkuhn of appendix; stem cell of intestinal crypt of Lieberkuhn of appendix vermiformis An intestinal crypt stem cell that is located in the vermiform appendix. These stem cells reside at the bottom of crypts in the appendix and are highly proliferative. They either differentiate into transit amplifying cells or self-renew to form new stem cells.

mesothelial cell of appendix also known as appendix mesothelial cell; mesothelial cell of appendix vermiformis; mesothelial cell of vermiform appendix A mesothelial cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.

enteroendocrine cell of appendix also known as appendix enteroendocrine cell; enteroendocrine cell of appendix vermiformis; enteroendocrine cell of vermiform appendix An intestinal enteroendocrine cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.
T cell of appendix also known as appendix T cell; T cell of appendix vermiformis; T cell of vermiform appendix A T cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.
B cell of appendix also known as appendix B cell; B cell of appendix vermiformis; B cell of vermiform appendix A B cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.
plasma cell of appendix also known as appendix plasma cell; plasma cell of appendix vermiformis; plasma cell of vermiform appendix A plasma cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.

dendritic cell of appendix also known as appendix dendritic cell; dendritic cell of appendix vermiformis; dendritic cell of vermiform appendix A dendritic cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.

stromal cell of lamina propria of vermiform appendix also known as stromal cell of appendix lamina propria; stromal cell of lamina propria of appendix vermiformis A stromal cell found in the lamina propria of the vermiform appendix.
appendix macrophage also known as macrophage of appendix; macrophage of appendix vermiformis; macrophage of vermiform appendix A macrophage located in the vermiform appendix.

lymph node mantle zone B cell also known as mantle zone B cell of lymph node A B lymphocyte that resides in the mantle zone of the lymph node germinal center. These are generally IgM and IgD positive activated B cells that form a 'corona' around the germinal center and are part of the establishment of a secondary lymphatic follicule.
colon macrophage also known as macrophage of colon A macrophage that is located in the colon.
colon goblet cell also known as goblet cell of colon A goblet cell that is located in the colon.
stromal cell of lamina propria of colon also known as stromal cell of colon lamina propria A stromal cell found in the lamina propria of the colon.
tuft cell of colon also known as colon tuft cell A tuft cell that is a part of the colon.
enteroendocrine cell of colon also known as colon enteroendocrine cell An enteroendocrine cell that is located in the colon.
intestinal crypt stem cell of colon An intestinal crypt stem cell that is located in the colon.

lymphocyte of small intestine lamina propria also known as gastrointestinal tract (lamina propria) lymphocyte of small intestine; lamina propria lymphocyte of small intestine; small intestine lamina propria lymphocyte A lymphocyte that resides in the lamina propria of the small intestine. Lamina propria leukocytes and intraepithelial lymphocytes are the effector compartments of the gut mucosal immune system. Lymphocytes circulate through gut associated lymphoid tissues until recruitment by intestinal antigens. They are involved in the gut immune response.
B cell of medullary sinus of lymph node A B cell found in the lymph node medullary sinus.
T cell of medullary sinus of lymph node A T cell found in the lymph node medullary sinus.
macrophage of medullary sinus of lymph node also known as lymph node medullary sinus macrophage A macrophage found in the medullary sinus of the lymph node.
anorectum macrophage also known as macrophage of anorectum A macrophage that is located in the anorectum.

smooth muscle cell of high endothelial venule of lymph node also known as high endothelial venule of lymph node smooth muscle cell A layer of smooth muscle cells that forms the outer layer of the high endothelial venule of lymph node and pumps to allow flow of lymph fluid carrying lymphocytes.
B cell of anorectum A B cell that is located in the anorectum.
T cell of anorectum A T cell that is located in the anorectum.
smooth muscle cell of anorectum also known as anorectum smooth muscle cell A smooth muscle cell that is located in the anorectum.
stromal cell of anorectum lamina propria A stromal cell found in the lamina propria of the anorectum.
microfold cell of epithelium proper of anorectum also known as M cell of anorectum A microfold cell (M cell) that is part of the anorectum.
paneth cell of anorectum also known as anorectum paneth cell A paneth cell that is located in the anorectum.
transit amplifying cell of anorectum also known as anorectum transit amplifying cell A transit amplifying cell that is located in the anorectum.
anorectum goblet cell also known as goblet cell of anorectum A goblet cell that is located in the anorectum.
enterocyte of anorectum also known as anorectum enterocyte An enterocyte that is located in the anorectum.
plasma cell of medullary sinus of lymph node A plasma cell that is located in the medullary sinus of the lymph node.
marginal zone B cell of lymph node also known as lymph node marginal zone B cell A mature B cell located in the marginal zone of the lymph node.
intestinal crypt stem cell of anorectum also known as anorectum intestinal crypt stem cell An intestinal crypt stem cell that is located in the anorectum.

germinal center T cell also known as lymph node germinal center T follicular helper cell; T follicular helper cell of germinal center of lymph node; T follicular helper cell of lymph node germinal center A specialized type of CD4 positive T cell, the follicular helper T cell (TFH cell), that upregulates CXCR5 expression to enable its follicular localization. These specialised T cells reside in the germinal center of the lymph node.
enteroendocrine cell of anorectum also known as anorectum enteroendocrine cell An enteroendocrine cell that is located in the anorectum.

lymph node paracortex T cell also known as T cell of lymph node paracortex A T cell located in the lymph node paracortex, where macrophages and dendritic cells present antigenic peptides to these nave T cells, stimulating them to become activated helper T cells or cytotoxic T lymphocytes.
tuft cell of anorectum also known as anorectum tuft cell An intestinal tuft cell that is located in the anorectum.
stratified squamous epithelial cell of anal canal also known as anal canal stratified squamous epithelial cell A stratified squamous epithelial cell that is part of the anal canal.

vacuolated fetal-type enterocyte An enterocyte found in the small intestine of newborn mammals and characterized by the presence of an apical canalicular system (ACS) leading to production of large vacuoles, important for colostral macromolecule uptake. After birth, the vacuolated fetal-type enterocytes are replaced with enterocytes lacking an ACS.
CD8aa(I) thymocyte An unconventional T lymphocyte population within the thymic medulla that is potentially a thymic resident population.
CD8aa(II) thymocyte An unconventional T lymphocyte population within the thymic medulla that expresses both alpha/beta and gamma/delta T cell signatures.
corticomedullary thymic epithelial cell A thymic epithelial cell located at the corticomedullary junction.
medullary thymic epithelial cell type 1 A thymic medullary epithelial cell considered to be a pre-AIRE mTEC population.
medullary thymic epithelial cell type 2 A thymic medullary epithelial cell that expresses AIRE or other canonical markers of mature mTECs like Fezf2.

medullary thymic epithelial cell type 3 A thymic medullary epithelial cell considered to be a post-AIRE cell. This group of AIRE-mTECs is heterogeneous and also includes mTECs within Hassall's Corpuscles.

medullary thymic epithelial cell type 4 A thymic medullary epithelial cell that expresses typical tuft cell markers instead of classical mTEC or cTEC markers. This population has a bulbous-like structure.
myo-medullary thymic epithelial cell A thymic medullary epithelial cell that expresses muscle-specific biomarkers.
neuro-medullary thymic epithelial cell A thymic medullary epithelial cell that expresses neuroendocrine biomarkers.
subcapsular thymic epithelial cell A thymic epithelial cell located within the subcapsular region of the thymus.
thymic fibroblast type 1 also known as thymic capsular fibroblast A fibroblast located in the thymic capsule.
thymic fibroblast type 2 also known as thymic interlobular fibroblast A fibroblast located between thymic lobules.

tuft cell of small intestine also known as brush cell of epithelium of small intestine; brush cell of epithelium proper of small intestine; brush cell of small intestine; tuft cell of epithelium of small intestine A tuft cell located in the small intestine.
specified double negative thymocyte (Homo sapiens) The human equivalent of a DN2 thymocyte; typically contains two phases, in the latter of which these thymocytes begin the process of beta selection.
committed double negative thymocyte (Homo sapiens) The human equivalent of a DN3 thymocyte; these thymocytes finish the process of beta selection.
rearranging double negative thymocyte (Homo sapiens) The human equivalent of a DN4 thymocyte.
epithelial cell of endometrial gland also known as endometrial glandular epithelial cell An epithelial cell that is part of an endometrial gland.

colony forming unit  Hill cell also known as CFU-Hill An adult endothelial progenitor cell characterised in vivo by homing to ischemic sites and paracrine support of angiogenesis. They may form discrete colonies.
endothelial cell of respiratory system lymphatic vessel An endothelial cell that is part of a respiratory system lymphatic vessel.
fused extravillous trophoblast also known as fused EVT An extravillous trophoblast that is polynuclear.
circulating angiogenic cell An adult endothelial progenitor cell characterised in vivo by homing to ischemic sites and paracrine support of angiogenesis. These cells do not form colonies.
lung pericyte also known as lung pericyte cell; pulmonary pericyte A pericyte cell that is part of a lung.

endothelial colony forming cell also known as ECFC An adult endothelial progenitor cell that is resident of adult vasculature and capable of differentiating to regenerate endothelial cell populations. Endothelial colony forming cells are characterised in vivo by clonal proliferative status, de novo vessel formation, homing to ischemic sites and paracrine support of angiogenesis. These cells are phenotypically similar to endothelial cells.

Leydig stem cell also known as stem Leydig cell A stem cell found in the interstitial compartment of the neonatal testis; it is capable of self-renewal as well as differentiation into steroidogenic cells (adult Leydig cells). Intermediate stages of development include progenitor Leydig cells and immature Leydig cells.
endothelial cell of placenta also known as placental endothelial cell An endothelial cell that is part of a placenta.
smooth muscle cell of placenta also known as placental smooth muscle cell A smooth muscle cell that is part of a placenta.
endothelial cell of hepatic portal vein An endothelial cell that is part of a hepatic portal vein.
endothelial cell of uterus also known as uterine endothelial cell An endothelial cell that is part of a uterus.

esophagus non-keratinized squamous epithelial cell also known as esophageal non-keratinized squamous epithelial cell; esophageal nonkeratinized squamous epithelial cell; esophagus non-keratinizing squamous epithelial cell; esophagus nonkeratinizing squamous epithelial cell; non-keratinized squamous epithelial cell of esophagus; non-keratinizing squamous epithelial cell of esophagus; nonkeratinized squamous epithelial cell of esophagus; nonkeratinizing squamous epithelial cell of esophagus Any cell that is part of the esophageal non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium. In humans, the esophagus, which requires flexibility to accommodate swallowing of a bolus, is covered with a non-keratinized epithelium.

embryonic skeletal muscle fiber A skeletal muscle fiber found in an embryo. In mammalian embryos, skeletal muscle expresses myosin heavy chain-embryonic (MyHC-emb, encoded by the MYH3 gene), which regulates skeletal muscle development.

fetal and neonatal skeletal muscle fiber A skeletal muscle fiber found at the fetal and neonatal stages. In mammalian fetuses and neonates, skeletal muscle expresses myosin heavy chain-neonatal (MyHC-neo, encoded by the MYH8 gene). This expression disappears shortly after birth and is replaced by expression of adult heavy chain myosins.

fibro/adipogenic progenitor cell also known as fibro/adipogenic progenitor A progenitor cell that is a tissue-resident mesenchymal cell, important for skeletal muscle regeneration, and able to differentiate into both adipocytes or fibroblasts.

hepatic portal fibroblast A fibroblast located in the portal triad. Hepatic portal fibroblast are a non-parenchymal cell population located adjacent to bile duct epithelia in liver and are distinct from stellate cells. They differentiate into fibrogenic myofibroblasts during chronic injury states producing high levels of collagen.
fibroblastic reticular cell A reticular cell involved in directing B cells and T cells to specific regions within a tissue.

lymph node fibroblastic reticular cell A specialized, fibroblastic reticular cell of mesenchymal origin found in lymph nodes. In human, it expresses several markers common to myofibroblasts (desmin, vimentin, CD73, CD90, -smooth muscle actin (SMA)), and can be differentiated from endothelial cells by its lack of CD31 expression. These cells are critical for the overall organization and function of the lymph node. Lymph node fibroblastic reticular cells (FRCs) can be further classified based on their location, function, and unique marker expression.
lymph node marginal reticular cell A fibroblastic reticular cell found in the lymph node subcapsular sinus.

B cell zone reticular cell also known as lymph node germinal center dark zone fibroblastic reticular cell A fibroblastic reticular cell found in the lymph node germinal center dark zone (B cell zone).
T cell zone reticular cell also known as lymph node T cell domain fibroblastic reticular cell A fibroblastic reticular cell found in the lymph node T cell domain.
medullary reticular cell also known as lymph node medullary reticular cell; medullary reticular cell of lymph node A specialized fibroblast found in the medulla of lymph node.

lymphatic endothelial cell of subcapsular sinus ceiling also known as lymphatic endothelial cell of subcapsular sinus ceiling of lymph node A lymphatic endothelial cell located in the subcapsular sinus ceiling of a lymph node. In human, it's characterized by a unique marker expression (NT5e+ and Caveolin-1+).

lymphatic endothelial cell of subcapsular sinus floor also known as lymphatic endothelial cell of subcapsular sinus floor of lymph node A lymphatic endothelial cell located in the subcapsular sinus floor of a lymph node. In human, it's characterized by a unique marker expression (TNFRSF9+).

lymphatic endothelial cell of trabecula also known as lymphatic endothelial cell of lymph node trabecula; lymphatic endothelial cell of trabeculae A lymphatic endothelial cell located in a lymph node trabecula.
lymphatic endothelial cell of medulla ceiling also known as lymphatic endothelial cell of lymph node medulla ceiling A lymphatic endothelial cell located in the ceiling part of a lymph node medulla.
centrocyte also known as lymph node centrocyte A germinal center B cell found in a lymph node germinal center light zone.
centroblast also known as lymph node centroblast A germinal center B cell found in a lymph node germinal center dark zone.
T follicular regulatory cell also known as follicular regulatory T cell A regulatory T cell present in the B cell follicles and germinal centers of lymphoid tissues. In humans, it is CXCR5+.

monocytoid B cell A B cell found in the perisinusoidal area of a lymph node. In humans, monocytoid B cells are a morphologically distinct B cell population (oval nuclei, abundant cytoplasm, monocyte-like appearance), share many similarities with marginal zone B cells including marker expression, and are increased in disease settings.
lymph node lymphatic vessel endothelial cell An endothelial cell located in a lymph node lymphatic vessel.

progenitor cell of mammary luminal epithelium also known as progenitor cell of luminal mammary epithelium A progenitor cell with the potential to differentiate into luminal epithelial cells of mammary glands. In mouse, CD61 and c-kit were found to be coexpressed by the majority of, but not all, committed luminal progenitor cells.

keratinized cell of hair follicle A hair follicle matrix region cell which synthesizes keratin and undergoes a characteristic change as it moves upward from the hair bulb to become the hair medulla cortex and hair root sheath.
stromal cell of bone marrow also known as bone marrow stromal cell A stromal cell that is part_of a bone marrow.
epithelial cell of umbilical artery also known as umbilical artery epithelial cell An epithelial cell that is part_of a umbilical artery.
mononuclear cell of bone marrow also known as bone marrow mononuclear cell A mononuclear cell that is part_of a bone marrow.
atrioventricular bundle cell also known as AV bundle cell A specialized cardiomyocyte that transmit signals from the AV node to the cardiac Purkinje fibers.
cardiac blood vessel endothelial cell Any blood vessel endothelial cell that is part of some heart.
His-Purkinje system cell Any cell that is part of some His-Purkinje system.
cardiac endothelial cell Any endothelial cell that is part of some heart.
camera-type eye photoreceptor cell also known as camera type eye photoreceptor cell Any photoreceptor cell that is part of some camera-type eye.
cerebellar stellate cell Any stellate neuron that has its soma located in some cerebellum.
cerebral cortex GABAergic interneuron A GABAergic interneuron whose soma is located in the cerebral cortex.
cerebral cortex neuron also known as cortical neuron; neuron of cerebral cortex A CNS neuron of the cerebral cortex.
type I pinealocyte also known as light pinealocyte type I pinealocyte_1
type II pinealocyte also known as dark pinealocyte type II pinealocyte_1
coronet cell A highly specialized cell type exclusive to and forming neuroepithelium of the Saccus vasculosus, covering the caudal diverticulum of the infundibular recess.

collar cell A cell with a flagellum surrounded by a collar of microvilli. The motion of the flagellum draws water past the microvilli, serving either a feeding or sensory function. Collar cells are found in multiple animals, including sponges, echinoderms, and cnidarians. They are also found outside animals in the choanoflagellates. Although collar cells are superficially similar, their cytoskeletal structure and functional biology are different in different groups of organisms.
zygote A zygote in a plant or an animal.
cardiac glial cell Any glial cell that is part of some heart.
cardiac myoblast Any myoblast that develops into some cardiac muscle cell.
cardiac neuron A neuron that has its soma in the heart.
dorsal horn interneuron A CNS interneuron located in the dorsal horn of the spinal cord.
spinal cord motor neuron A motor neuron that passes from the spinal cord toward or to a muscle and conducts an impulse that causes movement.
lateral motor column neuron A motor neuron that is generated only on limb levels and send axons into the limb mesenchyme.

magnocellular neurosecretory cell also known as magnocellular neuron A neurosecretory neuron residing mainly in the hypothalamic supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei and in a number of smaller accessory cell groups between these two nuclei, that is capable of secreting the hormones oxytocin or vasopressin, and sometimes both, into the systemic circulation.
lens fiber cell also known as lens fibre cell A vetebrate lens cell that is any of the elongated, tightly packed cells that make up the bulk of the mature lens in a camera-type eye.
GABAergic interneuron also known as GABAergic inhibitory interneuron An interneuron that uses GABA as a vesicular neurotransmitter. These interneurons are inhibitory
Lugaro cell An inhibitory GABAergic interneuron found in the cerebellar cortex.

paraxial cell also known as paraxial mesoderm cell; somitic mesoderm cell A cell in the area of mesoderm in the neurulating embryo that flanks and forms simultaneously with the neural tube. The cells of this region give rise to somites.
embryonic hemocyte A hemocyte derived from the embryonic head mesoderm, which enters the hemolymph as a circulating cell.
embryonic plasmatocyte A plasmatocyte derived from the embryonic head mesoderm.
lateral mesodermal cell A cell derived from the mesoderm that is found at the periphery of the embryo.
intermediate mesodermal cell A cell derived from the mesoderm that is located between the paraxial mesoderm and the lateral plate.

neural crest cell A cell of the neural crest. Neural crest cells are multipotent. Premigratory neural crest cells are found at the neural plate boarder, some of which will undergo ectomesynchymal transition and delamination to form migratory neural crest cells.
motile sperm cell A sperm cell that is cabaple of motion (motility).
non-motile sperm cell A sperm cell that is not cabaple of motion (motility).
amoeboid sperm cell A motile sperm cell that contain no F-actin, and their motility is powered by a dynamic filament system.
flagellated sperm cell A motile sperm cell that contains a slender threadlike microscopic appendage that enables motion.

vagal neural crest cell Cell that is part of the vagal neural crest population. The vagal neural crest arises from the axial level of somites 1-7 and has been described as a hybrid between the head and the trunk populations.

lymphoid tissueinducer cell also known as LTi; lymphoid tissue inducer cell A group 3 innate lymphoid cell that express ROR gamma t and IL-7R alpha in the absence of lineage markers (e.g. CD3, CD19, B220, CD11c, Gr-1), with the functional ability to interact with mesenchymal cells through lymphotoxin and tumor necrosis factor. Lymphoid tissue-inducer cells are key to the development of lymph nodes and Peyers patches.
mesothelial cell of epicardium A mesothelial cell that is part of the epicardium.
neural progenitor cell An undifferentiated cell that originates from a neural stem cell and has the capacity to generate multiple types of lineage-restricted progenitors but not to self-renew.
fibroblast of upper back skin A fibroblast that is part of upper back skin.
fibroblast of skin of back A fibroblast that is part of skin of back.
CD25+ mast cell also known as CD25+ neoplastic mast cell A mast cell that is CD25+.

double negative T regulatory cell also known as CD4-negative, CD8-negative, alpha-beta regulatory T cells; DN Treg; double-negative alpha-beta regulatory T cell A double negative thymocyte that is CD3-positive, CD4-negative, CD8-negative_1, that that are present in the periphery in very low numbers and predominantly produce INF-gamma, TNF-alpha, and a low amount of TGF-beta, but not IL-2, IL-4, IL-10 or IL-13 upon activation.

exhausted T cell also known as Tex cell An effector T cell that displays impaired effector functions (e.g., rapid production of effector cytokines, cytotoxicity) and has limited proliferative potential.

progenitor cell A precursor cell that has a tendency to differentiate into a specific type of cell. They are descendants of stem cells, only they are more constrained in their differentiation potential or capacity for self-renewal, and are often more limited in both senses.
skeletal muscle fibroblast also known as skeleton muscle fibroblast Any fibroblast that is part of skeletal muscle tissue.

olfactory ensheathing cell also known as OEC A neural-crest derived glial cell that supports the growth and survival of primary olfactory neuroons from the neuroepithelium in the nasal cavity to the brain by encasing large bundles of numerous unmyelinated axons.

cnidocyte also known as cnidoblast; nematocyte An explosive cell containing one giant secretory organelle called a cnidocyst (also known as a cnida (plural cnidae) or nematocyst) that contains a toxin responsible for the stings delivered by a cnidarian to other organisms. Cnidae are used to capture prey and as a defense against predators. The presence of cnidocytes defines the phylum Cnidaria (corals, sea anemones, hydrae, jellyfish, etc.).
dermal microvascular endothelial cell also known as dermal microvascular endothelium cell; DMEC cell Any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of the dermis.
monocyte-derived dendritic cell also known as MDDC cell A dendritic cell that develops from a monocyte.

lysosome-rich enterocyte also known as LRE An enterocyte that possesses a large supranuclear vacuolar system that preferentially internalizes dietary protein via receptor-mediated and fluid-phase endocytosis for intracellular digestion and trans-cellular transport. In zebrafish these cells are located in the posterior region of the mid intestine throughout life. In mammals they are found in the ileum pre-weaning and later are replaced by mature enterocytes.
galanergic neuron Neuron that secretes the neurotransmitter galanin.

chorionic trophoblast cell Cells of the uterine chorion that acquire specialized structural and/or functional features that characterize chorionic trophoblasts. These cells will migrate towards the spongiotrophoblast layer and give rise to syncytiotrophoblasts of the labyrinthine layer.

parasympathetic neuron Parasympathetic neurons are part of the parasympathetic nervous sysem and the cell bodies lie in the brain and sacral region of the spinal cord. The neurons are mainly cholinergic.
sympathetic neuron Sympathetic neurons are part of the sympathetic nervous system and are primarily adrenergic producing the neurotransmitter noradrenalin along with other neuropeptides.
interplexiform cell A type of interneuron in the retinal inner nuclear layer which carries information from the inner plexiform layer and the outer plexiform layer.
dopamanergic interplexiform cell A type of interneuron in the retinal inner nuclear layer which carries information from the inner plexiform layer and the outer plexiform layer, using dopamine.
GABAnergic interplexiform cell A type of interneuron in the retinal inner nuclear layer which carries information from the inner plexiform layer and the outer plexiform layer using GABA.
colon epithelial cell also known as colonic epithelial cell Epithelial cell that is part of the colon epithelium.
hypocretin-secreting neuron also known as orexin A neuron that releases hypocretin as a neurotransmitter.
histaminergic neuron Neuron that secretes histamine.

gonadotropin-releasing hormone neuron also known as GnRH neuron; GnRH-secreting neuron A neuroendocrine cell that secretes gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH). A GnRH neuron is born in the nasal placode during embryonic development and migrates through the nose and forebrain to the hypothalamus. This cell regulates reproduction by secreting GnRH into the pituitary portal vessels to induce the release of gonadotropins into the general circulation.
spiral ganglion neuron Neuron found in the spiral ganglion.

segmented neutrophil of bone marrow A segmented neutrophilic cell of the bone marrow reserve pool that expresses CD11b (integrin alpha-M) and high levels of CD16 (low affinity immunoglobulin gamma Fc region receptor III) on its cell surface.
precursor cell A cell that, by division or terminal differentiation, can give rise to other cell types.
astrocyte of the forebrain also known as forebrain astrocyte An astrocyte of the forebrain.
neuron of the forebrain also known as forebrain neuron A CNS neuron of the forebrain.
forebrain radial glial cell Any radial glial cell that is part of some forebrain.

cranial motor neuron also known as cranial motoneuron Motor neuron that innervate muscles that control eye, jaw, and facial movements of the vertebrate head and parasympathetic neurons that innervate certain glands and organs.
pulmonary ionocyte An ionocyte that is part of the lung epithelium. The cells from this type are major sources of the CFTR protein in human and mice.
splanchnic mesodermal cell A mesodermal cell that is part of the splanchnic layer of lateral plate mesoderm.

epithelial cell of prostatic urethra An epithelial cell that is part of the prostatic urethra.

telocyte A supportive cell with a small, oval-shaped body and one to five telopodes. Telopodes are cytoplasmic protrusions from tens to hundreds of micrometers long and mostly below 0.2 microns of caliber.
lymphoblast A lymphocyte that has gotten larger after being stimulated by an antigen.
B-lymphoblast A lymphocyte of B lineage that has gotten larger after being stimulated by an antigen.

banded nucleus A concave nuclear shape where the nucleus is indented to more than half the distance to the farthest nuclear margin, but in no area is the chromatin condensed to a single filament.
reniform nucleus A concave nucleus shape where the indentation is smaller than half of the distance to the farthest nuclear margin.

In mouse, lung parenchyma resident eosinophils are IL-5-independent Siglec-F(intermediate) CD62L+ CD101(low). In human, they are Siglec-8+ CD62L+ IL-3R(low).

extrahepatic cholangiocyte also known as large bile duct cholangiocyte An epithelial cell of the extrahepatic bile ducts, including the left and right hepatic duct, common hepatic duct, and common bile duct. They are columnar in shape, and have a large nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio relative to small/intrahepatic cholangiocytes.

endothelial cell of periportal hepatic sinusoid also known as periportal hepatic sinusoidal endothelial cell; periportal LSEC An endothelial cell found in the periportal region hepatic sinusoid, near the portal triad. The fenestrae of these cells are larger but fewer in number compared with those of endothelial cells near the centrilobular region of the hepatic sinusoid.

endothelial cell of pericentral hepatic sinusoid also known as central venous hepatic sinusoidal endothelial cell; pericentral LSEC An endothelial cell found in the centrilobular region hepatic sinusoid, near the central vein. The fenestrae of these cells are smaller but more numerous compared with those of endothelial cells near the periportal region of the hepatic sinusoid.
periportal region hepatocyte also known as periportal hepatocyte Any hepatocyte that is part of the liver lobule periportal region. These cells are primarily involved in oxidative energy metabolism.

midzonal region hepatocyte also known as midzonal hepatocyte Any hepatocyte that is part of the liver lobule midzonal region. These cells have mixed functionality in comparison with those in the other two regions of the liver lobule.

centrilobular region hepatocyte also known as centrilobular hepatocyte Any hepatocyte that is part of the liver lobule centrilobular region. These cells are the primary location for the biotransformation of drugs.

intestine goblet cell also known as intestinal goblet cell Goblet cells reside throughout the length of the small and large intestine and are responsible for the production and maintenance of the protective mucus blanket by synthesizing and secreting high-molecular-weight glycoproteins known as mucins. Human intestinal goblet cells secrete the MUC2 mucin, as well as a number of typical mucus components: CLCA1, FCGBP, AGR2, ZG16, and TFF3.

lung neuroendocrine cell also known as pulmonary neuroendocrine cell A neuroendocrine cell that is part of respiratory epithelium of the lung and is involved in the sensory detection of environmental stimuli, including hypoxia, nicotine and air pressure. Ultrastructurally, this cell type is characterized by the presence of cytoplasmic dense core granules, which are considered the storage sites of amine and peptide hormones. Lung neuroendocrine cells are innervated and appear as solitary cells or as clustered masses, localized at airway bifurcation sites, called neuroepithelial bodies that can release serotonin in response to hypoxia and interact with sensory nerve terminals. Lung neuroendocrine cells also function as reserve stem cells that repair the surrounding epithelium after injury.

kidney afferent arteriole endothelial cell An endothelial cell that lines the interior surface of the afferent arteriole and maintains vascular tone. periglomerular cell also known as glomerular layer cell; olfactory bulb (accessory) glomerular layer cell; olfactory bulb glomerular layer cell; olfactory bulb glomerularal cell; olfactory bulb periglomerular cell The small neuron in the glomerular layer of the olfactory bulb whose dendrites arborize within a glomerulus, where it receives synaptic input from olfactory receptor cell axon terminals, and also engages in dendrodendritic interactions with mitral and tufted cell dendrites; uses both GABA and dopamine as a neurotransmitter.
hair-tylotrich neuron The subcutaneous mechanoreceptors that innervate tylotrich hair follicles.

sensory neuron of dorsal root ganglion also known as proprioceptive neuron A sensory neuron of the dorsal root ganglia that senses body position and sends information about how much the muscle is stretched to the spinal cord.

medium spiny neuron also known as gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA)ergic spiny projection neuron; gamma-aminobutyric acid ergic spiny projection neuron; striatal medium spiny neuron An inhibitory, GABAergic projection neuron in the striatum that integrates glutamatergic signals arising from the cerebral cortex and thalamus.

mitral cell The large glutaminergic nerve cells whose dendrites synapse with axons of the olfactory receptor neurons in the glomerular layer of the olfactory bulb, and whose axons pass centrally in the olfactory tract to the olfactory cortex.

olfactory bulb tufted cell The principal glutaminergic neuron located in the outer third of the external plexiform layer of the olfactory bulb; a single short primary dendrite traverses the outer external plexiform layer and terminates within an olfactory glomerulus in a tuft of branches, where it receives the input from olfactory receptor neuron axon terminals; axons of the tufted cells transfer information to a number of areas in the brain, including the piriform cortex, entorhinal cortex, olfactory tubercle, and amygdala.

parvocellular neurosecretory cell also known as parvocellular neuron; parvocellular neurosecretory neuron The secretory neurons of the paraventricular nucleus that synthesize and secrete vasopressin, corticotropin-releasing factor (CRF) and thyrotropin-releasing hormone (TRH) into blood vessels in the hypothalamo-pituitary portal system.
glycinergic neuron The neurons that utilize glycine as a neurotransmitter.

pancreas exocrine glandular cell Glandular cell of exocrine pancreas epithelium. Example: pancreatic acinar cell, glandular cells in pancreatic canaliculi, glandular cells in pancreatic ducts.
adrenal gland glandular cell Hormone secreting cell located in the cortex of adrenal gland. Glandular cells in the adrenal cortex secrete mineralocorticoids, glucocorticoids and androgens.
cerebral cortex endothelial cell A distinct endothelial cell forming the walls of the capillaries within the cerebral cortex.

Anterior horn motor neurons project from the anterior portion of the grey matter in the spinal cord to some skeletal muscles.

placental villous trophoblast also known as vCTB; villous cytotrophoblast A trophoblast of placental villi. These cells fuse to form synctial trophoplast - the placental side of the interface between the placenta and maternal blood sinusoids in the decidua.

dentate gyrus granule cell also known as dentate gyrus of hippocampal formation granule cell A granule cell that has soma location in the dentate gyrus cell layer of the hippocampal formation and has an elliptical cell body and characteristic cone-shaped tree of spiny apical dendrites. The branches extend throughout the molecular layer and the distal tips of the dendritic tree end just at the hippocampal fissure or at the ventricular surface. The dentate gyrus granule cell is the principal cell type of the dentate gyrus.
dentate gyrus of hippocampal formation stellate cell Any stellate cell that is part of a dentate gyrus of hippocampal formation.

Hofbauer cell A tissue-resident macrophage that is part of the placenta. A Hofbauer cell expresses high levels of growth factors and metalloproteinases that support vasculogenesis, angiogenesis, branching morphogenesis and tissue remodeling. A Hofbauer cell has a fetal origin and is present throughout pregnancy.
sympathetic noradrenergic neuron Sympathetic noradrenergic neuron.
sympathetic cholinergic neuron Sympathetic cholinergic neuron.
peripheral sensory neuron Peripheral sensory neuron.
fibroblast of breast also known as breast fibroblast A fibroblast that is part of the breast.
fibroblast of skin of scalp also known as skin of scalp fibroblast A fibroblast that is part of the skin of scalp.

beta motor neuron A motor neuron that innervates both intrafusal and extrafusal muscle fibers. Low abundancy. They control both muscle contraction and responsiveness of the sensory feedback from muscle spindles.
static beta motor neuron A beta motor neuron that innervates nuclear chain fibers.
dynamic beta motor neuron A beta motor neuron that innervates the nuclear bag fibers of muscle spindles.

nuclear chain fiber A type of intrafusal muscle fiber that has nuclei arranged in a linear row. Unlike nuclear bag fibers, the equatorial region of these fibers (in the centre of the spindle) is not expanded. These fibers are responsible for the detection of changes in muscle length. They are innervated by static gamma motor neurons and are principally associated with type II sensory fibers.

nuclear bag fiber A type of intrafusal muscle fiber that lies in the center of a muscle spindle. Nuclei are clustered centrally and give the equatorial region a swollen appearance. They are associated with associated with dynamic gamma motor neurons, and the stretching of the equatorial region of the nuclear bag fibers results in an increase in the firing rate of type Ia sensory fibers.
dynamic nuclear bag fiber also known as bag1 fiber; nuclear bag1 intrafusal fiber A nuclear bag fiber that is sensitive mainly to the rate of change in muscle length.
static nuclear bag fiber also known as bag2 fiber; nuclear bag2 intrafusal fiber A nuclear bag fiber that is sensitive only changes in muscle length but not the rate of that change.

L2/3 bipolar VIP GABAergic interneuron (Mmus) also known as L2/3 bipolar Vip (Mus musculus) A VIP GABAergic cortical interneuron with bipolar morphology, with a soma found in L2/3. L2/3 bipolar VIP cells have extending axons across all layers (with preferences for layers II/III and Va) and a dendritic tree that is vertically more restricted than deeper layer VIP cells and extend fewer dendrites into the layers outside their home layer (location of soma). L2/3 bipolar VIP cells have great variability in firing patterns, though most are continuous adapting. L2/3 bipolar VIP cells are more depolarized in their resting state, had less fast rectification, and had smaller after hyperpolarization than deeper VIP cells.
intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic cortical neuron also known as IT neuron A glutamatergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that projects to structures of telencephalic origins.

extratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic cortical neuron also known as ET projecting neuron A glutamatergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that projects to structures not derived from telencephalon.

alpha7 GABAergic cortical interneuron (Mmus) also known as A7 cell (Mus musculus) A GABAergic cortical interneuron that is strongly labelled for 7 nAChRs. These cells have soma found in L1 and have multipolar dendrites with vertically descending axonal collaterals that project deep into the column, usually branching and terminating in L5A.

lamp5 GABAergic cortical interneuron A transcriptomically distinct GABAergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that expresses Lamp5. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: CGE-derived interneurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea_subclass', clusters Lamp5.
near-projecting glutamatergic cortical neuron also known as NP neuron A glutamatergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that projects axons locally rather than distantly.
corticothalamic-projecting glutamatergic cortical neuron also known as CT projecting neuron A glutamatergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that projects to the thalamus.

L5 VIP GABAergic interneuron (Mmus) also known as L5 VIP (Mus musculus) A VIP GABAergic cortical interneuron with a soma found in L5. L5 VIP cells have mostly local morphology with some deep-projecting axons. They show only moderate resistance, comparable to that of sst subclass and unlike typical VIP subclass cells that tend to show high input resistance. L5 VIP cells show particularly low resting membrane potential.

sncg GABAergic cortical interneuron A transcriptomically distinct GABAergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that expresses Gamma-synuclein. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: CGE-derived interneurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea_subclass', clusters Sncg.

VIP GABAergic cortical interneuron A transcriptomically distinct cortical GABAergic neuron that expresses the vasocactive intestinal polypeptide and that has its soma located in the cerebral cortex. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: CGE-derived interneurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea_subclass', cluster Vip.

sst GABAergic cortical interneuron A transcriptomically distinct GABAergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that expresses somatostatin (sst). The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: MGE-derived interneurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea_subclass', cluster Sst.

pvalb GABAergic cortical interneuron A transcriptomically distinct GABAergic interneuron with a soma located in a cerebral cortex and it expresses Parvalbumin. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: MGE-derived interneurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea_subclass', cluster Pvalb.

L5/6 cck, VIP GABAergic interneuron (Mmus) also known as L5/6 CCK Vip (Mus musculus) A VIP GABAergic cortical interneuron that expresses cck. L5/6 cck cells have soma found mainly in L5 and L6 and have large axonal arborization.

dynamic gamma motor neuron A gamma motor neuron that innervates dynamic nuclear bag fibers (bag1 fibers) and enhances the sensitivities of Ia sensory neurons. They alter muscle spindle sensitivity and increases its discharge in response to velocity of muscle length (rather than just magnitude).

static gamma motor neuron A gamma motor neuron that innervates static nuclear bag fibers (bag2 fibers) and increases their firing, in response to an increase in the magnitude of change in length, and controls the static sensitivity of the stretch reflex.

canopy lamp5 GABAergic cortical interneuron (Mmus) A Lamp5 GABAergic cortical interneuron that has extended axons in the surface of L1. Canopy Lamp5 cells resemble neurogliaform cells in having elongated horizontal axonal arbors largely confined to L1; but the dendritic arbors are wider and have fewer branches, while the axon is less tortuous and extends further from the soma

L5,6 neurogliaform lamp5 GABAergic interneuron (Mmus) also known as L5_1,6 NGC Lamp5 (Mus musculus) A lamp 5 GABAergic cortical interneuron with neurogliaform morphology with a soma found in L5,6. L5,6 NGC lamp5 have deep afterhyperpolarization (AHP) but narrow action potentials (APs). Unlike other deep neurogliaform cells (which are caudal ganglionic eminence (CGE) derived), L5,6 NGC lamp5 cells are medial ganglionic eminence (MGE)-derived

neurogliaform lamp5 GABAergic cortical interneuron (Mmus) also known as NGC Lamp5 (Mus musculus) A lamp5 GABAergic cortical interneuron with layer-adapting morphology. NGC lamp5 cells have a small round soma, short dendrites, and a wide dense axonal arbor that tends to establish a dense axonal mesh with high connection probability both to themselves and L2 pyramidal cells. NGC lamp5 cells have unique synaptic properties that distinguish them from other GABAergic interneurons, including the release of GABA to the extracellular space via volume transmission, and the ability to produce GABA-B responses in connected postsynaptic targets.

long-range projecting sst GABAergic cortical interneuron (Mmus) also known as LP SST (Mus musculus) A sst GABAergic cortical interneuron that is both an interneuron and a projecting neuron. They are found in all layers from upper L2/3 down to the bottom of L6. They have long-range projections, some with axons fading into white matter. These cells have low rebound potential, low hyperpolarization sag, and high variability in membrane time constant.

direct pathway medium spiny neuron also known as D1-MSN; dopamine 1 medium spiny neuron; dSPN A medium spiny neuron that expresses dopamine type 1 receptors and projects to the globus pallidus internus or the substantia nigra pars reticulata.

L5 sst T-Martinotti interneuron (Mmus) also known as L5 T Martinotti SST (Mus musculus) A sst GABAergic cortical interneuron with a soma found in L5 and possesses 'T-shaped' Martinotti morphologies with local axonal plexus in L5a and translaminar axons restricted to the uppermost part of L1. They show low-threshold spiking patterns with strong rebound firing, and inhibit the L1 apical tuft of nearby pyramidal cells.

L5 non-Martinotti sst GABAergic interneuron (Mmus) also known as L5 non-Martinotti SST (Mus musculus) A sst GABAergic cortical interneuron with a soma found in lower L5 with mostly local axonal arborization but with some sparse ascending axons. L5 non-Martinotti sst cells show somatic localization and local axon plexus in L5b and L5b/6 and substantial innervation of L3 and L4, and receive thalamic input from the ventral posteromedial nucleus and specifically target L4 neurons, avoiding L5 pyramidal cells. L5 non-Martinotti sst cells tend to show a higher input resistance and seem to be less stuttering.

indirect pathway medium spiny neuron also known as D2-MSN; dopamine 2 medium spiny neuron; iSPN A medium spiny neuron that expresses dopamine type 2 receptors and projects to the external globus pallidus.

L2/3/5 fan Martinotti sst GABAergic interneuron (Mmus) also known as L2/3/5 fan Martinotti SST (Mus musculus) A sst GABAergic cortical interneuron that has "fanning-out' Martinotti morphology that is found in layer 2/3/5 of the cerebral cortex. They have local axon arbor and long ascending axons that spreads horizontally and arborizes significantly in L1.

L4 sst Martinotti interneuron (Mmus) also known as L4 SST (Mus musculus) A sst GABAergic cortical interneuron with a soma found in lower L2/3 and upper 5, L4 Sst cells have Martinotti morphology with ascending axons but denser local axons and sparser fanning-out projections to L1. L4 sst cells have smaller membrane time constant to calb2 (L2/3/5 fan Martinotti Cell) and non-zero afterdepolarization (ADP).
ON retinal ganglion cell ON retinal ganglion cell_1
OFF retinal ganglion cell A retinal ganglion cell that is depolarized by decreased illumination of their receptive field center.
lateral ganglionic eminence derived neuron also known as LGE-derived neuron A neuron that is derived from a precursor cell in the lateral ganglion eminence.

chandelier pvalb GABAergic cortical interneuron also known as Chandelier PV A transcriptomically distinct pvalb GABAergic cortical interneuron that is recognizable by the straight terminal axonal 'cartridges' of vertically oriented strings of synaptic boutons. Chandelier PV cells' boutons target exclusively the axon initial segment (AIS) of pyramidal cells, with a single cell innervating hundreds of pyramidal cells in a clustered manner. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: CGE-derived interneurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea_subclass', clusters Chandelier.

L6b glutamatergic cortical neuron A glutamatergic neuron with a soma found in cortical layer 6b. They are transcriptomically related to corticothalamic-projecting neurons but have differential projections to the thalamus or anterior cingulate. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: Deep layer (non-IT) excitatory neuron', Author Categories: 'CrossArea_subclass', cluster L6b.
amygdala excitatory neuron Any neuron that has its soma located in some amygdala and is capable of some glutamate secretion, neurotransmission.
L2/3-6 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron also known as L2/3-6 IT projecting neuron An intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron with a soma found in cortical layers L2/3-6.

L5 extratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic cortical neuron also known as Pyramidal tract-like (PT-l); burst-firing layer 5 neuron; thick-tufted layer 5 (TTL5) pyramidal neuron A transcriptomically distinct glutamatergic neuron, with a soma found in the deeper portion of L5, that has long-range axonal projections including deep subcortical targets outside of the telencephalon and, in some cases, the spinal cord. While the L5 ET neuron projections are not limited to ET targets, they are clearly differentiated from the neuron subclasses whose projections are constrained to intratelencephalic (IT) targets. L5 ET neurons are generally the largest excitatory cortical neurons, typically having a thick apical dendrite with a prominent dendritic tuft in layer 1 and displaying burst-firing physiological characteristics. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: Deep layer (non-IT) excitatory neurons ', Author Categories: 'CrossArea_subclass', clusters L5 ET.

L6 corticothalamic-projecting glutamatergic cortical neuron also known as L6 CT A transcriptomically distinct corticothalamic-projecting neuron with a soma found in cortical layer 6. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: Deep layer (non-IT) excitatory neurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea_subclass', clusters L6 CT.

L5/6 near-projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex also known as L5/6 NP M1; L5/6 NP MOp A transcriptomically distinct near-projecting glutamatergic neuron with a soma found in layer 5/6 of the primary motor cortex. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: Deep layer (non-IT) excitatory neurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea_subclass', cluster L5/6 NP.

non-medulla, extratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex also known as non-MY ET M1; non-MY ET MOp (Mus) An extratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron located in layer 5b of the primary motor cortex that does not project to the medulla. Non-MY ET cells are large, big-tufted cells with the apical dendrite often bifurcating close to the soma, suggesting they are corticospinal cells. Non-MY ET cells have bigger hyperpolarization sag, lower input resistance, and smaller AP width, compared to L5 IT neurons.

medulla-projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex also known as medulla-projecting extratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex; MY ET M1; MY ET MOp An extratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron located in layer 5b of the primary motor cortex that projects to the medulla. MY ET cells are large, big-tufted cells with the apical dendrite often bifurcating close to the soma, suggesting they are corticospinal cells. MY ET cells have bigger hyperpolarization sag, lower input resistance, and smaller AP width, compared to L5 IT neurons.

L6b glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex also known as L6b subplate glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex An excitatory glutamatergic neuron transcriptomically related to the CT subclass, with a soma preferentially located in the bottom of L6 of the primary motor cortex.

L2/3 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex also known as L2/3 IT M1; L2/3 IT MOp An intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron with a soma found in cortical layer 2/3 of the primary motor cortex.

L4/5 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex also known as L4/5 IT M1; L4/5 IT MOp An intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic with a soma located in upper L5 of the primary motor cortex. These cells have thin untufted apical dendrites.

L5 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex also known as L5 IT M1; L5 IT MOp An intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron with a soma found in L5 of the primary motor cortex.

L6 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex also known as L6 IT M1; L6 IT MOp An intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron with a soma found in L6 of the primary motor cortex. These cells are short untufted pyramidal cells, which could be stellate or inverted.

vascular leptomeningeal cell also known as VLMC A transcriptomically distinct type of mesothelial fibroblast that is derived from the neural crest, is localized on blood vessels, and is a key component of the pia and arachnoid membranes surrounding the brain. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: Non-neuronal cells', Author Categories: 'CrossArea_subclass', clusters VLMC.
Betz upper motor neuron A Betz cell that synapses with lower motor neurons directly.
spinal interneuron synapsing Betz cell A Betz cell that syanpses with spinal interneurons.
mesothelial fibroblast A mesothelial cell that has undergone mesothelial-to-mesenchymal transition (MMT) to become a fibroblast cell.

corticothalamic VAL/VM projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex also known as CT VAL/VM M1; CT VAL/VM MOp A corticothalamic-projecting glutamatergic neuron that is located in L6 and lower L5 of the primary motor cortex, with a pyramidal morphology and mostly untufted apical dendrites terminating in midcortical layers. CT VAL/VM (ventroanterior-ventrolateral complex/ventromedial nucleus) cells have a near tonic firing pattern and are distinguished from L6 IT neurons by a lower inter-spike interval adaptation index.

vascular leptomeningeal cell (Mmus) also known as VLMC (Mus musculus) A type of mouse mesothelial fibroblast that is derived from the neural crest, is localized on blood vessels, and is a key component of the pia and arachnoid membranes surrounding the brain.
cerebellar inhibitory GABAergic interneuron Any GABAergic interneuron that has its soma located in some cerebellar cortex.
mesothelial fibroblast of the leptomeninx A mesothelial fibroblast found in the leptomeninx.
differentiation-committed oligodendrocyte precursor also known as COP; committed oligodendrocyte precursor An oligodendrocyte precursor cell that is committed to differentiate.
hippocampal CA1-3 neuron A neuron that has its soma located in CA1-3 of the hippocampus.
hippocampal CA4 neuron A neuron that has its soma located in CA4 of the hippocampus.
dentate gyrus neuron A neuron with its soma located in the dentate gyrus of the hippocampus.
medial ganglionic eminence derived interneuron also known as MGE interneuron An interneuron that is derived from the medial ganglionic eminence.

caudal ganglionic eminence derived cortical interneuron also known as caudal ganglionic eminence derived GABAergic cortical interneuron An interneuron that is derived from the caudal ganglionic eminence.
meis2 expressing cortical GABAergic cell A GABAergic cell located in the cerebral cortex that expresses meis2.

horizontal pyramidal neuron A pyramidal neuron which has an apical tree which is oriented parallel to the pia. This is unlike typical pyramidal neurons which have its apical dendrite aligned vertically.
thalamic excitatory neuron An excitatory neuron that has its soma located in the thalamic complex.

medial ganglionic eminence derived GABAergic cortical interneuron also known as MGE cortical interneuron A GABAergic cortical interneuron that develops from the medial ganglionic eminence and has migrated to the cerebral cortex.

L5/6 cck GABAergic interneuron (Mmus) also known as L5/6 CCK (Mus musculus) A GABAergic cortical interneuron that expresses cck. L5/6 cck cells have soma found mainly in L5 and L6 and have large axonal arborization.
brain vascular cell A cell that is part of the brain vasculature.
mammillary body neuron A neuron that has its soma located in the mammillary body.

L6 th sst GABAergic interneuron (Mmus) also known as L6 Th+ SST (Mus musculus); L6 tyrosine hydroxylase positive sst expressing GABAergic cortical interneuron (Mus musculus) A sst GABAergic cortical interneuron found in L6 that expresses tyrosine hydroxylase. L6 Th+ SST cells have mostly local axonal arborization within L6.

Martinotti neuron An interneuron that has Martinotti morphology. These interneurons are scattered throughout various layers of the cerebral cortex, sending their axons up to the cortical layer I where they form axonal arborization.

bitufted neuron A type of interneuron that has two clusters of dendritic branches that originate directly from the soma and extend in opposite directions and axons that form a plexus which spreads widely. Compared to bipolar neurons, bitufted neurons have branching that occur close to the soma.
midbrain-derived inhibitory neuron A GABAergic inhibitory neuron that is derived from the midbrain.

stellate L6 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex (Mmus) also known as stellate L6 IT MOp (Mus musculus) a L6 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex that has stellate pyramidal morphology.

inverted L6 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex (Mmus) also known as inverted L6 IT MOp (Mus musculus) a L6 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex that has inverted pyramidal morphology.

chandelier cell A GABAergic interneuron that selectively innervates the axon initial segment of pyramidal cells. Their local axonal clusters are formed by high-frequency branching at shallow angles, often ramifying around, above or below their somata with a high bouton density. The characteristic terminal portions of the axon form short vertical rows of boutons, resembling the candlesticks and candles of a chandelier. Chandelier cells can be multipolar or bitufted.
T Martinotti neuron also known as T-shaped Martinotti neuron A Martinotti neuron that has axons that form a horizontal ramification, making it T-shaped.
fan Martinotti neuron also known as fanning-out Martinotti neuron A Martinotti neuron that has axons that form a fan-like plexus.

large basket cell A basket cell that is large, and typically ascends to give rise to many long horizontally and vertically projecting axon collaterals that traverse neighboring columns and can extend through all cortical layers.

nest basket cell A basket cell which has simpler dendritic arbors (compared to small or large basket cells), and an axonal plexus of intermediate density, composed of a few long, smooth axonal branches.
small basket cell A basket cell with axonal arbors composed of frequent, short, curvy axonal branches that tend to be near their somata and within the same layer.
inverted pyramidal neuron A pyramidal neuron which has an apical tree which is oriented towards the white matter.
stellate pyramidal neuron A pyramidal neuron which lacks a tuft formation but extends small radial distances forming a star-like shape.
tufted pyramidal neuron A pyramidal neuron which has a distinctive tuft formation, distal from the soma.
untufted pyramidal neuron A pyramidal neuron which lacks a clear tuft formation but extends to large radial distances.

arachnoid barrier cell A mesothelial fibroblast of the arachnoid barrier layer. Arachnoid barrier cells make up the tight-junctioned layer in the leptomeninx that functions as the physiologic barrier between the cerebrospinal fluid in the subarachnoid space and the fenestrated capillaries in the dura.

reticulospinal neuron also known as RSN A neuron with soma location in the reticular formation with axons that extend into the spinal cord such. Reticulospinal neuron activity can lead to a variety of motor behaviors.
oxytocin-secreting magnocellular cell A magnocellular neurosecretory cell that is capable of producing and secreting oxytocin.
vasopressin-secreting magnocellular cell A magnocellular neurosecretory cell that is capable of producing and secreting vasopressin.
amygdala pyramidal neuron A pyramidal neuron with soma located in the amygdala.
cerebral cortex pyramidal neuron A pyramidal neuron with soma located in the cerebral cortex.

vestibular afferent neuron An afferent neuron of the vestibular system that innervate the base of the hair cell and increase or decrease their neural firing rate as the receptor cell is excited or inhibited.
bouton vestibular afferent neuron A vestibular afferent neuron that makes bouton synapses to type II hair cells.

calyx vestibular afferent neuron A vestibular afferent neuron which posseses a unique postsynaptic terminal, the calyx, which completely covers the basolateral walls of type I hair cells and receives input from multiple ribbon synapses.
type 1 spiral ganglion neuron also known as type I spiral ganglion cell A spiral ganglion neuron that innervates inner hair cells. Type 1 spiral ganglion neurons are myelinated and bipolar.
type 2 spiral ganglion neuron also known as type II spiral ganglion cell A spiral ganglion neuron that innervates outer hair cells. Type 1 spiral ganglion neurons are unmyelinated and unipolar.

L5/6 non-Martinotti sst GABAergic interneuron (Mmus) also known as L5/6 non-Martinotti morphology sst expressing GABAergic cortical interneuron (Mus musculus); L5/6 non-Martinotti SST (Mus musculus) A sst GABAergic interneuron does not have Martinotti morphology with a soma found in L5/6 of the cerebral cortex.

displaced amacrine cell also known as dACs; inverted amacrine cell A subpopulation of amacrine cell that migrate further than other amacrine cells, and come to lie basal to the inner plexiform layer (IPL) in the ganglion cell layer. Displaced amacrine cells still have their neurites extending apically into the IPL, and therefore exhibit an inverted polarity with respect to the other amacrine cells.
cochlea auditory hair cell also known as cochlear hair cell An auditory hair cell found in the cochlea.

sst chodl GABAergic cortical interneuron A transcriptomically distinct sst GABAergic cortical interneuron that also expresses Chodl. These neurons are rare and correspond to the only known cortical interneurons with long-range projection. The standard transcriptomic reference data for this cell type can be found on the CellxGene census under the collection: 'Transcriptomic cytoarchitecture reveals principles of human neocortex organization', dataset: 'Supercluster: MGE-derived interneurons', Author Categories: 'CrossArea_subclass', clusters Sst Chodl.
oxytocin receptor sst GABAergic cortical interneuron An interneuron located in the cerebral cortex that expresses the oxytocin receptor. These interneurons also express somatostatin.

hypothalamus kisspeptin neuron A kisspeptin neuron that is located in the hypothalamus. These neurons project to and activate gonadotrophin-releasing hormone neurons (acting via the kisspeptin receptor) in the hypothalamus and stimulate the secretion of gonadotrophin-releasing hormone.
dentate gyrus kisspeptin neuron A kisspeptin neuron that is located in the dentate gyrus of the hippocampus.
KNDy neuron also known as kisspeptin, neurokinin B and dynorphin expressing neuron A hypothalamus kisspeptin neuron that coexpresses kisspeptin, neurokinin B and dynorphin.
arcuate nucleus of hypothalamus KNDy neuron a KNDy neuron that is located in the arcuate nucleus of the hypothalamus.
rostral periventricular region of the third ventricle KNDy neuron also known as RP3V KNDy neuron a KNDy neuron that is located in the rostral periventricular region of the third ventricle.
retinoblast also known as retinal stem cell A retinal cell that is immature or undifferentiated.
kisspeptin neuron A neuron that expresses kisspeptin. These neurons are predominantly located in the hypothalamus, but also found in other parts of the brain including the hippocampal dentate gyrus.
myelinating glial cell A glial cell that myelinates axonal processes.

octopus cell of the mammalian cochlear nucleus A neuron in the posterior ventral cochlear nucleus that is distinguished by their long, thick and tentacle-shaped dendrites that typically emanate from one side of the cell body.
double bouquet cell An interneuron that has double bouquet morphology.

cartwheel cell A neuron of the dorsal cochlear nucleus with spiny dendrites that receive input from the axons of granule cells and with axons that release GABA and glycine onto cartwheel, pyramidal and giant cell targets.

unipolar brush cell An excitatory glutamatergic interneuron found in the granular layer of the cerebellar cortex and also in the granule cell domain of the cochlear nucleus. Unipolar brush cells have a round or oval cell body with usually a single short dendrite that ends in a brush-like tuft of short dendrites unique to them known as dendrioles.

bushy cell A neuron found in the anterior part of the ventral cochlear nucleus that has the appearance of bushes, having short dendrites. Bushy cells give outputs to different parts of the superior olivary complex.

spherical bushy cell A bushy cell that receives only few large excitatory endbulb synapses from auditory nerves. Spherical bush cells give excitatory input to the lateral and medial parts of the superior olive.

globular bushy cell also known as GBC A bushy cell that receives a large number of medium-sized synapses, called modified endbulbs. Globular bushy cells extend to the superior olive on both sides of the brainstem where they give input to the bipolar neurons.

somatosensory neuron A neuron that is part of the somatic sensory system. Somatosensory neurons innervate the skin or integument to detect different types of thermal, chemical, and mechanical touch stimuli.

trigeminal neuron A neuron that is responsible for sensation in the face or motor functions such as biting and chewing. Trigeminal neurons extend a single axon shaft along the lateral white matter of the hindbrain and spinal cord. The highly branched axons innervate the integument of the head.
trigeminal sensory neuron A trigeminal neuron that is responsible for sensation in the face.
trigeminal motor neuron A trigeminal neuron that is responsible for motor functions such as biting and chewing.

hypendymal cell A neurecto-epithelial cell that is part of the basal layer of the subcommissural organ and specializes in the secretion of proteins into the subarachnoid space. Hypendymal cells have similar characteristics to ependymal cells and express SCO-spondin.
koniocellular cell also known as K cell A neuron with a small cell body that is located in a koniocellular layer of the lateral geniculate nucleus (LGN).

midget ganglion cell of retina A retinal ganglion cell that originate in the ganglion cell layer of the retina, and project to the parvocellular layers of the lateral geniculate nucleus (LGN). These cells are known as midget retinal ganglion cells due to the small sizes of their dendritic trees and cell bodies.

parasol ganglion cell of retina A retinal ganglion cell located in the ganglion cell layer of the retina. This cell projects to magnocellular cells in the lateral geniculate nucleus (LGN). They have large cell bodies and extensive, branching dendritic networks that contribute to their large receptive fields.
pulmonary capillary endothelial cell also known as lung capillary endothelial cell Any capillary endothelial cell that is part of a lung.
alveolar capillary type 1 endothelial cell An alveolar capillary endothelial cell that is located distally to alveolar capillary type 2 endothelial cells.

alveolar capillary type 2 endothelial cell An alveolar capillary endothelial cell that is located proximally to alveolar capillary type 1 endothelial cells and in close apposition to alveolar type 1 epithelial cells (also known as type I pneumocytes).
alveolar type 1 fibroblast cell A pulmonary interstitial fibroblast that is part of the alveolus and contains lipid droplets.
alveolar adventitial fibroblast also known as alveolar type 2 fibroblast cell A pulmonary interstitial fibroblast that is part of the alveolus and localizes to vascular adventitia.
gamete-nursing cell A cell that supports the development of a gamete by providing it cytoplasmic material (including entire organelles) by direct cross-membrane channels (del Pino, 2021).
germline-derived nurse cell A gamete-nursing cell that derives from a germline cell (del Pino, 2021).
somatic nurse-like cell A gamete-nursing cell that derives from the somatic tissues of the gonad (del Pino, 2021).
choroidal melanocyte also known as uveal melanocyte A melanocyte located in the vascular uvea and involved in photoprotection, regulation of oxidative damage and immune responses.
stromal cell of thymus also known as thymic stromal cell A stromal cell that is part of the thymus.

effector memory CD45RA-positive, alpha-beta T cell, terminally differentiated also known as TEMRA cell; terminally differentiated effector memory CD45RA+ T cells; terminally differentiated effector memory cells re-expressing CD45RA An alpha-beta memory T cell with the phenotype CD45RA-positive.
interstitial cell of thymus also known as thymic interstitial cell A cell that makes up the loose connective tissue of the thymus.

thymic nurse cell A large epithelial cell found in the thymus. This cell type may internalize thymocytes through extensions of plasma membrane. The cell surface and cytoplasmic vacuoles of a thymic nurse cell express MHC Class I and MHC Class II antigens. The interaction of these antigens with a developing thymocyte determines whether the thymocyte undergoes positive or negative selection.

kidney collecting duct beta-intercalated cell also known as B-IC; kidney collecting duct intercalated cell type B A renal beta-intercalated cell that is part of the cortical collecting duct. The medullary collecting duct does not contain the renal beta-intercalated cell type.

fallopian tube secretory epithelial cell also known as uterine tube secretory epithelial cell An epithelial cell that is part of the fallopian tube epithelium that secretes mucous fluid and oviduct-specific products through the stimulation of estrogen and luteinizing hormone. The fallopian tube secretory cell has approximately the same height as the ciliated cell and is usually a more narrow columnar cell. The nucleus is ovoid and perpendicular to the long axis of the cell. The chromatin is more dense and the nucleolus smaller than that seen in the ciliated cell.

fallopian tube ciliated cell also known as uterine tube ciliated epithelial cell An epithelial ciliated cell that is part of the fallopian tube. This cell type is found mainly on the apex of the mucosal folds and contributes, together with peristaltic contractions, to the self-propulsion of spermatozoa, the transport of ovum during ovulation and the transport of the fertilized ovum to the intramural fallopian tube.
