sublaminar layer S2 A retinal neural layer that is immediately adjacent to the S1 and S3 layers and comprises 20 percent of the inner plexiform layer of retina.
sublaminar layer S3 A retinal neural layer that is immediately adjacent to the S2 and S4 layers and comprises 20 percent of the inner plexiform layer of retina.
sublaminar layer S4 A retinal neural layer that is immediately adjacent to the S3 and S5 layer and comprises 20 percent of the inner plexiform layer of retina.
sublaminar layer S5 A retinal neural layer that is immediately adjacent to the retinal ganglion cell layer and comprises 20 percent of the ganglion plexiform layer of retina.
sublaminar layers S1 or S2 One of sublaminar layers S1 or S2.
sublaminar layers S2 or S3 One of sublaminar layers S2 or S3.
sublaminar layers S4 or S5 One of sublaminar layers S4 or S5.
somatosensory cortex also known as somatic sensory cortex Area of the parietal lobe concerned with receiving general sensations. It lies posterior to the central sulcus.

primary somatosensory cortex also known as primary somatosensory cortex (area S1, areas 3,1,2); somatosensory area 1 (Chapin & Lin, 1984, rat): the region considered as the SI cortex is not a cytoarchitecturally homogeneous structure but consists instead of a patchwork array of areas containing dense aggregations of layer IV granule cells, surrounded by granule-cell-sparse regions. As was shown by Welker (b71,b76), and in our own mapping studies (see Fig. 3), this discontinuous pattern of granular, or koniocortical, zones contains within itself a map of the ratbs cutaneous periphery. There are clear subtypes within this cytoarchitectural subregion, notably including the bgranular aggregateb type of cytoarchitecture characteristic of the paw, limb, and mystacial vibrissae areas, and the bbarrel-fieldb type (originally described by Woolsey and Van der Loos, b70) seen in the nose and perioral regions. In the mouse, but not the rat, such barrels also cover the whole whisker representation (Welker and Woolsey, b74).
secondary somatosensory cortex also known as somatosensory area 2 The area of the upper bank of the lateral sulcus that is involved in somatic sensation.

gastropod cerebral ganglion also known as cerebral ganglion The cerebral ganglia are primarily sensual centres, that compute information from the eyes as well as from the tactile and position sensors (statocystes). Besides coordination they also serve the locational memory of a snail.

extraembryonic endoderm An extraembryonic epithelium that is formed by the delaminated cells of the primitive endoderm (hypoblast) that goes on to form the yolk sac. In mammals, as in avians, these cells do not produce any part of the newborn organism (i.e. they are extraembryonic).
lung parenchyma also known as respiratory portion of lung A parenchyma that is part of a lung.
respiratory primordium respiratory primordium_1
upper lobe of lung also known as cranial lobe of lung; lobus superior; lobus superior pulmonis; superior lobe of lung A lobe of the lung that is closest to the head.
lower lobe of lung also known as inferior lobe of lung; lobus inferior; lobus inferior pulmonis The bottom most subdivision of either the right or left lung.

azygous lobe of lung The azygous lobe of the lung is an accessory lobe of the right lung. It is rare and usually associated with an abnormality of the azygous vein. It is produced by an aberrant position of the azygous vein near the hilum of the lung. It divides the right superior lobe near the apex of the lung down to the hilum in roughly the median plane. The fissure created, the meso-azygous fissure, is lined by both visceral and parietal pleura. The lobe lies superomedial to the fissure.
left lung lobe also known as lobe of left lung; lobe of the left lung A lobe of lung that is part of a left lung.

upper lobe of left lung also known as left lung cranial lobe; left upper lobe; left upper lobe of lung; superior lobe of left lung; lobus superior (pulmo sinister); lobus superior pulmonis sinistri The lobe of the left lung that is closest to the head.

lower lobe of left lung also known as inferior lobe of left lung; left lower lobe; left lower lobe of lung; left lung caudal lobe; lobus inferior (pulmo sinister); lobus inferior pulmonis sinistri A lower lobe of lung that is part of a left lung.
lingula of left lung also known as left pulmonary lingula; lingula of lung; lingula of the lung Anterioinferior portion of left upper lung lobe.
middle lobe of lung also known as lung middle lobe A lobe of the lung that is situated somewhere between an upper lobe and lower lobe.

involucrum A layer of new bone growth outside existing bone seen in pyogenic osteomyelitis. It results from the stripping off of the periosteum by the accumulation of pus within the bone, and new bone growing from the periosteum.
sequestrum A piece of dead bone that has become separated during the process of necrosis from normal/sound bone..

auditory bulla A hollow bony structure on the ventral, posterior portion of the skull of placental mammals that encloses parts of the middle and inner ear. In most species, it is formed by the tympanic part of the temporal bone.

forelimb bone also known as free forelimb bone A bone that is part of a forelimb region. Examples: humerus, any of the phalanges. Counter-example: scapula (a bone of the pectoral girdle). Note that we consider the forelimb to end at the shoulder.

centrum semiovale also known as centrum ovale; corpus medullare cerebri; medullary center; substantia centralis medullaris cerebri The semioval center is the white matter found underneath the grey matter on the surface of the cerebrum. The term is synonymous with cerebral white matter. The white matter, located in each hemisphere between the cerebral cortex and nuclei, as a whole has a semioval shape. It consists of cortical projection fibers, association fibers and cortical fibers.

dental follicle A sac containing the developing tooth and its odontogenic organ. The dental follicle (DF) differentiates into the periodontal ligament. In addition, it may be the precursor of other cells of the periodontium, including osteoblasts, cementoblasts and fibroblasts. They develop into the alveolar bone, the cementum with Sharpey's fibers and the periodontal ligament fibers respectively.
left colon The distal portion of the colon; it develops embryonically from the hindgut and functions in the storage and elimination of waste.

right colon The proximal portion of the colon, extending from the ileocecal valve usually to a point proximal to the left colic flexure; it develops embryonically from the terminal portion of the midgut and functions in absorption.

apocrine gland also known as true apocrine gland Any exocrine gland whose cells bud their secretions off through the plasma membrane producing membrane-bound vesicles in the lumen; the apical portion of the secretory cell of the gland pinches off and enters the lumen; it loses part of its cytoplasm in their secretions; apocrine secretion is functional during hormonal stress or puberty; an example of true apocrine glands are mammary glands, responsible for secreting breast milk.
oviduct shell gland also known as shell gland A gland in the posterior expansion of the oviduct that secretes the calcareous surroundings of the egg shell.

pes anserinus of tibia also known as pes anserinus The pes anserinus is the insertion of the conjoined tendons of three muscles onto the anteromedial (front and inside) surface of the proximal extremity of the tibia.
anal sac In carnivores, either of two sacs found between the internal and external anal sphincters, lined with sebaceous glands and in some species with apocrine glands.
carcass A body of a multi-cellular organism that is no longer living.
fascia also known as fascia cluster A dense regular connective tissue that that connects muscles together[WP, modified].
renal parenchyma also known as parenchyma of kidney The functional tissue of the kidney, consisting of the nephrons.

submucosal esophageal gland also known as esophageal gland; glandulae oesophageae; mucous gland of submucosa of esophagus One of the racemose glands in the walls of the esophagus that in humans are small and serve principally to lubricate the food but in some birds secrete a milky fluid on which the young are fed.
chorion frondosum The part of the chorion where the villi persist, forming the foetal part of the placenta.
habenular nucleus Either of the two neural nuclei within the habenula.
equine glandular stomach Stomach found in horses; includes cardiac, proper gastric and pyloric glandular zones.

nucleus of cerebellar nuclear complex also known as cerebellar nucleus; deep cerebellar nucleus Four accumulations of gray substance embedded in the white substance of the cerebellum, comprising the nucleus dentatus, nucleus emboliformis, nucleus globosus, and nucleus fastigii.
vasculature of brain also known as brain vasculature; cerebrovascular system; intracerebral vasculature System pertaining to blood vessels in the brain.
ischial spine also known as spina ischialis A bony process projecting backward and medialward from the posterior border of the ischium.
placental membrane The membrane separating the fetal from the maternal blood in the placenta.
femorotibial joint also known as femoratibial joint; tibiofemoral joint One of the two primary bendings of a typical leg, pertains to the femur and the tibia.

deep inguinal lymph node also known as deep inguinal node; femoral lymph node; nodus lymphaticus inguinalis profundus One of several small inconstant lymph nodes, proximal, intermediate and distal deep to the fascia lata and medial to the femoral vein; they receive lymph from the deep structures of the lower limb, from the glans penis and from superficial inguinal nodes; efferents pass to the external iliac nodes.

superficial inguinal lymph node also known as lymph node of Cloquet; lymph node of Rosenmuller; nodus lymphaticus inguinalis superficialis; superficial inguinal node A group of 12-20 lymph nodes that lie in the subcutaneous tissue below the inguinal ligament and along the terminal part of the great saphenous vein; they drain the skin and subcutaneous tissue of the lower abdominal wall, perineum, buttocks, external genitalia, and lower limbs.

carotid sinus nerve also known as carotid branch of glossopharyngeal nerve; Hering sinus nerve; ramus sinus carotici; ramus sinus carotici nervi glossopharyngei; ramus sinus carotici nervus glossopharyngei; sinus nerve of Hering A sensory branch of the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX) carrying signals from the baroceptors (blood pressure receptors) in the bifurcation of the carotid artery to the nucleus of the solitary tract (nucleus solitarius).
periurethral tissue Any portion of tissue that surrounds a urethra.
white fibrocartilage Fibrocartilage in which strong bundles of white fibrous tissue predominate.
lower back skin A zone of skin that is part of a lower back.
upper back skin A zone of skin that is part of a dorsal thoracic segment of trunk.
ciliary stroma also known as ocular ciliary stroma; stroma of ciliary body ciliary stroma_1
left uterine horn An uterine horn that is in the left side of a uterus.
right uterine horn An uterine horn that is in the right side of a uterus.
gastroepiploic artery One of two (right and left) arteries along the greater curvature of the stomach that supply blood to the greater omentum and stomach.
iliac circumflex artery One of two (deep circumflex and superficial circumflex) iliac arteries that supply the lower abdomen, inguinal lymph nodes, sartorius, and tensor fasciae latae.
vesical artery also known as arteria vesicali; vesical arteries An artery that supplies blood to the urinary bladder.
pudendal vein also known as vena pudendae; vena pudendales Either the internal or external pudendal vein, running from the genital-vulvar area and abdomen and down the leg.
left pulmonary vein Vein that drains left lung and returns blood to the heart.
right pulmonary vein Vein that drains right lung and returns blood to the heart.
renal straight tubule also known as kidney straight tubule; straight tubule Any region of a nephron tubule that is straight. Examples: distal convoluted tubule, proximal convoluted tuble.
sulcus ampullaris also known as ampullary groove; ampullary sulcus The groove on the external surface of the ampulla of each semicircular duct where the nerve enters the ampullary crest.
lymph node germinal center A germinal center that is located in a lymph node.

deep circumflex iliac artery also known as arteria circumflexa ilium profunda The deep circumflex iliac artery (or deep iliac circumflex artery) is an artery in the pelvis that travels along the iliac crest of the pelvic bone.

superficial circumflex iliac artery also known as arteria circumflexa ilium superficialis The superficial iliac circumflex artery (or superficial circumflex iliac), the smallest of the cutaneous branches of the femoral artery, arises close to the superficial epigastric artery, and, piercing the fascia lata, runs lateralward, parallel with the inguinal ligament, as far as the crest of the ilium. It divides into branches which supply the integument of the groin, the superficial fascia, and the superficial subinguinal lymph glands, anastomosing with the deep iliac circumflex, the superior gluteal and lateral femoral circumflex arteries.

prostatic venous plexus The prostatic veins form a well-marked prostatic plexus which lies partly in the fascial sheath of the prostate and partly between the sheath and the prostatic capsule. It communicates with the pudendal and vesical plexuses.

pudendal venous plexus The pudendal plexus (vesicoprostatic plexus) lies behind the arcuate pubic ligament and the lower part of the pubic symphysis, and in front of the bladder and prostate. Its chief tributary is the deep dorsal vein of the penis, but it also receives branches from the front of the bladder and prostate. It communicates with the vesical plexus and with the internal pudendal vein and drains into the vesical and hypogastric veins.
inferior external pudendal vein inferior external pudendal vein_1
superior external pudendal vein superior external pudendal vein_1
deep external pudendal vein also known as vena pudendae externalis profunda; vena pudendales externalis profunda deep external pudendal vein_1
superficial external pudendal vein also known as vena pudendae externalis superficialis; vena pudendales externalis superficialis superficial external pudendal vein_1

nucleus of solitary tract also known as nucleus of the tractus solitarius; nucleus of tractus solitarius; nucleus tractus solitarii medullae oblongatae; solitary nucleus; solitary tract nucleus A neural nucleus that is part of the solitary tract nuclear complex. The solitary tract and nucleus are structures in the brainstem that carry and receive visceral sensation and taste from the facial (VII), glossopharyngeal (IX) and vagus (X) cranial nerves. [WP,unvetted].
gelatinous nucleus of solitary tract gelatinous nucleus of solitary tract_1
medial nucleus of solitary tract medial nucleus of solitary tract_1
dorsal nucleus of trapezoid body also known as dorsal nucleus of trapezoid body; nucleus dorsalis corporis trapezoidei dorsal nucleus of trapezoid body_1
closed circulatory system closed circulatory system_1
two-pass circulatory system A closed circulatory system in which blood passes twice through the heart to supply the body once.
one-pass circulatory system A closed circulatory system in which blood passes once through the heart to supply the body once.
faveolus also known as lung faveolus A bellows-shaped respiratory unit extending from the outer wall of the lung into a central air space.
inner medulla descending vasa recta inner medulla descending vasa recta_1
outer medulla descending vasa recta outer medulla descending vasa recta_1
ascending vasa recta ascending vasa recta_1
inner medulla ascending vasa recta inner medulla ascending vasa recta_1
outer medulla ascending vasa recta outer medulla ascending vasa recta_1
tip of renal papilla also known as papillary tip; papillary tips tip of renal papilla_1
gravid organism An organism containing a developing embryo, fetus, or unborn offspring within the body.
gravid uterus The uterus in pregnancy.
cervical thymus A mature thymus that is entirely part of the cervical region.
thoracic thymus A mature thymus that is entirely part of thoracic region.
indifferent gonad A gonad prior to differentiating into a definitive testis or ovary.
vomeronasal nerve Nerve carrying fibers from the vomeronasal organ epithelium to the accessory olfactory bulb.
adenohypophyseal placode The adenohypophyseal placode forms the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland and gives rise to the endocrine secretory cells of the pituitary.
geniculate placode also known as epibranchial placode 1; facial epibranchial placode; facial placode Rostralmost epibranchial placode. Associated with 1st branchial cleft.

petrosal placode also known as epibranchial placode 2; glossopharyngeal epibranchial placode; glossopharyngeal IX placode; glossopharyngeal placode Epibranchial placode between geniculate and nodose. Associated with 2nd branchial cleft.

nodosal placode also known as epibranchial placode 3; nodose placode; nodose placodes; vagal epibranchial placode; vagal epibranchial placodes Caudalmost epibranchial placode. Associated with 3rd branchial cleft.
epibranchial ganglion also known as epibranchial ganglia Cranial ganglion which develops from an epibranchial placode.

ventral midline In protostomes (such as insects, snails and worms) as well as deuterostomes (vertebrates), the midline is an embryonic region that functions in patterning of the adjacent nervous tissue. The ventral midline in insects is a cell population extending along the ventral surface of the embryo and is the region from which cells detach to form the ventrally located nerve cords. In vertebrates, the midline is originally located dorsally. During development, it folds inwards and becomes the ventral part of the dorsally located neural tube and is then called the ventral midline, or floor plate.

sulcus limitans of fourth ventricle In the floor of the fourth ventricle, the sulcus limitans separates the cranial nerve motor nuclei (medial) from the sensory nuclei (lateral). In the superior part of the rhomboid fossa, it corresponds with the lateral limit of the fossa and presents a bluish-gray area, the locus ceruleus (which owes its color to an underlying patch of deeply pigmented nerve cells, termed the substantia ferruginea). spinal nerve root also known as root of spinal nerve; spinal neural root; spinal root The paired bundles of nerve fibers entering and leaving the spinal cord at each segment. The dorsal and ventral nerve roots join to form the mixed segmental spinal nerves. The dorsal roots are generally afferent, formed by the central projections of the spinal (dorsal root) ganglia sensory cells, and the ventral roots efferent, comprising the axons of spinal motor and autonomic preganglionic neurons. There are, however, some exceptions to this afferent/efferent rule.

sacral nerve also known as nervus sacralis; sacral spinal nerve The five sacral nerves emerge from the sacrum. Although the vertebral components of the sacrum are fused into a single bone, the sacral vertebrae are still used to number the sacral nerves. Posteriorly, they emerge from the posterior sacral foramina, and form the posterior branches of sacral nerves. Anteriorly, they emerge from the anterior sacral foramina, and contribute to the sacral plexus (S1-S4) and coccygeal plexus.

ansa lenticularis also known as ansa lenticularis in thalamo; ansa lenticularis in thalamus; ventral peduncle of lateral forebrain bundle The ansa lenticularis (ansa lentiformis in older texts) is a part of the brain, making up the superior layer of the substantia innominata of Meynert. Its fibers, derived from the medullary lamina of the lentiform nucleus, pass medially to end in the thalamus and subthalamic region, while others are said to end in the tegmentum and red nucleus. It is classified by NeuroNames as part of the subthalamus.

nasal fin The nasal fin is an epithelial seam that develops by fusion between the epithelial linings of the medial and lateral nasal swellings. Shortly after its formation the nasal fin regresses and is replaced by mesenchyme, with exception of its most posterior portion which remains as the bucconasal membrane.

accessory XI nerve spinal component also known as spinal part of the accessory nerve The spinal root of accessory nerve (or part) is firm in texture, and its fibers arise from the motor cells in the lateral part of the anterior column of the gray substance of the medulla spinalis as low as the fifth cervical nerve. Passing through the lateral funiculus of the medulla spinalis, they emerge on its surface and unite to form a single trunk, which ascends between the ligamentum denticulatum and the posterior roots of the spinal nerves; enters the skull through the foramen magnum, and is then directed to the jugular foramen, through which it passes, lying in the same sheath of dura mater as the vagus, but separated from it by a fold of the arachnoid. In the jugular foramen, it receives one or two filaments from the cranial part of the nerve, or else joins it for a short distance and then separates from it again. As its exit from the jugular foramen, it runs backward in front of the internal jugular vein in 66.6 per cent. of cases, and behind in it 33.3 per cent. The nerve then descends obliquely behind the Digastricus and Stylohyoideus to the upper part of the Sternocleidomastoideus; it pierces this muscle, and courses obliquely across the posterior triangle of the neck, to end in the deep surface of the Trapezius. As it traverses the Sternocleidomastoideus it gives several filaments to the muscle, and joins with branches from the second cervical nerve. In the posterior triangle it unites with the second and third cervical nerves, while beneath the Trapezius it forms a plexus with the third and fourth cervical nerves, and from this plexus fibers are distributed to the muscle.

chorda tympani branch of facial nerve also known as chorda tympani; facial VII nerve chorda tympani branch; parasympathetic root of submandibular ganglion; radix parasympathica ganglii submandibularis The chorda tympani is a nerve that branches from the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) inside the facial canal, just before the facial nerve exits the skull via the stylomastoid foramen. Chorda tympani is a branch of the facial nerve (the seventh cranial nerve) that serves the taste buds in the front of the tongue, runs through the middle ear, and carries taste messages to the brain. The chorda tympani is part of one of three cranial nerves that are involved in taste. The taste system involves a complicated feedback loop, with each nerve acting to inhibit the signals of other nerves. The chorda tympani appears to exert a particularly strong inhibitory influence on other taste nerves, as well as on pain fibers in the tongue. When the chorda tympani is damaged, its inhibitory function is disrupted, leading to less inhibited activity in the other nerves.

lymph node medullary sinus The channels in the lymph node medulla that separate the medullary cords and are crossed by a reticulum of cells and fibers and bounded by littoral cells; lymph flows through the medullary sinus from the cortical sinuses and into the efferent lymphatic vessels.
lymph node medullary cord The dense rope-like structures of lymphatic tissue located between the medullary sinuses in the medulla of a lymph node.
head fold of embryonic disc also known as head fold The crescent-shaped, ventrally located fold of the embryonic disc at the future cephalic end of the developing embryo.
tail fold of embryonic disc also known as tail fold The crescent-shaped, ventrally located fold of the embryonic disc at the future caudal end of the developing embryo.
cephalic neural fold The elevated margins of the neural groove that are located in the future cephalic region of the embryo.

limb mesenchyme The primordial embryonic connective tissue of the developing limbs, autopods and digits, consisting of mesenchymal cells supported in interlaminar jelly, that derive mostly from the mesoderm and contribute to limb connective tissue, bone and musculature in conjunction with myotome cells.

cardiac mesenchyme also known as heart mesenchyme The embryonic connective tissue made up of loosely aggregated mesenchymal cells, supported by interlaminar jelly, that gives rise to the developing cardiac structures.
pancreas mesenchyme The embryonic connective tissue made up of loosely aggregated mesenchymal cells, supported by interlaminar jelly, that gives rise to the developing pancreas.
adrenal gland cortex zone also known as adrenal cortical region adrenal gland cortex zone_1
blubber A thick layer of vascularized adipose tissue found under the skin of all cetaceans, pinnipeds and sirenians.
abdominal ganglion A ganglion that is part of a abdominal segment of trunk.
proximal interphalangeal joint An inter-phalangeal joint that connects a proximal phalanx to either a medial or distal phalanx.
distal interphalangeal joint An inter-phalangeal joint that connects a distal phalanx to either a medial or proximal phalanx.
left common cardinal vein also known as common cardinal vein left left common cardinal vein_1
left anterior cardinal vein also known as left precardinal vein; precardinal vein left An anterior cardinal vein that is in_the_left_side_of a multicellular organism.
right anterior cardinal vein also known as precardinal vein right; right precardinal vein An anterior cardinal vein that is in_the_right_side_of a multicellular organism.

renal tubule also known as renal tubule (generic); tubule of excretory system A renal tubule is a tube that filters, re-absorbs and secretes substances to rid an organism of waste and to play a role in fluid homeostasis.

lateral medullary reticular complex also known as lateral group of medullary reticular formation; lateral medullary reticular group; lateral reticular formation of the medulla oblongata; nuclei laterales myelencephali A nuclear complex of the medullary reticular formation that can be divided into three subnuclei: the parvocellular, magnocellular and the subtrigeminal[WP,modified].
intermediate reticular formation intermediate reticular formation_1
intermediate reticular nucleus A nucleus of brain that is part of a intermediate reticular formation.
pleural sac A serous sac that has the pleura and the pleural cavity as parts.

cardiac muscle tissue of right auricle also known as cardiac muscle of right auricular region; right atrium auricular region heart muscle; right auricular region myocardium A cardiac muscle tissue that is part of a right atrium auricular region.

cardiac muscle tissue of left auricle also known as cardiac muscle of left auricular region; left atrium auricular region heart muscle A cardiac muscle tissue that is part of a left atrium auricular region.

dorsolateral prefrontal cortex The dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DL-PFC or DLPFC), according to a more restricted definition, is roughly equivalent to Brodmann areas 9 and 46.[1] According to a broader definition DL-PFC consists of the lateral portions of Brodmann areas 9 - 12, of areas 45, 46, and the superior part of area 47.[2] These regions mainly receive their blood supply from the middle cerebral artery. With respect to neurotransmitter systems, there is evidence that dopamine plays a particularly important role in DL-PFC.[2]DL-PFC is connected to the orbitofrontal cortex, and to a variety of brain areas, which include the thalamus, parts of the basal ganglia (the dorsal caudate nucleus), the hippocampus, and primary and secondary association areas of neocortex, including posterior temporal, parietal, and occipital areas.

anterior cingulate cortex The frontal part of the cingulate cortex that resembles a collar form around the corpus callosum. It includes both the ventral and dorsal areas of the cingulate cortex. Wikipedia:File:Gray727.svg.
fronto-orbital gyrus also known as fronto-orbital gyrus; orbito-frontal gyrus; orbitofrontal gyrus fronto-orbital gyrus_1

lower rhombic lip also known as caudal rhombic lip; lower (caudal) rhombic lip Posterior portion of the rhombic lip contained within rhombomeres 2-8. Gives rise to several brainstem nuclei and choroid plexus.

upper rhombic lip also known as cerebellar anlage; presumptive cerebellum; rostral rhombic lip; upper (rostral) rhombic lip Anterior-most region of dorsal hindbrain within rhombomere 1, adjacent the midbrain-hindbrain boundary.
glandular acinus The many-lobed berry cluster of cells that is the terminous of a gland where the secretion is produced is acinar in form.
prostate epithelial cord also known as cord of prostate epithelium; epithelial cord of prostate A solid cord of prostate epithelium.
urogenital sinus lumen An anatomical space that surrounded_by a primitive urogenital sinus.
urogenital sinus mesenchyme also known as UGM Mesenchyme that surrounds primitive urogenital sinus.
embryonic cloacal epithelium An epithelium that is part of a embryonic cloaca.
prostate field A specific region of the urogenital sinus epithelium into the area in which the prostate gland will develop.

zona limitans intrathalamica also known as ZLI A narrow stripe of cells that lies between the prospective dorsal and ventral thalami. This boundary contains signals that pattern the prethalamic and thalamic territories of the future mid-diencephalon.
border of sublaminar layers S4 and S5 The intersection of sublaminar layers S4 and S5.
border of sublaminar layers S2 and S3 The intersection of sublaminar layers S2 and S3.
body of uterus also known as corpus uteri; uterine body; uterine corpus The part of the uterus above the isthmus and below the orifices of the uterine tubes.
digestive tract diverticulum Branch or outpocketing of the digestive tract.
sac also known as pouch sac_1

cavum septum pellucidum also known as cave of septum pellucidum; cavum of septum pellucidum; septum pellucidum cave; ventriculus septi pellucidi A space enclosed within the laminae of the septum pelludicum, the membranous partition that seperates the frontal horns of the ventricle. contains cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) that filters from the ventricles through the septal laminae. bounded anteriorly by the genu of the corpus callosum; superiorly by the body of the corpus callosum; posteriorly by the anterior limb and pillars of the fornix; inferiorly by the anterior commissure and the rostrum of the corpus callosum; and laterally by the leaflets of the septum pellucidum.

outer fibrous layer of periosteum also known as capsular layer of periosteum; external layer of periosteum; external periosteum; fibrous layer of periosteum; outer fibrous layer of periosteum outer fibrous layer of periosteum_1
endosteum A thin layer of connective tissue that lines the surface of the bony tissue that forms the medullary cavity of long bones.

zone of stomach also known as gastric zone; region of stomach; section of stomach A division of the stomach. The stomach can be divided based on mucosal histology (glandular epithelium and gastric glands) and the relative position and type of gastric gland.
nephrogenic zone also known as cortical nephrogenic niche; cortical nephrogenic zone Outer portion of the renal cortex. Site of formation of medullary and cortical elements.

metapodium region also known as metacarpal or metatarsal part of limb; metacarpus/metatarsus region; metapodial segment Intermediate segment of the autopod, between the mesopodial region and and acropodial region. Examples: metacarpal region, metatarsal region.

mesopodial skeleton also known as basipodium skeleton; carpal/tarsal skeleton; mesopodial skeleton; mesopodium skeleton; skeletal parts of mesopodium The collection of all skeletal elements in a mesopodium. Examples: the tarsal skeleton, the carpal skeleton.

tarsal skeleton also known as hind mesopodium; hind mesopodial skeleton; hind mesopodium skeleton; set of tarsal bones; skeletal parts of hind mesopodium; tarsal bones set; tarsalia Subdivision of skeleton that consists of endochondral elements distal to the zeugopodial skeletal elements which constitute the proximal region of the posterior autopod skeleton[PHENOSCAPE:ad].

carpal skeleton also known as carpal bones; carpal bones set; fore mesopodial skeleton; fore mesopodium skeleton; ossa carpi; skeletal parts of fore mesopodium; skeleton of carpus Subdivision of skeleton that consists of the endochondral elements distal to the anterior limb/fin zeugopodial skeletal elements which constitute the proximal region of the anterior autopod skeleton[PHENOSCAPE:ad].
anterior lateral plate mesoderm also known as ALPM anterior lateral plate mesoderm_1

anal column also known as column of Morgagni One of a number of vertical folds, produced by an infolding of the mucous membrane and some of the muscular tissue in the upper half of the lumen of the anal canal[WP].

medullary ray also known as Ferrein's pyramid; kidney medullary ray; renal medullary ray A renal, cortical lobule, consisting of the ascending or descending limbs of the loop of Henle or of the collecting tubules; medullary rays are regions where parallel arrays of straight tubules travel perpendicular to the capsule and extend from the cortex to the medulla.
interlobar artery also known as interlobar artery of kidney; kidney interlobar artery; renal interlobar artery; arteriae interlobares renis An artery that supplies a renal lobe.
interlobar vein also known as interlobar vein of kidney; venae interlobares renis The interlobar veins are veins of the renal circulation which drain the renal lobes.

Koller's sickle also known as Kohler's sickle A local thickening of cells that acts as a margin separating sheets of cells from posterior margin of avian blastoderms from hypoblasts as they migrate anteriorly to push primary hypoblast cells anteriorly to form a secondary hypoblast known as the endoblast.

secondary heart field also known as anterior heart field; anterior/second heart field; second heart field A specific region of the lateral mesoderm that will form the majority of the mesodermal component of the right ventricle, arterial pole (outflow tract) and venous pole (inflow tract).
anterior intestinal portal also known as fovea cardiaca Opening of the foregut into the midgut.
facial mesenchyme also known as face mesenchyme; mesenchyme of face Mesenchyme that is part of a developing face.
right auditory cortex An auditory cortex that is in the left side of a brain.
left auditory cortex An auditory cortex that is in the right side of a brain.
pole of cerebral hemisphere The anterior end of the hemisphere is named the frontal pole. The posterior end is named the occipital pole. The anterior end of the temporal lobe, the temporal pole.
root of optic nerve also known as optic nerve root; optic tract root; root of optic tract A nerve root that extends_fibers_into a nerve connecting eye with brain.
sensory root of trigeminal nerve also known as radix sensoria (nervus trigeminus [v]); radix sensoria nervus trigemini sensory root of trigeminal nerve_1
caudal root of abducens nerve also known as radix caudalis nervi abducentis caudal root of abducens nerve_1
rostral root of abducens nerve rostral root of abducens nerve_1
posterior lateral plate mesoderm also known as PLPM posterior lateral plate mesoderm_1
lobule also known as lobulus lobule_1
anatomical lobe also known as lobus A portion of an organ, such as the liver, lung, breast, or brain.

renal lobe also known as kidney lobe; lobi renalis; lobus renalis The portion of a kidney consisting of a renal medullary pyramid and the renal cortex above it[MP]. It is composed of many renal lobules[WP].

renal lobule also known as kidney lobule; lobulus renalis The portion of a renal lobe consisting of nephrons grouped around a single medullary ray and draining into a single collecting duct; human kidneys have multilobular, multipapillary architecture while mice and rats have unilobular, unipapillary kidneys.
wall of ureter also known as ureteral wall An anatomical wall that is part of a ureter.
kidney corticomedullary boundary The region demarcating the renal medulla from the surrounding cortex; end-stage renal failure may be associated with loss of the normal corticomedullary boundary.

retrotrapezoid nucleus The loose collection of neurons that reside in the rostral medulla close to the medullary surface, ventral and immediately caudal of nVII, that are crucial for CO2 sensing in the brain.
ureter smooth muscle also known as ureteral smooth muscle; ureteral smooth muscle layer The smooth muscle tissue surrounding the epithelium of the ureter.
optic neural crest optic neural crest_1
olfactory bulb plexiform layer olfactory bulb plexiform layer_1

main olfactory bulb The main olfactory bulb has a multi-layered cellular architecture. In order from surface to the center the layers are: Glomerular layer, External plexiform layer, Mitral cell layer, Internal plexiform layer, Granule cell layer[WP].

dentate gyrus subgranular zone also known as subgranular zone; subgranular zone of dentate gyrus A narrow layer of cells located between the granule cell layer and hilus of the dentate gyrus, where adult neurogenesis occurs.
post-embryonic organism also known as postnatal organism A multicellular organism that existence_starts_with a post-embryonic stage.
vomeronasal system A vertebrate nasal chemosensory system that is responsible for detecting intraspecific pheromonal cues as well as environmental odorants.
neurogenic placode also known as neurogenic placodes Cranial ectodermal placode with potential to develop into a component of the nervous system, such as nerves or ganglia.
bladder lumen also known as bladder cavity; cavity of urinary bladder; lumen of urinary bladder; urinary bladder lumen An anatomical space that is enclosed by a urinary bladder.
lumen of oropharynx also known as oropharyngeal cavity; oropharynx lumen An anatomical space that is enclosed by a oropharynx.
esophagus smooth muscle circular layer also known as circular muscle layer of esophagus; inner circular muscle layer of esophagus A circular muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a esophagus.
esophagus smooth muscle longitudinal layer also known as longitudinal muscle layer of esophagus; outer longitudinal muscle layer of esophagus esophagus smooth muscle longitudinal layer_1
excretory gland A gland that discharges its secretion through a duct opening on an internal or external surface of the body, as a lacrimal gland.

internodal tract also known as interatrial conduction tract; internodal conduction tract; internodal fasciculus; internodal tract muscle tissue A conducting pathway in the conducting tissue of heart through which electrical activity spreads from the SA node to the AV node.
spleen venous sinus also known as sinus lienalis; sinus splenicus; splenic sinus; venous sinus of red pulp of spleen spleen venous sinus_1
primitive superior sagittal sinus primitive superior sagittal sinus_1
statoacoustic epithelium also known as stato-acoustic epithelium statoacoustic epithelium_1
epithelium of pancreatic duct also known as pancreatic duct epithelium; pancreatic ductal epithelium An epithelium that is part of a pancreatic duct.

principal gastric gland also known as acid gland; glandula gastrica propria; main gastric gland; oxyntic gland; principal gland of fundus of stomach One of the gastric glands that secretes the hydrochloric acid of the gastric juice[Stedman's].
ureteropelvic junction also known as pelviureteric junction; pelvoureteric junction The junction between the ureter and the renal pelvis of the kidney.

ureterovesical junction also known as vesico-ureteral junction; vesico-ureteric junction; vesicoureteric junction The valve-like structure found at the site of entry of the ureter into the urinary bladder, normally displays an oblique angulation through the detrusor to avoid reflux of urine up the ureters and the kidney.
lumen of Rathke's pouch An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a Rathke's pouch.
remnant of lumen of Rathke's pouch remnant of lumen of Rathke's pouch_1

hypothalamo-hypophyseal system also known as hypophyseal portal system; hypothalamic hypophyseal portal system; hypothalamohypophyseal portal system; venae portales hypophysiales An intrinsic circulatory network that transports hormones from the median eminence of the hypothalamus to the adenohypophysis.

natal tooth also known as natal teeth Predeciduous teeth present at birth. They may be well formed and normal or may represent hornified epithelial structures without roots. They are found on the gingivae over the crest of the ridge and arise from accessory buds of the dental lamina ahead of the deciduous buds or from buds of the accessory dental lamina. (From Jablonski, Dictionary of Dentistry, 1992).
epicondyle epicondyle_1
condyle also known as condylus An articular prominence of a bone, typically present in pairs, resembling a pair of knuckles. Examples: Condyle of humerus, condyle of femur.
condyle of femur also known as condylus femoralis; condylus femoris; femoral condyle A condyle that is part of a distal epiphysis of femur.

medial condyle of femur also known as condylus medialis femoris The medial condyle is one of the two projections on the lower extremity of femur. The medial condyle is larger than the lateral (outer) condyle due to more weight bearing caused by the center of gravity being medial to the knee. On the posterior surface of the condyle the linea aspera (a ridge running down the posterior shaft of the femur) turns into the medial supracondylar ridge. The outermost protrusion on the medial surface of the medial condyle is referred to as the 'medial epicondyle' and can be palpated by running fingers medially from the patella with the knee in flexion.

lateral condyle of femur also known as condylus lateralis femoris The lateral condyle is one of the two projections on the lower extremity of femur. It is the more prominent and is the broader both in its antero-posterior and transverse diameters.

lateral epicondyle of femur also known as epicondylus lateralis (femur); epicondylus lateralis femoris The lateral epicondyle of the femur, smaller and less prominent than the medial epicondyle, gives attachment to the fibular collateral ligament of the knee-joint. Directly below it is a small depression from which a smooth well-marked groove curves obliquely upward and backward to the posterior extremity of the condyle.

medial epicondyle of femur also known as epicondylus medialis (femur) The medial epicondyle of the femur is a bony protrusion located on the medial side of the bone's distal end. Located above the medial condyle, it bears an elevation, the adductor tubercle, which serves for the attachment of the superficial part, or 'tendinous insertion', of the adductor magnus. This tendinous part here forms an intermuscular septum which forms the medial separation between the thigh's flexors and extensors. Behind it, and proximally to the medial condyle is a rough impression which gives origin to the medial head of the Gastrocnemius.
condyle of humerus also known as condylus humeri; humeral condyle The distal end of the humerus, including the trochlea, capitulum and the olecranon, coronoid and radial fossae.
condyle of tibia also known as tibial condyle One of the lateral or medial condyles of the tibia.

medial condyle of tibia also known as condylus medialis (tibia); condylus medialis tibiae The medial condyle is the medial portion of the upper extremity of tibia. It is the site of insertion for the Semimembranosus muscle[WP].

lateral condyle of tibia also known as condylus lateralis (tibia); condylus lateralis tibiae The lateral condyle is the lateral portion of the upper extremity of tibia. It serves as the insertion for the Biceps femoris muscle[WP].

cranial sensory ganglion also known as cranial nerve sensory ganglion; ganglion sensorium cranialium; ganglion sensorium nervi cranialis; sensory ganglion of cranial nerve The ganglion found on the root of each cranial nerve, containing the cell bodies of afferent (sensory) neurons.
primary chorionic villus A chorionic villus that is a solid outgrowth of the cytotrophoblast that protrudes into the syncytiotrophoblast.
secondary chorionic villus A chorionic villus that is has a core of loose connective tissue, which in humans grows into the primary villi about the third week of development.

tertiary chorionic villus Tertiary chorionic villi contain embryonic blood vessels that develop from mesenchymal cells in the loose connective tissue core. These blood vessels connect up with vessels that develop in the chorion and connecting stalk and begin to circulate embryonic blood about the third week of development in humans.
multicellular anatomical structure also known as multicellular structure An anatomical structure that has more than one cell as a part.

cell cluster organ A small cluster of cells of various types which form a discrete structure, largely delimited by a morphological boundary and whose components work together to make the whole structure capable of a specific function.

pulmonary neuroendocrine body also known as pulmonary neuroepithelial body Corpuscular, organoid structures composed of PNECs, found as distinctive innervated clusters only within intrapulmonary airways, where they appear concentrated at airway branch points; NEBs reach from the basement membrane to the airway lumen and are thought to function as oxygen sensors.

placental cotyledon also known as placenta cotyledon Round structure consisting of chorionic villi[PMID]. A separation of the decidua basalis of the placenta, separated by placental septa. Each cotyledon consists of a main stem of a chorionic villus as well as its branches and subbranches. The cotyledons receive fetal blood from chorionic vessels, which branch off cotyledon vessels into the cotyledons, which, in turn, branch into capillaries. The cotyledons are surrounded by maternal blood, which can exchange oxygen and nutrients with the fetal blood in the capillaries[WP].
aggregate regional part of brain A regional part of brain consisting of multiple brain regions that are not related through a simple volummetric part of hierarchy, e.g., basal ganglia[NIF].

basal nucleus of telencephalon also known as basal nucleus; basal magnocellular nucleus (substantia innominata); basal nuclei of Meynert; basal nucleus of Meynert; basal substance of telencephalon; ganglion of Meynert; Meynert's nucleus; nucleus basalis; nucleus basalis of Meynert; substantia basalis telencephali A group of neurons in the basal forebrain that has wide projections to the neocortex and is rich in acetylcholine and choline acetyltransferase. It undergoes degeneration in paralysis agitans and Alzheimer's disease.

collection of basal ganglia also known as basal ganglia; basal ganglia set; basal nuclei (basal ganglia); set of basal ganglia Subcortical masses of gray matter in the forebrain and midbrain that are richly interconnected and so viewed as a functional system. The nuclei usually included are the caudate nucleus (caudoputamen in rodents), putamen, globus pallidus, substantia nigra (pars compacta and pars reticulata) and the subthalamic nucleus. Some also include the nucleus accumbens and ventral pallidum.

spiral valve of cystic duct also known as Heister's valve; plica spiralis; plica spiralis (ductus cysticus); spiral fold of cystic duct; valve of Heister A series of crescentic folds of mucous membrane somewhat spirally arranged on the interior of the gallbladder and continuing into the cystic duct.
tubotympanic recess epithelium The dorsal portion of the embryonic first endodermal pharyngeal pouch; it develops into the middle ear cavity.
dorsal part of pharyngeal pouch 1 also known as dorsal 1st branchial pouch; dorsal pharyngeal pouch 1 dorsal part of pharyngeal pouch 1
ventral part of pharyngeal pouch 1 also known as ventral 1st branchial pouch; ventral pharyngeal pouch 1 ventral part of pharyngeal pouch 1
dorsal part of pharyngeal pouch 2 also known as dorsal 2nd branchial pouch; dorsal pharyngeal pouch 2 dorsal part of pharyngeal pouch 2
ventral part of pharyngeal pouch 2 also known as ventral 2nd branchial pouch; ventral pharyngeal pouch 2 ventral part of pharyngeal pouch 2

dorsal part of pharyngeal pouch 3 also known as dorsal 3rd arch pharyngeal pouch endoderm; dorsal 3rd branchial pouch; dorsal pharyngeal pouch 3; dorsal wing of pharyngeal pouch 3 dorsal part of pharyngeal pouch 3

ventral part of pharyngeal pouch 3 also known as ventral 3rd arch pharyngeal pouch endoderm; ventral 3rd branchial pouch; ventral pharyngeal pouch 3; ventral wing of pharyngeal pouch 3 ventral part of pharyngeal pouch 3
dorsal part of pharyngeal pouch 4 also known as dorsal 4th branchial pouch; dorsal pharyngeal pouch 4 dorsal part of pharyngeal pouch 4
ventral part of pharyngeal pouch 4 also known as ventral 4th branchial pouch; ventral pharyngeal pouch 4 ventral part of pharyngeal pouch 4
dorsal part of pharyngeal pouch 5 also known as dorsal 5th branchial pouch; dorsal pharyngeal pouch 5 dorsal part of pharyngeal pouch 5
ventral part of pharyngeal pouch 5 also known as ventral 5th branchial pouch; ventral pharyngeal pouch 5 ventral part of pharyngeal pouch 5
6th arch mesenchyme also known as 6th pharyngeal arch mesenchyme Mesenchyme that is part of a pharyngeal arch 6.

anterior part of tongue The portion of the tongue in front of the terminal sulcus. At the apex, thin and narrow, it is directed forward against the lingual surfaces of the lower incisor teeth. It is derived primarily from the first pharyngeal arch.

posterior part of tongue also known as base of tongue; pars posterior (dorsum linguae); pars posterior dorsi linguae; pars posterior linguae; pars postsulcalis (dorsum linguae); pharyngeal part of tongue; pharyngeal portion of dorsum of tongue; posterior part of dorsum of tongue; postsulcal part of dorsum of tongue The Posterior tongue, or pharyngeal part, is the part of the tongue behind the terminal sulcus. At its root, it is directed backward, and connected with the hyoid bone by the Hyoglossi and Genioglossi muscles and the hyoglossal membrane; with the epiglottis by three folds (glossoepiglottic) of mucous membrane; with the soft palate by the glossopalatine arches; and with the pharynx by the Constrictores pharyngis superiores and the mucous membrane. It is derived primarily from the third pharyngeal arch. (The second arch has a substantial contribution during fetal development, but this later atrophies. The fourth arch may also contribute, depending upon how the boundaries of the tongue are defined.).

copula linguae also known as copula A single midventral prominence deriving from the ventral bases of pharyngeal arches 2, 3 and 4 - provides the covering of the posterior of the tongue //The furcula is at first separated from the tuberculum impar by a depression, but later by a ridge, the copula, formed by the forward growth and fusion of the ventral ends of the second, third, and part of the fourth branchial arches[WP].

fundic gastric gland also known as fundal gland; fundus gland; gastric fundal gland; gastric fundus gland; gastric gland of fundus of stomach The fundus glands (or fundic glands, or gastric glands) are found in the body and fundus of the stomach. They are simple tubes, two or more of which open into a single duct.
food storage organ An organ of the digestive tract that is capable of retaining and storing food.

stomach non-glandular epithelium also known as stomach aglandular epithelium Am epithelium that lines the stomach which lacks glands. In addition to a glandular epithelium, the stomachs of some vertebrates also has a second region characterized by a nonglandular epithelium, devoid of gastric glands.
median ovary median ovary_1
1st arch mesenchyme also known as mesenchyme of 1st arch Mesenchyme that is part of a pharyngeal arch 1.
1st arch maxillary mesenchyme also known as mesenchyme of maxillary component Mesenchyme that is part of a 1st arch maxillary component.

entire pharyngeal arch associated mesenchyme also known as associated mesenchyme of pharyngeal region; entire branchial arch associated mesenchyme; pharyngeal arch associated mesenchyme The sum total of mesenchymal tissue in the pharyngeal arch region. Pharyngeal mesenchyme is undifferentiated, loose connective tissue derived mostly from mesoderm, and also contains ectodermally derived neural crest cells.
oral gland Gland of the epithelium lining the oral cavity. The most common are the salivary glands.
mucosa of dorsum of tongue also known as mucosa of dorsal surface of tongue A mucosa that is part of a dorsum of tongue.
malleus cartilage element A malleus endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.
stapes cartilage element A stapes endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.
future tongue A compound organ that has the potential to develop into a tongue.
hypopharyngeal eminence also known as hypobranchial eminence hypopharyngeal eminence_1
hypoglossal cord hypoglossal cord_1

pharyngeal opening of pharyngotympanic tube also known as ostium pharyngeum tubae auditivae; ostium pharyngeum tubae auditoriae; pharyngeal opening of auditory tube; pharyngeal opening of eustachian tube; pharyngeal orifice of auditory tube; pharyngeal orifice of eustachian tube; pharyngeal orifice of pharyngotympanic tube; pharyngeal ostium of auditory tube; pharyngeal ostium of eustachian tube; pharyngeal ostium of pharyngotympanic tube; pharyngeal tubal ostium On the lateral wall of the nasal part of the pharynx is the pharyngeal opening of auditory tube (pharyngeal ostium), somewhat triangular in shape, and bounded behind by a firm prominence, the torus or cushion, caused by the medial end of the cartilage of the tube which elevates the mucous membrane.
lumen of nasopharynx also known as nasopharyngeal luman; nasopharynx cavity; nasopharynx lumen lumen of nasopharynx_1
pharyngotympanic tube epithelium also known as auditory tube epithelium; eustachian tube epithelium pharyngotympanic tube epithelium_1
tympanic cavity epithelium tympanic cavity epithelium_1
open anatomical space An anatomical space with at least one opening to another space or the exterior.
auditory meatus epithelium auditory meatus epithelium_1

tympanic plate also known as pars tympanica (os temporale); tympanic part of temporal bone The tympanic part of the temporal bone is a curved plate of bone lying below the squama and in front of the mastoid process.

outer epithelial layer of tympanic membrane also known as cuticular layer of tympanic membrane; cuticular stratum of tympanic membrane; outer cuticular layer of tympanic membrane; outer layer of tympanic membrane; tympanic membrane external acoustic meatus epithelial component A portion of the external acoustic meatus epithelium which makes up the outer (cuticular) layer of the tympanic membrane.

intermediate layer of tympanic membrane also known as connective tissue layer of tympanic membrane; fibrous layer of tympanic membrane; fibrous stratum of tympanic membrane; intermediate fibrous layer of tympanic membrane; tympanic endothelium The intermediate fibrous layer of the tympanic membrane.
layer of tympanic membrane also known as tympanic membrane layer layer of tympanic membrane_1
chromaffin system Organ system subdivision that consists primarily of chromaffin cells and their supporting structures.

sacral neural crest One of the 5 distinct and partially overlapping functional domains of the premigratory neural crest. The vagal and sacral neural crest cells develop into the ganglia of the enteric nervous system, also known as the parasympathetic ganglia.
network of trabecular spaces in bone tissue also known as trabecular network of bone tissue Tissue cavity consisting of intercommunicating trabecular spaces in the cancellous bone.
cuboidal epithelium An epithelium consisting of cuboidal epithelial cells.
optic choroid vascular plexus also known as CVP optic choroid vascular plexus_1
future common hepatic duct An extrahepatic bile duct that has the potential to develop into a common hepatic duct.
future dermis Mesenchyme that has the potential to develop into a dermis.
future diaphragm A structure that will develop into a diaphragm.
future falx cerebri A developing anatomical structure that has the potential to develop into a falx cerebri.
future hindbrain meninx also known as future hindbrain meninges A multi-tissue structure that has the potential to develop into a meninx of hindbrain.
future metencephalon A developing anatomical structure that has the potential to develop into a metencephalon.
future myelencephalon A developing anatomical structure that has the potential to develop into a myelencephalon.
future facial nucleus A gray matter that has the potential to develop into a facial nucleus.
future inferior salivatory nucleus A gray matter that has the potential to develop into a inferior salivatory nucleus.
future superior salivatory nucleus A gray matter that has the potential to develop into a superior salivatory nucleus.
future nucleus ambiguus A gray matter that has the potential to develop into a nucleus ambiguus.
future dorsal motor nucleus of vagus A gray matter that has the potential to develop into a dorsal motor nucleus of vagus nerve.

future pterygopalatine ganglion also known as future Meckel ganglion; future Meckel's ganglion; future nasal ganglion; future palatine ganglion; future pterygopalatine ganglia; future sphenopalatine ganglion; future sphenopalatine parasympathetic ganglion A ganglion that has the potential to develop into a pterygopalatine ganglion.
femur cartilage element also known as femoral cartilage condensation A femur endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.
embryonic autopod plate also known as autopod plate; limb plate The distal elements of the developing limb of vertebrates that will give rise to the autopod (e.g. manus, pes, paw).

conducting tissue of heart also known as specialized conducting tissue of heart; specialized muscle tissue of heart Any portion of cardiac muscle tissue that is part of the conducting system of heart or the Purkinje fibers.

gastroduodenal artery A small blood vessel in the abdomen that supplies blood directly to the pylorus (distal part of the stomach) and proximal part of the duodenum, and indirectly to the pancreatic head (via the anterior and posterior superior pancreaticoduodenal arteries).

neuroendocrine gland also known as neuroendocrine system gland Any of the organized aggregations of cells that function as secretory or excretory organs and that release hormones in response to neural stimuli.
secretory circumventricular organ A circumventricular organ that is capable of secreting substances into the cerebrospinal fluid.
sensory circumventricular organ A circumventricular organ that is capable of monitoring the levels of substances to the cerebrospinal fluid.
epithelial sheet An epithelial sheet is a flat surface consisting of closely packed epithelial cells.
polarized epithelium A polarized epithelium is an epithelium where the epithelial sheet is oriented with respect to the planar axis.
primitive sex cord of indifferent gonad also known as indifferent sex cord; primitive sex cords A sex cord that is part of a indifferent gonad.
seminal vesicle fluid also known as secretion of seminal vesicle; seminal vesicle secretion A bodily secretion that is produced by a seminal vesicle.

paraurethral gland also known as periurethral gland; Skene gland; Skene's gland; female prostate; para-urethral gland; urethral gland of clitoral urethra The numerous mucous-secreting glands found in several female mammalian species (including rodents and humans) on the anterior wall of the vagina, around the lower end of the urethra, and possessing a common paraurethral duct which opens (on each side) near the external urethral orifice; they are homologous with the prostate gland in males, have highly variable anatomy, and are believed to be the source of the female ejaculate, a lubricating fluid with a similar consistency to male prostatic fluid that is expelled through the urethra during sexual stimulation; like the male prostate, these glands are susceptible to infection (skenitis), cyst development, and cancer.

paraurethral duct also known as duct of paraurethral gland; duct of Skene's gland; female prostate duct; paraurethral gland duct; periurethral duct; Skene's duct The Skene's ducts are a pair of ducts leading from the Skene's glands to the surface of the vulva, to the left and right of the urethral opening.

male accessory sex gland Any gland, other than the gonad, associated with the genital tract, such as the ampulla of the ductus deferens and the bulbourethral, prostate and vesicular glands of the male.

mating plug also known as copulation plug; copulatory plug; sperm plug; vaginal plug A gelatinous secretion used in the mating of some species. It is deposited by a male into a female genital tract and later hardens into a plug or glues the tract together.
duct of major vestibular gland also known as duct of greater vestibular gland; greater vestibular gland duct One of a pair of ducts leading from the Bartholin's glands to the surface of the vulva.
duct of bulbourethral gland also known as bulbourethral gland duct; duct of bulbo-urethral gland; ductus glandulae bulbourethralis A duct that is part of a bulbo-urethral gland.
skin mucus A mucous secretion that is produced by glands in the epidermis.

parietomastoid suture also known as parieto-mastoid suture of skull; parietomastoid suture of skull Unites the mastoid process of the temporal with the region of the mastoid angle of the parietal[WP:Squamosal_suture].
sphenofrontal suture also known as frontosphenoid suture; sphenofrontal suture of skull The Sphenofrontal suture is the cranial suture between the sphenoid bone and the frontal bone.
sphenoparietal suture also known as spheno-parietal suture; sphenoparietal suture of skull The Sphenoparietal suture is the cranial suture between the sphenoid bone and the parietal bone.
sphenozygomatic suture also known as sphenozygomatica suture of skull The Sphenozygomatic suture is the cranial suture between the sphenoid bone and the zygomatic bone.

occipitomastoid suture also known as occipitomastoid suture of skull The occipitomastoid suture is the cranial suture between the occipital bone and the mastoid portion of the temporal bone. It is continuous with the lambdoidal suture.
lumen of lymphatic vessel also known as lumen of lymphatic duct; lymphatic vessel lumen An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a lymphatic vessel.
lumen of blood vessel also known as blood vessel lumen An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a blood vessel.

eyebrow The eyebrow is an area of thick, delicate hairs above the eye that follows the shape of the lower margin of the brow ridges. Their main function is to protect the eye, but they are also important to human communication and facial expression. It is not uncommon for people to modify their eyebrows by means of hair addition or removal, make up, or piercings.
collection of hairs also known as hairs; hairs set; pili; set of hairs An anatomical cluster that composed_primarily_of a strand of hair.
collection of hair on face also known as facial hairs set; set of facial hairs A collection of hairs that is part of a face.
coat of hair also known as hair coat; set of coat hairs coat of hair_1

beard The collection of hair that grows on the chin, cheeks and neck of human beings. Usually, only pubescent or adult males are able to grow beards. However, women with hirsutism may develop a beard. When differentiating between upper and lower facial hair, a beard specifically includes the moustache, which refers to hair above the upper lip and around it.
collection of eyelashes also known as cilia; eyelashes; eyelashes set; set of eyelashes A collection of hair on face that is part of a eyelash.

moustache also known as mustache Facial hair grown on the outer surface of the upper lip. It may or may not be accompanied by a type of beard, a facial hair style grown and cropped to cover most of the lower half of the face.
region of neural crest region of neural crest_1
strand of hair of face also known as face hair; face hair strand; hair of face A strand of hair that is part of a face.

bulb of aorta also known as aorta bulb; aortic bulb; aortic root; bulb of ascending aorta; bulbus aortae; root of aorta; supraaortic valve area The portion of the left ventricular outflow tract delineated by the sinotubular ridge superiorly and the bases of the valve leaflets inferiorly; it comprises the aortic sinuses, the aortic valve leaflets, the commissures, and the interleaflet triangles.
sinotubular junction also known as sinotubular ridge The point in the ascending aorta where the aortic sinuses end and the aorta becomes a tubular structure.

Schweigger-Seidel sheath A phagocytic sleeve that is part of a sheathed arteriole of the spleen, and is sometimes referred to as a splenic ellipsoid. It is a spindle-shaped thickening in the walls of the second part of the arterial branches forming the penicilli in the spleen.
nutrient foramen vein also known as nutrient vein A vein or veins draining a bone and emerging from a nutrient foramen.

nutrient foramen artery also known as nutrient artery The medullary or nutrient artery, usually accompanied by one or two veins, sends branches upward and downward to the bone marrow, which ramify in the medullary membrane, and give twigs to the adjoining canals.

straight venules of kidney also known as set of straight venules of kidney; venulae rectae of kidney; venulae rectae renis The straight venules of kidney are branches from the plexuses at the apices of the medullary pyramids, formed by the terminations of the arteriae rectae. They run outward in a straight course between the tubes of the medullary substance, and joining, as above stated, the interlobular veins, form venous arcades; these in turn unite and form veins which pass along the sides of the pyramids. Contains fenestrated capillaries.
liver trabecula also known as liver trabeculae A trabecula that is part of a liver.
rete ovarii also known as rete ovarii of ovary A structure formed from the primary sex cords in females, counterpart of the rete testis in males.

male urethral gland also known as gland of Littre; gland of male urethra; Littre's gland; male urethra gland; urethral gland (male) Any of the numerous small mucous-secreting glands located in the wall of the penile urethra.
female urethral gland also known as female urethra gland; gland of female urethra; urethral gland (female) An urethral gland that is part of a female urethra.
protuberance A roughly circular bulge in a surface.
right atrium venous valve right atrium venous valve_1

pair of dorsal aortae also known as paired dorsal aortae The paired arterial structures of the embryo that supplies each developing somite via efferent segmental arteries; the dorsal aortae articulate with the umbilical arteries, which return mixed blood to the villi of the chorion for reoxygenation.
aortic system aortic system_1
genital artery also known as gonadal artery One of the laterally paired arteries that supply the gonads.
renal portal vein also known as renal portal veins A portal vein that empties into capillaries within the kidneys.

hepatic portal system also known as hepatic-portal system; portal system of liver A portal system that begins in capillaries in the wall of the digestive tract and and runs as the hepatic portal vein to the liver.

trunk of common carotid artery also known as common carotid arterial trunk The initial part of the entire common carotid artery ending with the point where the artery bifurcates into an external carotid artery and an internal carotid artery.

carotid duct also known as ductus caroticus A segment of the embryonic dorsal aorta between points of juncture with the third and fourth arch arteries; it regresses early in development to allow the carotid axis to take its definitive appearance.
bona-fide anatomical boundary An anatomical boundary that corresponds to some physical discontinuity.

mesencephalic vein also known as vena mesencephalica; venae mesencephalicae One of the several veins that drain the mesencephalon; the posterior ones are tributaries to the great cerebral vein; the lateral ones are tributaries to the basal vein. The main veins are: pontomesencephalic vein [TA] (vena pontomesencephalica [TA]), interpeduncular veins [TA] (venae interpedunculares [TA]), intercollicular vein [TA] (vena intercollicularis [TA]), and lateral mesencephalic vein [TA] (vena mesencephalica lateralis [TA])[MedLex]. The major vein of the midbrain, which crosses the midbrain medially to meet it's partner the mesencephalic artery[XAO].

plica semilunaris of conjunctiva also known as plica semilunaris (conjunctiva); semilunar fold of conjunctiva The plica semilunaris is a small fold of bulbar conjunctiva on the medial canthus of the eye. It is loose, so that eye movements are not restricted.

blood clot also known as coagulated blood; fibrin clot; hemostatic plug; thrombus A semisolid gelatinous mass of coagulated blood that consists of red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets entrapped in a fibrin network.

granulation tissue Highly vascularized tissue that replaces the initial fibrin clot in a wound. Vascularization is by ingrowth of capillary endothelium from the surrounding vasculature. The tissue is also rich in fibroblasts (that will eventually produce the fibrous tissue) and leucocytes.

laryngeal apparatus also known as laryngeal cartilage system Apparatus located between the lungs and the buccal cavity. This apparatus is composed of a pair of arytenoid cartilages that are supported by the cricoid ring.
laryngeal pre-cartilage condensation laryngeal pre-cartilage condensation_1
cricoid pre-cartilage condensation cricoid pre-cartilage condensation_1
arytenoid swellings Paired primordial elevations, on either side of the embryonic larynx, within which the arytenoid cartilages are formed.
thyroid pre-cartilage condensation thyroid pre-cartilage condensation_1
arytenoid pre-cartilage condensation also known as arytenoid swelling pre-cartilage condensation arytenoid pre-cartilage condensation_1
laryngeal associated mesenchyme laryngeal associated mesenchyme_1
anatomical line between pupils also known as inter-pupillary line; interpupillary line anatomical line between pupils_1
left pupil also known as pupil of left eye A pupil that is part of a left eye.
right pupil also known as pupil of right eye A pupil that is part of a right eye.
thalamic complex A nuclear complex which in mammals consists of four parts, the hypothalamus, epithalamus, ventral thalamus, and dorsal thalamus[WP,modified].

future cardiac atrium also known as presumptive atrium heart tube; primordial atrium; primordial cardiac atrium Multi-tissue structure that is part of the heart tube and will become the cardiac atrium.
eyeball of camera-type eye also known as bulbus oculi; eye globe; eyeball The core globe-shaped component of the camera-type eye.
anatomical line between outer ears anatomical line between outer ears_1
placodal ectoderm placodal ectoderm_1
stroma of thyroid gland also known as thyroid gland stroma; thyroid stroma The connective tissue that supports the lobules and follicles of the thyroid gland.

palatopharyngeus muscle also known as palatopharyngeal muscle; palatopharyngeus; pharyngopalatinus muscle The palatopharyngeus or palatopharyngeal or pharyngopalatinus muscle is a long, fleshy fasciculus, narrower in the middle than at either end, forming, with the mucous membrane covering its surface, the palatopharyngeal arch.

uvular muscle also known as uvular muscle_1 The musculus uvulae (azygos uvulae) is a muscle of the soft palate. It arises from the posterior nasal spine of the palatine bones and from the palatine aponeurosis. It descends to be inserted into the uvula and functions to move and shape it. It is innervated by the pharyngeal branch of the vagus nerve via the pharyngeal plexus[WP].
molar gland also known as molar salivary gland molar gland_1
anterior buccal gland The racemose, mucous or serous glands in the submucous tissue of the cheeks.

merocrine gland An exocrine gland whose secretions are excreted via exocytosis from secretory cells into an epithelial-walled duct or ducts and thence onto a bodily surface or into the lumen; the gland releases its product and no part of the gland is lost or damaged.

posterior meningeal artery also known as terminal branch of ascending pharyngeal artery The posterior meningeal artery are small vessels which are branches of the ascending pharyngeal artery which supply the dura mater. It passes through the mastoid foramen before entering the cranium via the jugular foramen.

middle meningeal artery The middle meningeal artery is typically the third branch of the first part (retromandibular part) of the maxillary artery; one of the two terminal branches of the external carotid artery. After branching off the maxillary artery in the infratemporal fossa, it runs through the foramen spinosum to supply the dura mater and the calvaria. The middle meningeal artery is the largest of the three (paired) arteries which supply the meninges, the others being the anterior meningeal artery and the posterior meningeal artery. In approximately half of subjects it branches into an accessory meningeal artery. The middle meningeal artery runs beneath the pterion. It is vulnerable to injury at this point, where the skull is thin. Rupture of the artery may give rise to an epidural hematoma.

anterior meningeal artery also known as anterior meningeal branch of anterior ethmoidal artery; ramus meningeus anterior (arteria ethmoidalis anterioris) A meningeal branch to the dura mater arising from the anterior ethmoidal artery.
1st arch mandibular mesenchyme from neural crest Mesenchyme that develops_from a neural crest and is part of a 1st arch mandibular mesenchyme.
1st arch maxillary mesenchyme from neural crest Mesenchyme that develops_from a neural crest and is part of a 1st arch maxillary mesenchyme.

2nd arch mesenchyme from neural crest also known as neural crest derived arch 2 mesenchyme; pharyngeal arch 2 mesenchyme from neural crest Mesenchyme that develops_from a neural crest and is part of a 2nd arch mesenchyme.

4th arch mesenchyme from neural crest also known as 4th pharyngeal arch mesenchyme derived from neural crest; mesenchyme derived from neural crest of mesenchyme of 4th arch; neural crest derived arch 4 mesenchyme; pharyngeal arch 4 mesenchyme from neural crest Mesenchyme that develops_from a neural crest and is part of a 4th arch mesenchyme.

6th arch mesenchyme from neural crest also known as neural crest derived arch 6 mesenchyme; pharyngeal arch 6 mesenchyme from neural crest Mesenchyme that develops_from a neural crest and is part of a 6th arch mesenchyme.
