1st arch mesenchyme from neural crest also known as mesenchyme derived from neural crest of mesenchyme of 1st arch; neural crest derived arch 1 mesenchyme; pharyngeal arch 1 mesenchyme from neural crest Mesenchyme that develops_from a neural crest and is part of a 1st arch mesenchyme.

umbilical blood vessel also known as allantoic vessel; umbilical cord blood vessel; umbilical vessel One of the three blood vessels, usually one large umbilical vein and two small umbilical arteries, buried within Wharton's jelly, that transport blood to and from the placenta, where exchange between the mother and fetus takes place; the umbilical vein carries oxygenated, nutrient-rich blood from the placenta to the fetus, and the umbilical arteries carry deoxygenated, nutrient-depleted blood from the fetus to the placenta.

operculum of brain The most posterior portion of the inferior frontal gyrus of the frontal lobe in the brain. In an axial plane, the Sylvian fissure extends from the operculum posteriorly to divide the frontal from the temporal lobe. Broca's area is a notable part of the operculum, which plays a key role in conversation or speech production, reading and writing. Its vascular supply comes from the M3 branches of the middle cerebral artery[WP].
filum terminale internum also known as internal part of filum terminale filum terminale internum_1
filum terminale externum also known as external part of filum terminale filum terminale externum_1
hyoid apparatus A group of bones comprised of hyoid body and two pairs of cornua (i.e. greater cornua and lesser cornua), and lies just below the tongue, above the thyroid cartilage.
zone of hyoid bone also known as hyoid bone zone A zone of bone organ that is part of a hyoid bone.
space in vertebral column also known as vertebral column opening; vertebral conduit Any anatomical space that is part of a vertebral column.
mesocardium The part of the embryonic mesentery which connects the embryonic heart with the body wall in front and the foregut behind.

pericardial sinus There are two Pericardial sinuses: transverse and oblique. The cul-de-sac enclosed between the limbs of the inverted U of the venous mesocardium lies behind the left atrium and is known as the oblique sinus. The passage between the venous and arterial mesocardiabi.e. , between the aorta and pulmonary artery in front and the superior vena cava behindbis termed the transverse sinus. Also, the sinus that forms in the pericardial cavity where the dorso-mesentary pericardium reside. Can be used to pass ligature during cardiac surgery.

oblique pericardial sinus also known as oblique sinus of pericardial cavity The cul-de-sac enclosed between the limbs of the inverted U of the venous mesocardium lies behind the left atrium.[WP,unvetted].
lacrimal punctum A minute orifice on the summit of the papillae lacrimales, which is the commencement point of the lacrimal canaliculi.
midbrain basal plate also known as basal plate midbrain; basal plate midbrain region Portion of tissue that is dorsolateral to the floor plate and part of the midbrain.
midbrain neural tube Portion of neural tube that gives rise to the midbrain.
motor root of facial nerve also known as facial nerve motor root; motor component of the VIIth (facial) nerve; seventh cranial nerve motor root motor root of facial nerve_1
layer of sclera layer of sclera_1

episcleral layer of eyeball also known as episclera; episcleral layer; lamina episcleralis The episclera is the outermost layer of the sclera. It is composed of loose, fibrous, elastic tissue and attaches to Tenon's capsule. A vascular plexus is found between the conjunctiva and the sclera consisting of two layers of vessels, the superficial episcleral vessels and the deep episcleral vessels.

suprachoroid lamina also known as lamina suprachorioidea; lamina suprachoroidea On the external surface of the optic choroid is a thin membrane, the suprachoroid lamina, composed of delicate non-vascular lamellae-each lamella consisting of a network of fine elastic fibers among which are branched pigment cells.
scleral endothelium An endothelium that is part of a sclera.
substantia propria of sclera also known as scleral stroma; stroma of sclera; subsantia propria sclerae; substantia propria sclerae A stroma that is part of a sclera.
scleral mesenchyme Mesenchyme surrounding the developing optic cup which develops into the sclera.
epithelial scleral papilla layer also known as scleral papillae epithelial scleral papilla layer_1
extraembryonic epithelium also known as extra-embryonic epithelium An epithelium that is part of a extraembryonic structure.

non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium also known as epithelium stratificatum squamosum noncornificatum; nonkeratinizing stratified squamous epithelium; stratified squamous non-keratinized epithelium; stratified squamous nonkeratinizing epithelium Stratified squamous epithelium is a stratified squamous epithelium, the cells of which synthesizes but does not accumulate keratin. Examples: epithelium of vagina, epithelium of wall of esophagus.
subdivision of conjunctiva also known as conjunctiva region; region of conjunctiva One of the three major regions of the conjunctiva.
bulbar conjunctiva also known as ocular conjunctiva The conjunctiva covering the anterior surface of the sclera and the surface epithelium of the cornea.

conjunctival fornix also known as conjunctiva fornix; forniceal conjunctiva; fornix conjunctiva The space formed by the junction of the bulbar and palpebral portions of the conjunctiva, that of the upper lid being the superior conjunctival fornix (fornix conjunctivae superior) and that of the lower lid, the inferior conjunctival fornix (fornix conjunctivae inferior); the fornix is loose and flexible, allowing the free movement of the lids and eyeball.
immature eye also known as future eye Developing anatomical structure that develops into the eyeball and associated structures.
neural crest-derived structure An anatomical structure that develops from the neural crest.
structure with developmental contribution from neural crest An anatomical structure that has some part that develops from the neural crest.
germ layer / neural crest germ layer / neural crest_1
skeletal element of eye region A skeletal element that is part of a orbital region.
cranial skeletal system Skeletal subdivision of the head including skull (cranium plus mandible), pharyngeal and/or hyoid apparatus.
limb bud mesenchyme Mesenchyme that is part of a limb bud.
paired limb/fin bud mesenchyme Mesenchyme that is part of a limb/fin bud.
eyelid mesenchyme Mesenchyme that is part of a developing eyelid.
epithelium of handplate also known as handplate epithelium An epithelium that is part of a handplate.

maxillary process mesenchyme from head mesenchyme Mesenchyme that develops_from a head mesenchyme from mesoderm and is part of a maxillary process mesenchyme.

3rd arch mesenchyme from head mesenchyme also known as head mesenchyme derived arch 3 mesenchyme; mesenchyme derived from head mesoderm of mesenchyme of 3rd arch; pharyngeal arch 3 mesenchyme from head mesenchyme Mesenchyme that develops_from a head mesenchyme from mesoderm and is part of a 3rd arch mesenchyme.

4th arch mesenchyme from head mesenchyme also known as head mesenchyme derived arch 4 mesenchyme; mesenchyme derived from head mesoderm of mesenchyme of 4th arch; pharyngeal arch 4 mesenchyme from head mesenchyme Mesenchyme that develops_from a head mesenchyme from mesoderm and is part of a 4th arch mesenchyme.

otic capsule pre-cartilage condensation also known as otic capsule anlage An otic capsule endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.
Reichert's cartilage pre-cartilage condensation also known as future Reichert's cartilage; hyoid cartilage pre-cartilage condensation Reichert's cartilage pre-cartilage condensation_1

ossification center also known as centrum ossificationis; ossification centre The first step in ossification of the cartilage is that the cartilage cells, at the point where ossification is commencing and which is termed a ossification center, enlarge and arrange themselves in rows. The matrix in which they are imbedded increases in quantity, so that the cells become further separated from each other. A deposit of calcareous material now takes place in this matrix, between the rows of cells, so that they become separated from each other by longitudinal columns of calcified matrix, presenting a granular and opaque appearance. Here and there the matrix between two cells of the same row also becomes calcified, and transverse bars of calcified substance stretch across from one calcareous column to another. Thus there are longitudinal groups of the cartilage cells enclosed in oblong cavities, the walls of which are formed of calcified matrix which cuts off all nutrition from the cells; the cells, in consequence, atrophy, leaving spaces called the primary areolC&.

primary ossification center also known as centrum ossificationis primarium; primary ossification centre A primary ossification center is the first area of a bone to start ossifying. It usually appears during prenatal development in the central part of each developing bone. In long bones the primary centers occur in the diaphysis/shaft and in irregular bones the primary centers occur usually in the body of the bone. Most bones have only one primary center (e.g. all long bones) but some irregular bones such as the os coxa (hip) and vertebrae have multiple primary centers.

secondary ossification center also known as centrum ossificationis secundarium; secondary ossification centre A secondary ossification center is the area of ossification that appears after the primary ossification center has already appeared - most of which appear during the postnatal and adolescent years. Most bones have more than one secondary ossification center. In long bones, the secondary centres appear in the epiphyses.
arch of centrum of vertebra An arch-shaped structure of the vertebra that extends dorsally (neural arch) or ventrally (hemal arch) from the vertebral centrum.

pharyngeal arch mesenchyme from neural crest also known as arch mesenchyme from neural crest; branchial arch mesenchyme from neural crest; neural crest derived arch mesenchyme Mesenchyme that develops_from a neural crest and is part of a entire pharyngeal arch associated mesenchyme.

pharyngeal arch mesenchyme from head mesenchyme also known as arch mesenchyme from head mesenchyme; branchial arch mesenchyme from head mesenchyme; head mesenchyme derived arch mesenchyme Mesenchyme that develops_from a head mesenchyme from mesoderm and is part of a entire pharyngeal arch associated mesenchyme.
synostosis also known as bony union; junctura ossea Nonsynovial joint in which the articulating bones are connected by bone. Examples: epiphyseal junction, manubriosternal synostosis.

endoskeleton also known as replacement skeleton Skeletal subdivision that undergoes indirect development and includes elements that develop as a replacement or substitution of other elements or tissues.

endochondral element also known as endochondral replacement element A skeletal element that has the potential to participate in endochondral ossification, and may participate in intramembranous ossification.

dermal skeleton Skeletal subdivision that undergoes direct development and includes elements that either develop in association with the basement membrane of the ectoderm or are homologous with such elements; includes dermatocranium, components of the appendicular skeleton, teeth and tooth-like elements of the oropharynx, and integumentary elements.
odontoid tissue also known as odontogenic tissue Skeletal tissue that is part of the exoskeleton and derived from an odontogenic papilla.
conjunctival vasculature also known as conjunctival veins; conjunctival veins set; set of conjunctival veins; venae conjunctivales A vasculature that is part of a conjunctiva.
conjunctival vein A vein that is part of a conjunctiva.

pulmonary lobule also known as lobulus pulmonis The smallest anatomical unit of the lung, measuring 0.50 to 2.00 cm in diameter. Each lobule is composed of 4-8 terminal bronchioles and their distal alveolar ducts and sacs. The lobules are separated by fibrous interlobular septa.
secondary pulmonary lobule also known as lobulus pulmonis secondarius A unit of lung supplied by three to five terminal bronchioles and contained by fibrous septa.
tibial vein also known as vena tibialis One of the veins of the lower leg; empty into the popliteal vein.
ecto-epithelium also known as ectoderm-derived epithelium Epithelium composed of cells that develops from the ectoderm[FMA,modified].

uncinate process of ethmoid also known as uncinate process of the ethmoid; uncinate process of the ethmoid bone In the ethmoid bone, a curved lamina, the uncinate process, projects downward and backward from this part of the labyrinth; it forms a small part of the medial wall of the maxillary sinus, and articulates with the ethmoidal process of the inferior nasal concha.

uncinate process of pancreas also known as lesser pancreas; processus uncinatus (pancreas); Winslow's pancreas; processus uncinatus pancreatis In the head of the pancreas, the angle of junction of the lower and left lateral borders forms a prolongation, termed the uncinate process. During the embryonic development of the distal foregut, the duodenum c-shape is formed while rotating the ventral pancreatic bud into the dorsal bud. The dorsal and ventral pancreatic buds fuse. The dorsal pancreatic bud becomes the body, tail, and isthmus of the pancreas and the ventral pancreatic bud forms the pancreatic head and uncinate process[WP].
pancreas dorsal primordium pancreas dorsal primordium_1
pancreas ventral primordium pancreas ventral primordium_1
mesenchyme from somatopleure Mesenchyme that develops_from a somatopleure.
mesenchyme from splanchnopleure Mesenchyme that develops_from a splanchnopleure.
superior tarsal muscle also known as Mueller's muscle The superior tarsal muscle is a smooth muscle adjoining the levator palpebrae superioris muscle that helps to raise the upper eyelid.
enteric nerve The neurons that innervate the esophagus, stomach, small and large bowel.
lumen of laryngopharynx also known as laryngopharynx lumen An anatomical space that is enclosed by a hypopharynx.
Peyer's patch follicle also known as Peyer's patch follicle_1 A lymphoid follicle that is part of a Peyer's patch.
Peyer's patch T cell area The Peyer's patch area normally occupied by T lymphocytes.

proximal segment of rib also known as proximal part of rib; proximal rib; proximal rib segment The segment of the rib that connects to a vertebra[MP]. a small part of the rib composed of the head, neck, tuberculum and a short proximal part of the body[PMID].

pterygoid bone also known as lamina lateralis (processus pterygoideus); lamina lateralis processi pterygoideus ossis sphenoidalis; lateral lamina of pterygoid process; lateral plate of pterygoid process; lateral plate of sphenoid; lateral pterygoid plate A bone which corresponds to the inner plate of the pterygoid process of the human skull, but which, in all vertebrates below mammals, is not connected with the posterior nares, but serves to connect the palatine bones with the point of suspension of the lower jaw.
lumen of urethra also known as urethral lumen An organ cavity that is part of a urethra.
parametrium The subserous connective tissue of the pelvic floor of the supracervical portion of the uterus. The parametrium extends laterally between the layers of the broad ligament.
B cell domain B cell domain_1
T cell domain T cell domain_1
lymphocyte domain lymphocyte domain_1
lymph node primary follicle also known as primary follicle of lymph node An unstimulated network of follicular dendritic cells and small resting B cells in the lymph node cortex.

afferent lymphatic vessel also known as vasa afferentia lymphoglandula; vasa afferentia lymphoglandulae Lymphatic vessel that enters the lymph node. The afferent lymph vessels enter at all parts of the periphery of the lymph node, and after branching and forming a dense plexus in the substance of the capsule, open into the lymph sinuses of the cortical part. In doing this they lose all their coats except their endothelial lining, which is continuous with a layer of similar cells lining the lymph paths.

efferent lymphatic vessel Lymphatic vessel that exits the lymph node. The efferent lymphatic vessel commences from the lymph sinuses of the medullary portion of the lymph nodes and leave the lymph nodes either to veins or greater nodes. Efferent lymphatic vessels are also found in the thymus and spleen. This is in contrast to afferent lymphatic vessels, which are found only in lymph nodes.
spleen trabecular artery One of the branches of the splenic artery[MP].
spleen trabecular vein One of the veins that feed the splenic vein.

spleen central arteriole also known as follicular arteriole; splenic central arteriole A blood vessel surrounded by the periarteriolar lymphoid sheath that connects the trabecular artery to the trabecular vein.
epidermis suprabasal layer also known as suprabasal cell layer of skin; suprabasal layer of epidermis Any layer of the epidermis that is superior to the stratum basale.
brain marginal zone The part of the future brain that is derived from the mantle layer of the neural tube.

lateral ventricle subependymal layer A cell layer below the ependyma in the lateral ventricles of the brain. This region contains adult neural stem cells which have the potential to generate new neurons and glial cells via neurogenesis. It is an adult version of the embryonic forebrain germinal zone.

spinal cord lateral motor column Column of motor neurons which innervate muscles in the limb; motor neurons in the lateral motor column are further organized into pools, each of which innervates a specific muscle in the limb.
cholinergic enteric nerve Nerve fibers that utilize acetylcholine as a neurotransmitter to the intestinal system.

ocular angle artery also known as angular artery The angular artery is the terminal part of the facial artery; it ascends to the medial angle of the eye's orbit, imbedded in the fibers of the angular head of the Quadratus labii superioris, and accompanied by the angular vein.

ocular surface region also known as eye surface; eye surface region; ocular surface The integrated unit (of the eye) that consists of the conjunctiva, the corneal surface, and the ocular mucosal adnexa including the lid margins and the meibomian gland openings, the lacrimal glands and the lacrimal drainage system, all which are critical to maintain ocular surface integrity and provide protection from external antigens and pathogenic microorganisms.
inguinal fat pad also known as fat depot of inguinal region; inguinal fat depot Encapsulated adipose tissue found in the groin.
retroperitoneal fat pad also known as retroperitoneal fat depot Encapsulated adipose tissue found on the dorsal side of the peritoneum.
epididymal fat pad also known as periepididymal fat pad Encapsulated adipose tissue associated with the epididymis.

parametrial fat pad also known as parametrial fat depot Encapsulated adipose tissue associated with the extension of the subserous coat of the uterus laterally between the layers of the broad ligament.

omental fat pad also known as omental fat depot Encapsulated adipose tissue associated with the fold of peritoneal tissue that extends from the stomach to the posterior abdominal wall after associating with the transverse colon.

lymph node B cell domain also known as lymph node B cell dependent cortex; lymph node B-cell domain; nodular lymph node cortex A part of the lymph node cortex in which B lymphocytes home to primary follicles to survey follicular dendritic cells (FDCs); antigen stimulated B cells proliferate and differentiate within the follicles forming distinctive germinal centers.

lymph node T cell domain also known as lymph node deep cortex; lymph node T cell dependent paracortex; lymph node T zone; lymph node T-cell domain; T cell zone of lymph node; T zone of lymph node The paracortex and interfollicular cortex of the lymph node in which T lymphocytes home to survey dendritic cells.
urethral opening also known as urethral orifice An orifice that is part of a lower urinary tract.

lymph node germinal center mantle zone also known as lymph node B cell corona; lymph node follicular corona; lymph node follicular mantle; lymph node inactive zone; lymph node peripheral zone; mantle zone of lymph node germinal center A part of the secondary follicle in which naive B cells reside along with some helper T cells, macrophages and follicular dendritic cells; these are displaced by the expanding germinal centre and form a 'mantle' around it.

spleen B cell corona also known as follicle mantle; spleen B cell corona; spleen B-cell corona; spleen lymphocytic corona; splenic B cell corona The area of the (spleen) secondary B follicle that surrounds the germinal center and harbors the small recirculating B lymphocytes.
primary nodular lymphoid tissue also known as primary lymphoid follicle; primary lymphoid nodule A lymphoid follicle containing naive B cells.
primary lymphoid nodule of tonsil A primary nodular lymphoid tissue that is part of a tonsil.
distal segment of rib also known as distal part of rib; distal rib; distal rib segment distal segment of rib
internal naris also known as choana; internal choana A naris that is located inside the nasal cavity and connects to the pharynx.

ciliary processes also known as ciliary processes; ciliary processes set; processus ciliares; set of ciliary processes The ciliary processes are formed by the inward folding of the various layers of the choroid, i.e. , the choroid proper and the lamina basalis, and are received between corresponding foldings of the suspensory ligament of the lens.

flat bone A bone that is shaped as a broad flat plate and composed of two thin layers of compact tissue enclosing between them a variable quantity of cancellous tissue, which is the location of red bone marrow.
zygomaticus muscle also known as m. zygomaticus; zygomaticus One of: zygomaticus major, zygomaticus minor.
teres muscle also known as teres teres muscle
teres minor muscle also known as teres minor A narrow, elongated muscle of the rotator cuff.
pseudostratified columnar epithelium A simple columnar epithelium that looks stratified but is not, because its cells are arranged with their nuclei at different levels.

pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium also known as epithelium pseudostratificatum columnare ciliatum (trachea et bronchi) Epithelium composed of a single layer of cells, appearing as layered because the column-shaped cells vary in height so the nuclei are at different levels. The basal portions of all the cells are in contact with the basement membrane. It lines the respiratory system and the male reproductive tract. The cilia in the respiratory tract are motile, while the stereocilia in the male reproductive tract are immobile.
pseudostratified smooth columnar epithelium pseudostratified smooth columnar epithelium

periosteal dura mater also known as outer layer of dura mater; outer periosteal layer of dura mater; periosteal dura; periosteal layer of dura mater The outermost of the two layers of the cranial dura mater which normally always adheres to the periosteum of the bones of the cranial vault.

meningeal dura mater also known as inner layer of dura mater; meningeal dura; meningeal layer of dura mater The inner layer of the dura mater surrounding the brain. It is mostly fused with the outer layer, the endocranium that is adherent to the inner aspect of the cranial bones. These two layers form the dura mater. The latter covers and protects the brain and the spinal cord.

layer of dura mater The intracranial dura mater, consisting of two layers: the outer periosteal layer which normally always adheres to the periosteum of the bones of the cranial vault; and the inner meningeal layer which in most places is fused with the outer. The two layers separate to accommodate meningeal vessels and large venous (dural) sinuses. The meningeal layer is also involved in the formation of the various dural folds, such as the falx cerebri and tentorium cerebelli and is comparable to and continuous with the dural mater of the spinal cord. The cranial epidural space is then a potential space between the bone and the combined periosteum/periosteal layer of the dura mater realised only pathologically and is neither continuous with or comparable to the vertebral epidural space.
strand of pelage hair also known as pelage hair A strand of hair that is part of a coat of hair.
strand of auchene hair also known as auchene hair A truncal hair that has a single constriction and bend about midway along the hair shaft, and contains two or more air cells in the medulla.
strand of awl hair also known as awl hair A truncal hairs that is straight, but shorter than a guard hair, and contain two or more air cells in the medulla.

strand of guard hair also known as guard hair; guardhair; monotrich hair A long, straight truncal hair that contains two air cells in the medulla[MP]. A strand of hair from the top layer consisting of longer, often coarser, straight shafts of hair that stick out through the underfur. This is usually the visible layer for most mammals and contains most of the pigmentation.
strand of zigzag hair also known as zigzag hair A truncal hair that has two or more sharp bends with diameter constrictions at the bends, and contain one air cell in the medulla.
strand of duvet hair also known as duvet hair A strand of hair from the fine underhair of the coat.
electroreceptor organ also known as electric sense organ; electroreception organ An organ that is capable of detecting electrical stimulus.
replacement element Skeletal element that forms as a replacement or substitution of another element or tissue.

fibularis tertius also known as musculus peroneus tertius; peroneus digiti quinti; peroneus tertius; peroneus tertius muscle A muscle located in the lower limb that arises from the lower third of the anterior surface of the fibula; from the lower part of the interosseous membrane; and from an intermuscular septum between it and the peroneus brevis and inserted into the dorsal surface of the base of the metatarsal bone of the 5th digit. It is innervated by the deep fibular nerve. Its action is that of weak dorsiflexion of the ankle joint and to evert the foot at the ankle joint.

fibularis brevis also known as musculus peroneus brevis; peronaeus brevis; peroneus brevis; peroneus brevis muscle The peroneus brevis muscle (or fibularis brevis) lies under cover of the peroneus longus, and is a shorter and smaller muscle.

acropodial skeleton also known as acropodial skeleton; acropodium skeleton; set of phalanges; skeletal parts of acropodial region The subdivision of the skeleton that consists of all the skeletal elements at the distalmost end of the autopodium - i.e. the bones of the digits or their cartilaginous precursors[VSAO,modified].

metacarpus skeleton also known as anterior metapodial skeleton; metacarpal bones; metacarpal skeleton; metacarpals [I-V]; metacarpals set; ossa metacarpalia [I-V]; ossa metacarpi [I-V]; set of metacarpal bones; set of metacarpals; set of metacarpals [I-V]; skeleton of metacarpus The metacarpus is the intermediate part of the manus skeleton that is located between the phalanges (bones of the fingers) distally and the carpus which forms the connection to the forearm. The metacarpus consists of metacarpal bones. The metacarpals form a transverse arch to which the rigid row of distal carpal bones are fixed. The peripheral metacarpals (those of the thumb and little finger) form the sides of the cup of the palmar gutter and as they are brought together they deepen this concavity. The index metacarpal is the most firmly fixed, while the thumb metacarpal articulates with the trapezium and acts independently from the others. The middle metacarpals are tightly united to the carpus by intrinsic interlocking bone elements at their bases. The ring metacarpal forms a transitional element of the semi-independent last metacarpal. [WP,unvetted].

metatarsus skeleton also known as metatarsal bones set; metatarsal skeleton; metatarsals [I-V]; ossa metatarsalia [I-V]; ossa metatarsi[I-V]; posterior metapodial skeleton; set of metatarsal bones; set of metatarsals [I-V]; skeleton of metatarsus Limb segment that consists of the long bones of the pes. metapodial skeleton also known as metacarpal/metatarsal skeleton; metapodial skeleton; metapodium skeleton; skeletal parts of metapodium; skeleton of metapodium Subdivision of skeleton that corresponds to metapodium region, between acropodial skeleton and mesopdoial skeleton.

pectoral complex also known as pectoral appendage/girdle complex; pectoral girdle plus anterior limb or fin; pectoral girdle plus pectoral limb or fin Appendage girdle complex that when present, encompasses the pectoral appendicular skeleton and the pectoral girdle.

hindlimb zeugopod skeleton also known as crural skeleton; crus skeleton; hindlimb zygopod skeleton; posterior zeugopodium skeleton; skeleton cruris Subdivision of skeleton consisting of all skeletal elements in an hindlimb zeugopod region. Typically consists of the tibia and the fibula.

distal tarsal bone also known as cuneiform bone; distal tarsal; distal tarsal bone; os cuneiform; os cuneiforme There are three cuneiform bones in the human foot: the medial cuneiform the intermediate cuneiform also known as the middle the lateral cuneiform. They are located between the navicular bone and the first, second and third metatarsal bones and are medial to the cuboid bone[WP, unvetted, human specific].
accessory bone A bone which does not occur frequently in the body but is still present in a significantly large number of organisms.

os vesalianum pedis also known as pedal vesalian bone An accessory bone located proximal to the base of the fifth metatarsal. Its prevalence has been reported to be from 0.1% to 1.0%. This bone is found within the peroneus brevis tendon and is considered to be asymptomatic in the majority of people.
lateral tubercle of talus also known as os trigonum; accessory talus; os trigonum of talus; tuberculum laterale (talus) An accessory bone tubercle which if present lies posterior to the talus.

accessory navicular bone An accessory bone of the pes that occasionally develops abnormally in front of the ankle towards the inside of the pes. This bone may be present in approximately 2.5% of the general population and is usually asymptomatic.
os vesalianum manus also known as manual vesalian bone os vesalianum manus_1
sutural bone also known as Wormian bone A piece of bone that is located within a suture in the cranium.
sphenoid lesser wing pre-cartilage condensation An orbitosphenoid endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.
alisphenoid pre-cartilage condensation also known as sphenoid greater wing pre-cartilage condensation An alisphenoid endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.
alisphenoid cartilage element also known as sphenoid greater wing cartilage condensation An alisphenoid endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.
distal tarsal bone 4 also known as os tarsale IV Endochondral tarsal bone articulating with centralia and metatarsal 4.
distal tarsal bone 5 also known as distal tarsal 5; tarsal 5 Endochondral tarsal bone articulating with centralia and metatarsal 5.
distal carpal bone 5 also known as distal carpal 5 Endochondral carpal bone similar to distal carpal 4, but lost in most reptiles and mammals.
bone of appendage girdle complex A bone that is part of an appendage girdle complex (i.e. any bone in a limb, fin or girdle).
bone of pectoral complex A bone that is part of a pectoral complex. Examples: scapula, manus phalanx, any carpal bone, any bone of the pectoral fin.
bone of pelvic complex A bone that is part of a pelvic complex. Examples: pubis, ischium, fot phalanx, any tarsal bone, any bone of the pelvic fin or girdle.
meningeal cluster also known as cerebral meninges; cluster of meninges; meninges The collection of all meningeal layers that line a central nervous system.

sacral vertebra pre-cartilage condensation also known as sacral vertebral pre-cartilage condensation group A sacral vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.

sacral vertebra cartilage element also known as sacral vertebral cartilage condensation; sacral vertebral cartilage condensation group A sacral vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

iliac blade also known as a. ossis ilii; ala of ilium; ala ossis ilii; ilium ala; wing of ilium; wing of the ilium The extension of the ilium above the level of the acetabulum. Attachment site for both hindlimb and caudal musculature. Medially is the site of attachment of the sacral ribs, where these exist[PHENOSCAPE:ad].

body of ilium also known as ilium body The body of ilium enters into the formation of the acetabulum, of which it forms rather less than two-fifths. Its external surface is partly articular, partly non-articular; the articular segment forms part of the lunate surface of the acetabulum, the non-articular portion contributes to the acetabular fossa. The internal surface of the body is part of the wall of the lesser pelvis and gives origin to some fibers of the Obturator internus. Below, it is continuous with the pelvic surfaces of the ischium and pubis, only a faint line indicating the place of union.
lymph node follicle also known as follicle of lymph node A lymphoid follicle that is part of a lymph node.

middle pharyngeal constrictor also known as middle constrictor; middle constrictor of pharynx; middle constrictor pharyngeus; musculus constrictor pharyngis medius The middle pharyngeal constrictor is a fanshaped muscle, smaller than the Inferior pharyngeal constrictor muscle.
squamous part of temporal bone primordium also known as squamosal bone primordium; squamosal primordium squamous part of temporal bone primordium_1
exoccipital cartilage element An exoccipital endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.
lymph node secondary follicle A secondary follicle that is located in a lymph node.

germinal center also known as central zone of follice; reaction center of follicle A collection of activated B cells at the center of a secondary follicle, formed after B cells become activated and migrate to the center.
secondary follicle corona also known as inactive zone of follicle; peripheral zone of follicle The part of the secondary follicle that surrounds the germinal center.

spleen follicular dendritic cell network also known as spleen FDC network; splenic follicular dendritic cell network The enmeshed group of antigen presenting cells with extensive dendritic processes in the spleen B cell follicle that present antigen to B cells during an immune response.
rib 8 also known as costa VIII; eighth rib The eighth rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. Note that members of this class are not necessarily homologous[ncit,modified].

subdivision of organism along appendicular axis also known as appendage segment; appendicular segment A major subdivision of an organism that divides an organism along an axis perpedicular to the main body anterior-posterior axis. In vertebrates, this is typically a fin or limb segment. In insects, this includes segments of appendages such as antennae, as well as segments of the insect leg.
supraglenoid tubercle also known as supraglenoid tuberosity The supraglenoid tubercle is a region of the scapula to which the long head of the biceps brachii muscle attaches.
calcaneum pre-cartilage condensation also known as calcaneous pre-cartilage condensation A calcaneum endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.
calcaneum cartilage element also known as calcaneous cartilage element A calcaneum endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.
clavicle cartilage element A cartilaginous condensation that has the potential to develop into a clavicle.
clavicle pre-cartilage condensation A pre-cartilage condensation that has the potential to develop into a clavicle.
radius pre-cartilage condensation A pre-cartilage condensation that has the potential to develop into a radius bone.
ulna pre-cartilage condensation A pre-cartilage condensation that has the potential to develop into a ulna.
radius-ulna cartilage element also known as radio-ulna cartilage condensation A radius-ulna endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.
tibia cartilage element A cartilaginous condensation that has the potential to develop into a tibia.
tibia pre-cartilage condensation A pre-cartilage condensation that has the potential to develop into a tibia.
fibula cartilage element also known as fibulal cartilage condensation; fibular cartilage condensation A cartilaginous condensation that has the potential to develop into a fibula.
fibula pre-cartilage condensation also known as fibulal pre-cartilage condensation; fibular pre-cartilage condensation A pre-cartilage condensation that has the potential to develop into a fibula.

capitulum of humerus also known as humeral capitulum A smooth, rounded eminence on the lateral portion of the articular surface of the humerus. It articulates with the cupshaped depression on the head of the radius, and is limited to the front and lower part of the bone.
skin of front of neck also known as skin of anterior neck; skin of anterior part of neck; skin of anterior portion of neck; skin of throat A skin of neck that is part of a throat.
inter limb-segment region inter limb-segment region_1
tusk A calcareous tooth that is elongated and protrudes from the mouth.
gular fold A transverse fold of skin across the throat (Peters 1964).
limb cartilage element A skeletal element that is part of a limb and composed of cartilage tissue.
limb bone pre-cartilage condensation A skeletal element that is part of a limb and composed of pre-cartilage tissue.
forelimb cartilage element A cartilaginous condensation that has the potential to develop into a forelimb bone.
forelimb bone pre-cartilage condensation A pre-cartilage condensation that has the potential to develop into a forelimb bone.
hindlimb cartilage element also known as hindlimb cartilage condensation A cartilaginous condensation that has the potential to develop into a hindlimb bone.
hindlimb pre-cartilage condensation also known as hindlimb pre-cartilage condensation_1 A pre-cartilage condensation that has the potential to develop into a hindlimb bone.
tragus also known as tragal part of pinna A small pointed eminence of the external ear, situated in front of the concha, and projecting backward over the meatus.
ectethmoid also known as dorsal nasal capsule Either of two lateral parts of the ethmoid bone that form part of the anterior wall of the orbit.
pelvic complex muscle also known as pelvic girdle and hind limb muscles Muscles of the pelvic girdle, hindlimb or pelvic fin.
pectoral complex muscle also known as pectoral girdle and fore limb muscles A muscle of a pectoral girdle, pectoral fin or anterior limb.
mesethmoid element also known as ventral nasal capsule An endochondral element of the nasal capsule that forms septum between nasal capsules and usually remains unossified in mammals.
keratinous tooth also known as horny denticle keratinous tooth_1
sequential hermaphroditic organism Hermaphroditic organism that produces gametes first of one sex, and then later of the other sex.
synchronous hermaphroditic organism Hermaphroditic organism that produces both male and female gametes at the same time.
clavicle bone primordium also known as clavicle primordium A primordium that develops into a clavicle bone.
parafibula Third bone of the lower leg, normally restricted to the area of the knee, in multuberculates, monotremes and some therians.
opisthotic Posterior ossification of the otic capsule.
ossicle Skeletal element that is often isolated, small, and variable in composition.

subdivision of skeleton also known as skeletal subdivision Anatomical cluster consisting of the skeletal elements (i.e. bone elements, cartilage elements, cartilage condensations) that are part of an individual subdivision of the organism. Excludes joints.
vertebral element also known as vertebra element Skeletal element that forms around the notochord and is part of the vertebral column.
thyrohyoid ligament thyrohyoid ligament_1

median thyrohyoid ligament also known as ligamentum thyrohyoideum medianum; middle thyrohyoid ligament The middle thicker part of the thyrohyoid membrane is termed the median thyrohyoid ligament (middle hyothyroid ligament, middle thyrohyoid ligament), its lateral thinner portions are pierced by the superior laryngeal vessels and the internal branch of the superior laryngeal nerve. Its anterior surface is in relation with the Thyreohyoideus, Sternohyoideus, and Omohyoideus, and with the body of the hyoid bone.

lateral thyrohyoid ligament also known as ligamentum hyothyreoideum laterale; ligamentum thyrohyoideum laterale The lateral thyrohyoid ligament (lateral hyothyroid ligament) is a round elastic cord, which forms the posterior border of the hyothyroid membrane and passes between the tip of the superior cornu of the thyroid cartilage and the extremity of the greater cornu of the hyoid bone. The recurrent laryngeal nerve typical lies lateral to this ligament.

thyroepiglotticus muscle also known as pars thyroepiglottica (musculus thyroarytenoideus); pars thyroepiglottica musculus thyroarytenoidei; thyro-epiglottic part of thyro-arytenoid; thyroepiglottic; thyroepiglottic muscle; thyroepiglotticus; thyroepiglottus; thyroepiglottus muscle Fibers of the thyroarytenoid muscle that continue to the margin of the epiglottis; it closes the inlet to the larynx.

cricopharyngeus muscle also known as cricopharyngeal part of inferior constrictor pharyngeus; cricopharyngeal part of inferior pharyngeal constrictor; cricopharyngeal part of inferior pharyngeal constrictor muscle; cricopharyngeus; cricopharyngeus portion of the inferior pharyngeal constrictor; musculus cricopharyngeus; pars cricopharyngea (musculus constrictor pharyngis inferior); pars cricopharyngea musculus constrictoris pharyngis inferioris The cricopharyngeus is a pharyngeal arch 4/6 muscle that participates in oral/pharyngeal behaviors and is innervated by the pharyngeal plexus and the recurrent laryngeal n. (from Vagus, CN X), and is an integral part of the pharyngeal tube, and attaches to the cricoid cartilage and the midline raphe. It acts as a sphincter between the pharynx and esophagus.
stapedius pre-muscle condensation stapedius pre-muscle condensation_1
interhyoideus also known as interhyoideus muscle interhyoideus_1
intermandibularis also known as intermandibularis muscle Is a mandibular muscle that develops into the ventral intermandibularis anterior and posterior muscles.

crico-arytenoid muscle also known as crico-arytenoid; cricoarytenoid; cricoarytenoid muscle; cricoarytenoideus Cricoarytenoid muscles are muscles that connect the cricoid cartilage and arytenoid cartilage. More specifically, it can refer to: Posterior cricoarytenoid muscle Lateral cricoarytenoid muscle.

orbicularis oris muscle also known as orbicularis oris The orbicularis oris is a superficial facial muscle with fibers that encircle the opening of the oral cavity that attaches to the maxilla, mandible, skin and modiolus, and that participates in oral/pharyngeal behaviors, and is innervated by the facial nerve (CN VII).
tensor tympani pre-muscle condensation tensor tympani pre-muscle condensation_1

thyropharyngeus muscle also known as musculus thyropharyngeus; pars thyropharyngea (musculus constrictor pharyngis inferior); pars thyropharyngea musculus constrictoris pharyngis inferioris; thyropharyngeal part of inferior constrictor pharyngeus; thyropharyngeal part of inferior constrictor pharyngeus muscle; thyropharyngeal part of inferior pharyngeal constrictor; thyropharyngeus thyropharyngeus muscle_1

salpingopharyngeus muscle also known as salpingopharyngeus The salpingopharyngeus muscle arises from the inferior part of the cartilage of the pharyngotympanic tube (Eustachian tube) in the nasal cavity; it passes downward and blends with the posterior fasciculus of the palatopharyngeus muscle. The salpingopharyngeus is known to raise the pharynx and larynx during deglutition (swallowing) and laterally draws the pharyngeal walls up. In addition, it opens the pharyngeal orifice of the pharyngotympanic tube during swallowing. This allows for the equalization of pressure between the auditory canal and the pharynx. The salpingopharyngeus is innervated by the vagus nerve (CN X) via the pharyngeal plexus.
muscle belly also known as belly of muscle muscle belly_1
zygomaticomandibularis muscle also known as zygomaticomandibularis; zygomaticomandibularis muscle zygomaticomandibularis muscle_1
muscle of digastric group Either of the two muscles that comprise the digastric group (anterior or posterior).

anterior digastric muscle also known as anterior belly of digastric; anterior belly of digastric muscle; anterior digastric; anterior digastric muscle; digastric, anterior; digastricus anterior; digastricus anterior belly; digastricus, venter rostralis; venter anterior (musculus digastricus); venter posterior musculus digastrici anterior The anterior digastric is a pharyngeal arch I muscle that participates in oral/pharygeal behaviors and is innervated by the nerve to mylohyoid (a branch of the third division of the trigeminal nerve), is attached to the mandible and to the hyoid apparatus, and it is superficial to mylohyoid muscle.

posterior digastric muscle also known as digastric, posterior; digastricus posterior; digastricus posterior belly; digastricus, venter caudalis; m. digastricus posterior; posterior belly of digastric; posterior belly of digastric muscle; posterior digastric muscle; venter posterior musculus digastrici The posterior digastric is a pharyngeal arch II muscle that participates in oral pharyngeal behavior, is innervated by the digastric branch of facial nerve and attaches to the posterior cranial base and the hyoid apparatus. It is found superficial to the mylohyoid muscle.
jugulohyoideus muscle Runs from the processus jugularis to the os stylohyoideum; innervated with the ramus jugulohyoideus from the nervus facialis.

occipitofrontalis muscle The occipitofrontalis or epicranius is a muscle which covers parts of the skull. It consists of two parts or bellies: The occipital belly, near the occipital bone, and the frontal belly, near the frontal bone.

occipitalis also known as occipital belly of occipitofrontalis; occipital part of occipitofrontalis; venter occipitalis (musculus occipitofrontalis); venter transversa musculi occipitofrontalis occipitalis; venter transversa musculus occipitofrontalis occipitalis A belly of the occipitofrontalis muscle that is near the occipital bone.
cleidooccipital muscle also known as cleido-occipitalis; cleido-occipitalis muscle; cleidooccipital A muscle organ that attaches_to a clavicle and attaches_to a occipital bone.
sternooccipital muscle also known as sternooccipital A muscle organ that has_muscle_insertion a occipital bone and has_muscle_origin a sternum.

styloauricular muscle also known as mandibulo-auricularis; mandibulo-auricularis muscle; stylo-auricularis; stylo-auricularis muscle; styloauricularis An occasional small muscle extending from the root of the styloid process to the cartilage of the meatus of the ear.
interscutular muscle also known as interscutularis; musculus interscutularis A muscle that attaches to the base of the ear and to the middle of the skull.

frontalis muscle belly also known as frontal belly of occipitofrontalis; frontal part of occipitofrontalis; frontalis; frontalis muscke; orbito-temporo-auricularis; venter frontalis (musculus occipitofrontalis); venter frontalis musculus occipitofrontalis A belly of the occipitofrontalis muscle that is near the frontal bone.

nasalis muscle also known as nasalis The nasalis (compressor naris) is a sphincter-like muscle of the nose whose function is to compress the nasal cartilage. It consists of two parts, transverse and alar: The transverse part arises from the maxilla, above and lateral to the incisive fossa; its fibers proceed upward and medially, expanding into a thin aponeurosis which is continuous on the bridge of the nose with that of the muscle of the opposite side, and with the aponeurosis of the Procerus. The alar part is attached at one end to the greater alar cartilage, and at the other to the integument at the point of the nose. Other sources divide it into 'Compressor nasalis' and 'Dilator nasalis'.

ceratohyoideus muscle also known as ceratohyoideus The ceratohyoideus is a muscle of Pharyngeal Arch III that participates in oral/pharyngeal behaviors and is innervated by the glossopharyngeal n. , and attaches to the ceratohyal part of the hyoid apparatus and also to a non-ceratohyal part of the hyoid apparatus.[FEED].
trapezius pre-muscle mass trapezius pre-muscle mass_1

pterygopharyngeal part of superior pharyngeal constrictor also known as pars pterygopharyngea (musculus constrictor pharyngis superior); pars pterygopharyngea musculus constrictoris pharyngis superioris; pterygopharyngeal part of superior constrictor pharyngeus pterygopharyngeal part of superior pharyngeal constrictor_1

arytenoid muscle A single muscle, filling up the posterior concave surfaces of the arytenoid cartilages. It arises from the posterior surface and lateral border of one arytenoid cartilage, and is inserted into the corresponding parts of the opposite cartilage. It consists of oblique and transverse parts.
craniocervical muscle also known as muscle of head or neck Any muscle organ that is part of either the head or the neck.
