transverse tarsal joint also known as articulatio tarsi transversa; chopart's joint; midtarsal joint The transverse tarsal joint is formed by the articulation of the calcaneus with the cuboid, and the articulation of the talus with the navicular. The movement which takes place in this joint is more extensive than that in the other tarsal joints, and consists of a sort of rotation by means of which the foot may be slightly flexed or extended, the sole being at the same time carried medially (inverted) or laterally.

talocalcaneonavicular joint also known as articulatio talocalcaneonavicularis; talocalcaneonavicular articulation The talocalcaneonavicular articulation is an arthrodial joint: the rounded head of the talus being received into the concavity formed by the posterior surface of the navicular, the anterior articular surface of the calcaneus, and the upper surface of the plantar calcaneonavicular ligament. There are two ligaments in this joint: the articular capsule and the dorsal talonavicular.

calcaneocuboid joint also known as articulatio calcaneocubiodea; calcaneocuboid articulation; calcaneocuboidal joint Calcaneocuboid Articulation (articulation of the calcaneus with the cuboid). The ligaments connecting the calcaneus with the cuboid are five in number, viz. , the articular capsule, the dorsal calcaneocuboid, part of the bifurcated, the long plantar, and the plantar calcaneocuboid.
saddle joint also known as sellar joint In a saddle joint (sellar joint, articulation by reciprocal reception) the opposing surfaces are reciprocally concave-convex.
manubriosternal joint also known as manubriosternal symphysis The early union, by hyaline cartilage, of the manubrium and the body of the sternum, which later becomes a symphysial type of joint.

costotransverse joint The facet of the tubercle of the rib forms an articulation with the adjacent transverse process of a thoracic vertebra. This is a plane type synovial joint called the costotransverse joint. This articulation is present in all but the eleventh and twelfth ribs. Ribs 1 to 10 have two joints in close proximity posteriorly; the costovertebral joints and the costotranseverse joints. This arrangement restrains the motion of the ribs allowing them to work in a parallel fashion during breathing. If a typical rib had only one joint posteriorly the resultant swivel action would allow a rib to be non-parallel with respect to the neighboring ribs making for a very inefficient respiratory mechanism. The ventral rami innervate the costotransverse joints. Therefore, therapeutic medial branch blocks are ineffectual. The ligaments of the joint are: Articular capsule Posterior costotransverse Anterior costotransverse Ligament of the neck of the rib Ligament of the tubercle of the rib.
radio-carpal joint also known as radiocarpal joint; articulatio radiocarpea; radiocarpal articulation A skeletal joint that connects a radius bone and connects a carpal skeleton.

suspensory ligament of breast also known as retinaculum cutis mammae; suspensory ligament of cooper; suspensory retinaculum of breast Cooper's ligaments (also known as the suspensory ligaments of Cooper and the fibrocollagenous septa) are connective tissue in the breast that helps maintain structural integrity. Cooper's Suspensory Ligament should not be confused with the pectineal ligament (sometimes called the inguinal ligament of Cooper) which shares the same eponym.

infraspinatus tendon also known as tendon of infraspinatus muscle The infraspinatus muscle inserts at this tendon to the distal greater tubercle of the humerus. This tendon stretches across the shoulder joint to attach to the humerus and in doing so acts as a very strong ligament to hold the joint surface in apposition. This structure restricts the movement of the shoulder joint to flexion and extension (together with the suscapularis tendon and the supraspinatus tendon). A bursa lies under this tendon at the greater tubercle of the humerus. The bursa is lined by a synovial membrance and filled with synovial fluid and protects the infraspinatus tendon and the shoulder joint by allowing the transmissions of tension and sheer forces around an angle.

intercuneiform joint The intercuneiform articulations are articulations among the cuneiform bones[WP,unverified].

medial-intermediate intercuneiform joint medial-intermediate intercuneiform joint
prepollex skeleton prepollex skeleton
prehallux prehallux_1
pedal digit 7 also known as hind digit 7; hind digit VII; hind limb digit 7; pedal digit VII; pes digit VII; seventh toe; toe 7 pedal digit 7_1
pedal digit 8 also known as digitus octus pedis; eigth toe; hind digit 8; hind digit VIII; hind limb digit 8; pedal digit VIII; pes digit VIII; toe 8 pedal digit 8_1
segment of autopod segment of autopod_1
digitopodium region A segment of the autopod consisting of both acropodial region and metapodial region, but excluding the mesopodial/basopodial region.
manual digitopodium region A digitopodium region that is part of a manus[Obol]. This includes the fingers and metacarpal region, but excludes the carpal region.
pedal digitopodium region A digitopodium region that is part of a pes[Obol]. This includes the toes and metatarsal region, but excludes the tarsals region.
skeleton of digitopodium A subdivision of the autopod skeleton consisting of both acropodial skeleon and metapodial skeleton, but excluding the mesopodial/basopodial skeleton.
skeleton of manual digitopodium A subdivision of the manus skeleton consisting of both manual acropodial skeleton and metacarpal skeleton, but excluding the carpal skeleton.
skeleton of pedal digitopodium A subdivision of the pes skeleton consisting of both pedal acropodial skeleton and metatarsal skeleton, but excluding the tarsal skeleton.

buccal fat pad also known as Bichat's fat pad; cheek fat pad The Buccal fat pad is one of several encapsulated fat masses in the cheek. It is a deep fat pad located on either side of the face between the buccinator muscle and several more superficial muscles. It should not be confused with the malar fat pad, which is directly below the skin of the cheek. It should also not be confused with jowl fat pads. It is implicated in the formation of hollow cheeks and the nasolabial fold, but not in the formation of jowls.
umbilical cord blood Blood that remains in the placenta and in the attached umbilical cord after childbirth[WP].
core of nucleus accumbens also known as core of nucleus accumbens; core region of nucleus accumbens; nucleus accumbens core core of nucleus accumbens_1

shell of nucleus accumbens also known as nucleus accumbens shell; shell of nucleus accumbens; shell region of nucleus accumbens Crescent shaped outer zone of the nucleus accumbens, defined by a combination of chemoarchitecture and afferent and efferent connections. The shell is distinguished from the more centrally located core through the notable reduction in staining for the calcium-binding protein calbindin D28K, which is dense in the core and virtually absent in the shell.
stomach primordium A primordium that has the potential to develop into a stomach.

middle suprarenal artery also known as middle suprarenal arterial tree The middle suprarenal arteries (middle capsular arteries; suprarenal arteries) are two small vessels which arise, one from either side of the abdominal aorta, opposite the superior mesenteric artery. They pass laterally and slightly upward, over the crura of the diaphragm, to the suprarenal glands, where they anastomose with suprarenal branches of the inferior phrenic and renal arteries. In the fetus these arteries are of large size.
acoustico-facial VII-VIII ganglion complex also known as acousticofacial ganglion; facio-acoustic ganglion; facio-acoustic ganglion complex VII-VIII acoustico-facial VII-VIII ganglion complex_1
skin apocrine gland An apocrine gland that is part of a skin of body.
bone of pelvis bone of pelvis_1
head or neck skin A zone of skin that is part of a craniocervical region.

tonsil crypt also known as cryptae tonsillares; tonsillar crypt Tonsils consist of an extensive system of crypts, which result in a large internal surface. The tonsils contain four lymphoid compartments that influence immune functions, namely the reticular crypt epithelium, the extrafollicular area, the mantle zones of lymphoid follicles, and the follicular germinal centers. In human palatine tonsils, the very first part exposed to the outside environment is tonsillar epithelium.
ovary growing follicle An ovarian follicle undergoing maturation.

frontal artery also known as supratrochlear artery; supratrochlear branch of ophthalmic artery The supratrochlear artery (or frontal artery), one of the terminal branches of the ophthalmic artery, branches off where the ophthalmic travels posterior to the trochlea.
phrenic vein The veins that run parallel to the phrenic arteries which include the two superior and two inferior phrenic veins.
superior intercostal vein The superior intercostal veins are two veins that drain the 2nd, 3rd, and 4th intercostal spaces, one vein for each side of the body.
left superior intercostal vein left superior intercostal vein_1
right superior intercostal vein right superior intercostal vein_1
intercostal vein The intercostal veins are a group of veins which drain the area between the ribs.
intercostal space A space in the rib cage between two successive ribs.

posterior intercostal vein also known as venae intercostalis posterior The posterior intercostal veins are veins that drain the intercostal spaces posteriorly. They run with their corresponding posterior intercostal artery on the underside of the rib, the vein superior to the artery. Each vein also gives off a dorsal branch that drains blood from the muscles of the back. There are eleven posterior intercostal veins on each side. Their patterns are variable, but they are commonly arranged as: The 1st posterior intercostal vein, supreme intercostal vein, drains into the brachiocephalic vein or the vertebral vein. The 2nd and 3rd (and often 4th) posterior intercostal veins drain into the superior intercostal vein. The remaining posterior intercostal veins drain into the azygos vein on the right, or the hemiazygos vein on the left.
anterior intercostal vein The anterior intercostal veins are the veins which drain the anterior intercostal space.

intercostal lymph node also known as intercostal node; nodi lymphoidei intercostales; nodus intercostale The intercostal lymph nodes (intercostal glands ) occupy the posterior parts of the intercostal spaces, in relation to the intercostal vessels. They receive the deep lymphatics from the postero-lateral aspect of the chest; some of these vessels are interrupted by small lateral intercostal glands.
superior phrenic vein The superior phrenic vein, i.e. , the vein accompanying the pericardiacophrenic artery, usually opens into the internal mammary vein.

ureteric bud trunk Ureteric bud cells that elongate to form a rigid structure (stalk) consisting of polarized epithelial cells without branching; the stalks differentiate into the collecting system of the mature kidney, while the tip cells interact with the adjacent cells of the metanephric mesenchyme, inducing their conversion into nephrons.

urinary bladder vasculature also known as bladder vasculature; blood vessels of bladder; set of urinary bladder blood vessels Network of tubes that carries blood through the distensible musculomembranous organ that serves to collect and store urine excreted by the kidneys[MP].

urethral meatus also known as external meatus of urethra; external urethral orifice; external urethral ostium; external urinary meatus; meatus urinarius; orificium urethrae externum; orificium urethr externum; urethral meatus External opening or orifice of the urethra through which urine and seminal fluid (in males only) leave the body; in males the meatus presents as a vertical slit normally positioned at the tip of glans penis; in females the meatus is located between the clitoris and the vagina in the vulvular vestibule of the female genitalia[MP].

male urethral meatus also known as external orifice of male urethra; external urethral orifice (male); male urethra ostium; ostium urethrae externum (urethra masculina); urethral meatus of penile urethra A urethral meatus that is part of a male urethra[Automatically generated definition].

internal urethral orifice also known as internal meatus of urethra; internal urethral orifice of urinary bladder; internal urethral ostium; orificium urethrae internum; ostium orificium internum; ostium urethrae internum; vesicourethral orifice The usually crescent-shaped opening of the urinary bladder into the urethra, placed at the anteroinferior angle (apex) of the urinary bladder trigone.
stratum intermedium of epidermis A temporary layer between old and new skin that is invalided by white blood cells[Kardong].

thyroid follicular lumen also known as lumen of thyroid follicle; thyroid follicle lumen; thyroid follicular space A follicular lumen is the closed cavity within a follicle of the thyroid gland. It is surrounded by follicular cells and filled with colloid, a concentrated solution of thyroglobulin.
cervical gland also known as glandulae cervicales Mucus-secreting glands in the mucosa of the uterine cervix.
cervical mucosa Lining of the head of the uterus (cervix); contains large branched glands; does not undergo sloughing.

ectocervix also known as ectocervix; portio vaginalis; portio vaginalis cervicis; uterine ectocervix; vaginal part of cervix The part of the cervix uteri that protrudes into the vagina and is lined with stratified squamous epithelium.
cervix glandular epithelium A glandular epithelium that is part of a uterine cervix.
ectocervical epithelium also known as exocervical epithelium An epithelium that is part of a ectocervix.
endocervical epithelium also known as endocervical glandular epithelium The glandular epithelium that lines the endocervix.

cervical squamo-columnar junction also known as squamo-columnar junction of uterine cervix; squamocolumnar junction of uterine cervix Region of cervical epithelium where columnar epithelium of endocervic and the stratified non-keratinising squamous epithelium of the ectocervic meet.
abdominal aorta artery also known as abdominal artery; artery of abdomen An artery that originates from the abdominal aorta.

inferior phrenic artery also known as arteriae phrenicae inferiores The inferior phrenic arteries are two small vessels, which supply the diaphragm but present much variety in their origin. They may arise separately from the front of the aorta, immediately above the celiac artery, or by a common trunk, which may spring either from the aorta or from the celiac artery. Sometimes one is derived from the aorta, and the other from one of the renal arteries; they rarely arise as separate vessels from the aorta. They diverge from one another across the crura of the diaphragm, and then run obliquely upward and lateralward upon its under surface. The left phrenic passes behind the esophagus, and runs forward on the left side of the esophageal hiatus. The right phrenic passes behind the inferior vena cava, and along the right side of the foramen which transmits that vein. Near the back part of the central tendon each vessel divides into a medial and a lateral branch. The medial branch curves forward, and anastomoses with its fellow of the opposite side, and with the musculophrenic and pericardiacophrenic arteries. The lateral branch passes toward the side of the thorax, and anastomoses with the lower intercostal arteries, and with the musculophrenic. The lateral branch of the right phrenic gives off a few vessels to the inferior vena cava; and the left one, some branches to the esophagus. Each vessel gives off superior suprarenal branches to the suprarenal gland of its own side. The spleen and the liver also receive a few twigs from the left and right vessels respectively.
digestive syncytial vacuole digestive syncytial vacuole_1

forestomach-glandular stomach junction The distinct low fold of tissue that separates the non-glandular area of the stomach (forestomach) from the glandular stomach; the limiting ridge extends circumferentially from the large curvature of the stomach to the small curvature, just below the esophagus; at the esophagus, the course of the limiting ridge bends into a U-shape and almost surrounds the esophageal opening.

major duodenal papilla also known as greater duodenal papilla; tubercle of Vater The common bile duct and the pancreatic duct together perforate the medial side of the second portion of the duodenum obliquely, some 7 to 10 cm below the pylorus, forming a structure called the major duodenal papilla. The accessory pancreatic duct sometimes pierces it about 2 cm above and slightly in front of these.

minor duodenal papilla also known as lesser duodenal papilla; Santorini's caruncle; Santorini's minor caruncle The minor duodenal papilla is the opening of the accessory pancreatic duct into the duodenum. It is sometimes absent, and often nonfunctional.
periampullary region of duodenum also known as periampullary region periampullary region of duodenum_1

columnar epithelium An epithelium that consists of columnar epithelial cells. Columnar epithelia are epithelial cells whose heights are at least four times their width. Columnar epithelia are divided into simple (or unilayered), and the rarer stratified (or multi-layered).[WP, modified].
meso-epithelium also known as mesoderm-derived epithelium; mesoepithelium Epithelium that derives from the mesoderm. [Automatically generated definition].
endometrium glandular epithelium also known as glandular part of endometrium; uterine glands; uterine glands set endometrium glandular epithelium_1

gland of nasal mucosa also known as glandula nasalis; glandulae nasales The nasal glands are the seromucous glands in the respiratory region of the nasal mucous membrane. The three major types of nasal glands are anterior serous glands, seromucous glands, and Bowman glands.

chromaffin paraganglion Small bodies containing chromaffin cells occurring outside of the adrenal medulla, most commonly near the sympathetic ganglia and in organs such as the kidney, liver, heart and gonads.
mammary fat pad Encapsulated adipose tissue associated with the mammary gland.
femoral fat pad also known as femoral fat depot Encapsulated adipose tissue associated with the femur.
animal hemisphere The animal pole consists of small cells that divide rapidly, in contrast with the vegetal pole below it.
vegetal hemisphere The vegetal pole contains large yolky cells that divide very slowly, in contrast with the animal pole above it.
hemisphere of embryo One of two hemispheres of the embryo at the zygote or blastula stage[WP,modified].
Rathkes pouch epithelium An epithelial sac that is part of a Rathke's pouch.
centroquartal bone also known as os centroquartale; os naviculocuboideum A tarsal bone that is formed from the fusion of the central and 4th tarsal bones.
fused tarsal bones 2 and 3 also known as fused tarsals 2 and 3; os cuneiforme intermediolaterale; os tarsale II et III A tarsal bone that is formed from the fusion of the 2nd and 3rd tarsal bones.
fused carpal bones 2 and 3 also known as fused carpals 2 and 3 A carpal bone that is formed from the fusion of the 2nd and 3rd distal carpal bones.
lateral malleolus of fibula Malleolus is the name for the bony prominence on each side of the ankle.

embryonic cloacal fold One of the pair of mesenchymal swellings (folds) located on either side of the cloacal membrane during the indifferent stage of embryonic development; cranial to the cloacal membrane the folds unite to form the genital tubercle; caudally the folds are subdivided into urogenital folds anteriorly and anal folds posteriorly.
anal fold A slight elevation flanking the cloacal membrane and derived from a cloacal fold; anal folds form the border of the anus.

navicular fossa of spongiose part of urethra also known as fossa navicularis of urethra; fossa navicularis urethrae; fossa navicularis urethrae (pars spongiosa, urethra masculina); navicular fossa; navicular fossa of urethra The dilated terminal portion of the male spongy urethra located in the glans penis right before the external urethral orifice, also referred to as the most distal pendulous urethra; it is lined by stratified squamous, non-keratinizing epithelium; during development, the glans of the penis is initially solid but cannulates to give rise to the navicular fossa.

Gurin's valve also known as Gurin's fold; Guerin's valve; Gurin's valvule; urethral valve of Gurin; valve of fossa navicularis of urethra; valvula fossae navicularis An inconstant fold or valve of mucous membrane sometimes found in the root or upper wall of the navicular fossa of the urethra.
urethral crest also known as crista of urethra; crista urethralis; urethral crista A longitudinal mucosal fold in the dorsal wall of the urethra[MP].

male urethral crest also known as crista phallica; crista urethralis masculinae; urethral crest (male); urethral crest of male Narrow longitudinal fold of mucosa on the posterior wall of the male urethra, extending from the uvula of the bladder through the prostatic urethra; when distended, it may serve to prevent the passage of the semen backward into the bladder; on either side of the male urethral crest is a slightly depressed fossa, the prostatic sinus, the floor of which is perforated by the orifices of the prostatic ducts from the lateral lobes of the prostate; the ducts of the middle lobe open behind the crest; at the forepart of the crest, below its summit, is a median elevation, the colliculus seminalis, upon or within the margins of which are the orifices of the prostatic utricle and the slit-like openings of the ejaculatory ducts[MP].

female urethral crest also known as crista urethralis femininae; urethral crest (female); urethral crest of female The conspicuous longitudinal fold of mucosa on the posterior wall of the female urethra[MP].
mucosa of urethra also known as mucous membrane of urethra; tunica mucosa urethrae; urethral mucosa A mucosa that is part of a urethra.
limb paddle A transient developing limb structure that develops from the limb bud; it is a dorsoventral flattening of the limb bud structure and develops into the foot plate.
female membranous urethra A membranous urethra of male or female that is part of a female urethra.

male membranous urethra The shortest, least dilatable, and, with the exception of the external orifice, the narrowest part of the male urethral canal located in the deep perineal pouch and lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium; it extends downward and forward, with a slight anterior concavity, between the apex of the prostate and the bulb of the urethra, perforating the urogenital diaphragm below and behind the pubic symphysis; the membranous portion of the urethra is completely surrounded by the fibers of the sphincter urethrae membranaceae; on either side near its termination are the bulbourethral glands.

ureteral orifice also known as Mercier's bar; orifice of ureter; orificium ureteris; ostium ureteris; ureteral meatus; ureteral opening; ureteric orifice; ureteric ostium; ureterovesical orifice The slit-like opening of either ureter into the bladder; normally, the two ureteral orifices are placed at the posterolateral angles of the urinary bladder trigone while the internal urethral orifice is placed at its anteroinferior angle (apex); wide gaping usually indicates vesicoureteral reflux.

nasal diverticulum Caudally blind-ending cutaneous pouch lined with skin that occupies the nasoincisive notch. It's ventral and medial walls is formed by the alar fold. It's lateral wall is formed by the external nares and it's dorsal wall is formed by the straight fold. Lined by pigmented predominantly hairless skin. It has an external opening located on the dorsolateral aspect of the "true nostril". When the horse is exercising, obliteration of the nasal diverticulum greatly widens the nostrils increasing air intake[MURDOCH].
marginal cutaneous pouch of ear A fold of skin at the caudal border of the auricle.
lateral cervical lymph node also known as lateral cervical node A cervical lymph nodes are found in proximity to an internal or external jugular vein.
anterior cervical lymph node also known as anterior cervical node The anterior cervical lymph nodes are a group of nodes found on the anterior part of the neck.
superficial lateral cervical lymph node also known as superficial lateral cervical node The superficial lateral cervical lymph nodes are found in proximity to the external jugular vein.
superficial anterior cervical lymph node also known as anterior jugular lymph node The superficial anterior cervical lymph nodes are found in proximity to the anterior jugular vein.

deep lateral cervical lymph node also known as deep lateral cervical node The deep lateral cervical lymph nodes are found near the upper part of the internal jugular vein in the neck, lateral or posterior to the carotid sheath.
deep anterior cervical lymph node The deep anterior cervical lymph nodes are found near the middle cricothyroid ligament and the trachea.
maxillary process ectoderm maxillary process ectoderm_1
1st arch maxillary ectoderm also known as ectoderm of maxillary component 1st arch maxillary ectoderm_1
embryonic facial prominence One of five swellings formed during the development of the face.
incisive foramen also known as foramina incisivum; nasopalatine foramen; Stenson's foramen The point where the primary palate and both palatine shelves fuse.
primitive palate Roof of the buccal cavity, formed from the fusion of vomer, pterygoid, parasphenoid, palatine, ectopterygoid.

vagina orifice also known as opening of vagina; orifice of vagina; ostium vaginae; vagina opening; vaginal orifice The median slit located inferior and posterior to the external urethral orifice in the female; the exit for menstrual flow and birth and the entrance for the penis during sexual intercourse; the size and appearance of the vaginal orifice varies inversely with that of the hymen (G. membrane), a thin fold of mucous membrane that surrounds the vaginal orifice.

anterior ethmoidal artery also known as a. ethmoidalis anterior; arteria ethmoidalis anterior The anterior ethmoidal artery, also anterior ethmoid artery is an artery of the head. Once branching from the ophthalmic artery, it accompanies the nasociliary nerve through the anterior ethmoidal canal to supply the anterior and middle ethmoidal cells, frontal sinus, and anterosuperior aspect of the lateral nasal wall[WP].

posterior ethmoidal artery also known as a. ethmoidalis posterior; arteria ethmoidalis posterior The posterior ethmoidal artery is an artery of the head. It is smaller than the anterior ethmoidal artery, branches off from the ophthalmic artery when it reaches the medial wall of the orbit.
cervical artery An artery of the neck.
deep cervical artery The deep cervical artery (Profunda cervicalis) is an artery of the neck.

ascending cervical artery The ascending cervical artery is a small branch which arises from the inferior thyroid artery as that vessel is passing behind the carotid sheath; it runs up on the anterior tubercles of the transverse processes of the cervical vertebrC& in the interval between the Scalenus anterior and Longus capitis. To the muscles of the neck it gives twigs which anastomose with branches of the vertebral, and it sends one or two spinal branches into the vertebral canal through the intervertebral foramina to be distributed to the medulla spinalis and its membranes, and to the bodies of the vertebrC&, in the same manner as the spinal branches from the vertebral. It anastomoses with the ascending pharyngeal and occipital arteries.

transverse cervical artery The transverse cervical artery (transverse artery of neck, transversa colli artery) is a branch of the thyrocervical trunk, running at a higher level than the suprascapular artery.
gubernacular bulb The caudal, swollen portion of the gubernaculum.
pearly penile papule also known as hirsuties coronae glandis; hirsutoid papilloma Small saliences on the ridge of the glans of the male genital organs.

keratinized stratified squamous epithelium also known as epithelium stratificatum squamosum cornificatum Keratinized stratified squamous epithelium is a stratified squamous epithelium, the cells of which synthesize and accumulate keratin.
nasal-associated lymphoid tissue also known as NALT; naso-pharyngeal lymphoid tissue The lymphocytic cell population present in the mucosa of the nasopharyngeal duct of some animals.

mesosalpinx also known as fallopian tube mesosalpinx; mesentery of fallopian tube; mesentery of uterine tube; serous layer of fallopian tube A serous layer that is part of the peritoneal lining of the abdominal cavity in higher vertebrates, specifically the portion of the broad ligament that stretches from the uterine (fallopian) tube to the ovary. It is made up of epithelial cells of mesothelium and a mesh of serous membrane lining.
broad ligament of uterus also known as broad uterine ligament A broad fold of peritoneum that extends from the side of the uterus to the wall of the pelvis.
ovarian bursa A pouch formed by the mesosalpinx and the mesovarium that encloses the infundibulum of the uterine tube and the ovary.
perianal skin also known as skin of perianal area A zone of skin that is part of the area surrounding the anus.

cauda equina The cauda equina is a structure within the lower end of the spinal column of most vertebrates, that consists of nerve roots and rootlets from above. The space in which the cerebrospinal fluid is present is actually an extension of the subarachnoid space.

holocrine gland Any exocrine gland whose secretion consists of its own disintegrated secretory cells along with its secretory product; holocrine secretions are produced in the cytoplasm of the cell and released by the rupture of the plasma membrane, which destroys the cell and results in the secretion of the product into the lumen.
autopod pad Pigmented, keratinised, hairless epidermis covering subcutaneous, collagenous, and adipose tissue.
digital pad also known as acropodial pad; acropodium pad; interdigital pad A thick spongy structure at the base of the autopod, centred over the flexor surfaces of the distal interphalangeal joints.
carpal pad An autopod pad found in the carpal region of a manus. Used for additional traction when stopping or descending a slope in digitigrade species.
urachal lumen also known as urachus lumen An anatomical space that is enclosed by a urachus.
mesangial matrix also known as extracellular mesangial matrix Extracellular matrix secreted by intraglomerular mesangial cells.

acropodium region also known as acropodial limb segment; acropodial region; acropodial segment of autopod; set of digits The segment of the autopod that is distal to the metapodial region and consists of the digits.

manual acropodium region also known as acropodial hindlimb segment; acropodial region of manus; acropodial segment of manus; all fingers; anterior acropodium region; anterior acropodium segment of limb; digiti manus; digits of hand; fingers including thumb; fingers set; manual acropodium region; manual acropodium segment of limb; set of digits of hand; set of fingers The segment of the manus that is distal to the metacarpal region and consists of the manual digits (fingers).

pedal acropodium region also known as acropodial forelimb segment; acropodial region of pes; acropodial segment of pes; all toes; digits of foot; pedal acropodium region; set of toes; toes set The segment of the pes that is distal to the metatarsal region and consists of the pedal digits (toes).
digitopodium bone A bone that is part of a the digitopodium skeleton - i.e. the acropodial skeleton or the metapodial skeleton.
manual digitopodium bone also known as bone of forelimb digitopodium A bone that is part of a the manual digitopodium skeleton - i.e. the fingers or the metacarpal skeleton.
pedal digitopodium bone also known as bone of hindlimb digitopodium A bone that is part of a the pedal digitopodium skeleton - i.e. the toes or the metatarsal skeleton.
bone of jaw also known as jaw bone A bone element that is part of a jaw region.
internal anal region internal anal region_1
thyroid follicle epithelium also known as epithelium of thyroid follicle; thyroid follicle epithelium; wall of thyroid follicle An epithelium that is part of a thyroid follicle.
colloid of thyroid follicle also known as thyroid colloid; thyroid follicle colloid Portion of substance contained within the thyroid follicle lumen. Contains prohormone thyroglobulin.
muscle layer of intestine also known as intestinal muscularis propria; muscularis externa of intestine A muscle layer that is part of an intestine.
circular muscle layer of muscular coat The inner layer of the muscular coat.
longitudinal muscle layer of muscular coat The outer layer of the muscular coat.
sympathetic nerve plexus A nerve plexus that is part of a sympathetic nervous system.
subserosal plexus also known as subserous nerve plexus; subserous plexus; tela subserosa The subserous part of the enteric plexus of autonomic nerves.
subserosa A layer of tissue between the muscularis and serosa.
retromolar triangle The small area behind the wisdom teeth.
muscle layer of jejunum also known as muscularis externa of jejunum A muscular coat that is part of a jejunum.

muscle layer of urinary bladder also known as bladder muscular coat; muscle layer of urinary bladder; muscular coat of bladder; muscular coat of urinary bladder; muscular layer of bladder; muscular layer of urinary bladder; tunica musculari vesicae; tunica muscularis (vesica urinaria) A muscular coat that is part of a urinary bladder.
large intestine smooth muscle circular layer A circular muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a large intestine smooth muscle.
large intestine smooth muscle longitudinal layer A longitudinal muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a large intestine smooth muscle.

small intestine smooth muscle circular layer also known as circular layer of small intestine muscularis propria; circular muscle coat of small intestine; circular muscle layer of small intestine; circular muscle of small intestine; short pitch helicoidal muscle layer of small intestine; stratum circulare (tunica muscularis)(intestinum tenue); stratum circulare tunicae muscularis intestini tenuis; stratum helicoidale brevis gradus tunicae muscularis intestini tenuis A circular muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a small intestine smooth muscle.

small intestine smooth muscle longitudinal layer also known as long pitch helicoidal muscle layer of small intestine; longitudinal layer of small intestine muscularis propria; longitudinal muscle coat of small intestine; longitudinal muscle layer of small intestine; longitudinal muscle of small intestine; stratum helicoidale longi gradus tunicae muscularis intestini tenuis; stratum longitudinale (tunica muscularis) (intestinum tenue); stratum longitudinale tunicae muscularis intestini tenuis A longitudinal muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a small intestine smooth muscle.
respiratory system arterial smooth muscle respiratory system arterial smooth muscle_1
respiratory system venous smooth muscle A smooth muscle tissue that is part of a respiratory system venous blood vessel.

taenia coli also known as longitudinal band of large intestine muscularis The taeniae coli (also teniae coli) are three separate longitudinal ribbons of smooth muscle on the outside of the ascending, transverse, descending and sigmoid colons. They are visible, and can be seen just below the serosa or fibrosa. They are the Mesocolic, Free and Omental Coli. The teniae coli contracts length wise to produce the haustra, the bulges in the colon. The bands converge at the root of the vermiform appendix and the rectum. These bands correspond to the outer layer of the muscularis externa, in other portions of the digestive tract.
coprodeum also known as cloacal coprodeum; coprodaeum; coprodeal portion of cloaca Most proximal cloacal compartment, into which the large intestine empties[Kardong].
layer of microvilli A layer of microvilli, Thin cylindrical membrane-covered projections on the surface of an animal cell containing a core bundle of actin filaments[GO,modified].

brush border layer The microvilli-covered surface of simple cuboidal epithelium and simple columnar epithelium cells found in certain locations of the body; mainly in the small an large intestines and kidneys.
striated border microvillus layer A microvillus layer that is striated and found in the intestine.
short microvillus layer A layer of microvilli covering lymphocytes.
intestinal brush border layer also known as brush border microvillus layer of intestine; intestinal brush border A brush border layer that is part of a intestine.
proximal convoluted tubule brush border A brush border layer that is part of a proximal tubule in the kidney.
hematopoietic tissue also known as haemopoietic tissue; hematopoietic tissue; hemopoietic tissue; textus haemopoieticus Blood-forming tissue, consisting of reticular fibers and cells.

tunica fibrosa of eyeball also known as fibrous layer of eyeball The sclera and cornea form the fibrous tunic of the bulb of the eye; the sclera is opaque, and constitutes the posterior five-sixths of the tunic; the cornea is transparent, and forms the anterior sixth.
epithelial-mesenchymal boundary An anatomical line that adjacent_to a epithelium and adjacent_to a mesenchyme.
blastema of regenerating fin/limb A blastema that is part of a regenerating fin/limb.
blastema of regenerating digit tip A blastema that is part of a distal segment of digit.
endothelium of peritubular capillary also known as peritubular capillary endothelium An endothelium that is part of a peritubular capillary.

epiploic foramen also known as aditus to lesser sac; epiploic foramen of Winslow; foramen of Winslow; foramen omentale; foramen omentale (epiploicum); omental foramen The passage of communication, or foramen, between the general cavity (of the abdomen), and the omental bursa.
mechanoreceptor A sensory receptor that responds to mechanical pressure or distortion.

Meissner's corpuscle A type of nerve ending in the skin that is responsible for sensitivity to light touch. In particular, they have highest sensitivity (lowest threshold) when sensing vibrations lower than 50 Hertz. They are rapidly adaptive receptors.

sensory receptor also known as peripheral ending of sensory neuron A sensory nerve ending that responds to a stimulus in the internal or external environment of an organism. In response to stimuli the sensory receptor initiates sensory transduction by creating graded potentials or action potentials in the same cell or in an adjacent one.

nerve ending Specialized terminations of peripheral neurons. Nerve endings include NEUROEFFECTOR JUNCTION(s) by which neurons activate target organs and sensory receptors (see RECEPTORS, SENSORY) which transduce information from the various sensory modalities and send it centrally in the nervous system. Presynaptic nerve endings are PRESYNAPTIC TERMINALS.

Merkel nerve ending also known as Merkel's disc; Merkel's disk; Merkel's receptor; Merkel's tactile disc Mechanoreceptors found in the skin and mucosa of vertebrates that provide touch information to the brain. The information they provide are those regarding pressure and texture. Each ending consists of a Merkel cell in close apposition with an enlarged nerve terminal.
Ruffini nerve ending also known as corpusculum sensorium fusiforme; Ruffini's corpuscle An encapsulated nerve receptor present in subpapillary dermis and deep dermis of hairy and glabrous skin.
proctodeum portion of cloaca Most distal cloacal compartment; function is copulation and in some species develops a penis[Kardong].
cloacal lumen also known as cloacal chamber; cloaca lumen An anatomical space that is enclosed by a cloaca.
cloacal vent also known as cloacal opening The opening of the cloacal chamber to the outside of the organism. Birds maintain a single cloacal opening throughout their lives.
lumen of terminal part of digestive tract An anatomical space that is enclosed by a terminal part of digestive tract.
extraembryonic cavity extraembryonic cavity_1
enclosed anatomical space also known as closed anatomical space An anatomical space with no opening to another space or to the exterior.
external anal region external anal region_1
hepatogastric ligament also known as gastro-hepatic ligament; gastrohepatic ligament; hepato-gastric ligament; ligamentum hepatogastricum Ligament extending between the liver and stomach.

hepatoduodenal ligament also known as ligamentum hepatoduodenale The hepatoduodenal ligament is the portion of the lesser omentum extending between the porta hepatis of the liver and the superior part of the duodenum.
skeleton of pectoral complex The collection of all skeletal elements in a pectoral complex - i.e. the combination of free limb or fin plus pectoral girdle.
skeleton of pelvic complex The collection of all skeletal elements in a pelvic complex - i.e. the combination of free limb or fin plus pelvic girdle.

dorsal part of neck also known as back of neck; nape of neck; neck back; nucha; nuchal region; posterior cervical region; posterior neck region; posterior part of neck; regio cervicalis posterior The posterior region of the neck, including the suboccipital region.
cloacal gland A gland that is part of a cloaca.

cloacal mucosa also known as cloaca mucosa; cloaca mucosa of organ; cloaca mucous membrane; cloaca organ mucosa; cloacal mucous membrane; mucosa of cloaca; mucosa of organ of cloaca; mucous membrane of cloaca; organ mucosa of cloaca A mucosa that is part of a cloaca [Automatically generated definition].
cloacal epithelium An epithelium that is part of a cloaca.
submucosa of cloaca also known as cloaca submucosa; cloacal submucosa A submucosa that is part of a cloaca [Automatically generated definition].

serosa of cloaca also known as cloaca serosa; cloaca serous membrane; cloacal serosa; serous membrane of cloaca; visceral peritoneum of cloaca A serous membrane that is part of a cloaca [Automatically generated definition].
cloacal villus also known as cloacal villi cloacal villus_1
muscle layer of cloaca also known as muscularis externa of cloaca A muscular coat that is part of a cloaca.
muscle layer of duodenum also known as duodenal muscularis propria; muscularis externa of duodenum A muscular coat that is part of a duodenum.

muscle layer of colon also known as colonic muscularis propria; muscular coat of colon; muscular layer of colon; muscularis externa of colon; tunica muscularis coli A muscular coat that is part of a colon.

muscle layer of anal canal also known as anal canal muscularis propria; anal muscularis propria; muscular coat of anal canal; muscular layer of anal canal; muscularis externa of anal canal; muscularis propria of anal canal A muscular coat that is part of a anal canal.
muscularis mucosae of duodenum also known as lamina muscularis of duodenal mucous membrane; lamina muscularis of duodenum A muscularis mucosa that is part of a duodenum.
muscularis mucosae of rectum also known as lamina muscularis of rectal mucosa; lamina muscularis of rectal mucous membrane A muscularis mucosa that is part of a rectum.
serosa of appendix also known as appendiceal serosa; appendix serosa; serosa of vermiform appendix; visceral peritoneum of vermiform appendix A serous membrane that is part of a vermiform appendix.

serosa of fallopian tube also known as serosa of oviduct; serosa of uterine tube; serous coat of uterine tube; tunica serosa (tuba uterina); tunica serosa tubae uterinae; uterine tubal serosa; uterine tube serosa A serous membrane that is part of a fallopian tube.
serosa of fundus of stomach also known as visceral peritoneum of fundus of stomach A serous membrane that is part of a fundus of stomach.

adventitia of esophagus also known as adventitia of oesophagus; adventitious layer of esophagus; esophageal adventitia; esophagus adventitia; tunica adventitia (esophagus); tunica adventitia oesophageae An adventitia that is part of a esophagus.
umbilical smooth muscle A smooth muscle tissue that is part of a umbilical cord.

ampulla of fallopian tube also known as ampulla of oviduct; ampulla of uterine tube; ampulla tubae uterinae; uterine tube ampulla The ampulla is the second portion of the uterine tube. It is an intermediate dilated portion, which curves over the ovary. It is the most common site of human fertilization. The word ampulla is from the Latin for flask.
anococcygeus muscle also known as anococcygeus One of a pair of thin sheets of smooth muscle inserting on the rectum, having a tendinous origin largely on sacral vertebrae.
gastroduodenal junction An anatomical junction that connects a stomach and connects a duodenum.
mucosa of gastroduodenal junction also known as gastroduodenal mucosa A mucosa that is part of a gastroduodenal junction.
colorectum The subdivision of the digestive tract that consists of the colon and the rectum.
bronchial bud bronchial bud_1
colorectal mucosa A mucosa that is part of a colorectum.
palatine torus also known as torus palatinus A bony protuberance sometimes found on the hard palate at the junction of the intermaxillary suture and the transverse palatine suture.
popliteal area also known as popliteal fossa A depression on the ventral side of the femur, at the knee joint, between the condyles.
venom-injecting tooth A fang that is used to inject venom into prey, through either a tube or a groove.
angular/surangular bone Bone formed from the fusion of angular and surangular bones. Found in snakes.
pterygoideus glandulae muscle pterygoideus glandulae muscle_1
venom gland musculature venom gland musculature_1

sulcus of brain also known as cerebral sulci A depression or fissure in the surface of the brain. It surrounds the gyri, creating the characteristic appearance of the brain in humans and other large mammals.
haemal node also known as hemal node A lymphoid organ found in various mammals and some birds.
eyelid submuscular connective tissue eyelid submuscular connective tissue_1

proximal epiphysis of phalanx of pes also known as basal epiphysis of phalanx of foot; base of phalanx of foot; basis phalangis (pedis); basis phalangis pedis; proximal epiphysis of phalanx of toe proximal epiphysis of phalanx of pes_1

distal epiphysis of phalanx of pes also known as caput phalangis (pedis); caput phalangis pedis; distal end of phalanx of foot; distal epiphysis of phalanx of toe; head of phalanx of foot distal epiphysis of phalanx of pes_1
left posterior cardinal vein also known as left postcardinal vein; posterior cardinal vein left A posterior cardinal vein that is in_the_left_side_of a multicellular organism.
left subcardinal vein also known as subcardinal vein left A subcardinal vein that is in_the_left_side_of a multicellular organism.
vein of abdomen also known as abdominal vein A vein that is part of a abdomen.
pulmonary venous system also known as pulmonary venous circulatory system The part of the venous system that drains the lungs[Kardong].

bulb of penis also known as bulbus penis; penile bulb; urethral bulb Just before each crus of the penis meets its fellow it presents a slight enlargement, named by Kobelt the bulb of the corpus spongiosum penis. It is homologous to the vestibular bulbs in females.

bulb of vestibule also known as bulbus vestibuli vaginae; vestibular bulb; vestibular bulb of vagina Aggregations of erectile tissue that are an internal part of the clitoris. They can also be found throughout the vestibule: next to the clitoral body, clitoral crura, urethra, urethral sponge, and vagina.

penicillar arteriole also known as penicillus; penicilli One of the small straight arteries of the red pulp of the spleen; a branch of the spleen central artery that supplies the red pulp[WP,modified].

superior phrenic artery also known as arteria phrenicea superioris; arteriae phrenicae superiores A phrenic artery that arises from the lower part of the thoracic aorta and is distributed to the posterior part of the upper surface of the diaphragm, and anastomoses with the musculophrenic and pericardiacophrenic arteries.
interdental plate The interdental plate refers to the bone-filled mesial-distal region between the teeth.
vein of lip also known as labial vein of face; lip vein; vena labialis A vein that drains a lip.
external pudendal artery also known as arteriae pudendae externa; arteriae pudendales externa Either the superficial or deep external pudendal arteries.

coronary ligament of liver also known as coronary ligament; ligamentum coronarium; ligamentum coronarium hepatis The coronary ligament of the liver refers to parts of the peritoneal reflections that hold the liver to the inferior surface of the diaphragm.
ligament of liver also known as hepatic ligament; liver ligament A nonskeletal ligament that is part of a liver.
systemic vein also known as systemic venous tree organ part Any vein within the general circulation that transports blood back to the right atrium of the heart.
capillary bed A localized group of blood capillaries.
soleal vein also known as soleus vein; vein of soleus muscle; vena solealis A vein that drains the soleus.
gastrocnemius vein also known as vein of gastrocnemius muscle; vena gastrocnemii A vein that drains the gastrocnemius.
vein of genicular venous plexus vein of genicular venous plexus_1
accessory saphenous vein also known as posteromedial vein of thigh accessory saphenous vein_1
venous system of brain also known as brain venous system Missing definition for term UBERON:0013146. Please replace it using linked reference.
early mesencephalic vesicle also known as mesencephalic vesicle early mesencephalic vesicle_1
early midbrain vesicle also known as midbrain vesicle early midbrain vesicle_1
hindbrain vesicle also known as rhombencephalic vesicle hindbrain vesicle_1
future brain vesicle also known as early brain vesicle; primitive brain vesicle future brain vesicle_1

choroidal artery also known as artery of choroid plexus; choroid artery One of two arteries (anterior and posterior choroidal artery) that supply blood to the choroid plexus, optic tract, hippocampus, globus pallidus, and other various brain regions.

interventricular foramen of heart A temporary opening between the developing ventricles of the heart. The ventricles arise as a single cavity is divided by the developing interventricular septum. Before the septum closes completely, the remaining opening between the two ventricles is termed the interventricular foramen.
arachnoid villus Small protrusions of the arachnoid mater into vascular sinuses, acting as one-way pressure-sensitive valves.
1st arch maxillary endoderm also known as endoderm of maxillary component 1st arch maxillary endoderm_1
1st arch mandibular ectoderm also known as ectoderm of mandibular component 1st arch mandibular ectoderm_1
1st arch mandibular endoderm also known as endoderm of mandibular component 1st arch mandibular endoderm_1
1st arch maxillary-mandibular cleft also known as 1st arch maxillary-mandibular groove ectoderm; ectoderm of maxillary-mandibular groove 1st arch maxillary-mandibular cleft_1
foregut-midgut junction gland also known as gland of foregut-midgut junction A gland that is part of a foregut-midgut junction.
epithalamus mantle layer also known as mantle layer epithalamus; mantle layer of epithalamus epithalamus mantle layer_1
epithalamus ventricular layer also known as ventricular layer epithalamus; ventricular layer of epithalamus epithalamus ventricular layer_1
left lateral ventricle also known as left telencephalic ventricle A telencephalic ventricle that is in_the_left_side_of a telencephalon.
right lateral ventricle also known as right telencephalic ventricle A telencephalic ventricle that is in_the_right_side_of a telencephalon.
molariform tooth also known as postcanine tooth A molar or premolar.
epiglottic vallecula also known as vallecula epiglottica; vallecula of epiglottis A depression in front of the epiglottis, in which food is temporarily gathered as the animal chews.

vallecula of cerebellum also known as vallecula cerebelli On the upper surface of the cerebellum the vermis is elevated above the level of the hemispheres, but on the under surface it is sunk almost out of sight in the bottom of a deep depression between them; this depression is called the vallecula of the cerebellum, and lodges the posterior part of the medulla oblongata.
cricopharyngeal ligament also known as crico-pharyngeal ligament; ligamentum cricopharyngeum Laryngeal ligament that connects the cricoid cartilage to the pharynx[WP,modified].
thyroepiglottic ligament also known as ligamentum thyroepiglotticum; thyroepiglottic ligament Laryngeal ligament that connects the epiglottis to the thyroid cartilage[WP,modified].

vestibular ligament also known as ligamentum vestibulare; ventricular ligament; vestibular ligament of larynx The vestibular fold is a fibroelastic band which passes from the ventral margin of the cuneiform cartilage to the cranial dorsal surface of the thyroid cartilage. It forms the support for the free edge of the vestibular fold.
cricoarytenoid ligament also known as crico-arytenoid ligament; ligamentum cricoaryteneoideum Laryngeal ligament that connects the cricoid and arytenoid cartilages[WP,modified].

cricothyroid ligament also known as crico-thyroid ligament; ligamentum cricothyreoideum This attaches the caudal border of the thyroid cartilage to the ventral arch of the cricoid cartilage. Its sheetlike ventral portion is sometimes referred to as the cricothyroid membrane. Being elastic, it 'balances' movement at the hinge-like cricothyroid joint and determines the resting position of the larynx when the muscles are relaxed[MURDOCH]. The cricothyroid ligament is the larger part of the laryngeal membrane, continuing inferiorly as a median or anterior part and twin lateral ligaments. The median cricothyroid ligament is a flat band of white tissue joining the cricoid and thyroid cartilages, while the lateral cricothyroid ligament is also known as the cricothyroid membrane (also called conus elasticus).

cricotracheal ligament The cricotracheal ligament connects the cricoid cartilage with the first ring of the trachea[WP]. The caudal border of the cricoid cartilage is joined to the first ring of the trachea by this ligament. It is an extrinsic laryngeal ligament. It resembles the fibrous membrane which connects the cartilaginous rings of the trachea to each other.
anterior part of tympanic bone also known as anterior surface of tympanic plate; anterior wall of tympanic cavity; anterior wall of tympanum The anterior aspect of the tympanum.
entotympanic bone Entotympanics are independent elements present in the auditory bullae of various eutherians.

ovarian cortex also known as cortex of ovary; cortex ovarii (zona parenchymatosa) The layer of the ovarian stroma lying immediately beneath the tunica albuginea, composed of connective tissue cells and fibers, among which are scattered primary and secondary (antral) follicles in various stages of development; the cortex varies in thickness according to the age of the individual, becoming thinner with advancing years; included in the follicles are the cumulus oophorus, membrana granulosa (and the granulosa cells inside it), corona radiata, zona pellucida, and primary oocyte; the zona pellucida, theca of follicle, antrum and liquor folliculi are also contained in the follicle; also in the cortex is the corpus luteum derived from the follicles.

ovarian medulla also known as medulla of ovary; medulla ovarii (zona vasculosa) Highly vascular stroma found in the center of the ovary that forms from embryonic mesenchyme and contains blood vessels, lymphatic vessels, and nerves; this stroma forms the tissue of the hilum by which the ovarian ligament is attached, and through which the blood vessels enter; it does not contain any ovarian follicles.

parakeratinized epithelium An epithelium that is characterized by incomplete keratinization of the cells in the stratum corneum. The cells are flattened and composed primarily of packed tonofilaments. However, the cells may retain remnants of nuclei and other organelles.

orthokeratinized epithelium A keratinized epithelium in which the cells of the stratum corneum become very flat, loose their nuclei and cytoplasmic organelles and are now composed of densely packed tonofilaments cemented by filaggrin.
parakeratinized epithelium of gingiva also known as gingival parakeratinized epithelium A parakeratinized epithelium that is part of a gingiva.
stria of neuraxis also known as neuraxis stria; neuraxis striae stria of neuraxis

olfactory pathway Set of nerve fibers conducting impulses from olfactory receptors to the cerebral cortex. It includes the olfactory nerve; olfactory bulb; olfactory tract, olfactory tubercle, anterior perforated substance, and olfactory cortex. The term rhinencephalon is restricted to structures in the CNS receiving fibers from the olfactory bulb.

hypogastrium also known as hypogastric part of abdomen; hypogastric region; pubic part of abdomen; pubic region; regio pubica; suprapubic region The hypogastrium (or hypogastric region, or pubic region) is an area of the human abdomen located below the navel.

cerumen gland also known as cerumen-secreting gland; ceruminous gland; ceruminous sweat gland; earwax gland A specialized sudoriferous gland (sweat glands) located subcutaneously in the external auditory canal.
anal sac gland secretion A bodily secretion that is produced by a gland of anal sac.
udder A large pendulous organ consisting of two or more mammary glands enclosed in a common envelope and each provided with a single nipple.

zygomatic plate In rodent anatomy, the zygomatic plate is a bony plate derived from the flattened front part of the zygomatic arch (cheekbone). At the back, it connects to the front (maxillary) root of the zygomatic arch, and at the top it is connected to the rest of the skull via the antorbital bridge. It is part of the maxillary bone, or upper jaw, which also contains the upper cheekteeth. Primitively, rodents have a nearly horizontal zygomatic plate. In association with specializations in zygomasseteric system, several distinct morphologies have developed across the order. The term is also used for an analogous structure in some South American typotheres, including Pseudotypotherium and Medistylus.

rete mirabile A rete mirabile (Latin for 'wonderful net'; plural retia mirabilia) is a complex of arteries and veins lying very close to each other, found in some vertebrates. The rete mirabile utilizes countercurrent blood flow within the net (blood flowing in opposite directions. ) It exchanges heat, ions, or gases between vessel walls so that the two bloodstreams within the rete maintain a gradient with respect to temperature, or concentration of gases or solutes.

alveolar gland In contrast to tubular glands, in the second main variety of gland, the secretory portion is enlarged and the lumen variously increased in size. These are termed alveolar glands (or saccular glands, or acinar glands, or acinous glands). Some sources draw a clear distinction between acinar and alveolar glands, based upon the shape of the lumen. A further complication in the case of the alveolar glands may occur in the form of still smaller saccular diverticuli growing out from the main sacculi. These are termed alveoli. The term 'tubulo-alveolar' (or 'tubulo-acinar', or 'compound tubulo-acinar', or 'compound tubulo-alveolar') is used to describe glands that start out as branched tubular, and branch further to terminate in alveoli. This type of gland is found in the salivary glands, esophagus, and mammary glands. The term 'racemose gland' is used to describe a 'compound alveolar gland' or 'compound acinar gland'.

Ciaccio's gland also known as gland of Wolfring; gland of Wolfring and Ciacco; Wolfring's gland Ciaccio's glands are small tubular accessory lacrimal glands (glandulae lacrimales accessoriae) found in the lacrimal caruncle of the eyelid. They are located in the upper border of the tarsus, approximately in the middle between the extremities of the tarsal glands. Sometimes they are situated slightly above the tarsus. There are usually 2 to 5 of these glands in the upper eyelid, and their function is to produce tears which are secreted onto the surface of the conjunctiva. They are named after Italian anatomist Giuseppe Vincenzo Ciaccio (1824b1901), who described these glands in 1874. They are sometimes called Wolfring's glands after Polish ophthalmologist Emilj von Wolfring (1832-1906), who described them during the same time period as did Ciaccio. Another type of accessory lacrimal gland are Krause's glands, which are smaller, more numerous than Ciaccio's glands and are found along the superior and inferior fornices of the conjunctival sac.

accessory lacrimal gland also known as glandulae lacrimales accessoriae Serous gland with distended lumen. It includes the gland of Krause in the lacrimal sac and the gland of Wolfring on the inner surface of the upper eyelid. (NCI).

crypt of Henle also known as crypts of Henle; gland of Henle; Henle's gland Crypts of Henle are microscopic pockets found in scattered sections of the conjunctiva around the eyeball. They are responsible for secreting mucin, a proteinous substance that makes up the inner layer of tears. It coats the cornea to provide a hydrophilic layer that allows for even distribution of the tear film. The layer of mucin allows tears to glide evenly across the eye's surface[WP].

sweat gland of eyelid also known as ciliary gland; ciliary gland of moll; ciliary sweat gland of eyelid; gland of Moll; Moll's gland Glands of Moll, also known as ciliary glands, are modified apocrine sweat glands that are found on the margin of the eyelid. They are next to the base of the eyelashes, and anterior to the Meibomian glands within the distal eyelid margin. These glands are relatively large and tubular-shaped. The glands of Moll are named after Dutch oculist Jacob Anton Moll (1832-1914). Glands of Moll empty into the adjacent lashes. Glands of Moll and Zeis secrete lipid that adds to the superficial layer of the tear film, retarding evaporation. The glands of Moll are prone to infection and blockage of its duct with sebum and cell debris. Blockage of the gland's duct causes swelling which can manifest itself as a stye.
eyelid gland also known as gland of eyelid Any gland that is part of an eyelid. This includes sebaceous glands (Zeis gland, tarsal gland) and sweat glands (Moll's gland).
sebaceous gland of eyelid Any of the sebaceous glands that are in the eyelid. Examples: gland of Zeis (services eyelashes), gland of Meibom (tarsal gland - unconnected to eyelids).
serous acinus also known as acinus of serous gland The secretory unit of a serous gland. The acinar portion is composed of serous secreting cells.

ventrum also known as front of body proper; ventral part of organism; ventral region of organism A major organism subdivisionthat is the entire part of an anatomical structure ventral to a horizontal plane and bounded on one side by the same horizontal plane.
ventral trunk also known as anterolateral part of trunk; front of trunk; trunk front; trunk proper The subdivision of the trunk that overlaps with the ventrum.

genital papilla of vulva also known as mammalian genital papilla The genital papilla is a part of female external genitalia not present in humans, which appears as a small, fleshy flab of tissue. The papilla covers the opening of the vagina.
future glans future glans_1
future glans penis also known as glans of male genital tubercle A future glans that is part of a male genital tubercle.
future glans clitoris also known as glans of female genital tubercle A future glans that is part of a female genital tubercle.
embryonic urethral groove also known as sulcus urethralis primarius; urethral groove; urethral sulcus The precursor of the urethra.
vaginal plate The vaginal plate is a precursor to the inferior portion of the vagina. They form from sinovaginal bulbs.
sinovaginal bulb Solid evaginations of the UG sinus that develops into a vaginal plate that which will will eventually canalize to form the inferior portion of the vagina.
male paramesonephric duct An epithelial tube that develops from a Mullerian duct in a male. Later degenerates.

paradidymis also known as organ of Giraldes; organ of Giralds; Waldeyer's organ A small collection of convoluted tubules, situated in front of the lower part of the cord above the head of the epididymis. These tubes are lined with columnar ciliated epithelium, and probably represent the remains of a part of the Wolffian body but are functionless and vestigial. The Wolffian body operates as a kidney (metanephros) in fishes and amphibians, but the corresponding tissue is co-opted to form parts of the male reproductive system in other classes of vertebrate. The paradidymis represents a remnant of an unused, atrophied part of the Wolffian body[WP,modified].
paroophoron also known as Kobelt's tubules A collection of a few scattered rudimentary tubules child, situated in the broad ligament between the epoophoron and the uterus.

vesicular appendage of epoophoron also known as appendix vesiculosus; female cystic vesicular appendage In connection with the fimbriae of the uterine tube, or with the broad ligament close to them, there are frequently one or more small pedunculated vesicles. These are termed the vesicular appendages of the epoophoron.

remnnant of ductus deferens also known as ductus deferens vestige; ductus deferens vestigialis; vestige of ductus deferens Remnant in a female of the portion of the embryonic mesonephric duct that develops into the ductus deferens in males.

remnant of processus vaginalis also known as processus vaginalis vestige; vestige of processus vaginalis Incompletely obliterated remnants of the vaginal process of the peritoneum remaining in the spermatic cord.

canal of Nuck A patent pouch of peritoneum extending into the labia majora of women. It is analogous to the processus vaginalis in males. The pouch accompanies the gubernaculum during development of the urinary and reproductive organs, more specifically during the descent of the ovaries, and normally obliterates.
diaphysis of fibula also known as body of fibula; corpus fibulae; fibula diaphysis; shaft of fibula A diaphysis that is part of a fibula[Automatically generated definition].
diaphysis of tibia also known as body of tibia; corpus tibiae; shaft of tibia; tibial diaphysis A diaphysis that is part of a tibia.

stratum argenteum of choroid also known as choroid stratum argenteum A silver reflective layer in the outer choroid, adjacent to the sclera, frequently present in fish larvae but not as frequent in adults.
choroidal gland A gland that is part of a optic choroid.

blood vessel layer of choroid also known as lamina choroideae vasculosa; lamina vasculosa (choroid); lamina vasculosa of choroid; outer layer of choroid proper; vessel layer of choroid blood vessel layer of choroid_1
asterion of skull The asterion is the point on the skull corresponding to the posterior end of the parietomastoid suture.
bregma The bregma is the anatomical point on the skull at which the coronal suture is intersected perpendicularly by the sagittal suture.
cranial cavity also known as cavitas cranii Anatomical cavity that is the lumen of the skull and contains the brain.
crotaphion The crotaphion refers to two points on the skull at the tips of the greater wing of sphenoid bone. It is near the pterion.
epicranium The Epicranium is the medical term for the collection of structures covering the cranium. It consists of the muscles, aponeurosis, and skin.
groove for sigmoid sinus Groove for Sigmoid Sinus is a groove in the posterior cranial fossa.

infratemporal fossa The infratemporal fossa is an irregularly shaped cavity, situated below and medial to the zygomatic arch. Boundaries defined by: anteriorly, by the infratemporal surface of the maxilla and the ridge which descends from its zygomatic process posteriorly, by the articular tubercle of the temporal and the spinal angularis of the sphenoid superiorly, by the greater wing of the sphenoid below the infratemporal crest, and by the under surface of the temporal squama, containing the foramen ovale, which transmits the mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve, and the foramen spinosum, which transmits the middle meningeal artery inferiorly, by the medial pterygoid muscle attaching to the mandible medially, by the lateral pterygoid plate laterally, by the ramus of mandible, which contains the mandibular foramen, leading to the mandibular canal through which the inferior alveolar nerve passes. This also contains the lingula, a triangular piece of bone that overlies the mandibular foramen antero-medially. Finally, the mylohyoid groove descends obliquely transmitting the mylohyoid nerve the only motor branch of the anterior division of the trigeminal nerve.
jugal point The jugal point is the point at the anterior end of the upper border of the zygomatic arch where the masseteric and maxillary edges meet at an angle.

anatomical point connecting sagittal and lambdoidal sutures The occipital angle is rounded and corresponds with the point of meeting of the sagittal and lambdoidal sutures-a point which is termed the lambda (after the Greek letter of the same name); in the fetus this part of the skull is membranous, and is called the posterior fontanelle.
obelion The point of the sagittal suture which is on a level with the parietal foramina.
occipital bun A prominent bulge, or projection, of the occipital bone at the back of the skull[WP].
ophryon The ophryon is the point in the forehead just above the optic foramen, or eyesocket, and glabella.

porion The porion is the point on the human skull located at the upper margin of each ear canal (external auditory meatus, external acoustic meatus). It underlies the tragus. The anatomical landmark has significance in biological anthropology and craniometry.
postorbital process The Postorbital Process marks the rear, upper edge of the eye socket and is a projection from the frontal bone.

pterygomaxillary fissure The pterygomaxillary fissure is a fissure of the human skull. It is vertical, and descends at right angles from the medial end of the inferior orbital fissure; it is a triangular interval, formed by the divergence of the maxilla from the pterygoid process of the sphenoid. It connects the infratemporal with the pterygopalatine fossa, and transmits the terminal part of the maxillary artery. Alveolar branches of the maxillary nerve go from the pterygopalatine fossa to the infratemporal region via this fissure. In older texts, the pterygomaxillary fissure is sometimes called the pterygopalatine fissure.

sagittal crest of skull also known as crista sagittalis externa A ridge of bone running lengthwise along the midline of the top of the skull of many mammalian and reptilian skulls and serves as an attachment site for the temporailis muscle[WP,modified].
sagittal keel The Sagittal keel (torus) is a thickening of bone on part or all of the midline of the frontal bone, or parietal bones where they meet along the sagittal suture, or on both bones..

spheno-maxillary fossa The speno-maxillary fossa is a small triangular space situated at the angle of the junction of the spheno-maxillary and pterygo-maxillary fissures, and placed beneath the apex of the orbit. It is formed above by the under surface of the body of the sphenoid and by the orbital process of the palate bone.

spheno-petrosal fissure also known as fissura sphenopetrosa; sphenopetrosal fissure The sphenopetrosal fissure (or sphenopetrosal suture) is the cranial suture between the sphenoid bone and the petrous portion of the temporal bone. It is in the middle cranial fossa.
stephanion The point where the upper temporal line cuts the coronal suture is named the stephanion.
suprainiac fossa The suprainiac fossa is an elliptic depression on the occiput above the superior nuchal line, or inion.
sylvian point The Sylvian point is the point on the human skull nearest the Sylvian fissure and is located about 30 millimeters behind the Zygomatic process of frontal bone.
temporal fossa The temporal fossa is a shallow depression on the side of the skull bounded by the temporal lines and terminating below the level of the zygomatic arch.

zygomatic fossa The Zygomatic Fossa is an irregularly shaped cavity, situated below and on the inner side of the zygoma; bounded, in front, by the zygomatic surface of the superior maxillary bone and the ridge which descends from its malar process; behind, by the posterior border of the external pterygoid plate and the eminentia articularis; above, by the pterygoid ridge on the outer surface of the great wing of the sphenoid and the under part of the squamous portion of the temporal; below by the alveolar border of the superior maxilla; internally, by the external pterygoid plate; and externally, by the zygomatic arch ramus of the lower jaw. It contains the lower part of the temporal, the External and Internal pterygoid muscles, the internal maxillary artery and vein, and inferior maxillary nerve and their branches. At its upper and inner part may be observed two fissures, the spheno-maxillary and pterygo-maxillary.

external occipital protuberance Near the middle of the occipital squama is the external occipital protuberance, and extending lateralward from it on either side is the superior nuchal line, and above this the faintly marked highest nuchal line. It is less pronounced in females. The inion is the highest point of the external occipital protuberance. a projection on the external surface of the squamous part of the occipital bone in the midline.

retromolar space also known as retromolar gap The retromolar space or retromolar gap is a space at the rear of a mandible, between the back of the last molar and the anterior edge of the ascending ramus where it crosses the alveolar margin.[WP].
upper esophagus The upper one third of esophagus in which the muscle layer is composed of muscle cells of the striated type.
lower esophagus also known as esophagus distal third The lower one third of the esophagus in which the muscle layer is composed of muscle cells predominantly of the smooth type.
middle part of esophagus The middle one third of the esophagus in which the muscle layer is composed of muscle cells of the striated and smooth types.

gustatory gland also known as posterior deep lingual gland; posterior lingual serous gland; von Ebner gland; von Ebner's gland A serous salivary gland which resides adjacent to the moats surrounding the circumvallate papillae in the posterior one-third of the tongue, anterior to the terminal sulcus.
dermal layer of tongue also known as tongue (dermal layer) Missing definition for term UBERON:0013476. Please replace it using linked reference.
lung endothelium A blood vessel endothelium that is part of a lung [Automatically generated definition].
crypt of Lieberkuhn of ileum also known as ileal crypt; ileal crypt of Lieberkuhn; ileal intestinal crypt An intestinal crypt that is located in the ileum.
crypt of Lieberkuhn of duodenum also known as duodenal crypt; duodenal crypt of Lieberkuhn An intestinal crypt that is located in the duodenum.
crypt of Lieberkuhn of jejunum also known as jejunal crypt; jejunal crypt of Lieberkuhn An intestinal crypt that is located in the jejunum.

crypt of Lieberkuhn of colon also known as colonic crypt; colonic crypt of Lieberkuhn An intestinal crypt that is located in the colon. The colonic crypts of Lieberkhn are straight and unbranched and lined largely with goblet cells.
crypt of Lieberkuhn of appendix also known as appendiceal crypt; appendiceal crypt of Lieberkuhn An intestinal crypt that is located in the appendix.
epidermal ridge of digit The grooves in the outermost layer of skin on the palms of the hands and soles of the feet where sweat glands open.

panniculus adiposus also known as panniculus adiposus group The panniculus adiposus is the fatty layer of the subcutaneous tissues, superficial to a deeper vestigial layer of muscle, the panniculus carnosus. An example is the Fascia of Camper. Another example is the superficial cervical fascia[WP].

superficial cervical fascia also known as lamina superficialis fasciae cervicalis; superficial cervical fascia; superficial layer of cervical fascia; superficial layer of deep cervical fascia Superficial cervical fascia is a thin layer of subcutaneous connective tissue that lies between the dermis of the skin and the deep cervical fascia. It contains the platysma, cutaneous nerves, blood, and lymphatic vessels. It also contains a varying amount of fat, which is its distinguishing characteristic.

deep cervical fascia also known as deep cervical fascia; deep fascia of neck; investing cervical fascia; investing layer of cervical fascia The deep cervical fascia (or fascia colli in older texts) lies under cover of the Platysma, and invests the neck; it also forms sheaths for the carotid vessels, and for the structures situated in front of the vertebral column. Its attachment to the hyoid bone prevents the formation of a dewlap. The investing portion of the fascia is attached behind to the ligamentum nucha and to the spinous process of the seventh cervical vertebra. The 'alar fascia' is a portion of deep cervical fascia.
cervical fascia also known as fascia of neck Any fascia tissue that is part of the neck region.

prevertebral cervical fascia also known as lamina prevertebralis (fascia cervicalis); lamina prevertebralis fasciae cervicalis; prevertebral fascia; prevertebral layer of cervical fascia; prevertebral layer of deep cervical fascia The prevertebral fascia (or prevertebral layer of cervical fascia) is a fascia in the neck.
abdominal fascia also known as endo-abdominopelvic fascia; fascia of abdomen A fascia that is part of a abdomen.
muscularis orbicularis also known as orbicularis muscle A fringe of muscle running along the periphery of the panniculus.

cloacal sphincter also known as sphincter cloacae A sphincter muscle that is part of a cloaca.
5th arch mesenchyme also known as 5th pharyngeal arch mesenchyme A mesenchyme that is part of a pharyngeal arch 5.

caudal vertebra cartilage element also known as coccygeal vertebra cartilage element; coccygeal vertebral cartilage condensation group; tail vertebral cartilage condensation A caudal vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

caudal vertebra pre-cartilage condensation also known as coccygeal vertebra pre-cartilage condensation; tail vertebral pre-cartilage condensation A caudal vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.
cervical vertebra cartilage element also known as cervical vertebral cartilage condensation group A cervical vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.
cervical vertebra pre-cartilage condensation A cervical vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.
thoracic vertebra cartilage element also known as thoracic vertebral cartilage condensation group A thoracic vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.
