basibranchial 4 tooth plate also known as basibranchial 4 toothplate Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies dorsal to basibranchial 4 bone.
basibranchial 4 tooth Tooth that is attached to the basibranchial 4 tooth plate.
basibranchial 2 tooth plate also known as basibranchial 2 toothplate Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies dorsal to basibranchial 2 bone.
basibranchial 2 tooth Tooth that is attached to the basibranchial 2 tooth plate.
rudimentary neural arch Neural arch on the urostyle. It does not support a neural spine. Sanger and McCune 2002.
infraorbital 6 Infraorbital that is the sixth bone of the infraorbital series.

mesethmoid cornu also known as cornu; cornua; cornuae Bony projection that extends from the mesethmoid anteriorly. Mesethmoid cornua are paired processes each articulating with its ipsilateral premaxilla and both cornua bounding a median mesethmoid cleft.
mesethmoid-premaxillary joint Joint that articulates the mesethmoid and premaxilla. Mesethmoid-premaxillary joint is paired.
mesethmoid-nasal joint Joint that articulates the mesethmoid and nasal. Mesethmoid-nasal joint is paired.
mesethmoid-frontal joint Joint that articulates the mesethmoid and frontal. Mesethmoid-frontal joint is paired.
mesethmoid-vomer joint also known as mesethmoid-prevomer joint Joint that articulates the mesethmoid and vomer. Mesethmoid-vomer joint is unpaired.
cornu mesial process Bony projection that is mesially-directed and off the anteromedial corner of each mesethmoid cornu.
transcapular ligament also known as Baudelot's ligament; transscapular ligament Ligament that is attached to supracleithrum and basioccipital.

ossified transcapular ligament also known as ossified Baudelot's ligament; ossified transscapular ligament Membrane bone that is fused to supracleithrum and is jointed to basioccipital and exoccipital.
lateral ethmoid-ectopterygoid ligament Lateral ethmoid-ectopterygoid ligament is a ligament that connects the lateral ethmoid to the ectopterygoid.

bony shelf above orbit The bony shelf above orbit is an anatomical cluster formed by the dorsolateral portions of the lateral ethmoid, frontal and sphenotic bones that forms the dorsal margin of the orbit.

interopercular-mandibular ligament also known as interopercular-retroarticular ligament; interoperculo-mandibular ligament; interoperculomandibular ligament Interopercular-mandibular ligament is a ligament that connects the interopercle to an element of the lower jaw, typically the retroarticular.

median premaxilla Dermal bone that is located in the middle of the upper jaw, independently formed by fusion of tooth bases attached to soft tissue in the middle portion of the upper lip. The median premaxilla bears teeth in adults.
protractor operculi Muscle located in the lateral region of the cheek, linking the lateral surface of opercle with the posterolateral margin of the suspensorium (usually the preopercle).

humerovertebral ligament Ligament that links the tip of the postcleithral process of the cleithrum with either the vertebral column (at the vertebral parapophysis or rib of the sixth vertebra) or with the soft tissue around the postcleithral region.

mediopharyngobranchial Pharyngeal arch cartilage, elongate and usually bifurcated posteriorly, located anteriorly on the upper branchial arches, attached to the anterior tips of the first infrapharyngobranchials. It supports rows of gill rakers on each side and is not homologous to other structures in the teleost gill-arch skeleton. One or two mediopharyngobranchials may be present.

gongyloid cartilage Pharyngeal arch cartilage present on the dorsal surface of the middle portion of the upper branchial arches, dorsal to the point of contact between the second and third infrapharyngobranchials. It is round or cylyndrical in shape. Not homologous to the mediopharyngobranchial.

transverse radial Endochondral bone, which may be ossified or not in adults, located immediately anteriorly to the pterygiophore series of the anal fin. The structure is usually cylindrical, and its plane of symmetry is transverse to that of pterygiophores and fin rays.
basibranchial 5 bone Basibranchial bone that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 5 (pharyngeal arch 7). Develops in posterior copula cartilage or basibranchial 5 cartilage.
infraorbital 7 Infraorbital that is the seventh bone of the infraorbital series.
infraorbital 8 Infraorbital that is the eighth bone of the infraorbital series.
infraorbital 9 Infraorbital that is the ninth bone of the infraorbital series.
infraorbital 10 Infraorbital that is the tenth bone of the infraorbital series.
infraorbital 11 Infraorbital that is the eleventh bone of the infraorbital series.
infraorbital 12 Infraorbital that is the twelfth bone of the infraorbital series.

dermosphenotic Infraorbital that is the last bone of the infraorbital series, carrying the infraorbital canal, and sometimes also the supraorbital, temporal, and/or preopercular canals. The dermosphenotic is sometimes sutured or fused completely to the skull, e.g. to the autosphenotic.
infraorbital series Anatomical cluster that is the series of dermal bones surrounding the orbit and associated with the infraorbital sensory canal.
opercle-interopercle joint Joint that articulates the opercle and interopercle. Opercle-interopercle joint is paired.
frontal-pterotic joint Joint that articulates the frontal and pterotic. Frontal-pterotic joint is paired.
vertebral element 5 Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 4.

mesethmoid ventral diverging lamella Bony projection that is the posterolaterally oriented projection on the ventral region of the mesethmoid. Mesethmoid ventral diverging lamellae are paired and posteriorly contact the lateral ethmoid bones.
posterior process of basipterygium also known as ischiac process; ischiatic process; posterior pelvic process Process that is the posteriorly oriented, paired projection of the basipterygium.
scapular foramen Foramen that is located in the scapula. The scapular foramen is paired and formed by a ring of bone.
anterior cranial fontanel also known as frontal fontanelle; frontal fontanel Fontanel that is located between the contralateral frontals and anterior to the epiphyseal bar.

posterior cranial fontanel also known as parietal fontanel Fontanel that is located posterior to the epiphyseal bar, and typically located between the contralateral frontals and parietals (if present) and bordered posteriorly by the supraoccipital.

trigeminofacial foramen also known as trigemino-facialis foramen; trigeminofacial nerve foramen; trigeminofacialis foramen Foramen through which branches of cranial nerves V (trigeminal) and VII (facial) exit.
auditory foramen Foramen through which cranial nerve VIII (auditory) exits.
replacement tooth trench also known as replacement tooth crypt; replacement tooth crypts Anatomical space within a bone in which teeth develop.
premaxilla replacement tooth trench Replacement tooth trench that is located in the premaxilla.
dentary replacement tooth trench Replacement tooth trench that is located in the dentary.

lateral mesethmoid wing also known as mesethmoid lateral wing; premaxillary articular process Bony projection located on the anteroventral region of the mesethmoid which articulates with the premaxilla.
superficial ophthalmic nerve foramen Foramen through which the superficial ophthalmic nerve passes.
dentary-anguloarticular joint Joint that articulates the dentary and anguloarticular. Dentary-anguloarticular joint is paired.
rib of vertebra 6 also known as sixth pleural rib Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the sixth centrum.
rib of vertebra 5 also known as fifth pleural rib Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the fifth centrum.
pre-narial cartilage The pre-narial cartilage is a cartilage that is located anterior to the anterior naris.

posttemporal fossa also known as temporal groove Fossa where the exoccipital forms the medial portion and the epioccipital forms the lateral margin. The posttemporal fossa in most species has two openings separated by the epioccipital bridge.
retractor tentaculi Bilaterally paired dorsal hyoid arch muscle that retracts the maxillary barbel.

supraoccipital crest also known as supraoccipital process; supraoccipital spine Process that is part of the supraoccipital. It is a posteriorly directed and unpaired median projection off the posterior margin of the supraoccipital bone.
pharyngobranchial 3 bone uncinate process Bony projection that is part of the pharyngobranchial 3.
pharyngobranchial 4 bone uncinate process also known as infrapharyngobranchial 4 bone uncinate process Bony projection that is part of the pharyngobranchial 4.
orbitosphenoid-prootic joint Joint that articulates orbitosphenoid and prootic bones. Orbitosphenoid-prootic joint is paired.
ceratohyal foramen also known as bericiform foramen; beryciform foramen Foramen in the anterior ceratohyal for passage of the hyoidean artery.
epibranchial 2 bone uncinate process Epibranchial uncinate process that is part of epibranchial 2 bone.
epibranchial 1 bone uncinate process Epibranchial uncinate process that is part of epibranchial 1 bone.
epicentral bone also known as dipipleural; neoneural Intermuscular bone that articulates with the vertebral centrum.
recessus lateralis Intracranial space formed by confluence of supraorbital, infraorbital, preopercular and temporal sensory canals. See also Di Dario (2004).
cephalic rib Modified epicentral intermuscular bone that connects the back of the skull with the pectoral girdle.
olfactory nerve foramen Foramen for the passage of the olfactory nerve or cranial nerve 1.

articular bone also known as articular Endochondral bone that is located posterior to the dentary, medial to the angular and antero-dorsal to the retroarticular forming the lower jaw. The articular bears a dorso-posterior articular facet for the condyle of the quadrate. The articular is a paired bone.
preepiotic fossa also known as preepioccipital fossa Fossa that is a concavity on the dorsolateral surface of the skull roof found at least partially on the epiotic (epioccipital).
facial foramen also known as anterior opening trigeminofacialis chamber Foramen through which cranial nerve VII (facial) exits.
trigeminal foramen also known as posterior opening of trigeminofacialis chamber Foramen through which cranial nerve V (trigeminal) exits.
nuchal plate Dermal bone that is a bony expansion in the integument anterior to or flanking the dorsal fin that is part of and at the distal end of a supraneural or dorsal fin proximal radial.

anterior nuchal plate also known as first nuchal plate Nuchal plate that is unpaired and part of the supraneural and in contact, or not, with the supraoccipital crest anteriorly and middle nuchal plate posteriorly.
epibranchial 3 bone uncinate process Epibranchial uncinate process that is part of epibranchial 3 bone.
epibranchial 4 bone uncinate process Epibranchial uncinate process that is part of epibranchial 4 bone.
premaxillary-maxillary ligament Ligament that connects the premaxilla to the maxilla.
primordial ligament also known as articular-maxillary ligament; ligamentum primordiale; maxillo-mandibular ligament Ligament that connects the maxilla with the lower jaw.
pterosphenoid-orbitosphenoid joint Joint that articulates the pterosphenoid and orbitosphenoid. Pterosphenoid-orbitosphenoid joint is paired.
parasphenoid-basioccipital joint Joint that articulates the parasphenoid and basioccipital. Parasphenoid-basioccipital joint is unpaired.
premaxillary tooth row Tooth row that is on the premaxilla.
tip also known as tips Anatomical point that is the apex of a projection or anything long and tapered; can be bony or cartilage.
interhyal-epihyal joint Joint that articulates the interhyal and epihyal bones, or interhyal and ceratohyal cartilages. Interhyal-epihyal joint is paired.
epihyal-ceratohyal joint Joint that articulates the epihyal and ceratohyal bones. Epihyal-ceratohyal joint is paired.
epihyal-branchiostegal ray joint Joint that articulates the epihyal and branchiostegal ray bones. Epihyal-branchiostegal ray joint is paired.
ceratohyal-branchiostegal ray joint Joint that articulates the ceratohyal and branchiostegal ray bones. Ceratohyal-branchiostegal ray joint is paired.
postcleithrum 1 Postcleithrum that anteriorly articulates with the supracleithrum and/or the cleithrum of the pectoral girdle; most dorsal element in a series of postcleithra.
postcleithrum 2 Postcleithrum that articulates dorsally with postcleithrum 1, ventrally with postcleithrum 3, and anteriorly with cleithrum.
postcleithrum 3 Postcleithrum that articulates dorsally with postcleithrum 2 and, sometimes, anteriorly with cleithrum.

hyomandibular condyle for the opercle also known as opercular process of hyomandibular Process on the dorso-posterior margin of the hyomandibula cartilage or bone that articulates with a depression on the antero-dorsal margin of the opercle.
gill ray Gill ray is a slender, usually rod-like cartilage within a gill filament and ligamentously tied to its associated pharyngeal arch bone or cartilage.

suprapharyngobranchial also known as branchial spiracle A pharyngobranchial bone that articulates with the neurocranium dorsally and epibranchial 1 and pharyngobranchial 2 ventrally; lies dorsal to other elements of the dorsal portions of the branchial arches.
pharyngobranchial 1 tooth plate also known as pharyngobranchial 1 toothplate Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies ventral to pharyngobranchial 1 bone.

epibranchial 4-upper pharyngeal toothplate joint Joint that articulates the epibranchial 4 cartilage or bone and upper pharyngeal toothplate. Epibranchial 4-upper pharyngeal toothplate joint is paired.
epibranchial 3-pharyngobranchial 3 joint Joint that articulates the epibranchial 3 cartilage or bone and pharyngobranchial 3 cartilage or bone. Epibranchial 3-pharyngobranchial 3 joint is paired.
epibranchial 3-pharyngobranchial 4 joint Joint that articulates the epibranchial 3 cartilage or bone and pharyngobranchial 4 cartilage or bone. Epibranchial 3-pharyngobranchial 4 joint is paired.
inter-hypobranchial 3 joint Joint that articulates the left and right hypobranchial 3 cartilages or bones. Inter-hypobranchial 3 joint is unpaired.
basibranchial 1 cartilage Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 1 (pharyngeal arch 3).
basibranchial 4 cartilage Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 4 (pharyngeal arch 6).
basibranchial 5 cartilage Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 5 (pharyngeal arch 7).

post-ceratobranchial cartilage also known as basibranchial 6; copula 4; pericardial cartilage Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and at or posterior to the juncture of the bilaterally paired ceratobranchial 5 cartilage or bone.
supraneural 2 cartilage Postcranial axial cartilage located dorsal to vertebra 2.
supraneural 3 cartilage Postcranial axial cartilage located dorsal to vertebrae 3 and 4.
basibranchial 2 cartilage Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 2 (pharyngeal arch 4).
opercular series opercular series_1
basibranchial 3 cartilage Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 3 (pharyngeal arch 5).
neural arch 1 Neural arch that is the anteriormost neural arch.
rib of vertebra 2 Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the second centrum.
rib of vertebra 1 Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the first centrum.
rib of vertebra 3 Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the third centrum.
rib of vertebra 4 Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the fourth centrum.
parapophysis + rib of vertebra 3 parapophysis + rib of vertebra 3_1
parapophysis + rib of vertebra 3 + rib of vertebra 4 parapophysis + rib of vertebra 3 + rib of vertebra 4_1
accessory neural arch Neural arch that is located posterior to the neurocranium and anterior to neural arch 1. The accessory neural arch is not associated with a vertebral centrum.
neural spine 1 Neural spine that is associated with the first vertebra.
neural spine 2 Neural spine that is associated with the second vertebra.
neural spine 3 Neural spine that is associated with the third vertebra.
supraneural 1 bone Supraneural bone located dorsal to vertebra 1.
supraneural 1 cartilage Postcranial axial cartilage located dorsal to vertebra 1.

interhyal element also known as stylohyal element Skeletal element that is bilaterally paired and articulates dorsally with the hyosymplectic cartilage or the articulation of the hyomandibula and symplectic.
hypobranchial element Skeletal element that is bilaterally paired and articulates medially with a median skeletal element and laterally with a ceratobranchial element.
hypobranchial 1 element Skeletal element that is ventral, bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 1 element laterally.
hypobranchial 2 element Skeletal element that is ventral, bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 2 element laterally.
hypobranchial 3 element Skeletal element that is ventral, bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 3 element laterally.
hypobranchial 4 element Skeletal element that is ventral, bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 4 element laterally.
ceratobranchial element Skeletal element that is bilaterally paired and forms part of the ventral branchial arches.
ceratobranchial 1 element ceratobranchial 1 element_1
ceratobranchial 2 element ceratobranchial 2 element_1
ceratobranchial 3 element ceratobranchial 3 element_1
ceratobranchial 4 element ceratobranchial 4 element_1
ceratobranchial 5 element ceratobranchial 5 element_1
epibranchial element also known as epibranchial elements Skeletal element that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial element.
epibranchial 1 element epibranchial 1 element_1
epibranchial 2 element epibranchial 2 element_1
epibranchial 3 element epibranchial 3 element_1
epibranchial 4 element epibranchial 4 element_1
pharyngobranchial element also known as infrapharyngobranchial element Skeletal element of the branchial arches located medial to the epibranchials.
pharyngobranchial 1 element also known as infrapharyngobranchial 1 element Most anterior pharyngobranchial element, located medial to the epibranchials.
pharyngobranchial 2 element also known as infrapharyngobranchial 2 element Pharyngobranchial element, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 1 element.
pharyngobranchial 3 element also known as infrapharyngobranchial 3 element Pharyngobranchial element, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 2 element.
pharyngobranchial 4 element also known as infrapharyngobranchial 4 element Most posterior pharyngobranchial element, located medial to the epibranchials.
basibranchial 1 element Skeletal element that is median and associated with branchial arch 1.
basibranchial 2 element Skeletal element that is median and associated with branchial arch 2.
basibranchial 3 element Skeletal element that is median and associated with branchial arch 3.
basibranchial 4 element Skeletal element that is median and associated with branchial arch 4.
basibranchial 5 element Skeletal element that is median and associated with branchial arch 5.
pseudotympanum also known as humeral hiatus Anatomical structure that is formed as a hiatus in the muscles covering the anterior chamber of the swim bladder in the area of ribs 5 and 6.
inter-frontal joint also known as interfrontal suture Joint between the left and right frontal bone.
aortic canal Canal that houses the dorsal aorta.
occipital artery foramen Foramina that allow passage of occipital arteries.
spiracular canal Foramen for passage of nerve supplying otic lateral line.
posterior myodome Fossa or chamber on posterior portion of orbital region of neurocranium that serves as attachment site for posterior extrinsic eye muscles.
anterior myodome Fossa or chamber on anterior portion of orbital region of neurocranium that serves as attachment site for anterior extrinsic eye musculature.
articular fossa of opercle Fossa of opercle that articulates with hyomandibular condyle for opercle.
epioccipital posterior process Process of the epioccipital that extends posteriorly, is laminar in form and is usually attached to Weberian apparatus.
accessory vomerine tooth plate Dermal bone that is located lateral to vomer off midline of palate. Accessory vomerine tooth plate bears teeth and may be present as one or more pairs.
rostral plate Dermal bone that is located on midline of snout in skin above mesethmoid and lateral ethmoid bones. Rostral plate bears type 1 odontodes and is unpaired.
oral disk Lip that is expanded to form a broad, rounded cup around the mouth.
posterior nasal barbel Barbel that is attached to the anterior rim of the posterior nostril. Posterior nasal barbel is paired.
anterior nasal barbel Barbel that is associated with the anterior nostril. Anterior nasal barbel is paired.
maxillary barbel Barbel that is attached to the distal end of the maxilla and that originates on the side of the mouth. Maxillary barbel is paired.
inter-basipterygium joint also known as pelvic girdle symphysis; pelvic symphysis Joint that articulates the left and right basipterygium cartilage or bone. Inter-basipterygium joint is unpaired.
vertebra 4-vertebra 5 joint Joint between the centra, and sometimes the neural arches or parapophyses of vertebra 4 and vertebra 5.
metapterygoid-autopalatine ligament Ligament that connects the metapterygoid to the autopalatine.
lateral ethmoid-autopalatine ligament Lateral ethmoid-autopalatine ligament is a ligament that connects the lateral ethmoid to the autopalatine.
mesethmoid-premaxillary ligament Mesethmoid-premaxillary ligament is a ligament that connects the mesethmoid to the premaxilla.
mesethmoid-maxillary ligament Mesethmoid-maxillary ligament is a ligament that connects the mesethmoid to the maxilla.

hyomandibular-otic region joint Joint that articulates the hyomandibular cartilage or bone and otic region cartilage or sphenotic bone, and often pterotic bone and prootic bone. Hyomandibular-otic region joint is paired.
inter-premaxillary joint Joint that articulates the left and right premaxillary bones. Inter-premaxillary joint is unpaired.
skin flap Surface structure that is a portion of skin that projects or hangs from the body.
dentary tooth row Tooth row that is on the dentary.

epibranchial 1 bone proximal cartilage also known as epibranchial 1 anterior cartilage; epibranchial 1 mesial cartilage Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the proximal end of epibranchial 1 bone, and that usually articulates with a pharyngobranchial element. Epibranchial 1 bone proximal cartilage is paired.

epibranchial 2 bone proximal cartilage also known as epibranchial 2 anterior cartilage; epibranchial 2 mesial cartilage Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the proximal end of epibranchial 2 bone, and that usually articulates with a pharyngobranchial element. Epibranchial 2 bone proximal cartilage is paired.

ceratobranchial 3 bone distal cartilage also known as ceratobranchial 3 bone lateral cartilage; ceratobranchial 3 bone posterior cartilage Pharynbeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of ceratobranchial 3 bone, and that usually articulates with epibranchial 3 element. Ceratobranchial 3 bone distal cartilage is paired.

ceratobranchial 4 bone proximal cartilage also known as ceratobranchial 4 bone anterior cartilage; ceratobranchial 4 bone mesial cartilage Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the proximal end of ceratobranchial 4 bone, and that usually articulates with basibranchial 4 element. Ceratobranchial 4 proximal cartilage is paired.

ceratobranchial 4 bone distal cartilage also known as ceratobranchial 4 bone lateral cartilage; ceratobranchial 4 bone posterior cartilage Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of ceratobranchial 4 bone, and that usually articulates with epibranchial 4 element. Ceratobranchial 4 distal cartilage is paired.

ceratobranchial 5 bone distal cartilage also known as ceratobranchial 5 bone lateral cartilage; ceratobranchial 5 bone posterior cartilage Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of ceratobranchial 5 bone. Ceratobranchial 5 bone distal cartilage is paired.

hypobranchial 1 bone distal cartilage also known as hypobranchial 1 bone lateral cartilage; hypobranchial 1 bone posterior cartilage Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of hypobranchial 1 bone, and that usually articulates with ceratobranchial 1 element. Hypobranchial 1 bone distal cartilage is paired.

hypobranchial 2 bone distal cartilage also known as hypobranchial 2 bone lateral cartilage; hypobranchial 2 bone posterior cartilage Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of hypobranchial 2 bone, and that usually articulates with ceratobranchial 2 element. Hypobranchial 2 bone distal cartilage is paired.

epibranchial 3 bone uncinate process cartilage Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of epibranchial bone 3 uncinate process. epibranchial bone 3 uncinate process cartilage is paired.

epibranchial 4 bone uncinate process cartilage Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of epibranchial bone 4 uncinate process. Epibranchial bone 4 uncinate process cartilage is paired.
epibranchial 5 element epibranchial 5 element
outer mental barbel Mental barbel that originates on the chin, in a posterolateral position relative to the inner mental barbel.

inner mental barbel Mental barbel that originates on the chin, in an anteromedial position relative to the outer mental barbel. The inner mental barbel is nearer to the mandibular symphysis than is the outer mental barbel.
parapophysis 4 Parapophysis that is the lateral projection from the fourth centrum. Parapophysis 4 is bilaterally paired.
intercostal ligament Ligament that connects one rib to another.
subtemporal fossa subtemporal fossa_1
suprabranchial artery suprabranchial artery_1
interorbital septum Anatomical cluster composed of one or more bones and tissue that separates the orbits.
pad also known as pads Surface structure that is a portion of the integument thickened relative to surrounding area.
maxillary tooth row Tooth row that is on the maxilla.
vertebral element 6 Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 5.
vertebral element 7 Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 6.
vertebral element 8 Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 7.
centrum 1 Centrum that is part of vertebra 1.
centrum 2 Centrum that is part of vertebra 2.
centrum 3 Centrum that is part of vertebra 3.
centrum 4 Centrum that is part of vertebra 4.
centrum 5 Centrum that is part of vertebra 5.
centrum 6 Centrum that is part of vertebra 6.

mandibular-hyoid median cartilage also known as hyomandibular cartilage sensu Schaefer (1990) Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is a spherical mass of cartilage located between the mandibular symphysis and ventral hyoid arch. Mandibular-hyoid median cartilage is unpaired.

epibranchial arborescent organ also known as suprabranchial organ Anatomical cluster that is an outgrowth of the soft tissue around the dorsolateral corner of a branchial arch that is internally supported by a core of rigid cartilage-like tissue. Epibranchial arborescent organ is paired.
lateral bone Membrane bone extending between a transverse process of the second proximal dorsal-fin radial and the pleural rib of the sixth vertebra. Lateral bone is paired.
papilla also known as papillae Surface structure that is a small, fleshy protuberance.
maxillary canal maxillary canal_1

parietal-supraoccipital also known as parieto-supraoccipital Compound dermal and endochondral bone that results from the fusion of the paired dermal parietal bones and the median endochondral supraoccipital. Forms the dorso-posterior element of the dermatocranium.

posttemporal-supracleithrum also known as postemporo-supracleithrum; posttemporo-supracleithrum Dermal bone that results from the fusion of the dermal posttemporal and the dermal supracleithrum. Forms the upper skeletal element of the pectoral girdle between the cleithrum and neurocranium. Posttemporal-supracleithrum is paired.
canal plate Dermal bone that is ventral to the preopercle and bears a portion of the preopercular sensory canal.
axillary pore Pore that is located ventral to the posterior cleithral process and medial to the pectoral fin. Axillary pore is at the end of a duct from an integumentary gland.
supraneural 4 bone Supraneural dorsal to neural spine 4.
hyoideomandibular nerve Nerve that is a branch of cranial nerve VII that passes through or around the suspensorium to innervate muscles and sensory organs on or near pharyngeal arch 2.
lateral fontanel of frontal Fontanel within the frontal bone near the frontal-sphenotic joint. Lateral fontanel of frontal is paired.
dentary foramen Foramen located on the dentary for passage of the mandibular nerve.
ascending limb of ceratobranchial 5 bone Process that is the dorsally directed portion of ceratobranchial 5 bone.
ascending limb of ceratobranchial 5 cartilage Process that is the dorsally directed portion of ceratobranchial 5 cartilage.
pharyngobranchial tooth plate also known as pharyngobranchial toothplate Dermal bone of upper pharyngeal arches associated with pharyngobranchial bones or cartilages, usually bearing teeth.
pharyngobranchial 4 tooth plate also known as pharyngobranchial 4 toothplate Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies ventral to pharyngobranchial 4.
anterior limb of ceratobranchial 5 bone Process that is the anterior and medially directed portion of ceratobranchial 5 bone part of ceratobranchial 5 bone.
anterior limb of ceratobranchial 5 cartilage Process that is the anterior and medially directed portion of ceratobranchial 5 cartilage.
pterotic-posttemporal-supracleithrum also known as pterotic-supracleithrum Bone that is a fusion of the pterotic, posttemporal, and supracleithrum bones.
hypomaxilla Dermal bone bearing teeth located between the distal end of the premaxilla and the middle of the maxilla. The hypomaxilla is a paired bone.

ascending process of the parasphenoid also known as ascending ramus of the parasphenoid Process that is the lateral projection of the parasphenoid arising and articulating with the more dorsal portions of the neurocranium, usually at the level of the prootic.
dermethmoid Dermal bone of the dorsal surface of the olfactory region. Dermethmoid can be paired or median.
second preethmoid bone Endochondral bone found between the preethmoid and maxilla.
mental barbel Barbel that originates on the chin.
orbital foramen Foramen in the bone or cartilage comprising the anterior wall of the orbit, and through which passes at least the deep ophthalmic branch of cranial nerve V (trigeminal).
prootic-pterosphenoid joint Joint that articulates the prootic and pterosphenoid. prootic-pterosphenoid joint is paired.
prootic-exoccipital joint Joint that articulates the prootic and exoccipital. Prootic-exoccipital joint is paired.
basioccipital-exoccipital joint Joint that articulates the basioccipital and exoccipital. Basioccipital-exoccipital joint is paired.
dilatator fossa Fossa located on the neurocranium that is formed from portions of the sphenotic, frontal and pterotic bones.
inter-coracoid joint Joint between the right and left coracoid bones of the pectoral girdle.
parapophysis 6 Parapophysis that is the lateral projection from the sixth centrum.
parapophysis 5 Parapophysis that is the lateral projection from the fifth centrum.

posterior limb of parapophysis 4 also known as posterior branch of parapophysis 4; posterior wing of parapophysis 4 Process that arises and projects posterolaterally from parapophysis 4. Posterior limb of parapophysis 4 is bilaterally paired.

anterior limb of parapophysis 4 also known as anterior branch of parapophysis 4; anterior wing of parapophysis 4; Mullerian ramus; Mllerian ramus Process that arises and projects anterolaterally from parapophysis 4. Anterior limb of parapophysis 4 is bilaterally paired.
prootic depression Shallow area that exists on the prootic.

bony plate also known as armor; armor plate; osteoderms Dermal bone that is located on or subjacent to the surface anywhere on the body and that is not part of the general complement of scales, dermal bone of the dermatocranium, postcranial axial skeleton or paired fin skeleton. Bony plate may exist singly, or as unpaired or paired clusters or series.
vertebra 5-vertebra 6 joint Joint between the centra, and sometimes the neural arches or parapophyses.
vertebra 6 - vertebra 7 joint Joint between the centra, and sometimes the neural arches or parapophyses of vertebra 6 and vertebra 7.
Weberian complex centrum Centrum that is the fusion of centra 2-4.
posttemporal-parietal joint posttemporal-parietal joint_1
predorsal vertebra Vertebra that is positioned between the vertebra immediately anterior to the first dorsal-fin pterygiophore to the anteriormost vertebra.
nuchal plate series Anatomical cluster that consists of more than one type of nuchal plate in an individual.
auditory fenestra Opening in the neurocranium to allow communication between the swimbladder and the inner ear.
distal cartilage of posterior process of basipterygium Process that is cartilaginous and arises from the distal margin or tip of posterior process of basipterygium and projects posteriorly.

internal anterior process of basipterygium also known as internal anterior arm of basipterygium; internal arm of the basipterygium; mesial anterior arm of basipterygium; mesial anterior process of basipterygium Process that is bony and arises from anteromedial corner of basipterygium and projects anteriorly or anteromedially.
distal cartilage of internal anterior process of basipterygium Process that is cartilaginous and arises from the distal tip of internal anterior process of basipterygium.

middle anterior process of basipterygium also known as middle anterior arm of basipterygium Process that is bony and arises from anterior margin of basipterygium between internal anterior process of basipterygium and external anterior process of basipterygium. Middle anterior process of basipterygium projects anteriorly or anteromedially.
distal cartilage of middle anterior process of basipterygium Process that is cartilaginous and arises from the distal tip of middle anterior process of basipterygium.

external anterior process of basipterygium also known as external anterior arm of basipterygium; external arm of basipterygium; lateral anterior process of basipterygium; lateral pelvic process Process that is bony and arises from anterolateral corner of basipterygium and projects anteriorly or anteromedially.
distal cartilage of external anterior process of basipterygium Process that is cartilaginous and arises from the distal tip of external anterior process of basipterygium.

lateral process of basipterygium also known as posterolateral process of basipterygium Process that is bony and arises from lateral margin of basipterygium lateral to pelvic fin lepidotrichium 1 and projects laterally or anterolaterally.
spina occipitalis Process that is a ventral projection from the supraoccipital that extends between the exoccipitals to the dorsal margin of the foramen magnum.
interhaemal bone A small bone articulating distally with the haemal arch or a short haemal spine.

gular plate also known as median gular; median gular plate Dermal bone located on the ventral surface of the skull and positioned between the two rami of the lower jaw. Anteriorly the gular attaches to the symphysis of the lower jaw through fibrous connective tissue. The gular is an unpaired median bone.
pro-otic fossa also known as prootic fossa pro-otic fossa_1
rostral cartilage Median chondrified cartilage bound to premaxillary ascending process by a rostro-premaxilla ligament.

ventromedial opening of posttemporal fossa also known as third posttemporal fossa A third opening of the posttemporal fossa posteriorly located relative to the fossa. It is bordered completely by the epiocciptial, or by both the epioccipital and exoccipital.
bony plate series also known as armor plate series Anatomical cluster that consists of more than one bony plate in an individual.
sensory canal pore series Anatomical cluster that consists of more than one sensory canal pore.
branchiostegal ray series Anatomical cluster that consists of the branchiostegal rays within an individual.
epibranchial series also known as epibranchials Anatomical cluster that consists of the epibranchial elements within an individual.
ceratobranchial series Anatomical cluster that consists of the ceratobranchial elements within an individual.
electrosensory lateral line lobe also known as ELL Anatomical structure located in the hindbrain that receives primary electroreceptor input.
eminentia granularis also known as EG Anatomical structure that is a subdivision of the cerebellum; it is the location of some lateral line nerve synapses.

medullary command nucleus also known as MCN; medullary pacemaker nucleus; pacemaker nucleus Anatomical structure that consists of two neuron types: pacemaker cells and relay cells. The medullary command nucleus commands the timing of the electric organ discharge.
buccal papilla Papilla that is part of the mouth.
metapterygoid-quadrate fenestra metapterygoid-quadrate fenestra_1
prootic bulla prootic bulla_1
cotylephore also known as cotylephores Multi-tissue structure that is a transient outgrowth of tissue on skin brooding fish that acts as an attachment site for embryos.

ovipositor Organ that functions in egg deposition.
orbitosphenoid septum orbitosphenoid septum_1
neural arch 5 neural arch 5_1

nuptial tubercle also known as breeding tubercle; contact organ Surface structure that is a small protuberance on the surface of the body. Nuptial tubercles primarily function to facilitate contact between individuals for breeding.
myorhabdoid bone also known as myorhabdoi Intermuscular bone that is located in the dorsal and ventral forward flexures of the myoseptum.
cavum sinus imparis also known as cavum sinus impar cavum sinus imparis_1
caudal appendage also known as caudal filament Multi-tissue structure that is region of the body posterior to the last anal-fin ray.
dorsal organ Surface structure that is a midsaggital strap of flattened ectodermal tissue extending along the posterodorsal midline.
annular ligament Ligament that is in the eye and is located at the angle between the cornea and the iris.

opercular cavity Anatomical space which is located beneath the operculum and external to the gills.
preural centrum 1 + ural centrum 1 + ural centrum 2 Urostyle that is the result of fusion of preural centrum 1 with ural centra 1 and 2.
branchial mesenchyme branchial mesenchyme_1

octaval nerve motor nucleus Hindbrain nucleus which consists of cell bodies whose axons exit the hindbrain via cranial nerve VIII and innervate hair cells of the lateral line and inner ear. The neurons of these nuclei are unusual in that they extend both contra- and ipsilateral dendrites.

caudal octaval nerve motor nucleus caudal octaval nerve motor nucleus_1
dorsolateral motor nucleus of vagal nerve also known as dlX Motor nucleus of vagal nerve that is located within the dorsolateral portion of rhomobomere 8.
dorsolateral septum Portion of tissue that grows in from the dorsolateral wall of the otic vesicle, forming a dorsolateral partition between the developing anterior and posterior semicircular canals.
epidermal placode Portion of tissue that is a thickening and reshaping of the epidermal basal stratum cells beneath which fibroblasts accumulate to form the scale primordium.

hypobranchial muscle Head muscle that originates on the anterior region of the cleithrum and inserts on the urohyal. The hypobranchial forms initially as left and right parts that later fuse together forming a cone shape.
intermediate nucleus Diencephalic nucleus which is located between the dorsal hypothalamus and the caudal tuberal nucleus and does not contain tyrosine hydroxylase immunoreactive cells.

preglomerular nucleus Diencephalic nucleus which is located in the caudal tuberculum. The preglomerular nuclei make up most of the migrated nuclei within the caudal tuberculum. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.

body marking also known as markings Surface structure that is a visible mark on the body resulting from pigmentation.
basal communicating artery also known as BCA basal communicating artery_1

mid cerebral vein also known as MCeV; mid-cerebral vein; middle cerebral vein The mesencephalic veins (MsV) enter the mid cerebral veins (MCeV) at the dorsal midline. THe MCeVs originate at the dorsal midline, proceede lateraly in a ventral direction to drain into the paired primordial midbrain channels (PHBC). ogai et al. 2001., Kimmel et al. 1993.
pseudobranchial artery A vascular loop attached to the efferent part of the mandibular arch that forms at 3.5 dpf. Isogai et al. 2001.
primordial midbrain channel also known as PMBC The vessel between the anterior cerebral vein and the mid cerebral vein. Isogai et al. 2001.
central artery also known as CtA Arteries that irrigate the forebrain and midbrain Isogai et al. 2001.
cerebellar central artery also known as CCtA Extend upward from the PCS, branch to provide an arterial feed to the hindbrain, then drain back down into the PHBC Isogai et al. 2001.

opercular artery also known as ORA The opercular artery arises from the hyoid stump on the first aortic arch, then follows the lateral margin of the operculum (gill covering) ventrally to reconnect into the proximal part of the first aortic arch. Isogai et al. 2001.

primary head sinus also known as lateral head vein; PHS Main route for venous drainage of the anterior and mid cerebral veins as well as portions of the primordial hindbrain channel. Isogai et al. 2001.

posterior cerebral vein also known as caudal cerebral vein; PCeV Vein that drains the dorsal longitudinal vessel and the caudal portions of the venous capillary network of the medulla oblongata. Isogai et al. 2001.
rostral blood island also known as RBI Hematopoietic tissue derived from the cephalic mesoderm. Predominantly produces myeloid cells. de Jong and Zon 2005.
dorsal ciliary vein also known as DCV dorsal ciliary vein_1
dorsal longitudinal vein also known as DLV Vessel that connects to the primitive hindbrain channel and the basilar artery at the caudal end of the medulla oblongata. Isogai et al. 2001.
optic vein also known as OV Vein that connects to the hyaloid vein that drains the eye. External to eye. Isogai et al. 2001.
supraintestinal artery also known as SIA A continuation of the anterior mesenteric artery, which branches out from the dorsal aorta just caudal to the pronephric glomus. Isogai et al. 2001.
supraintestinal vein supraintestinal vein_1
anterior lateral mesoderm anterior lateral mesoderm_1
optic artery The artery that carries blood to the eye. It branches from the internal carotid artery and enters the eye ventrally through the optic fissure. Isogai et al. 2001.

primitive prosencephalic artery also known as PPrA Vessel that branches from cranial division of the internal carotid artery, extending laterally around the rostral end of the head. Isogai et al. 2001.

prosencephalic artery also known as PrA After the primitive prosencephalic artery forms it becomes disconnected from the cranial division of the internal carotid artery and instead it connects to the anterior mesencephalic central artery and the communicating vessels of the palatocerebral artery.

palatocerebral artery also known as PLA The PLA branches ventrally from the CrDI. It extends rostrally along the base of mid- and forebrain, then loops medially and links to the corresponding vessel from the other side of the embryo. Isogai et al. 2001.
communicating vessel palatocerebral artery also known as CMV; communicating vessels Connect the palatocerebral artery with the prosencephalic artery. Isogai et al. 2001.

anterior mesencephalic central artery also known as AMCtA; rostral mesencephalic central artery Arteries that irrigate rostral regions of the midbrain. They extend between the Basial communicating artery to the anterior cerebral vein. Isogai et al. 2001.
nasal ciliary artery also known as NCA nasal ciliary artery_1
inner optic circle also known as IOC inner optic circle_1

median palatocerebral vein also known as MPLV Drains the PLA loop proceeds straight caudally along the cranial midline just above the pharynx, just below the diencephalon. Forms a 'T' with the palatocerebral veins. Isogai et al. 2001.
palatocerebral vein also known as PLV Vein that drains the median palatocerebral vein into the optic vein. Isogai et al. 2001.
bulbus arteriosus outer layer also known as bulbus arteriosus externa Composed of scattered layers of interrupted elastic lamina. Hu et al. 2001.

bulbus arteriosus middle layer also known as bulbus arteriosus media Composed of 7-10 layers of helically arranged smooth muscle cells surrounded by a fine network of collagen, reticular, and elastic fibrils. Hu et al. 2001.

bulbus arteriosus inner layer also known as bulbus arteriosus intima Composed of subendothelium with longitudinally oriented collagen, reticular fibrils, elastic fibers, and smooth muscle cells bound by a thin endothelial layer. Hu et al. 2001.
endocardial ring endocardial ring_1
atrioventricular ring also known as AV ring atrioventricular ring_1
central cardiac conduction system Cardiac conduction system, characterized by slow impulse propagation and prolonged refractory periods.
peripheral cardiac conduction system Portion of the cardiac conduction system, with rapid impulse propagation.
middle mesencephalic central artery also known as MMCtA Project rostrally and dorsally from the AMCtA to to irrigate the midportion of the midbrain Isogai et al. 2001.
posterior mesencephalic central artery also known as caudal mesencephalic central artery; PMCtA Project dorsally from BCA to irrigate the caudal part of midbrain Isogai et al. 2001.
anterior mesenteric artery also known as AMA; rostral mesenteric artery Unpaired artery departing from dorsal aorta, typically supplying the small intestine.

ventral branch nasal ciliary artery ventral branch nasal ciliary artery_1

metencephalic artery These arteies branch dorsally from both sides of the posterior communicating artery looping up to join with the opposite MtA as well as with both middle cerebral veins at the dorsal midline of the head. Isogai et al. 2001.

nasal artery also known as NA The nasal arteries start at the internal carotid artey and travel rostrally, passing along the right and left walls of the nasal sac at the most rostral end of the head. From the nasal sac, the NA flows into the nasal veins. Isogai et al. 2001.
pectoral vein also known as PV pectoral vein_1
posterior mesenteric artery also known as caudal mesenteric artery; PMA Unpaired artery departing from dorsal aorta that typically supplies the large intestine.
nasal vein also known as NV nasal vein_1
longitudinal lateral lymphatic vessel also known as LLL longitudinal lateral lymphatic vessel_1

barbel primordium also known as barbel primordia A surface structure that will eventually grow to form a barbel. The primordium is rich in taste buds. The final location for taste buds present in the primordium is the distal tip of the mature barbel.
dorsal axial hypoblast dorsal axial hypoblast_1
intestinal bulb epithelium Intestinal epithelium which lines the lumen of the intestinal bulb.

primary dental epithelium also known as pharyngeal tooth epithelium; primary tooth epithelium Epithelium that surrounds a primary tooth. This epithelium is committed to formation of replacement teeth.
ampullary nerve A branch of the 8th cranial nerve that innervates the cristae ampullaris.
distal epidermal cap of regenerating fin/limb Part of regeneration epithelium at the tip of the fin/limb [ZFA,modified].
basal regeneration epithelium of regenerating fin/limb also known as basal wound epidermis Layer of the wound epidermis that surrounds the blastema in the fin or limb[ZFA,modified].
extrahepatic duct Bile duct that collects from the intrahepatic ducts and feeds into the common bile duct.
choroid plexus vascular circuit also known as CVC Cranial vasculature where the posterior cerebral veins and the trans-choroid plexus branch form a circuit around the 4th ventricle choroid plexus.

lateral larval melanophore stripe lateral larval melanophore stripe_1

inter-parietal joint Fibrous joint connecting the parietal bones.
trans-choroid plexus branch also known as TCB trans-choroid plexus branch_1

intervillus pockets A portion of tissue formed between the base of the intestinal villi that is part of the intestinal epithelium where intestinal stem cells are located. In the intestine no crypts are present, but, the regions between the villi, the intervillus pockets, have a crypt-like function. Cells are produced in the intervillus pockets and shed from the villus tips.

continuous capillary also known as continuous blood vessel endothelium; continuous capillary vessel Capillary that has endothelial cells that provide an uninterrupted lining, and only allow small molecules, like water and ions to diffuse through tight junctions which leave gaps of unjoined membrane which are called intercellular clefts.

fenestrated capillary also known as fenestrated capillary vessel Capillary that has pores in the endothelial cells (60-80 nm in diameter) that are spanned by a diaphragm of radially oriented fibrils and allow small molecules and limited amounts of protein to diffuse.
supraoccipital-parietal joint supraoccipital-parietal joint_1
hyomandibula-opercle joint Synovial joint that articulates the hyomandibula and the opercle.
pterotic fossa Fossa on the pterotic where the hyomandibula articulates.
erector muscle Muscle that moves parts of the body in a superior direction to an erect position. Antagonistic to depressor muscle.
preopercle horizontal limb-symplectic joint Joint that articulates the posterior edge of the preopercle horizontal limb with the symplectic.
hypophyseal fenestra Space enclosed by the trabeculae cranii. The anterior tip of the notochord extends into the posterior region of the hypophyseal fenestra.
depressor muscle A muscle that moves body parts into an inferior direction or lowered position. Antagonistic to erector muscle.

immature gonad also known as juvenile gonad Immature reproductive tissue that has not undergone final maturation into either testis or ovary. During gonadal development, the gonad may be transiently intersexual where there is a parallel presence of both oocytes and spermatocytes.
intestinal mucosal muscle A thin layer of smooth muscle immediately beneath the base of the villi which permits the intestinal mucosa to dynamically move and fold.
hyomandibular foramen Foramen in the hyomandibula that allows passage of the anterior lateral line nerve and the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII).

extrapancreatic duct Portion of the pancreatic duct, external to the pancreas body that connects the pancreas with the hepatopancreatic ampulla.
pars superior ear The dorsal part of the ear. Comprises the three semicircular canals, which connect to the utricle.

dorso-rostral cluster also known as dorsorostral cluster; drc Early-forming telencephalic neural cluster. Neurons of the dorso-rostral cluster (drc) extend axons to form the supra-optic tract (SOT) and the anterior commissure (AC). Ross et al., 1992.

ventro-rostral cluster also known as ventrorostral cluster; vrc Early-forming neural cluster located in the rostral diencephalon. At 19 h, axons arising from the vrc grow caudally to pioneer the tract of the postoptic commissure (TPOC). Ross et al., 1992.

ventro-caudal cluster also known as vcc; ventrocaudal cluster Early-forming neural cluster of the ventral midbrain. At 16 h, axons of the vcc grow caudally to pioneer the medial longitudinal fasciculus (MLF), which is part of the larger ventral longitudinal tract (VLT). Later, neurons from this cluster project axons rostrally into the tract of the post-optic commissure (TPOC). Ross et al., 1992.

epiphysial cluster also known as ec Early-developing neuronal cluster of the epiphysis. By 24 hpf the pioneer axon of the dorsoventral diencephalic tract (DVDT) has arisen from the ec and grown ventrally. As this axon encounters axons of the TPOC, it makes a near-90 rostral turn and grows rostrally among axons of the TPOC growing in the opposite direction. Ross et al., 1992.

alary cartilage Paired, cup-shaped cartilage that are dorsal to the septomaxillae and anterior to the oblique cartilage. The anterior, convex face of each alary cartilage is synchondrotically fused to the superior prenasal cartilage and the ventral edge is fused to the superior margin of the crista intermedia.

alary process of premaxilla Dorsal process that extends toward the nasal bone. The posterior (inner) face of each alary process is concave and is invested dorsomedially by the superior prenasal cartilage and ventromedially by the inferior prenasal cartilage.

Bidder's organ Anatomical structure which forms from an enlargement of the anterior portion of each gonad in all male bufonid larvae and consists of ovarian tissues.
braincase and auditory apparatus The part of the skull that encloses the brain and surrounds the inner ear.
braincase and otic capsule opening braincase and otic capsule opening_1

canalis semicircularis anterior canalis semicircularis anterior_1
capsular process Narrow process of the skeletal support that projects forward.
cartilago ectochoanalis Lateral cartilaginous border of the fenestra endochoanalis.

cartilago orbitalis Lateral wall of chondrocranial braincase between lamina orbitonasalis and pila metoptica.
