ramus hyomandibularis The posttrematic branch of the facial nerve, both motor and sensory in function.
limb villosities limb villosities_1
ramus palatinus Sensory branch of facial nerve from palatal region.
levator quadrati Responsible for the closing of the jaw, and innervated by the trigeminal nerve.
M. coracoradialis Muscle which originates from the omosternum and epicoracoid cartilage and inserts on the proximal radioulna.
ramus muscularis of glossopharyngeus nerve Branchiomotor branch of the glossopharyngeus nerve innervating the m. subarcuales rectus I.
otic opercular element also known as otic operculum Round, flat bone or cartilage that lies in the fenestra ovalis and articulates with the columella.
M. coracobrachialis longus Muscle which originates as a long belly from the dorsal coracoid near the sternum and inserts on the shaft of the humerus.
M. coracobrachialis brevis Muscle which originates on the dorsal surface of the coracoid and scapula and inserts on the deltoid crest of the humerus.
M. flexor carpi ulnaris Muscle which originates from the medial condyle of the humerus and inserts on the carpus.
ramus anterior of CN VIII Formed by fibers from the anterior semicircular canal and sacculus.
ramus posterior of CN VIII Composed of two rami: a short ventral ramus innervating the cochlea (lagena and papille basilar), and a long dorsal ramus innervating the posterior semicircular canal.
M. palmaris longus Originates from the medial epicondyle of the humerus and inserts on the palmar aponeurosis.
M. palmaris profundis Originates on the ulnar aspect of the radioulna and inserts on the palmar aponeurosis.
M. flexor antibrachii medialis Originates on the medial epicondyle of the humerus and inserts on the radial aspect of the radioulna.
ramus auricularis of the vagus nerve An afferent branch of the vagus nerve.
M. ulnocarpalis Originates along distal third of the ulna and inserts on the ulnare.
interhyoideus posterior interhyoideus posterior_1

M. flexor antibrachii lateralis superficialis Originates as a superior and inferior head. The superior head originates on the outer edge of the humerus and the inferior head originates on the lateral epicondyle of the humerus. Both bellies converge to form a tendon, which inserts on the carpus and the extensor tendon of digit I.
M. flexor antibrachii lateralis profundus Originates on the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and inserts on the lower ridge of the radioulna.
M. coccygeosacralis Originates on the lateral surface of the urostyle and inserts on the neural arch of the sacrum or on the sacral diapophysis.
T-shaped terminal phalanx T-shaped terminal phalanx_1
submentalis submentalis_1
M. coccygeoiliacus Originates on the lateral surface of the urostyle and passes ventral to the sacral diapophysis to insert on the anterior and medial surfaces of the ilial shaft.
M. iliolumbaris Originates on the anterior and lateral aspect of the ilial shaft and inserts on the transverse processes of presacral vertebrae IV-VII.
descending branch of the vagus nerve Major branch of the vagus supplying parasympathetic innervation to viscera.
ramus muscularis of vagus nerve Motor nervous branch of the vagus innervating m. subarcualis rectus I.
ramus recurrens Branch of the vagus nerve that separates from the vagus well postcranially, then continues anteriorly to innervate the larynx.
M. coccygeocutaneus Originates from the posterior tip of the urostyle and inserts on the cloacal musculature and the overlying skin.
laryngeus ventralis A branch of the vagus nerve innervating heart, stomach, and lung muscle.
dorsal sympathetic chain dorsal sympathetic chain_1
ventral sympathetic chain ventral sympathetic chain_1
M. dorsalis trunci Originates on the postero-dorsal edge of the postzygopophyses and insert on the dorsal surface of the neural arch of the posterior, adjacent vertebra.
pars recta pars recta_1
pars convoluta of oviduct pars convoluta of oviduct_1
m. oblique externus Originates on the posterior margin of the suprascapula and the epaxial fascia and inserts ventrally on the lateral fascia of the M. rectus abdominus and the ilial shaft.

m. oblique internus A muscular sheet in which the fibers run in right angles to those of the m. oblique externus, slanting downward anteriorly. This is one of three sheets composing the flank musculature.
m. transversus m. transversus_1
pars subvertebralis pars subvertebralis_1
pars transversalis pars transversalis_1
muscle rectus abdominis superficialis A component of the rectus abdominal muscle that is some taxa.
musculus rectus abdominis profundus A component of the rectus abdominal muscle that is some taxa (see comment) forms a disctinct and separate muscle.

m. ypsiloideus anterior Hypaxial muscle in which contraction elevates the ypsiloid cartilage; originates from the anterior edge of the lateral process of the ypsiloid cartilage and insert on the anteriorly adjacent inscription.

m. ypsiloideus posterior Contraction depresses the ypsiloid cartilage; arises from the anterodorsal edge of the pubis deep to the m. rectus abdominis profundus and spreads anteriorly in a fan shape to insert on the lateral edges of the shaft and the posterior edges of the lateral processes of the ypsiloid cartilage .
courtship gland courtship gland_1
vent glands vent glands_1
m. flexor indicis superficialis proprius Originates on the internal border of the distal carpal 5-4-3 and inserts on the distal end of phalynx I.
hepatic peritoneum Peritoneum that surrounds the liver.
gastrointestinal peritoneum Peritoneum that surrounds the stomach and intestines.
anterior prenasal cartilage anterior prenasal cartilage_1
commissura terminales of hyoid apparatus commissura terminales of hyoid apparatus_1
sulcus intermedius sulcus intermedius_1
spicule spicule_1
occipito-petrosal also known as occipital-petrosal Fusion of the occipital segment or occipital ring and otic capsule (Francis, 1934).
occipital segment Metameric segment forming the back of the skull.

posterolateral supplementary element A muscle slip arising from the ventral surface of the mandible by means of the ligament near the site of mandibular articulation. The fibers pass anteromedially and attach upon the ventral surfaces of the principal element of the m. intermandibularis (Tyler, 1971).

apical supplementary element A muscle slip arising from the lingual surface of the mandible on each side of the m. submentalis. The fibers pass posteromedially and attach upon the median raphe of the principal element (Tyler, 1971).

anterolateral supplementary element A muscle slip arising from the lingual surface of the mandible on the anterior portion of the bone. The fibers pass anteriorly, parallel to the mandible, and attach upon the ventral surface of the m. submentalis (Tyler, 1971).
first pancreatic bud first pancreatic bud_1
early proximal tubule also known as PT2 early proximal tubule_1
late distal segment late distal segment_1
permanent cartilage Chondrogenic element that is composed of cartilage that is not replaced.
mineralized skeletal tissue Skeletal tissue that is mineralized.
mineralized extracellular matrix Extracellular matrix that is mineralized.
integumentary papilla also known as scale papilla Odontogenic papilla that is located in the integument.
oropharyngeal papilla also known as oropharyngeal dental papilla Odontogenic papilla located along the jaws or pharyngeal skeleton.
vacuolated notochordal tissue also known as notochord proper Connective tissue that is matrix-poor with large number of vacuolated cells.

avascular GAG-rich matrix also known as avascular glycosaminoglycan-rich matrix; cartilage matrix; cartilage-like matrix Proteinaceous extracellular matrix that is avascular and consists primarily of glycosaminoglycans.
non-mineralized chondroid tissue non-mineralized chondroid tissue_1

chondroid tissue also known as chondroid bone tissue Skeletal tissue that is mineralized, has large chondrocyte-like cells, sparse extracellular matrix, and minimal perichondrium; develops from non-mineralized chondroid tissue.
secondary cartilage tissue Cartilage tissue that is part of the exoskeleton, deposited adjacent to bone after bone formation.
cosmine also known as cosmoid scale tissue cosmine_1
mineralized cartilage tissue Cartilage tissue that is mineralized.
integumentary skeleton Skeletal subdivision that is part of the extra-oral dermal skeletal system that develops and remains invested within the integument, primarily the dermis.
orthodentine Odontoid tissue that typically contains tubules and is acellular.
osteodentine osteodentine_1
vasodentine also known as vascular dentine Dentine tissue that lacks dentine tubules and that is penetrated by blood capillaries.
non-mineralized hyaline cartilage tissue Hyaline cartilage tissue that is not mineralized.
mineralized hyaline cartilage tissue Hyaline cartilage tissue that is mineralized.
mineralized bone tissue Bone tissue mineralized with hydroxyapatite.
cellular bone tissue Mineralized bone tissue that always includes non-terminally differentiated osteoblasts and osteocytes.
non-mineralized avascular GAG-rich matrix also known as non-mineralized cartilage Avascular GAG-rich matrix that is not mineralized.
mineralized avascular GAG-rich matrix Avascular GAG-rich matrix that is mineralized.
acellular bone tissue Mineralized bone tissue that has terminally differentiated osteoblasts but lacks osteocytes.

odontode tissue Skeletal tissue that is avascular tubular mineralized matrix, primarily made of dentine that is deposited by odontoblasts that are excluded from the matrix; develops from pre-dentine tissue.
ossified tendon Sesamoid that develops within a tendon, distal to an articulation or joint.
ligamentous replacement element Replacement element that forms as a replacement of a ligament.

transient cartilaginous element also known as endochondral replacement cartilage Chondrogenic element that is composed of cartilage during development and has the potential to become replaced by another tissue.
ossified ligament Sesamoid that develops within a ligament, distal to an articulation or joint.
anocleithrum also known as anocleithra Dermal bone of pectoral girdle that is dorsal to and articulates with the cleithrum.

scapular complex Skeletal subdivision of dermal bones that may include the anterolateral plate (AL), the spinal process (Sp), and anteroventral plate (AV) and other dermal bones that are part of the pectoral girdle.
skeletal element projection Anatomical projection that is composed of bone or cartilage tissue.
articular surface Anatomical surface that is part of a skeletal element and articulates with another skeletal element.
ischial peduncle Bony projection (peduncle) that is located on the posterior portion of the ilium, posterior to the acetabulum.
second phalanx Second most proximal phalanx in manual or pedal digits.

pectoral articular facet Facet of scapulocoracoid with which the pectoral fin radial(s) articulates. Facet of scapulocoracoid with which the pectoral fin radial(s) articulates. Based on Goujet and Young (1995).
pedal digit 7 phalanx Phalanx of the 7th pedal digit.
post-glenoid process Distinct notch ventral to the glenoid.
postacetabular buttress A bony process at the distal margin of the acetabulum formed by the ischium and/or the ischial peduncle of the ilium.
postacetabular zone Region of the ilium posterior and dorsal to the acetabulum.
postcoracoid The posterior of the two coracoid elements found in basal tetrapods. Corresponds directly to the 'coracoid' of synapsids.
posterior process of ilium A posteriorly directed bony projection from the ilium that is the attachment site of the iliofibularis muscle (see Sumida, 1997).
parasphenoid flange Lateral expansion of the parasphenoid.
radial facet Facet to accommodate the radius on the distal end of the humerus.
dermal intracranial joint Hinge in the skull skeleton to allow for kinetic movement of different parts.
anterior distal condyle of femur Anatomical projection in the distal region of the femur.
spiracular notch Soft tissue notch/opening lying on a spiracle.
posterior distal condyle of femur Anatomical projection in the posterior/distal region of the femur.
presacral rib Rib located anterior to the sacral region.
trunk rib Rib located in the trunk (ribcage) area (i.e. excluding cervical and caudal axial series.
extratemporal bone also known as postspiracular Extratemporal bone: Skull bone in the posterior half of the cranium, bordering the squamosal and opercular.
medial blade of ilium The medial surface of the iliac blade. Origin site of the iliofemoralis internus muscle and its homologues.
postpubis The region of the pubis posterior to the acetabulum.
intertrochanteric fossa Depression on the ventreal side of the femoral head. Associated with the pubioischiofemoralis externus muscle.
infraglenoid buttress An anatomical projection ventral to the glenoid fossa on the scapulocoracoid that abuts on the cliethrum (if present).
transverse pelvic ridge The transverse pelvic ridge is a short crest directly anterior to, and not extending posterior to, the prominent supra-acetabular buttress from Pawley and Warren 2006.
inter-clavicle joint also known as interclavicle joint Joint that articulates left and right clavicles.
ventral humeral ridge A distinct bony ridge on ventralsurface of the humeral shaft that corresponds to the attachment site of the pectoralis muscle.
pedal centrale A centrale found in the pes.
ectepicondylar flange Flange present of the distal region of the humerus, associated with extensor musculature of forelimb.
flexor surface Surface of a long bone that possess the flexor muscle attachment sites.
lateral tuber of ulna Projection on the lateral side of proximal part of the ulna.
inner digits of foot The medial most digits of the pes.
calcaneal tuber An enlargement of the distal region of the calcaneum that corresponds to the attachment site for the foot extensor muscles.
preacetabular process Process on ilium located anteriorly to acetabulum.
suprascapular fossa Fossa on the medial surface on the scapula above the glenoid.
astragalus-calcaneum unit Osteological unit consisting of the astragalus and calcaneum.
extracleithrum Narrow bone that lies ventral to the level of insertion of the pectoral fin and is sutured to the posterior edges of both the clavicle and cleithrum. Based on Forey 1998.
ascending process of the astragalus Flattened process of the dorsl surface of the astragalus which contacts the tibia anteriorly.
supraglenoid foramen Foramen that perforates supraglenoid buttress.
supraglenoid buttress A bony projection dorsal to the glenoid articulation on the scapulocoracoid.
adductor blade A prominent ridge in basal tetrapods on the ventral side of the femur that includes the fourth trochater, internal trochanter and the adductor crest (based on Coates, 1996).
adductor crest A bony crest on venteral side of femur that is the attachment site for the adductor muscles.
antitrochanter Raised surface at the posterior portion of the acetabulum (see Nesbitt, 2011).

caudalipuboischiotibialis Muscle that is associated with tail flexion. Orginates on one of the first post sacral vertebrae posteriorly and inserts on the posterior edge of the m.puboischiotibialis. (modified from Duellman and Trueb 1994).
clavicle blade Expanded and flattened ventral region of clavicle bone.
cnemial crest Longitudnal bony ridge on tibia, attachment site of the major extensor muscle of the hind limb.

internal trochanter A boney projection on the internal diaphysis of the femur anterior or medial to the intertrochanteric fossa, below the femoral head. Muscle attachment site for ventral muscle mass notably the puboischiofemoralis externus. Modified from Romer 1956.
supinator process A bony process that corresponds to the attachment site for the forelimb supinator muscles in tetrapods, distal to the deltopectoral crest and anterior to the radial condyle.
subscapular fossa A marked depression on the medial side of the scapula blade, often opposite the glenoid region.

supraacetabular buttress A bony protuberance dorsal to the acetabulum on the ilium, confluent with the supraacetabular crest (when present). Acts as a bone brace to prevent excessive femoral abduction and the origin site for part of the M. iliofemoralis.

aponeurosis palmaris The palmar aponeurosis is a fibrotendinous complex that functions as the tendinous extension of the palmaris longus, when present, and as a strong stabilizing structure for the palmar skin of the hand. It has five longitudinal slips that project into the base of each digit and a deeper transverse portion that crosses the palm at the proximal end of the metacarpals bones (from Wikipedia).
brevis shelf Anatomical projection on the ilium, anchoring caudal muscles.
brevis fossa Fossa located on the brevis shelf.
articular surface for the calcaneum on the astragalus Contact surface between the calcaneum and the astragalus located on the astragalus.
articular surface for the astragalus on the calcaneum Contact surface between the calcaneum and the astragalus located on the calcaneum.
astragalo-calcaneal canal The astragalo-calcaneal canal forms a foramen between the articulated astragalus and calcaneum when the canal is ossified (Nesbitt, 2011).
attachment site Morphological structure denoting the extent of an attachment site for a soft tissue on a skeletal element.
bicipital crest also known as crista bicipitalis; crista tuberculi majoris Anatomical projection that is an expansion on the proximal region of the humerus.
cartilago sesamoides A sesamoid found in the found in the ligamentum calcanei of a wide variety of frogs. (based on Nussbaum, R. A. 1982.
cotyla A cup shaped articular surface on a bone.
cotyloid notch A notch or opening in the ventral part of the acetabular rim.
crista tibiofibularis Tuberosity on the posterior surface of the lateral femoral condyle.
ectepicondylar foramen Formen present on the ectepicondyle of the humerus.
ectocondylar tubercle Posteriorly projecting bony tubercle that is located proximal to the lateral condyle of the femur.
prepubic element A small plate of cartilage synchondrotically united with the pubis. Modified from Baez and Harrison 2005.
sternal keel also known as carina; carina sterni; crista sterni The vertical plate of bone or cartilage attached to the median line of the sternum. Modified from Baumel et al. 1993.
trunk armor pectoral fenestra also known as trunk armour pectoral fenestra An opening in the dermal armour of basal gnathostomes that encloses the pectoral fins. (modified from Young 2010).
clavicular facet A notch for the articulation of the clavicle on other girdle elements.
dorsal iliac process Posteriordorsal process of the ilium.
fibular crest A bony projection on the lateral side of the tibia, allowing contact between the later and the fibula.
postaxial centrale Centrale in the postaxial region of the mesopodium.
preaxial centrale Centrale in the preaxial side of the mesopodium.
iliac neck also known as neck of ilium A constricted region of the ilium which is dorsal to the acetabulular region. Prior to the expansion of the iliac blade.
iliac peduncle Bony projection that is part of the dorsal surface of the ischim, where it articulates with the ilium.
iliac peduncle of the pubis Bony projection that is part of the dorsal surface of the pubis where it meets the ilium.
fibular facet of the calcaneum Articular surface on calcaneum for the fibula.
fibular facet of the astragalus Articular surface on the astragalus for the fibula.
ethomosphenoid region Region consisitng of the ethmoid and sphenoid bones.
flexor tubercle of ungual Eminence on the proximo-dorsal surface of the ungual, for attachment of flexor muscles.
inner digits of hand The medial most digit of the manus skeleton.
infraspinous process Process on infraspinous (region below the spine) of scapula.

intercondylar fossa also known as femoral groove; femoral sulcus; femoropatellar groove; patellar groove; patellar sulcus; patellar surface of femur; patellofemoral groove; trochlea of femur; trochlear groove of femur; trochlear sulcus of femur; trochlear surface of femur The deep fossa between the femoral condyles in which the cruciate ligaments are attached. From Medilexicon.com.
intermediate spine Spine ventrally located on the body and not part of the pectoral, pelvic or anal fins.
ischial foot Expansion of the distal region of the ischium.
lateral extrascapular The most lateral of the paired series of extrascapular bones and is the bone where the intersection of the otic, postotic and extrascapular or supratemporal canals occur.
latissimus dorsi process A bony process on the dorsal side of the proximal region of the humerus which corresponds to the insertion site of the Latissimus dorsi muscle.
m.scapulotriceps Muscle that represents one branch of the larger triceps brachii, origination site near the glenoid fossa on the scapula.
median dorsal plate Dermal armour plate that is situated behind the head and constitute the dorsal most portion of the dermal shoulder girdle. Modified from Brazeau 2009, Young 2010.
median extrascapular The medial of the the paired series of extrascapular bones which carries the extrascapular or supratemporal canal.
metacarpal extensor pit Pits located on the proximodorsal part of metacarpals denoting the attachemnt sites for ligaments.
nerve foramen Opening and/or passageway for nerve(s) in bone.
muscle scar A distinct region on a skeletal element that demarcates the attachment area of a muscle or tendon. Often associated with rugosity or tubercles.
obturator process of ischium Process located on the ventral shaft of the ischium that denotes the attachment site of the pubio-ischio-femoralis externus.
outer digit of hand The flanking digit of the manus.
outer digits of pes The flanking digit of the pes.
prepectoral spine Spine located anterior to the pectoral fin.
prepelvic fin spine Spine located anterior to the pelvic fin and posterior to the pectoral fin.
prepectoral space A triangular, anteroventrally facing area developed between the preaxial margin of the humerus and the proximal limb of the ventral humeral ridge. Based on Callier et al. 2009 .
prepubic process Elongate process forming the anteriormost part of the pubis.
presupracleithrum An skeletal element of the upper pectoral girdle overlapped by the opercular and posttemporal bones.
pteroid Slender bone connected to the carpus in pterosaurs. The bone, which may have pointed forward, supports the propatagium, a membrane located between the carpus and pectoral region.
pubic boot Anteroposterior expansion of the distal region of the pubis.
pubic peduncle Bony projection on the anterior portion of the ilium, anterior to the acetabulum that articulates with the pubis.
pubis-ischium contact Contact zone between the pubis and the ischium.
puboischiadic plate A broad expnase of bone incorperating both the pubis and the ischium. Origin site for ventral limb muscle including the pubioishciofemoralis externus. Modified from Romer 1956 .

puboischiotibialis muscle also known as M. puboischiotibialis; puboischiotibialis A muscle that originates from the puboischaidic plate and inserts on the tibia. Acts to adduct the hindlimb. Is anterior to cloacal gland in males. Modified from De luliis and Pulera.
pubotibialis Originates in on the pubic cartillage and inserts on the tibia, acts to adduct the hindlimb. Modified from De luliis and Pulera.
scapular process The dorsal extension of the scapulocoracoid above the level of the glenoid region in basal gnathostomes. Modified from Brazeau 2009.
sternal trabecula Anatomical projections that are elongate processes in the mid and posterior regions of the sternum.
supraacetabular crest Anatomical projection (crest) located dorsaly to the acetabulum.
supraacetabular rim Bony rim that is part of the supraacetabular region.

suprascapula foramen The route through which structures pass between the base of the neck and the posterior scapular region. It is formed by the suprascapular notch of the scapula and the superior transverse scapular ligament. From http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/suprascapular+foramen.

synarcual region of vertebral column also known as synarcuum Series of fused cervical vertebrae or vertebral elements. Based on Jeffrey C. Carrier. Biology of Sharks and Their Relatives, 2012. CRC Press.
synarcual region Axial subdivision that includes a series of fused cervical vertebrae or vertebral elements. Based on Jeffrey C. Carrier. Biology of Sharks and Their Relatives, 2012. CRC Press.
tibial facet of astragalus Facet for the articulation of the tibia on the astragalus (talus).
trochanteric shelf Anatomical projection on the anterolateral region of the proximal end of the femur.
crest A ridge or similar projection rising above the surface of an anatomical structure.
antimere A part in the body of an organism that corresponds to an opposite symmetrical part.

puboischiadic bar A transverse flattened or cylindrical plate in the posterior body wall opposite the anterior ends of the pelvic fins, in front of the vent and at the posterior end of the body cavity, that supports a few anterior pelvic radials and a basal cartilage, the basipterygium. from Leonard J. V. Compagno. 2001. Sharks of the World: An Annotated and Illustrated Catalogue of Shark Species Known to Date. Volume 2.

prepollical element Is a endochondral element that is part of the mesopodial skeleton and is contained within the prepollex which in some taxa appears as a pre-axial digit-like projection anterior to the first digit of the hand.

prehallical element Is a endochondral element that is part of the mesopodial skeleton and is contained within the prehallux which in some taxa appears as a pre-axial digit-like projection anterior to the first digit of the foot.
accessory foramen Foramen found on the humerus of tetrapodomorphs beyond the entepicondyle and ectepicondyle foramen. Often denoted as foramen 'c' and 'd' after Jarvik 1996.
toe disc toe disc_1
intertarsale sesamoid Sesamoid bone in the tarsal region.
metatarsal bone of digit 6 metatarsal bone of digit 6
metapodium bone 6 metapodium bone 6
metapodium bone 7 metapodium bone 7
metapodium bone 8 metapodium bone 8
metatarsal bone of digit 7 metatarsal bone of digit 7
metatarsal bone of digit 8 metatarsal bone of digit 8

ventral ridge system A collection of attached ridges on the ventrl surface of the femur consisting of the internal and fourth trochanters plus the adductor blade and crest. Most notible in early amniotes (based on Romer 1956).
hindlimb interepipodial space The space between the bones of the tibia and the fibula.
mesial pelvic ridge mesial pelvic ridge
process 2 of entepicondyle Process on the humerus of basal tetrapods, anterior to the entepicondyle and associated with subscapularis muscle (based on Coates 1996).
process 3 of entepicondyle Process on the humerus of basal tetrapods, anterior to the entepicondyle and adjacent to process 4 of entepicondyle (see Coates 1996).
process 4 of entepicondyle Process on the humerus of basal tetrapods, anterior to the entepicondyle and adjacent to process 3 of entepicondyle (see Coates 1996).
neck of humerus also known as collum anatomicum (Humerus); collum anatomicum humeri; humeral neck neck of humerus
dorsal ridge dorsal ridge
distal condyle of humerus The area encompassing the radial and ulnar condyles of the humerus.
supraglenoid region supraglenoid region_1
ascending process of clavicle A bony dorsal extension of the clavicle.
supracondyle tubercle supracondyle tubercle_1
semilunate carpal The moon shaped fusion of distal carpals 1 and 2 found in some theropod dinosaurs, permitting greater wrist mobility.
astragalus head also known as talus head The region of the astragalus/ talus that carries the articular surface for the navicular or central metatarsal.
lateral tubercle of astragalus lateral tubercle of astragalus_1

bicipital tuberosity The rough eminence which is on the anterior inner aspect of the neck of the radius and into which the tendon of the biceps is inserted. From http://www.merriam-webster.com/medical.
ulnar tuberosity His roughened area of bone sits distomedially at the base of the coronoid process. It is the attachment site for the brachialis muscle. From http://www.anatomyexpert.com/.
entepicondyle fossa A fossa on the distal humerus proximal to the entepicondyle.
distal keel of metacarpal III distal keel of metacarpal III_1
manual toe disc manual toe disc_1
pedal toe disc pedal toe disc_1
zygosphene An articular process on anterior surface of neural arch of vertebrae which fits into zygantrum. Modified from Henderson's dictionary of Biological terms 12th Edition.
ulnar facet of the humerus ulnar facet of the humerus_1
posterodorsal process of ilium Anatomical project part of the blade of the ilium that projects posteriorly.
intercentrum The anteriormost of the two possible elements found in the tetrapod centrum (when the centrum is not a single element).
pleurocentrum The posteriormost of the two possible elements found in the tetrapod centrum (when the centrum is not a single element).
atlas intercentrum The intercentrum unit of the atlas vertebra.
anterior humeral ridge Ridge or keel at the proximal end of the humerus. (see Laurin 1998).
incisor process Process that is part of the mandible that is in close proximity to the incisor teeth.
sallet sensory system also known as sallet restraint system Ciliary restraint system in the inner ear that uses sallets instead of the tectorial membrane.
humeral facet on the ulna Facet on the ulna for articulation with the ulnar condyle of the humerus.
humeral facet on radius also known as proximal articular surface of radius Facet on the radius for articulation with the radial condyle of the humerus.
postaxial process of the ulnare A projection on the postaxial region of the ulnare.
postaxial process of the femur A projection on the postaxial region of the femur.
postaxial process of the fibula A projection on the postaxial region of the fibula.
pectoral process of humerus pectoral process of humerus_1
deltoid process deltoid process_1
epipodial facet Facets for the articulation of the epipodial (zeugopodial) elements.
suture Line of junction between two parts immovably connected. Modified from Henderson's Dictionary of Biological Terms.
fibula facet of femur Facet on the femur for the fibula.
tibial facet of femur Facet on the femur for the tibia.
musculotendinous bundle A collection of muscle and tendinous tissue.
middle phalanx of manual digit 1 middle phalanx of manual digit 1_1
iliac ramus iliac ramus_1
growth line Distinct layer that indicate the growth of an organism.
distal groove of humerus Groove along the distal margin of the humerus, ventral to the radial and ulnar condyle.
foramen C Foramen located on the scapulocoracoid, located just behind the cleithral anteroventral process(the articulation with the cleithrum). Modified from Coates 1996.

columnar area Modified from Garvey et al. 2005. ' Between the dorsal ridge and the caput humeri is a futher recessed area......that clearly separates the two structures and is slightly separted from the dorsal surface of the entepicondyle, and more specifically from the unfinished bone of the entepicondyle, by a narrow ridge.'.

scapulohumeralis muscle Muscle found primarily in basal sarcopterygians that runs between teh scapulocoracoid and the humerus. Its exact homologies with more derived shoulder muscles in Tetrapoda is unclear.

surface of bone also known as bone surface An anatomical surface that is part of a bone.
unfinished bone surface A bone surface that is not smooth and periosteal. The usual implication is that the bone was still growing, was covered in cartilage, or both. From Paleos.com.
finished bone surface A smooth periosteal bone surface.

dorsal clavicular process also known as ascending dorsal clavicular process A process, extending dorsally from the clavicular plate, that attaches to the cleithrum. Modified from Clack 2012 and Coates 1996.

parasymphysial plate Bone, often with tooth attachments, on the lingual side of the anterior of the lower jaw.

meckelian bone The ossification of the Meckel's cartilage.

palatine prong A process on the palatine that projects outward and upward and articulates with a depression (maxillary saddle) in the proximal end of the maxilla [Gosline WA et al, 1966; Baldwin, CC and Johnson GD. 1996. Interrelationships of Aulopiformes. Pages 355-404 in MLJ Stiassny, LR Parenti, and DG Johnson, (eds.), Interrelationships of fishes. Academic Press, San Diego, CA.].
aphakic space The space in the pupil, which is not occupied by the lens. A rostral aphakic space may enhance the forward binocular field of vision.
medial pelvic process Process that is posteriorly oriented and medially located on the basipterygium. It is a paired projection. [PHENOSCAPE:bf].
epipleural series Anatomical cluster that consists of the epipleurals.
clavus also known as pseudo-caudal fin; pseudocaudal fin A rudder-like lobe formed from extensions of dorsal and anal fin rays.
dorsal cleithrum dorsal cleithrum_1
ventral cleithrum ventral cleithrum_1

rostrodermethmoid Dermal bone formed by the fusion of dermethmoids and rostral bones [Fink, W L Weitzman, S H. 1982. Relationships of the stomiiform fishes (Teleostei), with a description of Diplophos Bulletin of The Museum of Comparative Zoology 150:31-93. http://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/part/28697].
anterolateral plate also known as AL Dermal bone that is part of the scapular complex in placoderm fishes.

anteroventral plate also known as AV; anterior ventral plate Dermal bone that is part of the scapular complex in placoderms, located in the ventral armour adjacent to the interolateral (IL) and anterior ventrolateral (AVL) plates.
interolateral plate also known as IL Dermal bone that is part of the scapular complex in placoderms, and located anterior to the anterior ventrolateral (AVL) plate.
spinal plate also known as Sp Dermal bone that is part of the scapular complex in placoderms, and located lateral to the anterior ventrolateral (AVL) plate.
posterior dorsolateral plate also known as PDL Dermal bone that is part of the scapular complex in placoderms, located posterior to the main components of the complex.

anterior ventrolateral plate also known as AVL Dermal bone that is part of the ventral region of scapular complex in placoderms (see also posterior ventrolateral plate). In most placoderms with a long ventral armour, the ventral wall is typically composed of two large paired lateral plates (anterior and posterior ventrolaterals).

posterior ventrolateral plate also known as PVL Dermal bone that is part of the ventral region of scapular complex in placoderms (see also anterior ventrolateral plate). In most placoderms with a long ventral armour, the ventral wall is typically composed of two large paired lateral plates (anterior and posterior ventrolaterals).

dermal neck joint also known as cervical neck joint Dermal articulation between skull and shoulder girdle localized to paired dermal neck-joint between anterior dorsolateral plate (ADL) and paranuchal (PNu) plates in placoderms.
flexor caudalis muscle flexor caudalis muscle_1

antorbital cartilage Cartilage element on the neurocranium of sawsharks and batoids, separate cartilages attached to the sides of the nasal capsules that support the sides or front of the head. [Compagno, L.J.V. Sharks of the world. An annotated and illustrated catalogue of shark species known to date. Volume 2. Bullhead, mackerel and carpet sharks (Heterodontiformes, Lamniformes and Orectolobiformes). FAO Species Catalogue for Fishery Purposes. No. 1, Vol. 2. Rome, FAO. 2001. 269p. ISBN 92-5-104543-7].
supraneural element Endochondral element that is median and located in the dorsal skeletogenous septum between the cranium and the dorsal fin.
supraneural cartilage supraneural cartilage_1
facet A small smooth area on a bone or other firm structure. A worn spot on a tooth, produced by chewing or grinding.
X bone The x bone is a detached neural spine anterior to the neural spine of preural centrum 2.
Y bone The y bone is a detached neural spine anterior to the haemal spines of preural centrum 2.
mesocoracoid element mesocoracoid element_1

ectocoracoid bone A paired dermal bone in Gasterosteiformes connected with the coracoid and extending posteriorly. Has also been applied to the element below the scapula and applied to the coracoid in Dipnoi. Dictionary of Ichthyology.
caudal vertebra 1 Caudal vertebra that is the anteriormost element of the series.
ventral limb of posttemporal Zone of bone organ that is the ventral extension of the posttemporal.
lateral ethmoid cartilage lateral ethmoid cartilage_1

lateral ethmoid element Endochondral element that separates the olfactory region from the orbit, extends medially to meet its fellow medially below the frontal bones and is bordered by the mesethmoid anteriorly. It may articulate with the autopalatine and infraorbital 1 laterally. The lateral ethmoid is paired.
glenoid region Region surrounding the glenoid fossa on the scapulocoracoid.
zygantrum A fossa on the posterior median part of the neural arch of a vertebra (as of a snake) that accommodates the zygosphene of the next vertebra.
pre-axial region Anatomical region lying to the anterior or dorsal side of the metapterygial axis.
axis intercentrum The intercentrum unit of the axis vertebra. .
dorsal iliac ridge Ridge that is part of the ilium.

tectorial restraint system Tectorial restraint system is a type of ciliary restraint system for hair cells in the inner ear. In tectorial restraint systems, the tectorial membrane restrains the cilia of the hair cells by attaching either directly to ciliary tufts or indirectly through various kinds of fibrous structure (simple fibers, fibrous strands, finger-like processes, tectorial plates) [Phylogenetic Relationships of the Lizard Families: Essays Commemorating Charles L. Camp. 1988. Eds. R Estes, GK Pregill. Stanford University Press].
nuchal crest Bony protuberance on the external surface of the occipital bone.[PHENOSCAPE:AD].
sacral rib Elements of the sacrum joining true sacral vertebrae to pelvis [12th edition of Henderson's Dictionary of Biological terms].
dorsal pelvic gland Cloacal glands that secrete into the dorsal roof of the cloacal tube and or the anterior cloacal chamber. Found in male salamanders.
lateral pelvic gland lateral pelvic gland_1
glossopharyngeal nerve foramen also known as nerve foramen IX Foramen for the passage of the glossopharyngeal nerve IX.
upper jaw symphyseal region also known as upper jaw symphysial region The region of the upper jaw on or near the midline.

lateral commissure Region of the braincase which bears the facets for the hyomandibula in fishes. This region disappears in the origin of tetrapods and the space it occipied comes to contribute to the fenestra vestibulii. Clack, JA, 2001. Ch. 23, The otoccipital region. In Major Events in Early Vertebrate Evolution. Per Ahlberg editor.
upper jaw symphyseal tooth also known as upper jaw symphysial tooth Tooth of the upper jaw that is adjacent to the upper jaw symphysis.
lingual region The region of an anatomical structure (such as a tooth or jaw bone) facing the tongue.
labial region The region of an anatomical structure, such as a tooth or jaw bone, facing the lips.[PHENOSCAPE:WD].
posterolingual region The region of an anatomical structure, such as a tooth or jaw bone, oriented posteriorly and facing the lips.
mesial region The region of an anatomical structure, such as a tooth or jaw bone, facing the midline of the jaw.
internal carotid foramen Foramen for the passage of the internal carotid artery.
profundus foramen Foramen for the profundus or ophthalmic nerve.
gill membrane Membrane organ that is usually supported by branchiostegal rays and forms the ventral and posterior wall of the gill cavity.

pelvic intercleithral cartilage Cartilage element that lies between processes of the cleithrum and pelvic girdle in gobioid fishes. Posterodorsal to the ventral end of each cleithrum is a posteriorly projecting process. The pelvic intercleithral cartilage (an unpaired, median structure) forms a bridge between the processes (From Springer, 1983).

accessory nasal sac Accessory nasal sacs are found in a variety of teleosts (Webb, 1993) and likely assist in ventilating the olfactory epithelium by transmitting pressure fluctuations associated with gill irrigation from theoral cavity to the nasal (or sensory) sac (Jakubowski,1975; Webb, 1993; Belanger et al., 2003). [def from Eastman, J. T. and Lannoo, M. J. (2004)].

Sharpey's fiber Sharpey's fibres (bone fibres, or perforating fibres) are a matrix of connective tissue consisting of bundles of strong collagenous fibres connecting periosteum to bone. They are part of the outer fibrous layer of periosteum, entering into the outer circumferential and interstitial lamellae of bone tissue.
anterodorsal crest anterodorsal crest_1
midshaft Region in the middle of the shaft of a long bone (e.g. humerus, femur etc).
ectepicondylar depression ectepicondylar depression_1

inner tooth row of dentary Dentary tooth row that is lingual in position relative to other tooth rows.
inner tooth row of premaxilla Tooth row on the premaxilla that is lingually located relative to other tooth rows.

isthmus The fleshy throat region of a fish which extends forward from the ventral part of the chest and narrows anteriorly, and externally separating the two gill chambers; that narrowed portion of the breast which lies between the gill chambers and separates them.
neural spine 5 Neural spine that is associated with the fifth vertebra.
neural spine 6 Neural spine that is associated with the sixth vertebra.
neural spine 7 Neural spine that is associated with the seventh vertebra.
parapophysis 3 Parapophysis that is the lateral projection from the third centrum. Parapophysis 3 is bilaterally paired.

rostral tubule also known as rostral tubuli Consists of a set of tubuli occupying the space between the external dermal bones above the dorsal and anterior wal of the nasal capsule below. Thomson and Campbell (1971).
processus descendens of sphenoid also known as otico-sphenoid bridge processus descendens of sphenoid_1

Westoll line also known as Westoll lines More or less concentric lines of discontinuity in the cosmine of Dipnoi, probably due to cyclic resorption and redeposition during growth occurring on the bases of individual scales and also as large structures between headshield plates.[Fishbase].
postsplenial Dermal bone of the lower jaw.
postparietal shield also known as parietal shield Dermal bones (postparietals, supratemporals, intertemporals, extrascapulars) posterior to the intracranial joint. Forey 1997.
subepiotic fossa Fossa for epaxial musculature inserting on the braincase. Forey et al. 1996.

endoskeletal cranial joint also known as endoskeletal intracranial joint The braincase of most plesiomorphic sarcopterygians is divided by the intracranial point into ethmosphenoid and otic-occipital portions each covered by dermal bones. The function of the joint is presumably to increase the gape of the mouth rapidly during opening phases. (Forey 1997).
tectum orbitale The dorsal portion of the endocranium that covers the orbital region. Hanken and Hall (1993).
palato-maxillary ligament Ligament between the palatine and maxilla [Stiassny 1986].
mandibulo-lacrimal ligament Ligament that connects the ventromedial end of the lacrimal to the anguloarticular (or 'mandible'). Parenti (2008).

lateral plate Body plates on the lateral sides of the body that occur as single bilateral rows and their number is highly heritable. Bell and Richkind (1981).
acrodin Odontoid tissue forming a cap on teeth found in teeth of actinopterygian fishes.

precaudal vertebra Vertebral bone lacking hemal spines (Weitzman, 1962), refers generally to the anterior vertebral region bounding the abdominal cavity. Alternate but not quite synonymous terms are abdominal or trunk vertebrae, which bear parapophyses and ribs. In many actinopterygians dorsal to the posterior abdominal cavity there are transitional vertebrae lacking ribs but also without hemal spines or sometimes even enclosed hemal arches. The primary definition would identify these vertebrae as precaudal. Bird and Mabee, 2003.

precaudal vertebra endochondral element Vertebral elements lacking hemal spines (Weitzman, 1962), refers generally to the anterior vertebral region bounding the abdominal cavity. Alternate but not quite synonymous terms are abdominal or trunk vertebrae, which bear parapophyses and ribs. In many actinopterygians dorsal to the posterior abdominal cavity there are transitional vertebrae lacking ribs but also without hemal spines or sometimes even enclosed hemal arches. The primary definition would identify these vertebrae as precaudal.(Bird and Mabee, 2003).

precaudal vertebra cartilage element Vertebral cartilage elements lacking hemal spines (Weitzman, 1962), refers generally to the anterior vertebral region bounding the abdominal cavity. Alternate but not quite synonymous terms are abdominal or trunk vertebrae, which bear parapophyses and ribs. In many actinopterygians dorsal to the posterior abdominal cavity there are transitional vertebrae lacking ribs but also without hemal spines or sometimes even enclosed hemal arches. The primary definition would identify these vertebrae as precaudal.(Bird and Mabee, 2003).

ethmo-palatine cartilage The ethmo-palatine cartilage (EPC) is a distinct body situated between the posterior surface of the upper arm of the premaxilla and the anterior margin of the palatine. There is usually only a single cartilage mass lying between these bones, although that cartilage is apparently subdivided into two units in some taxa (e.g., the Old World characiform family Citharinidae, Vari, 1979:294). Vari 1989a.

manual digit 8 digitopodial skeleton also known as manual digit VIII digitopodial skeleton A subdivision of the skeleton of the autopod consisting of the phalanges of manual digit 8 plus the associated metapodial element.

pedal digit 6 digitopodial skeleton also known as pedal digit VI digitopodial skeleton A subdivision of the skeleton of the autopod consisting of the phalanges of pedal digit 6 plus the associated metapodial element.

pedal digit 7 digitopodial skeleton also known as pedal digit VII digitopodial skeleton A subdivision of the skeleton of the autopod consisting of the phalanges of pedal digit 7 plus the associated metapodial element.

pedal digit 8 digitopodial skeleton also known as pedal digit VIII digitopodial skeleton A subdivision of the skeleton of the autopod consisting of the phalanges of pedal digit 8 plus the associated metapodial element.
panarthropod head panarthropod head_1
insect pharynx Section of the insect foregut anterior to the esophagus.
proximal-most point of head of femur The proximal-most point of the head of a femur.
proximal-most point of head of humerus The proximal-most point of the head of a humerus.
proximal-most point of ventral tubercle of humerus The proximal-most point of the ventral tubercle of a humerus.
proximal-most point of greater trochanter of femur The proximal-most point of the greater trochanter of a femur.
lower fourth secondary molar tooth also known as lower fourth permanent molar tooth The molar tooth of the lower jaw that is phylogenetically number 4.
lower fourth secondary premolar tooth also known as lower fourth permanent premolar tooth The premolar tooth of the lower jaw that is phylogenetically number 4.
lower third secondary premolar tooth also known as lower third permanent premolar tooth The premolar tooth of the lower jaw that is phylogenetically number 3.
molar tooth 4 also known as fourth molar tooth; molar 4; molar 4 tooth The molar tooth of the upper or lower jaw that is phylogenetically number 4.
premolar 3 also known as premolar tooth 3; third premolar tooth The premolar tooth of the upper or lower jaw that is phylogenetically number 3.
upper fourth secondary molar tooth also known as upper fourth permanent molar tooth The molar tooth of the upper jaw that is phylogenetically number 4.
upper fourth secondary premolar tooth also known as upper fourth permanent premolar tooth The premolar tooth of the upper jaw that is phylogenetically number 4.
upper third secondary premolar tooth also known as upper third permanent premolar tooth The premolar tooth of the upper jaw that is phylogenetically number 3.

trochlear ridge of humerus The ridge of the trochlea on a humerus lies in the middle of the distal end of a humerus on the lateral side of the trochlea and the medial side of the capitulum (capitellum).
tibial tuberosity also known as fossa digitalis The tibial tuberosity is on the anterior side of a tibia and is where a patella ligament attaches.

trochlea of talus also known as trochlea for tibia; trochlea of astragalus; trochlea tali The articular surface of a talus that interacts with a tibia. It has a deep depression that forms the trochlear groove and is bounded by the medial and lateral condyles.
trochlear groove of talus also known as trochlear groove of astragalus The furrow between the lateral and medial condyles of the trochlea of talus.
condyle of talus also known as condyle of astragalus An articular prominence of a talus that engages with the tibia.

medial condyle of talus also known as medial condyle of astragalus The medial condyle of talus is an articular prominence of bone on medial side of the trochlea of a talus, which engages with the tibia.

lateral condyle of talus also known as lateral condyle of astragalus The lateral condyle of talus is an articular prominence of bone on the lateral side of the trochlea of a talus, which engages with the tibia.
ridge of medial condyle of talus also known as ridge of medial condyle of astragalus The crest of the medial condyle of a talus.
ridge of lateral condyle of talus also known as ridge of lateral condyle of astragalus The crest of the lateral condyle of a talus.
sulcus tali also known as sulcus for flexor hallucis longus tendon A depression that runs between the two facets of a talus that interact with a calcaneum.
left nasal bone Nasal bone on the left side of an organism when in anatomical position.
right nasal bone Nasal bone on the right side of an organism when in anatomical position.
left zygomatic arch Zygomatic arch on the left side of an organism when in anatomical position.
right zygomatic arch Zygomatic arch on the right side of an organism when in anatomical position.
styloid process of radius also known as radial condyle; radial styloid process A condyle on the distal end and lateral side of a radius.
articular surface for carpals also known as distal articular surface of radius The articular surface on the distal end of a radius that interacts with carpals.
articular surface for the tibia on the talus Contact surface between the tibia and the talus located on the talus.
greater palatine foramen A foramen of the skull found at either posterior angle of the hard palate, for the transmission of the descending palatine vessels and greater palatine nerve.

lesser palatine foramen A foramen of the skull found at either posterior angle of the hard palate behind the greater palatine foramen. One or more lesser palatine foramina perforate the pyramidal process of the palatine bone and carry the lesser palatine nerve.
endodontium also known as endodont; pulp-dentin complex A pulp-dentin complex or endodont that is part of a calcareous tooth.
posterior articular facet for talus of calcaneus also known as proximal facet of calcaneum Posterior-most facet on the proximal surface of the calcaneus for the articulation of the talus bone.
middle articular facet for talus of calcaneus Middle facet on the proximal surface of the calcaneus for the articulation of the talus bone.
anterior articular facet for talus of calcaneus also known as distal facet of calcaneum Anterior-most facet on the proximal surface of the calcaneus for the articulation of the talus bone.
calcaneal body also known as corpus calcanei The calcaneus body is the part of the bone not used for articulation with other bones.
tubercle of calcaneus also known as calcaneal tubercle; calcaneal tuberosity; tuberosity of calcaneus A raised projection on the calcaneus.
lateral tubercle of calcaneus also known as lateral tuberosity of calcaneus A raised projection on the lateral side of a calcaneus.
medial tubercle of calcaneus also known as medial tuberosity of calcaneus A raised projection on the medial side of a calcaneus.
antorbital notch The antorbital notch is a prominence of bone located anterolaterally of the antorbital fenestra.

preorbital bone region Part of the orbital plate formed by the jugal (part of the zygomatic), lacrimal (which is sometimes fused), sometimes nasal (typically in species with elongated rostra), and maxilla bones anterior to the orbit.
preorbital fossa A hollow (fossa) in the preorbital region, typically lying on the maxillary bone, although sometimes can touch nasal bones (e.g., modern Equus).
coracoid process of calcaneus also known as processus coracoideus of calcaneus At the dorsal part of the base of the calcaneal tuberoisty is a pointed process called the coracoid process.
hormion A craniometric point at the junction of the posterior midline border of the vomer with the sphenoid bone on the sphenovomerine suture.
sphenovomerine suture A suture joining a sphenoid bone with the alae of a vomer to form a schindylesis type of joint.
cheek tooth also known as cheektooth Any of the post-canine teeth, which are the multicuspidate molars or premolars used for shearing and grinding food in mammals.
basion An anatomical point on the antero-ventral margin of foramen magnum in the median plane.
synsphenion A craniometric point on the ventral surface of the intersphenoid suture, along the midline of the skull.
intersphenoid suture also known as intersphenoidal synchondrosis A suture joining the basisphenoid bone and the presphenoid bone of a sphenoid bone.
prosthion also known as alveolar point; prostheon A craniometric point that is the most anterior point in the midline on the alveolar process of the maxilla between the incisors (premaxilla bone).
akrokranion The most dorsoanterior point on the supraoccipital crest in the medial plane.
cheek tooth row also known as cheektooth row An anatomical row consisting of adjacent cheek teeth.
sagittal crest also known as sagittal ridge A ridge or similar projection rising above the surface of an anatomical strucuture along the sagittal (midline) plane.
opisthocranion also known as opisthokranion A craniometric point which is the furthest point from the glabella along the midline.
opisthion A craniometric point at the posterior margin of the foramen magnum along the midline.
ectorbitale An anatomical point on the most lateral point of the frontal bone of tetrapods on the occipital side of the orbit.
zygion The most lateral anatomical point of the zygomatic arch.
paroccipital process also known as estiloid process; paracondylar; parajugular; paramastoid process; paraoccipital A process of bone extending downward from the jugular process of the occipital bone.
incisor tooth 3 also known as third incisor tooth The incisor tooth of the upper or lower jaw that is phylogenetically number 3.
incisor tooth 4 also known as fourth incisor tooth The incisor tooth of the upper or lower jaw that is phylogenetically number 4.
incisor tooth 5 also known as fifth incisor tooth The incisor tooth of the upper or lower jaw that is phylogenetically number 5.
molar tooth 5 also known as fifth molar tooth The molar tooth of the upper or lower jaw that is phylogenetically number 5.
otion The most lateral anatomical point on the mastoid process of temporal bone.

cranial temporal crest A ridge or similar projection connected to the temporal lines and nuchal crest on the squamous part of the occipital bone. It bounds the posteroventral part of the temporal fossa.

central retina Region of retina around the fovea that extends approximately for 6 mm. Central retina is considerably thick due to increased density of photoreceptors, particularly cones and their associated bipolar and ganglion cells.

Henle's fiber layer also known as Henle fiber layer; HFL; nerve fiber layer of Henle This layer contains bundles of unmyelinated cone and rod photoreceptor axons terminating in the pedicles and spherules that synapse in the retinal outer plexiform layer (OPL).
left side of back Left part of the organism dorsal to a horizontal plane and bounded on one side by the same transverse plane.
right side of back Right part of the organism dorsal to a horizontal plane and bounded on one side by the same transverse plane.
cementocyte lacuna The small cavity within the cellular cementum that is occupied by a cementocyte cell body.

Purkinje fiber network also known as Purkinje fibre network A collection of Purkinje fibers that receives signals from the right and left bundle branches and innervates the ventricular cardiac muscle. The Purkinje fiber network creates synchronized contractions of the heart ventricles.
skin of scalp also known as adult scalp zone of skin; scalp skin; scalp zone of skin; zone of skin of adult scalp; zone of skin of scalp A zone of skin that is part of a scalp.
right forelimb A forelimb that is on the right side of a pectoral complex.
left forelimb A forelimb that is on the left side of a pectoral complex.
right hindlimb A hindlimb that is on the right side of a pelvic complex.
left hindlimb A hindlimb that is on the left side of a pelvic complex.

hepatic acinus zone 1 also known as hepatic acinus periportal zone The region of the hepatic acinus that is closest to the arterial blood supply and has the highest oxygen concentration. Zone 1 is located in the periportal region of the liver lobule, closest to the portal triad. Hepatocytes in this region are primarily involved in oxidative energy metabolism.

hepatic acinus zone 3 also known as hepatic acinus centrilobular zone; hepatic acinus pericentral zone; hepatic acinus perivenous zone The region of the hepatic acinus immediately surrounding the central veins. This region has the lowest oxygen concentration in the acinus. Zone 3 is located in the centrilobular region of the liver lobule, closest to the central vein. Hepatocytes in this region are the primary location for the biotransformation of drugs.

hepatic acinus zone 2 also known as hepatic acinus intermediary zone The region of the hepatic acinus in between zones 1 and 3. Blood in this region has an intermediate oxygen concentration relative to the other two zones of the hepatic acinus. Zone 2 is located in the midzonal region of the liver lobule. Hepatocytes in this region have mixed functionality in comparison with those in zones 1 and 3.

metabolic zone of liver also known as hepatic acinus metabolic zone Any of the metabolic zones found in the liver. Liver tissue is heterogenous at the level of morphometry and histochemistry. This heterogeneity is linked to the position of a cell within the functional unit of the tissue, which, in turn, is related to the blood supply: cells located in the upstream zone differ from those in the downstream zone with respect to subcellular structures, key enzymes, translocators, and receptors and, therefore, have different metabolic capacities. This is the basis for 'metabolic zonation', a concept first proposed in mammals for carbohydrate metabolism and later expanded to include amino acid and ammonia metabolism, xenobiotic metabolism, protective metabolism, and formation of plasma proteins.
liver lobule periportal region The region of the liver lobule that is closest to the portal triad. The functionally-defined hepatic acinus zone 1 is generally found in this region.
liver lobule centrilobular region The region of the liver lobule that is closest to the central vein. The functionally-defined hepatic acinus zone 3 is generally found in this region.
liver lobule midzonal region The region of the liver lobule that is between the periportal and centrilobular regions. The functionally-defined hepatic acinus zone 2 is generally found in this region.

liver serosa also known as serosa of liver; tunica serosa hepatis Hepatic serous coat; peritoneal covering of the liver, enclosing almost all except for a triangular area on its posterior surface (the 'bare area of the liver') and a smaller area where the liver and gallbladder are in direct contact.

liver subserosa also known as hepatic subserosa; subserosal tissue of liver; subserous layer of liver; tela subserosa (hepar); tela subserosa hepatis Subserosal tissue of liver. A zone of areolar connective tissue lying beneath the serous coat of the liver and distinguished with difficulty from the fibrous capsule of Glisson.

subcapsular region of liver also known as liver subcapsular region; liver subcapsular tissue; subcapsular tissue of liver Region of liver parenchyma immediately below the capsule. This region is frequently specified in pathology diagnoses.
duodeno-jejunal junction also known as duodeno-jejunal flexure; duodenojejunal flexure; duodenojejunal junction; flexura duodenojejunalis The anatomical junction between the duodenum and the jejunum.
small intestine venule also known as venule of small intestine Venule of villus of small intestine.
small intestine lymphatic vessel also known as lymphatic vessel of small intestine A lymphatic vessel that supplies the small intestine.

ductal plate In human, ductal plate is a double-layered cylindrical structure of bile duct epithelium that surrounds the portal ramifications by the eighth gestational week. After approximately the 12th gestational week, remodelling of ductal plate begins, and maturity is attained by the end of gestation or early postnatal period.
small intestine arteriole also known as arteriole of small intestine; arteriole of villus of small intestine; small intestine villus arteriole Arteriole of villus of small intestine.

transitional glandular epithelium of anorectum also known as anorectum transitional glandular epithelium; glandular epithelium of anal transition zone; glandular epithelium of the anal transition zone Glandular epithelium of the anal transition zone. The anal transition zone is defined loosely as the tissue interposed between the uninterrupted squamous epithelium of the anoderm and the uninterrupted mucosal epithelium of the anal canal in the anorectum.
submucous nerve plexus of anorectum also known as anorectum submucous nerve plexus Submucous nerve plexus that is located in the anorectum.
myenteric nerve plexus of anorectum also known as anorectum myenteric nerve plexus Myenteric nerve plexus that is located in the anorectum.
venule of anorectum also known as anorectum venule A venule that is located in the anorectum.
arteriole of anorectum also known as anorectum arteriole An arteriole that is located in the anorectum.

fimbria of fallopian tube also known as fimbria of uterine tube; fimbriae of fallopian tube; fimbriae of uterine tube A fringe of tissue around the ostium of the fallopian tube, in the direction of the ovary.

myenteric nerve plexus of appendix also known as myenteric nerve plexus of appendix vermiformis; myenteric nerve plexus of vermiform appendix Myenteric nerve plexus that is located in the vermiform appendix.

submucous nerve plexus of appendix also known as submucous nerve plexus of appendix vermiformis; submucous nerve plexus of vermiform appendix Submucous nerve plexus that is located in the vermiform appendix.

afferent lymphatic vessel valve also known as valve of afferent lymphatic vessel A valve in an afferent lymphatic vessel. It manages the flow of lymphatic fluid into the lymph node carrying immune cells and is essential for the correct flow of fluid through the lymphatic system.

efferent lymphatic vessel valve also known as valve of efferent lymphatic vessel A valve in an efferent lymphatic vessel. It manages the flow of lymphatic fluid out of the lymph node carrying immune cells and is essential for the correct flow of fluid through the lymphatic system.
arteriole of colon An arteriole located in the colon.
descending sigmoid junction also known as descending-sigmoid colon junction; descending-sigmoid junction The anatomical junction between the descending colon and the sigmoid colon.
left colic vein A portal vein that drains the descending colon. It is a tributary of the inferior mesenteric vein, and follows the path of its corresponding artery, the left colic artery.
right colic vein A portal vein that drains the ascending colon. It is a tributary of the superior mesenteric vein, and travels with its corresponding artery, the right colic artery.

jejuno-ileal junction also known as jejunoileal junction The area where the jejunum ends and the ileum part of the intestine begins. Although there is no clear distinct section, the ileum is narrower and has smaller villi than the jejunum.
venule of appendix also known as venule of vermiform appendix; vermiform appendix venule A venule located in the vermiform appendix.

inguinal region skin also known as groin skin; inguinal skin; skin of groin; skin of inguinal region; zone of skin of groin; zone of skin of inguinal region The skin covering the inguinal region between the abdomen and the thigh on either side of the pubic bone.

left colic artery The first branch of the inferior mesenteric artery (IMA) is the left colic artery. The left colic artery supplies blood flow to the distal third of the transverse colon and the entirety of the descending colon. Once diverging from the IMA, the left colic artery runs anterior to the left ureter, left internal spermatic vessels (males), and psoas major before branching into its ascending and descending segments.

right colic artery The right colic artery may arise directly from the superior mesenteric artery (SMA) but often arises from a common trunk with the ileocolic artery or middle colic artery. It supplies the ascending colon.
intestinal junction also known as junction of intestine An anatomical junction between two parts of the intestine.

transition zone of prostate also known as prostate transition zone The region of the prostate gland anterior to the central and peripheral zones, surrounding the proximal urethra. It is the zone of the human prostate gland that grows the most throughout life, and is responsible for benign prostatic hypertrophy.

peripheral zone of prostate also known as prostate peripheral zone The region of the prostate that is located posterior to the central and transition zones, surrounding the distal urethra. It is the zone of origin for the vast majority of human prostatic cancers.

central zone of prostate also known as prostate central zone The region of the prostate gland that is located between the peripheral and transition zones, surrounding the ejaculatory ducts. It gives rise to a very small percentage of human prostate cancers, often aggressive and invading the seminal vesicles.

arteriole of appendix also known as appendix vermiformis arteriole; arteriole of appendix vermiformis; arteriole of vermiform appendix; vermiform appendix arteriole An arteriole located in the vermiform appendix.
lymphatic capillary of appendix also known as lymphatic capillary of appendix vermiformis; lymphatic capillary of vermiform appendix A lymphatic capillary that is located in the vermiform appendix.
lymphatic vessel of appendix also known as lymphatic vessel of appendix vermiformis; lymphatic vessel of vermiform appendix A lymphatic vessel located in the vermiform appendix.
muscularis mucosae of appendix also known as muscularis mucosae of appendix vermiformis; muscularis mucosae of vermiform appendix A muscularis mucosa that is part of a vermiform appendix.

trabecular sinus of lymph node also known as lymph node trabecular sinus The trabecular sinus is the lymph-filled space outside the trabeculae between lobules of the lymph node. This is a continuation of the subcapsular sinus which receives the afferent vessels and is present beneath the capsule. This space is traversed by both reticular fibers and cells in the lymph.
lymph node vein also known as hilar vein of lymph node; vein of lymph node A vein where lymph node venules condense and which exits at the lymph node hilum. It is also called hilar vein.
lymph node artery also known as artery of lymph node; hilar artery of lymph node An artery that enters the lymph node at the hilum and branches into smaller arterioles.
medullary arteriole of lymph node also known as arteriole of medulla of lymph node An arteriole that arises from the hilar artery of a lymph node and radiates centrifugally, branching in the medulla.

medullary venule of lymph node also known as venule of medulla of lymph node Medullary venules are a continuation of high endothelial venules which condense repeatedly in the interfollicular cortex and peripheral deep cortical unit and then transition to medullary venules at the corticomedullary junction. The medullary venules condense and return centripetally to the hilar vein.

high endothelial venule High endothelial venules are specialized blood vessels adapted for lymphocyte trafficking. They form a spatially organized network, which controls both the type of lymphocyte and the site of entry into lymphoid tissues. Uniquely, high endothelial venules express vascular addressins that regulate lymphocyte entry into lymphoid organs. They perform this function in all lymphoid organs except the spleen.
high endothelial venule of lymph node also known as lymph node high endothelial venule A high endothelial venule that is part of a of lymph node.

high endothelial venule of appendix also known as appendix high endothelial venule; high endothelial venule of appendix vermiformis; high endothelial venule of vermiform appendix A high endothelial venule that is located in the vermiform appendix.

high endothelial venule of small intestine Peyer's patch also known as high endothelial venule of Peyer's patch of small intestine A high endothelial venule that is located in a Peyer's patch in the small intestine.
venule of lymph node also known as lymph node venule A venule that is part of a lymph node.
arteriole of lymph node also known as lymph node arteriole An arteriole that is part of a lymph node.
bronchus submucosal gland also known as bronchial submucosal gland; submucosal bronchial gland; submucosal bronchus gland A submucosal gland located in a bronchus.
vein of appendix also known as vein of appendix vermiformis; vein of vermiform appendix A vein that is part of a vermiform appendix.
artery of appendix also known as artery of appendix vermiformis; artery of vermiform appendix An artery that is part of a vermiform appendix.

appendix smooth muscle circular layer also known as smooth muscle circular layer of appendix; smooth muscle circular layer of appendix vermiformis; smooth muscle circular layer of vermiform appendix A circular muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a vermiform appendix smooth muscle.

appendix smooth muscle longitudinal layer also known as smooth muscle longitudinal layer of appendix; smooth muscle longitudinal layer of appendix vermiformis; smooth muscle longitudinal layer of vermiform appendix A longitudinal muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a vermiform appendix smooth muscle.
venule of colon A venule located in the colon.

serosal nerve fiber of appendix also known as nerve fiber of serosa of appendix; nerve fibre of serosa of appendix; serosal nerve fiber of appendix vermiformis; serosal nerve fiber of vermiform appendix; serosal nerve fibre of appendix; serosal nerve fibre of appendix vermiformis; serosal nerve fibre of vermiform appendix A nerve fiber that is located in the serosa of vermiform appendix.
anorectum A subdivision of the digestive tract in humans that includes the rectum, the anal canal and the anus.
lymphatic vessel of colon A lymphatic vessel located in the colon.

lymph node germinal center light zone also known as light zone of lymph node germinal center Lymph node germinal centers contain two microenvironments: the light zone and the dark zone. The light zone is sparsely populated with B cells and includes additional cell types such as follicular dendritic cells, lymph node tingible macrophages and T follicular helper cells.

lymph node germinal center dark zone also known as dark zone of lymph node germinal center Lymph node germinal centers contain two microenvironments: the light zone and the dark zone. The dark zone is densely populated with B cell blasts and reticular cells.
lymphatic capillary of colon A lymphatic capillary located in the colon.
lymphatic capillary of anorectum A lymphatic capillary located in the anorectum.
capillary of anorectum also known as blood vessel capillary of anorectum A capillary that is part of the anorectum.
capillary of colon also known as blood vessel capillary of colon A capillary that is part of the colon.
myenteric nerve plexus of colon Myenteric nerve plexus that is located in the colon.
submucous nerve plexus of colon Submucous nerve plexus that is located in the colon.
colon smooth muscle circular layer also known as smooth muscle circular layer of colon A circular muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a colon smooth muscle.
colon smooth muscle longitudinal layer also known as smooth muscle longitudinal layer of colon A longitudinal muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a colon smooth muscle.
parasympathetic cholinergic nerve A parasympathetic nerve that releases acetylcholine.
myenteric nerve plexus of small intestine Myenteric nerve plexus that is part of the small intestine.
submucous nerve plexus of small intestine Submucous nerve plexus that is located in the small intestine.

lymph node follicle marginal zone also known as marginal zone of lymph node follicle Histologically, the marginal zone pattern of the lymph node is characterized by lymphoid follicles with three distinct layers. The inner layer is composed of follicular center zones, the middle layer of darkly stained mantle zones, and the outer layer of marginal zones. However, the marginal zone pattern is rarely seen in reactive lymph nodes except for mesenteric lymph nodes. Lymph node marginal zones are populated by marginal zone B cells which express CD19 and CD20 and have the phenotypic features of memory B cells.

lymph node paracortex The lymph node paracortex is the middle layer of the lymph node and is mostly populated by T cells and dendritic cells. The paracortex also contains specialised blood vessels called high endothelial venules which allow lymphocytes to enter the node.

lymph node interfollicular cortex also known as interfollicular cortex of lymph node Follicules in the lymph node are surrounded and separated by the interfollicular cortex. Together with the lymph node follicle, the interfollicular cortex of the lymph node lobule make up the superficial cortex of the lymph node. Capillaries empty into the high endothelial venules located in the interfollicular cortex. The interfollicular cortex also serves as transit corriders for lymphocytes migrating between the B and T cell areas.
capillary of small intestine also known as blood vessel capillary of small intestine; small intestine capillary A capillary that is part of a small intestine.

levator costarum also known as levator costarum muscle; levatores costarum; levatores costarum muscles; musculi levatores costarum A chest muscle with a role in forceful inspiration. In human, there are twelve levatores costarum on either side of the chest; they are small tendinous and fleshy bundles arising from the ends of the transverse processes of the seventh cervical and upper eleven thoracic vertebrae. They pass obliquely downward and laterally, like the fibers of the intercostales externi, and each is inserted into the outer surface of the rib immediately below the vertebra from which it takes origin, between the tubercle and the angle (levatores costarum breves). Each of the four lower muscles divides into two fasciculi, one of which is inserted as above described; the other passes down to the second rib below its origin (levatores costarum longi).

subcapsular sinus ceiling also known as ceiling of subcapsular sinus of lymph node; floor of capsule of lymph node; subcapsular sinus of lymph node ceiling The section of the lymph node capsule that faces the subcapsular sinus. In human, it's characterized by specific protein markers.

subcapsular sinus floor also known as ceiling of cortex of lymph node; floor of subcapsular sinus of lymph node; subcapsular sinus of lymph node floor The section of the lymph node cortex that faces the subcapsular sinus. In human, it's characterized by specific protein markers.
medullary region of kidney also known as kidney medullary region A part of the kidney that comprises kidney pyramids and renal columns.
lymph node paracortical sinus A lymph node sinus intimately associated with paracortical cords that originate in the interfollicular cortex and extend into the medullary cords.
lymph node paracortical cord Lymph node paracortical parenchyma containing dense networks of T cells, B cells, fibroblastic reticular cells, and dendritic cells.

glomus coccygeum also known as coccygeal body; coccygeal gland; coccygeal glomus; gland of Luschka; glands of Luschka; glomus body; Luschka's gland A glomus-like dermal microanatomical structure found in human and placed in front of, or immediately below, the tip of the coccyx. Each glomus consists of one or more arterial segments that branch into a number of glomic arterioles surrounded by rows of round, uniform, epithelioid contractile cells, that drain into a collecting venous plexus.
airway submucosal gland also known as respiratory tract submucosal gland; submucosal gland of respiratory tract A submucosal gland found in a respiratory tract.

right lymphatic duct also known as ductus lymphaticus dexter A great lymphatic vessel that empties lymph into one of the subclavian veins. In humans, there are two lymph ducts in the body: the right lymphatic duct and the thoracic duct. The right lymphatic duct drains lymph from the right upper limb, right side of thorax and right halves of head and neck. The thoracic duct drains lymph into the circulatory system at the left brachiocephalic vein between the left subclavian and left internal jugular veins.
red bone marrow of iliac crest also known as iliac crest red bone marrow Red bone marrow located in an iliac crest.
red bone marrow of sternum also known as sternum red bone marrow Red bone marrow located in the sternum.

blood microvessel Any of the smallest blood vessels where blood circulates within organ tissues. Microvessels include terminal arterioles, metarterioles, capillaries, and venules (but exclude lymphatic capillaries). Arterioles carry oxygenated blood to the capillaries, and blood flows out of the capillaries through venules into veins.
hair of scalp Hair that grows on the scalp.
ethmoidal vein A vein that accompanies an ethmoidal artery and drains the ethmoidal cells.
anterior ethmoidal vein An ethmoidal vein that accompanies an anterior ethmoidal artery. The anterior ethmoidal vein normally drains into the inferior root of the superior ophthalmic vein.
posterior ethmoidal vein An ethmoidal vein that accompanies a posterior ethmoidal artery. The posterior ethmoidal vein often drains into a venous network under the orbital roof.
