cortical layer II/III also known as cerebral cortex layer 2/3; neocortex layer 2/3 A laminar subdivision of the neocortex that is comprised of a part of layer II and a part of layer III.
cortical layer IV/V also known as cerebral cortex layer 4/5; neocortex layer 4/5 A laminar subdivision of the neocortex that is comprised of a part of layer IV and a part of layer V.
cortical layer V/VI also known as cerebral cortex layer 5/6; neocortex layer 5/6 A laminar subdivision of the neocortex that is comprised of a part of layer V and a part of layer VI.

cortical layer VIb also known as cerebral cortex layer 6b; neocortex layer 6b The deepest layer of the neocortex. While layer 6b is considered part of layer 6, it is distinct morphologically, genetically, and developmentally from the rest of layer 6. Neurons in L6b project to cortical targets and higher-order thalamus and develop from a precursor population that arises from the subplate.
laminar subdivision of the cortex One or a subset of adjacent layers of the neocortex.

rostral periventricular region of the third ventricle also known as RP3V A functional anatomical construct containing the key estrogen-regulated inputs to gonadotropin-releasing hormone expressing (GnRH) neurons necessary for estrogen positive feedback. The rostral periventricular region of the third ventricle contains a population of neurons, scattered through the nuclei of the anteroventral periventricular (AVPV), periventricular preoptic (PVpo), and median preoptic (MEPO), that project directly to GnRH neurons and express ER-alpha.
periventricular hypothalamic nucleus, anterior part also known as PVa The anterior part of the periventricular hypothalamic nucleus.
periventricular hypothalamic nucleus, intermediate part also known as PVi The intermediate part of the periventricular hypothalamic nucleus.

Brodmann (1909) area 17 also known as area 17 of Brodmann-1909; b09-17; BA17; Brodmann area 17; Brodmann area 17, striate; primate striate cortex A subdivision of the cytoarchitecturally defined occipital region of cerebral cortex in the human. Defined by the band of Gennari, which gives it the name striate (furrowed) area, it occupies the banks of the calcarine sulcus which are located in the cuneus and the lingual gyrus of the occipital lobe. Cytoarchitecturally it is bounded by the area 18 of Brodmann (human) which surrounds it ( Brodmann-1909 ). In the mouse ( Paxinos-2001 ) and the rat ( Swanson-1998 ) it is located on the dorsolateral surface of the cerebral hemisphere[BrainInfo].
cortical visual area The part of the cortex that is responsible for processing visual information.

cerebral nuclei also known as CNU One of three components of the cerebrum that is a composite structure of the endbrain defined on the basis of origin from the ventricular ridge of the embryonic Encephalon. It consists of the extended striatum and the extended pallidum.

fasciola cinerea also known as FC A small paired band that passes around the splenium of the corpus callosum from the lateral longitudinal stria to the dentate gyrus. The FC exhibits clear anatomical borders with the distalmost region of the CA1.

ventrolateral preoptic nucleus also known as intermediate nucleus of the preoptic area (IPA); VLPO A small cluster of neurons situated in the anterior hypothalamus, sitting just above and to the side of the optic chiasm in the brain of humans and other animals.
noradrenergic cell groups Collections of neurons in the central nervous system that have been demonstrated by histochemical fluorescence to contain the neurotransmitter norepinephrine (noradrenalin).
noradrenergic cell group A1 A group of cells in the vicinity of the lateral reticular nucleus of the medullary reticular formation that label for norepinephrine in primates.
noradrenergiccell group A2 A group of cells in the vicinity of the dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus nerve in the medulla that label for norepinephrine in primates and rodents.

noradrenergic cell group A4 A group of cells exhibiting noradrenergic fluorescence that, in the rat, are located in the Tegmen ventriculi quarti (roof of the fourth ventricle) ventral to the cerebellar nuclei, and in the macaque, are found at the edge of the lateral recess of the fourth ventricle caudally, extending to beneath the floor of the ventricle where they merge with the noradrenergic group A6, the locus ceruleus.
noradrenergic cell group A5 A group of cells in the vicinity of the superior olivary complex in the pontine tegmentum that label for norepinephine in primates, rodents, and other mammals.

noradrenergic cell group A7 A group of cells fluorescent for norepinephrine that is located in the pontine reticular formation ventral to the superior cerebellar peduncle of the pons in rodents and in primates.

noradrenergic cell group Acg A group of cells fluorescent for norepinephrine that are located in the central gray of the midbrain at the level of the trochlear nucleus in the squirrel monkey (Saimiri) and to a lesser degree in the macaque.

parapyramidal nucleus also known as PPY A small group of cells located lateral to the pyramid of the medulla in the rat and the mouse that functionally it belongs to the reticular formation of the subcortical motor system.
parapyramidal nucleus, deep part also known as PPYd The part of the parapyramidal nucleus that is closely adjacent to the inner surface of the pyramidal tract.
parapyramidal nucleus, superficial part also known as PPYs The part of the parapyramidal nucleus that is located on the ventral surface of the medulla lateral to the pyramidal tract.

Perihypoglossal nuclei also known as nuclei perihypoglossales; perihypoglossal complex; perihypoglossal nuclear complex; PHY; satellite nuclei A group of neurons in the floor of the fourth ventricle, in close proximity to the nucleus of the hypoglossal nerve in the gray substance of the medulla oblongata, all of which contain cells with characteristics suggestive of reticular connections.

rubroreticular tract Nerve fibers that originate in the magnocellular red nucleus, cross to the other side of the midbrain, and descend in the lateral part of the brainstem tegmentum in the midbrain, and travel through the lateral funiculus of the spinal cord, coursing adjacent to the lateral corticospinal tract.

striatum-like amygdalar nuclei also known as sAMY A part of the striatum which is primarilly composed of amygdalar areas. The sAMY is composed of the anterior amygdalar area, central amygdalar nucleus, intercalated amygdalar nucleus, medial amygdalar nucleus, and the bed nucleus of the accessory olfactory tract.

medial corticohypothalmic tract also known as mct The main route taken by fibers from the ventral subiculum to the hypothalamus, where they innervate the medial preoptic area, shell of the ventromedial nucleus, dorsomedial nucleus, ventral premammillary nucleus, and cell-poor zone around the medial mammillary nucleus.

prelimbic area also known as PL; prelimbic cortex; PrL A region in the medial prefrontal cortex that is dorsal to the infralimbic area important in expression of conditioned reward and fear behaviour.

infralimbic area also known as IL (brain); ILA; infralimbic cortex A region in the medial prefrontal cortex that is ventral to the prelimbic area important in supression of conditioned reward and fear behaviour.
bulbocerebellar tract also known as bct A subdivision of inferior cerebellar peduncle that connects the medulla to the cerebellum.
sublaterodorsal nucleus also known as SLD; sublaterodorsal tegmental nucleus A region in the dorsal pons that plays a central role in inducing motor suppression during REM sleep.
supratrigeminal nucleus also known as SUT; Vsup A premotoneuron pool in the trigeminal reflex arc that is a key structure of jaw movement control.
accessory facial motor nucleus also known as ACVII A small cluster of neurons dorsal to the facial motor nucleus in the pontine tegmentum.
efferent vestibular nucleus also known as EV A small region of neurons in the brainstem, dorsolateral to the genu of facial nerve, that have efferents to the vestibular periphery.
piriform-amygdalar area also known as PAA (brain) The cortical region between the cortical amygdalar area and the piriform area.

dorsal peduncular area also known as DP A cytoarchitectonic area on the medial surface of the cerebral hemisphere rostral to the septum, ventral to the infralimbic area and dorsal to the tenia tecta in the mouse and rat.

superior paraolivary nucleus also known as SPON A structure embedded in the superior olivary complex that is driven by input pathways from the octopus cells in the cochlear nucleus and the neurons of the medial nucleus of the trapezoid body.
upper layers of the cortex A laminar subdivision of the neocortex that is comprised of the more surface layers, commonly layers two through four.
lower layers of the cortex A laminar subdivision of the neocortex that is comprised of the deeper layers, commonly layers five and six, however, could also consist part of layer four.

lateral tegmental nucleus also known as LTN A nucleus of the brain that is embedded in the pontine tegmentum, it is defined on the basis of inputs from the lateral hypothalamic area and central amygdalar nucleus, it is located ventral to the locus ceruleus, dorsal to Barrington's nucleus, lateral to the laterodorsal tegmental nucleus, and medial to the midbrain trigeminal nucleus.

magnocellular reticular nucleus also known as MARN A nucleus of the brain that is the most ventral portion of the gigantocellular nucleus in the medullary reticular formation, between the lateral paragigantocellular nucleus and the midline or nucleus raphe magnus. Functionally it belongs to the reticular formation (functional) of the subcortical motor system.

interstitial nucleus of the vestibular nerve also known as INV; ISVe A cluster of large nerve cells distributed in the vestibular component of vestibulocochlear nerve fibers that functionally belong to the vestibulomotor regions of the behavioral control column.
gustatory cortex also known as gustatory area The part of the cerebral cortex that is responsible for the perception of taste.
somatomotor area A part of the cerebral cortex that comprises of the primary motor cortex and the premotor cortex.
rhinal incisure A fissure in the cerebral cortex that separates the tenia tecta rostrally from the orbital gyri and caudally from the infralimbic cortex
egg follicle An individual reproductive unit containing a single oocyte and one or several layers of support cells (Armstrong et al., 2020).
excretory system An anatomical system that eliminates waste products that arise as a result of metabolic activity.
embryonic craniocervical region A craniocervical region that is part of an embryo.
placental blood Blood located in the placenta.

sublumbar lymph node A lymph node with a lymph center located within the caudal abdomen and pelvis, on the ventral side of the lumbar region. Includes the medial iliac, internal iliac (previously termed hypogastric) and sacral lymph nodes.

moderator band also known as septomarginal trabecula A muscular trabecula in the right ventricle of the heart that connects the interventricular septum to the anterior wall and to the base of the anterior papillary muscle of the right ventricle.
iliac vein smooth muscle tissue A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of an iliac vein.
capillary of brain A capillary that is part of the brain.
thoracic aorta smooth muscle tissue A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of the thoracic aorta.
iliac artery smooth muscle tissue A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of an iliac artery.
iliac vein endothelium An endothelium that is part of an iliac vein.
placental artery endothelium An endothelium that is part of the placental artery.
mesenteric lymphatic vessel Lymphatic vessel that is part of the mesentery.
placental artery An artery that is part of the placenta.
placental vein A vein that is part of the placenta.
tendon of semitendinosus also known as semitendinosus tendon A tendon that attaches to a semitendinosus.

perianal space An anatomical space located at the level of the anal orifice that is continuous with the ischioanal space laterally and superiorly and extends into the space between the external and internal sphincters.
deep post-anal space An anatomical space found at the front of the apex of the coccyx that is limited superiorly by the plate of the levator ani muscle and inferiorly by the anococcygeal raphe.
intersphincteric space An anatomical space located between the internal and external anal sphincters that continues inferiorly into the perianal space and superiorly into the rectum wall.
ischiorectal space also known as ischioanal space An anatomical space that extends from the levator ani muscle to the perineum lateral to the anal canal.
skin of buttock A zone of skin that is part of the buttock.

supra levator space also known as pelvic-rectal space An anatomical space limited superiorly by the peritoneum, laterally by the pelvic wall, medially by the rectal wall, and inferiorly by the levator ani muscle.

perirenal space also known as perinephric space A retroperitoneal space that lies between the anterior and posterior renal fascia; it is a paired inverted cone shaped of tissue containing the kidney, the proximal portion of the collecting system, renal and perirenal vasculature, perirenal lymphatics, adrenal glands and variable amount of fat.

anterior pararenal space A space that is bounded anteriorly by the posterior parietal peritoneum, laterally by the lateroconal fascia and posteriorly by the anterior renal fascia; it contains the pancreatic gland, retroperitoneal segments of the duodenum, ascending and descending colon and the mesenteric root, as well as adipose tissue.

posterior pararenal space A space that is bound anteriorly by the posterior renal fascia and posteriorly by the transversalis fascia, and it only contains adipose tissue, lymphatics and blood vessels.

perirectal space An extraperitoneal space bounded laterally by the perirectal fascia, posteriorly by the posterior pelvic fascia, and anteriorly by the rectovesical fascia in the male and the rectovaginal fascia in the female.

perivesical space An extraperitoneal space circumscribed by the umbilicovesical fascia anterior and laterally, and rectovaginal (in females) or rectovesical (in males) septum posteriorly, it encounters the urachus, obliterated umbilical vessels, urinary bladder and the lower uterine segment or seminal vesicles.

prevesical space An extraperitoneal space anterior and lateral to the umbilicovesical fascia, and posterior to the trasversalis fascia. Prevesical space laterally communicates with the properitoneal space of the abdominal wall and flanks; posteroinferiorly it surrounds the lateral walls of the urinary bladder, and anteroinferiorly it forms the retropubic space (the space of Retzius).

piriform sinus also known as piriform fossa; piriform recess; pyriform fossa; pyriform recess; pyriform sinus; smuggler's fossa A recess on either side of the laryngeal orifice, which is bounded medially by the aryepiglottic fold, laterally by the thyroid cartilage and thyrohyoid membrane. The pyriform sinus is involved in speech.
skin of lateral lumbar region of abdomen also known as skin of flank A zone of skin that is part of the lateral lumbar region of abdomen.
skin of sacral region A zone of skin that is part of the sacral region.
skin of clavicle region A zone of skin that is above the clavicle zone in the pectoral girdle region.
skin of iliac crest region A zone of skin that is above the iliac crest in the pelvic girdle bone/zone.
temple also known as temple region The region where the frontal, parietal, temporal, and sphenoid bones fuse.
skin of temple A zone of skin that is part of the temple.
skin of external genitalia A zone of skin that is part of the external genitalia.
skin of breast A zone of skin that is part of the breast.

tooth root apical papilla also known as apical papilla; apical papilla of immature permanent teeth The portion of the dental papilla located at the apex of the root of developing permanent tooth that is responsible for the progressive elongation and maturation of the root tooth.
neck of pancreas also known as neck of the pancreas; pancreatic neck The portion of the pancreas that connects the head of pancreas and the body of pancreas.

interlobular stroma of mammary gland The interlobular stroma of the mammary gland lobule separates the lobules and intralobular stroma from any substantial direct contact with the adipose tissue. It is more compact than the intralobular stroma.
intralobular stroma of mammary gland The intralobular stroma of the mammary gland lobule contains loosely connected fibroblasts. It is surrounded by the more compact interlobular stroma.

cervical transformation zone epithelium The area of epithelium that lies between the native and unaffected columnar epithelium of the endocervical canal and the native squamous epithelium deriving from the vaginal and ectocervical squamous epithelium.

posterior wall of the glottis also known as posterior end of the glottis; posterior glottis; posterior portion of the glottis Part of the glottis most closely associated with the pharynx represented anatomically by the posterior union of the developing cricoid cartilage.

subserosa of fallopian tube also known as subserosa of oviduct; subserosa of uterine tube Subserosa that is part of the uterine tube. It contains loose connective tissue, blood vessels and lymphatic tissue.
menstrual fluid Fluid that consists of necrotic and shed endometrial tissue and blood from mucosal vessels discharged during the reproductive years approximately once a month.

pelvic wall The tissues that surround the organs that are present within the pelvic region of the trunk. The walls of the pelvis are formed by bones and ligaments that are partly lined with muscles covered with fascia and parietal peritoneum.
long bone cartilage element also known as long bone cartilage A skeletal element that is part of a long bone and composed of cartilage tissue.
subiliac lymph node A lymph node located inferior to the ilium.

retroauricular region also known as retro-auricular area; retro-auricular part of head; retro-auricular region; retroauricular area The retroauricular region is the area located behind the auricle of the outer ear.

calf also known as calf of leg; posterior curral region; posterior leg region; posterior part of leg; posterior region of leg; regio cruris posterior; regio surae; sura; sural region The posterior aspect of the lower extremity that extends from the knee to the foot.

front hindlimb zeugopod also known as anterior crural region; anterior leg region; anterior region of leg; front of the lower leg; shin The frontal aspect of the lower extremity that extends from the knee to the foot.
skin of calf also known as skin of posterior part of leg Skin of the back of the lower leg.
thoracolumbar junction also known as thora-columbar junction Area of transition between the posterior curvature of the thoracic spine and the anterior curvature of the lumbar spine.
skin of thoracolumbar junction A zone of skin that is part of the thoracolumbar junction.
skin of umbilical area A zone of skin that is part of the umbilicus and the periumbilical region.
ileocecal lymph node also known as ileocaecal lymph node Mesenteric lymph node embedded in the ileocecal fold at both sides of the concavity of the cecum. It drains the terminal ileum.

subcarinal lymph node also known as subcarinal node Superior mediastinal lymph node located in the thoracic cavity between the lungs. It is bordered by the carina of the trachea, the lower lobe bronchus on the left and the intermediate bronchus on the right.

left supraclavicular lymph node Supraclavicular lymph node located on the left side of a entire appendicular skeleton. The left supraclavicular lymph node drains the kidney, cervix, testis, and pancreas into the thoracic duct.

right supraclavicular lymph node Supraclavicular lymph node located on the right side of a entire appendicular skeleton. The right supraclavicular lymph node drains the breast, lung and upper esophagus into the right lymphatic duct.

Virchow's lymph node also known as Virchow's node Lymph node that is the most proximal of the left supraclavicular lymph nodes. It receives afferent lymphatic drainage from the left head, neck, chest, abdomen, pelvis, and bilateral lower extremities, and drains into the jugulo-subclavian venous junction via the thoracic duct.
perigastric lymph node also known as peri-gastric lymph node; peri-gastric node; perigastric node Lymph node located in the perigastric region.
paraspinal region also known as paraspinal The region of the body adjacent to the vertebral column.
pericardial region The region of the body adjacent to the pericardium and heart.
femoral head cartilage A hyaline articular cartilage that covers the head of femur. Provides cushioning, softness and low friction for the hip joint.

dorsal iris also known as dorsal rim of the iris The dorsal part of the iris. In urodeles (newts and salamanders) the dorsal iris is involved in lens regeneration in a process named Wolffian lens regeneration.
secretory coil of eccrine sweat gland Tightly coiled tubule whose function is the production of sweat. The secretory tubule has three types of cells: clear, dark, and myoepithelial.

labial gland also known as labial minor salivary gland; labial salivary gland The labial gland is one of the minor salivary glands, located mainly under the mucosal epithelium of the upper and lower lip and within the orbicularis oris muscle fibers. The labial gland secrete mucous and serous substances to maintain oral health. In particular, the inferior labial gland not only promotes moisturization in the oral cavity but also secretes substances with antibacterial effects.
interscapular region The region in the upper part of the back between the shoulder blades.
bone marrow microvessel Microvessel located in the bone marrow, including arterioles and sinusoids.
saphenous vein smooth muscle tissue A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of a saphenous vein.
temporofacial region The region at each side of the face comprising the temple and the cheek.

lateral wall of nasal cavity also known as lateral wall of the nose; nasal lateral wall An anatomical wall that surrounds the nasal cavity. The lateral walls of the nasal cavity are spiral shaped mucosal folds that overlie the turbinate and sinus ducts draining into the ostia.
skin of shin A zone of skin on the front hindlimb zeugopod.
skin of scapula region A zone of skin that is above the scapula in the upper back region.
skin of gonad A zone of skin part of some gonad.

right upper third secondary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth 1; FDI tooth 18; right upper third secondary molar tooth A upper third secondary molar tooth that is in the right side of the upper jaw region.

right upper second secondary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth 2; FDI tooth 17; right upper second secondary molar tooth A upper second secondary molar tooth that is in the right side of the upper jaw region.

right upper first secondary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth 3; FDI tooth 16; right upper first secondary molar tooth A upper first secondary molar tooth that is in the right side of the upper jaw region.

right upper second secondary premolar tooth also known as ADA tooth 4; FDI tooth 15; right upper second secondary premolar tooth A upper second secondary premolar tooth that is in the right side of the upper jaw region.

right upper first secondary premolar tooth also known as ADA tooth 5; FDI tooth 14; right upper first secondary premolar tooth A upper first secondary premolar tooth that is in the right side of the upper jaw region.
right upper secondary canine tooth also known as ADA tooth 6; FDI tooth 13; right upper secondary canine tooth A upper secondary canine tooth that is in the right side of the upper jaw region.

right upper lateral secondary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth 7; FDI tooth 12; right upper lateral secondary incisor tooth A upper lateral secondary incisor tooth that is in the right side of the upper jaw region.

right upper central secondary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth 8; FDI tooth 11; right upper central secondary incisor tooth A upper central secondary incisor tooth that is in the right side of the upper jaw region.

right lower third secondary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth 32; FDI tooth 48; right lower third secondary molar tooth A lower third secondary molar tooth that is in the right side of the lower jaw region.

right lower second secondary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth 31; FDI tooth 47; right lower second secondary molar tooth A lower second secondary molar tooth that is in the right side of the lower jaw region.

right lower first secondary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth 30; FDI tooth 46; right lower first secondary molar tooth A lower first secondary molar tooth that is in the right side of the lower jaw region.

right lower second secondary premolar tooth also known as ADA tooth 29; FDI tooth 45; right lower second secondary premolar tooth A lower second secondary premolar tooth that is in the right side of the lower jaw region.

right lower first secondary premolar tooth also known as ADA tooth 28; FDI tooth 44; right lower first secondary premolar tooth A lower first secondary premolar tooth that is in the right side of the lower jaw region.
right lower secondary canine tooth also known as ADA tooth 27; FDI tooth 43; right lower secondary canine tooth A lower secondary canine tooth that is in the right side of the lower jaw region.

right lower lateral secondary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth 26; FDI tooth 42; right lower lateral secondary incisor tooth A lower lateral secondary incisor tooth that is in the right side of the lower jaw region.

right lower central secondary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth 25; FDI tooth 41; right lower central secondary incisor tooth A lower central secondary incisor tooth that is in the right side of the lower jaw region.

right upper second primary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth A; FDI tooth 55; right upper second primary molar tooth A upper second primary molar tooth that is in the right side of the upper jaw region.

right upper first primary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth B; FDI tooth 54; right upper first primary molar tooth A upper first primary molar tooth that is in the right side of the upper jaw region.
right upper primary canine tooth also known as ADA tooth C; FDI tooth 53; right upper primary canine tooth A upper primary canine tooth that is in the right side of the upper jaw region.

right upper lateral primary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth D; FDI tooth 52; right upper lateral primary incisor tooth A upper lateral primary incisor tooth that is in the right side of the upper jaw region.

right upper central primary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth E; FDI tooth 51; right upper central primary incisor tooth A upper central primary incisor tooth that is in the right side of the upper jaw region.

right lower second primary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth T; FDI tooth 85; right lower second primary molar tooth A lower second primary molar tooth that is in the right side of the lower jaw region.

right lower first primary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth S; FDI tooth 84; right lower first primary molar tooth A lower first primary molar tooth that is in the right side of the lower jaw region.
right lower primary canine tooth also known as ADA tooth R; FDI tooth 83; right lower primary canine tooth A lower primary canine tooth that is in the right side of the lower jaw region.

right lower lateral primary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth Q; FDI tooth 82; right lower lateral primary incisor tooth A lower lateral primary incisor tooth that is in the right side of the lower jaw region.

right lower central primary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth P; FDI tooth 81; right lower central primary incisor tooth A lower central primary incisor tooth that is in the right side of the lower jaw region.

left upper third secondary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth 16; FDI tooth 28; left upper third secondary molar tooth A upper third secondary molar tooth that is in the left side of the upper jaw region.

left upper second secondary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth 15; FDI tooth 27; left upper second secondary molar tooth A upper second secondary molar tooth that is in the left side of the upper jaw region.

left upper first secondary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth 14; FDI tooth 26; left upper first secondary molar tooth A upper first secondary molar tooth that is in the left side of the upper jaw region.

left upper second secondary premolar tooth also known as ADA tooth 13; FDI tooth 25; left upper second secondary premolar tooth A upper second secondary premolar tooth that is in the left side of the upper jaw region.

left upper first secondary premolar tooth also known as ADA tooth 12; FDI tooth 24; left upper first secondary premolar tooth A upper first secondary premolar tooth that is in the left side of the upper jaw region.
left upper secondary canine tooth also known as ADA tooth 11; FDI tooth 23; left upper secondary canine tooth A upper secondary canine tooth that is in the left side of the upper jaw region.

left upper lateral secondary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth 10; FDI tooth 22; left upper lateral secondary incisor tooth A upper lateral secondary incisor tooth that is in the left side of the upper jaw region.

left upper central secondary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth 9; FDI tooth 21; left upper central secondary incisor tooth A upper central secondary incisor tooth that is in the left side of the upper jaw region.

left lower third secondary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth 17; FDI tooth 38; left lower third secondary molar tooth A lower third secondary molar tooth that is in the left side of the lower jaw region.

left lower second secondary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth 18; FDI tooth 37; left lower second secondary molar tooth A lower second secondary molar tooth that is in the left side of the lower jaw region.

left lower first secondary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth 19; FDI tooth 36; left lower first secondary molar tooth A lower first secondary molar tooth that is in the left side of the lower jaw region.

left lower second secondary premolar tooth also known as ADA tooth 20; FDI tooth 35; left lower second secondary premolar tooth A lower second secondary premolar tooth that is in the left side of the lower jaw region.

left lower first secondary premolar tooth also known as ADA tooth 21; FDI tooth 34; left lower first secondary premolar tooth A lower first secondary premolar tooth that is in the left side of the lower jaw region.
left lower secondary canine tooth also known as ADA tooth 22; FDI tooth 33; left lower secondary canine tooth A lower secondary canine tooth that is in the left side of the lower jaw region.

left lower lateral secondary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth 23; FDI tooth 32; left lower lateral secondary incisor tooth A lower lateral secondary incisor tooth that is in the left side of the lower jaw region.

left lower central secondary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth 24; FDI tooth 31; left lower central secondary incisor tooth A lower central secondary incisor tooth that is in the left side of the lower jaw region.

left upper second primary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth J; FDI tooth 65; left upper second primary molar tooth A upper second primary molar tooth that is in the left side of the upper jaw region.
left upper first primary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth I; FDI tooth 64; left upper first primary molar tooth A upper first primary molar tooth that is in the left side of the upper jaw region.
left upper primary canine tooth also known as ADA tooth H; FDI tooth 63; left upper primary canine tooth A upper primary canine tooth that is in the left side of the upper jaw region.

left upper lateral primary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth G; FDI tooth 62; left upper lateral primary incisor tooth A upper lateral primary incisor tooth that is in the left side of the upper jaw region.

left upper central primary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth F; FDI tooth 61; left upper central primary incisor tooth A upper central primary incisor tooth that is in the left side of the upper jaw region.

left lower second primary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth K; FDI tooth 75; left lower second primary molar tooth A lower second primary molar tooth that is in the left side of the lower jaw region.
left lower first primary molar tooth also known as ADA tooth L; FDI tooth 74; left lower first primary molar tooth A lower first primary molar tooth that is in the left side of the lower jaw region.
left lower primary canine tooth also known as ADA tooth M; FDI tooth 73; left lower primary canine tooth A lower primary canine tooth that is in the left side of the lower jaw region.

left lower lateral primary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth N; FDI tooth 72; left lower lateral primary incisor tooth A lower lateral primary incisor tooth that is in the left side of the lower jaw region.

left lower central primary incisor tooth also known as ADA tooth O; FDI tooth 71; left lower central primary incisor tooth A lower central primary incisor tooth that is in the left side of the lower jaw region.

cranial temporal line A dorsally concave, laterally-directed line on either side of the skull that runs along the temporal fossa, starting from above the zygomatico-frontal suture. It bounds the anterodorsal part of the temporal fossa and its the attachment site to the temporalis muscle.
euryon An anatomical point on the most lateral point of the neurocranium.
supraorbital foramen A bony elongated opening located above the orbit and under the forehead.
supraorbitale An anatomical point on the median point of the line joining the aboral borders of the supraorbital foramen.
entorbitale An anatomical point on the naso-medial indentation of the orbit that corresponds with the inner angle of the eye in the living animal.
lobular bronchiole also known as preterminal bronchiole A conductive airway that branches into terminal bronchioles.
epithelium of lobular bronchiole also known as epithelium of preterminal bronchiole; lobular bronchiole epithelium An epithelium of the lobular bronchiole.
mucosa of lobular bronchiole A mucosa that is part of a lobular bronchiole.
smooth muscle tissue of lobular bronchiole A smooth muscle tissue that is part of a lobular bronchiole.
visceral muscle tissue also known as visceral muscle A muscle tissue that is associated with soft internal organs (viscera).
visceral smooth muscle tissue also known as smooth musculature of viscera; visceral smooth muscle A smooth muscle tissue that is associated with soft internal organs (viscera).
visceral striated muscle tissue also known as striated visceral muscle tissue A striated muscle tissue that is associated with soft internal organs (viscera).
visceral transversely striated muscle tissue also known as transversely striated visceral muscle tissue A striated visceral muscle tissue that has a transverse striation.
visceral obliquely striated muscle tissue A striated visceral muscle tissue that has an oblique striation.
subsegmental bronchus Branch of conducting airway between a segmental bronchus and a preterminal bronchiole.
bronchial submucosal gland ciliated duct A ciliated duct part of a bronchial submucosal gland.
tracheal submucosal gland ciliated duct A ciliated duct part of a tracheal submucosal gland.
submucosal gland acinus A spherical or tubular structure in a submucosal gland that produces and secretes mucus and other substances into the ducts leading to the surface epithelium.
submucosal gland collecting duct A non-secretory tubular structure in the submucosal gland where secretions are collected before flowing towards the surface epithelium.
submucosal gland ciliated duct A ciliated tubular structure in a submucosal gland connecting the submucosal gland collecting duct with the surface epithelium.
posterior sector of right lobe of liver also known as lateral sector of right lobe of liver; right hepatic posterior sector The posterior sector of the right lobe of the liver.
anterior sector of right lobe of liver also known as medial sector of right lobe of liver; right hepatic anterior sector The anterior sector of the right lobe of the liver.

bronchopulmonary segment also known as lung segment A discrete anatomical unit of the lung that is composed of a segmental bronchus and the lung tissue supplied by that bronchus. A bronchopulmonary segment exhibits a pyramidal shape, with its apex pointing towards the center of the lung and its base toward the pleural surface.

neuroendocrine system A regulatory system of the body that integrates the nervous system and the endocrine system. This system is formed by specialized neuroendocrine cells located mainly in the nervous system and neuroendocrine glands. However, they can also be found as either single cells or small clusters of cells dispersed throughout the surface epithelium of different tissues. The neuroendocrine system functions through the release of neurotransmitters and neurohormones, enabling communication between the endocrine and nervous systems to govern vitally important processes that include growth, reproduction, metabolism and energy homeostasis, electrolyte and water balance, and responses to stress.

placental basal plate also known as placenta basal plate A maternal facing structure of the placental disc, adjacent to the intervillous space. Major components of the placental basal plate include decidua basalis, fibrinoid, connective tissue, extravillous trophoblasts, and residues of degenerating villi and maternal vessels.

placental septum also known as placenta septum An extension of the basal plate that protrudes into the intervillous space, creating a system of grooves which delimit elevated areas, also known as cotyledons or maternal lobes.
chorionic plate blood vessel A blood vessel that is part of the chorionic plate.

pulmonary interlobular septum A septum that surrounds and gives shape to the secondary pulmonary lobules, it is composed of connective tissue within which run the pulmonary veins and lymphatic vessels.

placental villous stroma also known as chorionic villous stroma A stroma that is part of a chorionic villus (placental villus). A placental villous stroma supports the fetal capillaries and villous trophoblast.

pulmonary venule A venule that is part of a lung and drains oxygenated blood from pulmonary capillaries. A pulmonary venule merges into a pulmonary vein branch that runs in the pulmonary interlobular septa.

intervillous space An anatomical space that separates the basal plate and the chorionic plate. The intervillous space is filled with endometrial gland secretions during early stages of the pregnancy and later perfused with maternal blood, bathing the chorionic villous tree.

chorionic villous tree also known as placental villous tree A tree-like structure formed by chorionic villi that sprouts from the chorionic plate in the placental disc. The arborous shape of the chorionic villous tree provides maximal contact area with maternal blood in the intervillous space.

chorionic stem villus also known as placental stem villus A chorionic villus that provides structural support to the villous tree. A chorionic stem villus is characterized by a condensed fibrous stroma in which fetal arteries, veins, arterioles, and venules are embedded. It represents a distributing framework for fetal chorionic circulation, supplying the floating villi. It can exhibit a diameter ranging from approximately 3000 m (trunci near the chorionic plate) to 80 m (smallest ramuli chorii).

chorionic mesenchymal villus The first generation of a tertiary villus that is derived from a syncytial sprout by the invasion of the mesenchyme, in which blood vessels differentiate through vasculogenesis, and gradually transforms into a new immature intermediate villus. A chorionic mesenchymal villus has a thick trophoblastic covering, and cytotrophoblast cells are interposed between syncytium and the trophoblastic basal lamina over 50100% of the surface. The stroma is characterized by loosely arranged collagen fibers that enmesh mesenchymal and some villous macrophages. The fetal capillaries are poorly developed.

chorionic immature intermediate villus A bulbous, immature chorionic villus that is formed of loose connective tissue with few fetal vessels. A chorionic immature intermediate villus develops from a chorionic mesenchymal villus, and is the forerunner of a chorionic stem villus.

chorionic terminal villus The most distal part of a chorionic villus. A chorionic terminal villus is a grape-like structure characterized by a high degree of capillarization and highly dilated sinusoids. A terminal villus has less stroma and a discontinuous cytotrophoblast layer, and contains 46 fetal capillaries per cross section. It exhibits a diameter ranging from 40 to about 80 m.

chorionic mature intermediate villus A slender branch of a chorionic stem villus. A chorionic mature intermediate villus lacks fetal arterioles and venules in the stroma, which is composed of slender fetal capillaries embedded into a loose connective tissue that is rich in cells but poor in fibers. It exhibits a diameter ranging from 60 to about 100 m.
chorionic floating villus A chorionic villus that is not attached to the placental basal plate and it is immersed in maternal blood.

chorionic anchoring villus A distal smaller chorionic stem villus that is connected to the maternal side of the placenta (in early gestational stages to the decidua, and later to the developing basal plate) via a cytotrophoblast cell column. A chorionic anchoring villus stabilizes the position of the villous tree in the maternal intervillous bloodstream.
jejunum lamina propria also known as jejunal lamina propria; lamina propria of jejunum A lamina propria that is part of a jejunum.
ileum lamina propria also known as ileal lamina propria; lamina propria of ileum A lamina propria that is part of an ileum.

kidney loop of Henle long descending thin limb outer medulla also known as long descending limb of the loop of Henle in the outer medulla A section of the long descending thin limb of the loop of Henle that is part of the outer medulla of the kidney.

kidney loop of Henle long descending thin limb inner medulla also known as long descending limb of the loop of Henle in the inner medulla A section of the long descending thin limb of the loop of Henle that is part of the inner medulla of the kidney.

placental disc also known as placental disk A disc-shaped structure that is part of the placenta. A placental disc supports fetal development through the exchange of nutrients between maternal and fetal bloodstreams. The placental disc is structured to keep the blood streams separate, while maximizing surface area for the transport of nutrients between them, to maintain an immunological barrier.
chorionic villous mesenchyme A mesenchyme that is part of a chorionic villus.
chorionic stem villous blood vessel A blood vessel that is part of a chorionic stem villus.

chorionic terminal villous capillary A capillary that is part of a chorionic terminal villus. This capillary is generally narrow, but displays sinusoidal dilations along its length, often at the points of acute bends. These dilations bring the capillary endothelium into close contact with the overlying syncytiotrophoblast to form a vasculosyncytial membrane.
endometrial lymphatic vessel A lymphatic vessel that is part of an endometrium.
lateral wall of urinary bladder A wall of the urinary bladder that is situated on the sides or flanks.
left lateral wall of urinary bladder also known as left wall of urinary bladder A lateral wall of the urinary bladder that is located on the left side.
right lateral wall of urinary bladder also known as right wall of urinary bladder A lateral wall of the urinary bladder that is located on the right side.
anterior wall of urinary bladder The most anterior wall of the urinary bladder.
posterior wall of urinary bladder The most posterior wall of the urinary bladder.

apex of urinary bladder also known as vertex of urinary bladder The anterior angle of the superior surface of the urinary bladder. The apex of urinary bladder is connected to the umbilicus by the urachus in embryos, and by the median umbilical ligament, a remnant of urachus, in adults.
dome of urinary bladder The anterosuperior surface of the urinary bladder, with boundaries at the apex and fundus of the urinary bladder.

trophoblast island also known as intraplacental trophoblast island; trophoblastic cell island An accumulation of extravillous trophoblast cells at the tip of a floating villus or occasionally attached to the chorionic plate embedded in fibrin.
segmental pulmonary vein A vein that is tributary of the main pulmonary veins and drains oxygenated blood from a segment of the lung.
subsegmental pulmonary vein A vein that is tributary of the segmental pulmonary veins and drains oxygenated blood from a subsegment of the lung.
esophageal vein A vein that is tributary of the azygos vein and drains blood from the esophagus.
supreme intercostal vein also known as first posterior intercostal vein A vein that is tributary of the superior intercostal vein and drains the first intercostal space.
atrioventricular nodal artery also known as atrioventricular node branch of right coronary artery An artery that branches from the right coronary artery and supplies the atrioventricular node.
lateral sacral vein A vein that is tributary of the internal iliac vein and drains the anterior surface of the sacrum.
middle hemorrhoidal vein also known as middle rectal vein A vein that is tributary of the internal iliac vein.
uterine vein A vein that is tributary of the internal iliac vein and drains the uterus.
deep cervical vein A vein that is tributary of a vertebral vein and drains the suboccipital region, adjacent vertebral column, and deep muscles of the neck.
subsegmental pulmonary artery An artery that is a branch of the segmental pulmonary artery and supplies deoxyge blood to a smaller subsegment of the lung.
intra-acinar venule A venule that receives drainage from the capillary beds after blood has perfused the pulmonary alveoli, and is tributary of the pulmonary venules.
thyrocervical trunk An artery that branches from the subclavian artery and supplies the thyroid gland, neck, and upper back regions.
septal perforating artery An artery that branches from the left anterior descending artery and supplies the interventricular septum of the heart.
posterolateral artery An artery that branches from the right coronary artery or the circumflex artery and supplies the posterior and lateral walls of the left ventricle.
lateral femoral circumflex vein also known as set of lateral circumflex femoral veins A vein that is tributary of the femoral vein and drains blood from the front and middle areas of the thigh.
basivertebral vein A vein that is tributary of the anterior internal vertebral venous plexus and drains blood from the vertebral bodies.
bronchial venule A venule that is tributary of the bronchial veins and drains blood from the bronchi and bronchioles of the lungs.
mental vein A vein that is tributary of the facial vein and drains blood from the chin and lower lip.
deep lingual vein A vein that is tributary of the lingual vein and drains blood from the tongue.
dorsal lingual vein A vein that is tributary of the lingual vein and drains blood from the dorsum of the tongue, and the sides of the tongue.
sublingual vein A vein that is tributary of the lingual vein and drains blood from the ventral (inferior) surface of the tongue and the sublingual glands.
glandular venous plexus also known as thiroid venous plexus A venous plexus tha connects the middle and superior thyroid veins.
circumflex humeral vein A vein that is tributary of the axillary vein and drains blood from the region around the neck of the humerus.

thoracoacromial vein also known as thoraco-acromial vein A vein that is tributary of the axillary vein and drains blood from the thoracoacromial region, including the pectoral, shoulder, and clavicular regions.
transverse cervical vein A vein that is tributary of the external jugular vein and drains blood from the superficial muscles of the back, mainly the trapezius muscle.
suboccipital venous plexus A venous plexus that is tributary of the deep cervical veins and drains blood from the suboccipital region.

pulmonary arteriole also known as set of all pulmonary arterioles An arteriole that branches from the pulmonary arteries and supplies deoxygenated blood to the pulmonary capillaries and alveolar capillaries of the lungs.
ascending pharyngeal artery An artery of the neck that branches from the external carotid artery and supplies the pharynx.
dural artery An artery that branches from the internal carotid artery and supplies the anterior clinoid process of the dura mater.
pericardial artery An artery that branches from the descending thoracic aorta and supplies the dorsal portion of the pericardium.
percardiacophrenic artery also known as pericardiacophrenic artery An artery that branches from the internal thoracic artery and supplies the pericardium and the diaphragm.

superficial iliac circumflex vein also known as superficial circumflex iliac vein A vein that is tributary of the great saphenous vein and drains blood from the inguinal region and the anterior abdominal wall.
fibular vein also known as set of peroneal veins A vein that is tributary of the posterior tibial vein and drains blood from the lateral compartment of the leg.
prostatic venule A venule that is tributary of the prostatic venous plexus and drains blood from the prostate gland.

hepatic portal venule A venule that branches from the hepatic portal vein to transport nutrient-rich blood from the gastrointestinal tract and spleen to supply the liver. The hepatic portal venule is tributary of the hepatic sinusoids.
incisor artery An artery that branches from the inferior alveolar artery and supplies the roots and pulp of the teeth of the lower jaw. It forms anastomoses with its contralateral partner.
external nasal vein A vein that is tributary of the angular vein and drains blood from the superficial tissues and skin of the dorsum (bridge) and ala (wings) of the nose.
supratrochlear vein A vein that is tributary of the angular vein and drains blood from the muscles and skin of the forehead.
transverse nasal root vein A vein that is tributary of the angular veins and drains blood from the bridge of the nose.
hypophyseal vein A vein that is tributary of the cavernous sinus and drains blood from the pituitary gland.

inferior anastomotic vein A vein that is tributary of the transverse sinus and drains blood from the adjacent cortical regions of the temporal lobe. The inferior anastomotic vein forms an anastomosis (connection) between the superficial middle cerebral vein anteriorly and the transverse sinus posteriorly.
radial vein A vein that is tributary of the brachial vein and drains blood from the lateral structures of the forearm, carpal and metacarpal bones, joints of the hand, and lateral forearm muscles.
ulnar vein A vein that is tributary of the brachial vein and drains blood from the hand and medial and posterior aspect of forearm.
intra-acinar arteriole An arteriole that branches from the pulmonary arteriole and supplies deoxygenated blood to the pulmonary capillaries in the alveoli of the lungs.
ascending palatine artery An artery that branches from the facial artery, and branches to supply the soft palate and the palatine tonsil.
submental artery An artery that branches from the facial artery that runs forward under the mouth, then turns upward upon reaching the chin.

deep lingual artery also known as third part of lingual artery An artery that branches from the lingual artery and supplies blood to the tongue itself, particularly the body and tip of the tongue. The deep lingual artery travels superiorly in a tortuous course along the under (ventral) surface of the tongue, below the longitudinalis inferior, and above the mucous membrane.

dorsal lingual artery An artery that branches from the lingual artery and supplies the soft palate, tonsils, epiglottis, palatoglossal arch, and adjacent mucous membrane. The dorsal lingual artery runs along the upper border of the hyoid bone and anastomises with its fellow of the opposite side.

accessory meningeal artery An artery that branches from the maxillary artery and supplies the meninges. The accessory meningeal artery ascends through the foramen ovale to enter the cranial cavity and supply the dura mater of the floor of the middle cranial fossa and of the trigeminal cave, and to the trigeminal ganglion.

artery of pterygoid canal An artery that branches from the maxillary artery and supplies blood to structures in the auditory tube, tympanic cavity, and upper pharynx. The artery of the pterygoid canal courses through the pterygoid canal, a small bony canal located in the sphenoid bone of the skull.
descending palatine artery An artery that branches from the maxillary artery and supplies the hard and soft palate.

left anterior descending artery also known as anterior interventricular branch of left coronary artery An artery that branches from the left coronary artery and supplies the anterior wall of the left ventricle, the interventricular septum, and the apex of the heart.

anterior internal vertebral venous plexus A venous plexus that is tributary of the basivertebral veins and internal vertebral veins, draining blood from the vertebrae and spinal cord. The anterior internal vertebral venous plexus is located within the vertebral canal.

intervertebral vein A vein that drains blood from the vertebral column and intervertebral discs. In the neck, it is tributary of into the vertebral veins. In the thorax, it is tributary of the posterior intercostal veins. In the lumbar and sacral regions, it is tributary of the lumbar and lateral sacral veins
lumbar vein also known as set of lumbar veins A vein that is tributary of the inferior vena cava and drains blood from the posterior abdominal wall and lumbar region.

anterior humeral circumflex artery An artery that branches from the axilliary artery and supplies the deltoid, biceps brachii, and coracobrachialis muscles, the glenohumeral joint, the proximal humeral head, and the skin overlying the anterior aspect of the proximal humerus. This artery courses laterally across the anterior surface of the humerus and anastomoses with the posterior humeral circumflex artery.

posterior humeral circumflex artery An artery that branches from the axilliary artery and supplies the deltoid, teres major, teres minor, and long and lateral heads of the triceps brachii muscles, glenohumeral joint, and the cutaneous supply to the area posterolateral to the proximal humerus. This artery courses posteriorly with the axillary nerve, through the quadrangular space, to the posterior aspect of the humerus and anastomoses with the anterior humeral circumflex artery.

proximal ureter also known as abdominal ureter; upper ureter A segment of the ureter that extends from the renal pelvis to the common iliac artery bifurcation (to form the internal and external iliac arteries).

distal ureter also known as lower ureter; pelvic ureter A segment of the ureter that extends from the common iliac artery bifurcation to the bladder. From there, the ureter curves back and follows the lateral pelvic wall inferiorly to connect with the posterolateral bladder wall.

intramural ureter also known as intravesical ureter The terminal segment of the ureter that is continuous with the distal ureter, lies where the ureter enters the bladder and extends within the bladder wall. The intramural ureter is aperistaltic, serving as a reflux-preventing mechanism, preventing the backflow of urine from the bladder into the ureters.
right distal ureter also known as right lower ureter; right pelvic ureter A distal ureter that is part of the right ureter.
left distal ureter also known as left lower ureter; left pelvic ureter A distal ureter that is part of the left ureter.
right proximal ureter also known as right abdominal ureter; right upper ureter A proximal ureter that is part of the right ureter.
left proximal ureter also known as left abdominal ureter; left upper ureter A proximal ureter that is part of the left ureter.
right intramural ureter also known as right intravesical ureter An intramural ureter that is part of the right ureter.
left intramural ureter also known as left intravesical ureter An intramural ureter that is part of the left ureter.
antimesosalpinx also known as anti-mesosalpinx; posterior free border of mesosalpinx; posterior free edge of mesosalpinx A posterior free border of a mesosalpinx.

aorta-gonad-mesonephros A transient organ in the developing embryo composed of the dorsal aorta, developing gonads, and embryonic kidney. This structure is located in the embryonic mesoderm and serves as the primary site for the generation of definitive hematopoietic stem cells.

follicle associated epithelium also known as FAE A specialized epithelial layer overlying the luminal surface of lymphoid follicles in gut-associated lymphoid tissue. It is found in Peyer's patches of the small intestine and appendix in humans and in the intestine and caecal patches in mice. This layer contains specialised M cells and has fewer goblet cells compared to surrounding tissue. This layer plays a crucial role in mucosal immune surveillance.

stratum spinosum of esophageal epithelium The second deepest layer of the stratified squamous epithelium lining the esophagus, positioned directly above the stratum basale. It consists of multiple layers of keratinocytes connected by strong intercellular junctions called desmosomes, giving the cells a characteristic "spiny" appearance. This layer provides structural support, contributes to the epithelial barrier function, and serves as a transitional zone for keratinocytes migrating towards the luminal surface, playing a crucial role in maintaining the integrity and protective properties of the esophageal lining.
lumen of pulmonary alveolus also known as cavity of pulmonary alveolus; pulmonary alveolar cavity An anatomical cavity that is part of the alveolus of the lung

sensory corpuscle also known as cutaneous end-organ complex A mechanosensory complex in the terminal end of some nerves that forms a corpuscle. It consists of one or more neuronal terminations and associated non-neuronal cells.
